<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<bible xml:lang="bko" backtTranslaltionDefaultLanguage="en" oxes="2.0">
  <book id="MAT" stage="Final" version="C">
    <Annotation class="History">
      <Message author="John Wimbish" created="2009-10-05 05:42:04Z" when="2009-10-05 05:42:04Z" stage="Draft">drafted by Lazarus Aplugi; keyboarded by Helena Aplugi; team revision October 2008; with advisor Feb 2009 &amp; May 2009 (Kupang-S);</Message>
    </Annotation>
    <p class="Header" usfm="h">Mateos</p>
    <p class="Title Secondary" usfm="mt2">Lii lolo Be'a nèti Lamatua Yesus<bt>Lord Yesus' Good Story</bt></p>
    <p class="Title Secondary" usfm="mt2">madhutu sasuri<bt>according to the writing of</bt></p>
    <p class="Title Main" usfm="mt">Mateos<bt>Mateos</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p" />
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">J'aj'aj'i nèti Lamatua Yesus<bt>The Lord Yesus' origins ancestor list/genealogy</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="list/genealogy"><Message author="Chuck" created="2009-11-23 00:52:08Z" status="Anyone">One UNS not know kabhia, but can guess from context</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Lukas 3:23-38)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="1" />
      <v n="1-2" />Sasuri ne, lole j'ara mamuri nèti Yesus Kristus, nuka Dhèu dhu Ama Lamatua padhadha mema ho neo pua mai. Yesus ne, ana-èpu dhèu aae Daud dènge Abraham.<bt>This book/writing stories/tells about the life of Yesus Kristus, Person whom *God [Ama Lamatua] promised beforehand from long ago to send. This Yesus, was the descendant (doublet) of king Daud and Abraham.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kabhia = sil-silah, genealogy"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">kabhia = sil-silah, genealogy</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nèt"><Message author="From Merge" created="2009-11-26 09:34:51Z" status="Anyone">Merge Conflict: Original was "NOW IS THE TIME FOR ALL GOOD MEN... Sasuri ne, lole j'ara mamuri nèt"; Ours was "Sasuri ne, lole j'ara mamuri nèt"; Theirs was "Sasuri ne, lole j'ara mamur"</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Karèi nèti Abraham toke dhèu aae Daud, abhu 14 (canguru èpa) bèi-baki. Kabhia Na sèmi ne'e:<bt>Beginning from Abraham until king Daud there are/were 14 forefathers (doublet). His list of ancestors/genealogy, is like this:</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tèlu tanga bèi-baki = tiga lapis"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">tèlu tanga bèi-baki = tiga lapis</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Abraham matana Isak,<bt>Abraham gave birth [as males can] to Isak,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Isak matana Yakob,<bt>Isak gave birth to Yakob,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Yakob matana Yahuda dènge a'ari na,<bt>Yakob gave birth to Yahuda and his elder-younger siblings,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="3" />Yahuda matana Peres dènge Sera (ina ra, ngara na Tamar)<bt>Yahuda gave birth to Peres and Sera (their mother, [was] named Tamar),</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Peres matana Herson,<bt>Peres gave birth to Herson,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Herson matana Ram,<bt>Herson gave birth to Ram,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="4" />Ram matana Aminadab,<bt>Ram gave birth to Aminadab,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Aminadab matana Nahason,<bt>Aminadab gave birth to Nahason,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Nahason matana Salmon,<bt>Nahason gave birth to Salmon,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="5" />Salmon matana Boas (ina na, ngara na Rahab)<bt>Salmon gave birth to Boas (his mother, [was] named Rahab),</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Boas matana Obet (ina na, ngara na Rut),<bt>Boas gave birth to Obet (his mother, [was] named Rut),</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Obet matana Isai,<bt>Obet gave birth to Isai,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="6a" />Isai matana Daud.<bt>Isai gave birth to Daud.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6b-11" />Nèti Daud toke lod'o dhu ra babège suku Isra'el asa Babel, abhu hari 14 (canguru èpa) bèi-baki, nuka:<bt>From Daud until that time when the Israel people/nation was thrown out/exiled to Babel, there were 14 more descendants, that were:</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Daud matana Soleman (ina na, uru èèna dhèu èmu Uria).<bt>Daud gave birth to Soleman (his mother, previously [was] Uria's wife).</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Soleman matana Rehabeam,<bt>Soleman gave birth to Rehabeam,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Rehabeam matana Abia,<bt>Rehabeam gave birth to Abia,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Abia matana Asaf,<bt>Abia gave birth to Asaf,</bt><note reference="1:7" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Sasuri lii Yunani dhu be'a risi, suri <span class="Italic">Asaf</span>. Abhu sasuri cahag'e dhu leo, dhu suri, na, <span class="Italic">Asa</span>. Dhèu ne'e, èci èèna ka dènge dhèu dhu cèu d'ara sasuri <span class="Italic">1 Sejara nèti Isra'el dènge Yahuda</span> 3:10.<bt>The best Yunani language writings write <span class="Italic">Asaf</span>. There are some other writings that write, <span class="Italic">Asa.</span> This person is the same as the one who appears in 1 Chron. 3:10. [NOTE: on Asaf vs. Asa, see Carson, AGNT, NRSV, NLT. But TB writes Asa.]</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Asaf matana Yosafat,<bt>Asaf gave birth to Yosafat,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Yosafat matana Yoram,<bt>Yosafat gave birth to Yoram,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Yoram matana Usia,<bt>Yoram gave birth to Usia,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Usia matana Yotam,<bt>Usia gave birth to Yotam,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Yotam matana Ahas,<bt>Yotam gave birth to Ahas,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ahas matana Heskia,<bt>Ahas gave birth to Heskia,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Heskia matana Manase,<bt>Heskia gave birth to Manase,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Manase matana Amos,<bt>Manase gave birth to Amos,</bt><note reference="1:10" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Sasuri lii Yunani cahag'e suri, na, <span class="Italic">Amos</span>. Aa abhu cahag'e dhu suri, na, <span class="Italic">Amon</span>.<bt>Some Yunani language writings write <span class="Italic">Amos</span>, and some others write <span class="Italic">Amon</span>. [NOTE: on Amos vs. Amon, see Carson, AGNT, NRSV, NLT. But TB writes Amon.]</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Amos matana Yosias,<bt>Amos gave birth to Yosias,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Yosias matana Yekonya dènge ari na, lod'o babège si asa Babel.<bt>Yosias gave birth to Yekonya and his younger siblings when they were thrown/exiled to Babel.</bt><note reference="1:11" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">2 Dhèu Aae sèra 24:14-15, 2 Sejara nèti Isra'el dènge Yahuda 36:10, Yermia 27:20</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12-16" />Lod'o babège si asa Babel, toke d'ai rara iisi Yesus, abhu 14 (canguru èpa) bèi-baki, nuka:<bt>When they were thown/exiled to Babel until Yesus, there were again 14 descendants, that is:</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Yekonya matana Saltiel,<bt>Yekonya gave birth to Saltiel, [EXEG: TH, TN and TRT note this follows the LXX here, not the Hebrew; if one follows the Heb, Zerubbabel is actually the grandson of Shealtiel (Pedaiah was the father); although CONNOT says he was probably the nephew of Shealtiel. AGNT, NRSV, TB, TH, TN use ‘Jechoniah’ here. NLT, CEV and Morris use ‘Jehoiachin’ without comment. CONNOT says Jechoniah = Jehoiachin without additional discussion. We follow TB.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Saltiel matana Serubabel,<bt>Saltiel gave birth to Serubabel,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Serubabel matana Abihut,<bt>Serubabel gave birth to Abihut,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Abihut matana Elyakim,<bt>Abihut gave birth to Elyakim,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Elyakim matana Asor,<bt>Elyakim gave birth to Asor,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Asor matana Sadok,<bt>Asor gave birth to Sadok,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Sadok matana Akim,<bt>Sadok gave birth to Akim,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Akim matana Eliut,<bt>Akim gave birth to Eliut,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Eliut matana Eliasar,<bt>Eliut gave birth to Elieser,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Eliasar matana Matan,<bt>Eliasar gave birth to Matan,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Matan matana Yakob,<bt>Matan gave birth to Jakob,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Yakob matana Yusuf,<bt>then Yakob gave birth to Yusuf.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Yusuf ne, dhèu èmu Maria. Maria ne ka dhu nara iisi Yesus Kristus.<bt>That Yusuf, married Maria who gave birth to Yesus Kristus.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />De karèi nèti Abraham toke Daud, abhu 14 (canguru èpa) bèi-baki; nèti Daud toke lod'o ra babège si asa Babel abhu 14 (canguru èpa) bèi-baki; aa nèti lod'o ra babège si asa Babel d'ai Maria nara iisi Yesus, abhu 14 (canguru èpa) bèi-baki.<bt>So, from Abraham until Daud there were 14 descendants; from Daud until they thrown to Babel there were 14 descendants, and from Babel until giving birth to Kristus, there were 14 descendants.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Maria nara iisi Lamatua Yesus<bt>Maria gives birth to the Lord Yesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Lukas 2:1-7)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Lii lolo Maria nara iisi Yesus sèmi ne'e ka:<bt>The story of Maria giving birth to Yesus is like this:</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Maria dhu tunanga le dènge Yusuf. Dua ra pa'èci rèdhi mèka sama sèmi dhèu èmu-kamali, te ngaa te'a boe na, Maria dhu dènge le babia nèti Roh Ama Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci.<bt>Maria was engaged (loan) with Yusuf. The two of them had never sleep together as spouses, but it became apparent (contrary to expectation) that Maria was pregnant from the *Holy Spirit (God's Spirit who is Clean/Holy).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lii dai le = su maso"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">lii dai le = su maso minta (implication: they are considered married) ; tunanga = bertunangan</Message></Annotation><note reference="1:18" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lukas 1:27</note><v n="19" />Ropa Yusuf ne'a, ka na neo pama'ète lii rèngu dua ra. Te ngaa na d'èi boe pamakae Maria ètu madha dhèu ae, lula nèngu ne ca dhèu dhu d'ara mola. Nèti èèna ka, na neo pamau eele lii rèngu ne.<bt>When Yusuf knew/found out, then he wanted to sever their agreement. But he did not want to shame/embarass Maria in front of many people, because his insides were straight [=he was righteous]. That's why he wanted to quietly end their agreement.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Te ngaa lod'o dhu na pangee era, d'ara ca mèda sa, ka nèngu nii. Ètu d'ara nii ne, ladhe nèdhi ana pajuu Ama Lamatua nèti sorga mai peka dènge ne, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Yusuf! Èu ne, ana-èpu dhèu aae Daud. Èu mage makae leo dènge Maria. Te ana dhu na kad'o èèna, j'aj'i nèti Roh Ama Lamatua.<bt>But while he was still thinking about it one night, he dreamed. In his dream, he saw God's underling from heaven {*angel} come tell him, saying, &lt;&lt;Yusuf! You-s here, are king Daud's descendant. You don't be ashamed to marry with Maria. Cuz (elaboration) the child which is in her womb there, came into being from God's Spirit. [NOTE to daughter translations: Morris, TRT, TN all agree this is not fear of physical danger, but of social danger, so in these lgs, “don't be embarrassed to marry Mary...” might be an acceptable alternative (suggested by Dhao team).]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="CULTURE: team wanted don't be embarrased"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">CULTURE: team wanted don't be embarrased to marry Maria ; kad'o = mengandung</Message></Annotation><v n="21" />Bèli-camèd'a Maria nara iisi ana mone ca dhèu. Aa èu hud'i pangare Ne, <span class="Italic">Yesus,</span> te Nèngu ka dhu patabuli dhèu unu Ama Lamatua nèti koasa sasala-sasigo ra.&gt;&gt;<bt>Later, Maria will give birth to a male child. Then you must name him, <span class="Italic">Yesus</span>, cuz (elaboration) He is the one who will distribute life/salvation to (*save) God's people from their sins (doublet).&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="1:21" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Ngara <span class="Italic">Yesus</span> sasoa na, &lt;&lt;Lamatua patabuli dhèu nèti koasa sasala-sasigo ra.&gt;&gt;.<bt>The name <span class="Italic">Yesus</span> means 'The Lord gives life/salvation to (*saves) people.'</bt></note><note reference="1:21" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lukas 1:31</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />J'ara ne j'aj'i sèmi èèna, lula Ama Lamatua dhu peka mema nèti uru ka, re dhèu nèti lii padhai Na, ngara na Yesaya, dhu suri, peka na,<bt>This thing will happen like that, because God has told [it] in.advance from long ago, by way of His *prophet {spokesperson} Yesaya who wrote, saying,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="J'ara ne j'aj'i madhutu lii nèti"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">J'ara ne j'aj'i madhutu lii nèti ca dhèu nèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua, nuka, Yesaya dhu suri mema na,</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="23" />&lt;&lt;Mi nanene! Bèli-camèd'a abhu ana bhèni ca dhèu dhu kalora iisi,<bt>&lt;&lt;You-p listen up! Later there will be a maiden who is still a virgin, [CHECK key term with another group of UNSs]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">te'a boe na, nèngu dhu dènge babia le.<bt>it will become apparent that she is pregnant.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Èèna na nara iisi Ana Mone ca dhèu.<bt>Then, she will give birth to a male Child.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Ka ra pangare Ne, <span class="Italic">Imanuel</span>.&gt;&gt;<bt>They will name Him, <span class="Italic">Imanuel</span>.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">(Lii Ibrani, &lt;Imanuel&gt; sasoa na:<bt>(In Hebrew language, ‘Imanuel’ means:</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Ama Lamatua bera-bera dènge èdhi.)<bt>God is together with us.)</bt><note reference="1:23" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 7:14</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Ropa nii èle, Yusuf kèd'i nèti bhèj'i na. Ka na madhutu ka lii padhai Ama Lamatua dhu na tadèngi ètu d'ara nii deo na. Ka nare Maria j'aj'i dhèu èmu na.<bt>When the dream ended, Yusuf got/woke up. Next he immediately followed what God had said. He took Maria to become his spouse.</bt><v n="25" />Te ngaa na j'unu pa'èci boe dènge Maria, toke Maria nara iisi aa'i. Nara iisi nare ka, Yusuf pangare Ana ne, <span class="Italic">Yesus.</span><bt>But he did not sleep together with Maria until Maria had given birth. After giving birth, Yusuf named that Child, <span class="Italic">Yesus.</span> [NOTE to daughter translations: TB uses /bersetubuh/ Avoid problem of saying in 24 he took her as wife, then in 25 only they were not together as husband-wife until the birth, which ambiguously can mean they didn't live in the same house, at odds with 24. So “sleep together” is important here, and more refined than the TB.]</bt><note reference="1:25" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lukas 2:21</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu dhu d'èlu-mèu ladhe hua-hètu, mai tenge Yesus<bt>People who are skilled in looking at stars come looking for Yesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="2" />
      <v n="1" />Lod'o rara iisi Yesus ètu rae Betlehem, ètu propensi Yudea, dhèu aae Herodes dhu nèd'u paredha ètu èèna. Lod'o èèna, dhèu pèri-pèri nèti era kaj'èu, mai nèti bèka dhimu asa kota Yerusalem. Rèngu se, dhu re'a mèu ladhe hua-hètu.<bt>When Yesus was born in Betlehem village in Yudea province, king Herodes was holding rule/authority. At that time, several people came from a far place on the east side/direction to Yerusalem city. They were people who were really understood looking at stars.</bt><v n="2" />Ropa ra d'ai Yerusalem dhèu se pakarèi, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu Aae nèti dhèu Yahudi, dhu heka rara iisi hiu èèna, era na buli mia, ee? Ji'i ngèdhi hua-hètu cue ètu bèka dhimu, dhu j'aj'i mi tadha dhu peka na, rara iisi le Nèngu. Nèti èèna ka, ji'i mai neo pahaha iisi mi Nèngu.&gt;&gt;<bt>When they arrived in Yerusalem, they asked around, saying, &lt;&lt;That King of the Yahudi people who was just recently born, where is his place, ee? We-exc have seen a star on the east side, which was a sign saying He has been born. That's why we come wanting to worship Him.&gt;&gt;</bt><v n="3" />Ropa dhèu aae Herodes tadèngi lii ne'e, hèia d'ara na susa. Nèti èèna ka, dhèu aa'i-aa'i ètu Yerusalem sèra, d'ara ra susa kahèi.<bt>When king Herodes heard this talk, then his insides were troubled. That is why everyone in Yerusalem also had troubled insides. [NOTE to daughter translations: TB missed the meaning of the Gk here. Herod was stressed out, not surprised.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Èle èèna ka, dhèu aae Herodes paroa nare kètu agama Yahudi dènge mese agama aa'i-aa'i sèra, ka na karèi si, peka na, &lt;&lt;Miu peka sèku dènge ja'a la! Kristus, dhu Ama Lamatua padhadha tèke èèna, rara iisi Ne ètu mia?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then, king Herodes gathered together all the *chief priests (heads of the Yahudi *priests) and the religious teachers (*scribes), and asked them, saying, &lt;&lt;You-p try and tell me [mild imperative]! Kristus, whom God has promised, He is going to be born where?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Hèia ra dhaa, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ètu rae Betlehem, propensi Yudea. Te ca dhèu nèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua, ngara na Mika, dhu suri tèke le karèi nèti uru ka, na:<bt>Then they answered saying, &lt;&lt;In the village of Betlehem, in Yudea province. Cuz (elaboration) the Lord's spokesperson named Mika has written in.advance from long ago, saying:</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="6" />&lt;Wee! Miu dhèu Betlehem ètu propensi Yudea sèra.<bt>&lt;Wee! You-pl Betlehem people, in Yudea province over.there.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Baku pangee na, rae miu ne,<bt>You don't think, that your village,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">ca rae iiki dhu dhèu ige boe.<bt>[is] merely a small village which people don't count.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Te bèli-camèd'a dhèu kapai ca dhèu cèu mai nèti rae ne'e.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) later there will be a big/important person who comes out from that village.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Èèna na Nèngu j'aj'i dhèu madhenga mi dhèu Ja'a, dhèu Isra'el.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>He will become a shepherd/watchman for My people, the people of Isra'el.&gt;&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="2:6" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mika 5:1; 2 Samuel 5:2</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Ropa tadèngi nare sèmi èèna, hèia dhèu aae Herodes paroa mau-mau dhèu dhu d'èlu-mèu ladhe hua-hètu sèra. Ka na karèi, na, &lt;&lt;Lod'o mia miu ladhe mèdhi hua-hètu ne cèu ètu dedha-liru?&gt;&gt; Hèia ra peka dènge ne.<bt>After hearing like that, then king Herodes silently/ secretly called those people who were skilled in looking at stars. Then he asked them, &lt;&lt;When was it that you-pl saw that star appear in the sky?&gt;&gt; So they told him.</bt><v n="8" />Èle ka, na hia si lasi asa Betlehem. Na moa dènge ra, peka na, &lt;&lt;Lami ho tenge palème era, ètu mia Ana ne. Ladhe miu rage, na, lèpa hari mai sèna ka peka dènge ja'a. Te ja'a neo laku pahaha iisi mi Nèngu kahèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then He sent them to go to Betlehem. He instructed them, saying, &lt;&lt;You-p go look all around for that Child. If/when you find (Him), na, return back here to tell me. Cuz (elaboration) I also want to go worship Him.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <fig path="HK-LB\LB00295C.tif" rtfFormat="width:5.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left">Dhèu d'èlu-mèu hua-hètu hia hadia<bt>People skilled with stars give gifts</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Ropa tadèngi rare lii padhai dhèu aae, hèia lasi dènge ka. Kaca'a laa, rèngu rèdhi hari hua-hètu dhu uru èèna rèdhi ètu bèka dhimu. Hua-hètu ne cèu ètu madha rèngu, na kako uru nèti rèngu, hèia tèja ètu dedha era Ana ne pea.<bt>After hearing the king's speaking, then they went right away. Unexpectedly, they saw that star again which previously they had seen on the east side. That star appeared in front of them, and.then it travelled/went ahead of them until stopping above that Child's staying/living place.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tèja = berhenti"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">tèja = berhenti</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Ropa rèdhi, hèia ra karej'e titu kèna.<bt>When they saw that, they were very happy.</bt><v n="11" />Èle ka lasi asa d'ara èmu, hèia ladhe rèdhi Ana ne dènge ina Na Maria. Hèia ra patitu kètu urutuu ho pahaha iisi mi Ana ne. Ka dhèu se bhoke mèdha dhu kab'ua rèti hia Ana ne. Ra hia hualaa, kemenyan dènge raa aj'u hèu mèngi.<bt>Then they entered that house, and they saw that Child with His mother Maria. Then they knelt to worship the Child. Then these people opened their valuable things, to give to that Child. They gave gold, and incense (assimilated loan) and fragrant sap.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Nèbhu boe, ka dhèu se abhu nii nèti Ama Lamatua, peka na, &lt;&lt;Lami ia ka asa dhèu aae Herodes.&gt;&gt; Nèti èèna ka, ra lèpa hari asa rai rèngu re j'ara leo.<bt>Not long, then they got a dream from God, saying, &lt;&lt;You-p don't return to king Herodes anymore.&gt;&gt; That's why they returned home to their country by way of a different road.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yusuf si rai asa Masir<bt>Yusuf (collective) run/flee to Masir (Egypt)</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Lod'o dhèu d'èlu-mèu ladhe hua-hètu se lèpa, hèia ana pajuu Lamatua èci nèti sorga, mai peka dènge Yusuf ètu d'ara nii, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Yusuf! Pakèd'i dènge ka d'ara lai-lai ne! Mèti Ana ne dènge ina Na lami asa Masir. Pea ètu nèi, toke Ja'a peka d'ai lod'o mia miu lèpa hari. Te dhèu aae Herodes tenge j'ara ho pamadhe Ana ne!&gt;&gt;<bt>When those people who skilled in looking at stars were returning home, then one of the Lord's underlings from heaven came to tell Yusuf in a dream, saying, &lt;&lt;Yusuf! Get/Wake up immediately! Take that Child and His mother and go to Masir. Stay there (remote), until I tell when you may return home. Cuz (elaboration) king Herodes is looking for a way to kill this Child!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kako karohe = jalan cepat"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">kako karohe = jalan cepat</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Hèia Yusuf kèd'i nèti bhèj'i. Ka mèda èèna kahèi, nèti dhèu èmu na dènge Ana ne, rai lasi asa Masir.<bt>Then Yusuf woke from his sleep. And that same night he took his spouse and that Child, running/fleeing to Masir.</bt><v n="15" />Ra pea ètu nèi toke dhèu aae Herodes madhe. J'ara èèna, nuka sèmi ca dhèu nèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua, ngara na Hosea, suri tèke karèi nèti uru ka, na,<bt>They stayed/lived there until king Herodes died. This (event), was like what God's spokesperson named Hosea had told in.advance from long ago, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Ja'a paroa hari Ana Ku, ho lèpa ka nèti Masir.&gt;&gt;<bt>&lt;&lt;I summon home My Child to come home from Masir.&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="2:15" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Hosea 11:1</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu aae Herodes pamadhe ana iiki ae-ae ètu Betlehem<bt>King Herodes kills a great many small children in Betlehem</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Ropa dhèu aae Herodes ne'a nare, na, dhèu d'èlu-mèu ladhe hua-hètu sèra leko-monya ne, hèia na nasa titu kèna. Na paredha sordad'u na sèra, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Lami asa rae Betlehem nèi, aa asa rae-rae leo dhu padètu ètu èèna. Pamadhe aa'i ana mone iiki dhu dua tèu asa haha mai.&gt;&gt; Herodes hia paredha ne, lula na sanèd'e lii lolo nèti dhèu d'èlu-mèu sèra. Na ige karèi nèti rèngu rèdhi hiu-hiu hua-hètu cèu ètu dedha-liru.<bt>When king Herodes found out that those people skilled at watching stars had decieved him, then he became very angry. He ordered his soldiers, saying, &lt;&lt;Go to Betlehem village (remote) and to the villages which are near there. Kill all the small male children who are two years and under.&gt;&gt; Herodes ordered this, because he remembered those experts' story/account. He counted started from the first time that saw that star appear in the sky (doublet).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ag'o = UNS's not know"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">ag'o = UNS's not know</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />J'ara se'e aa'i-aa'i j'aj'i madhutu ngaa dhu dhèu nèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua, ngara na Yermia, suri tèke, peka na,<bt>All these things happened, in accord with what God's spokesperson named Yermia had previously written, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="18" />&lt;&lt;Abhu lii tangi dènge lii roma iisi dhèu nèti kota Rama.<bt>&lt;&lt;There is the sound crying and lamtentation of people from Rama city.</bt><note reference="2:18" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Rama èèna, kota cue dhu padètu dènge kota Yerusalem.<bt>That Rama is/was a city near Yerusalem city.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Rahel tangi d'ara pèd'a,<bt>Rahel is crying in grief,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">lula ana-ana na madhe aa'i.<bt>because her children are all dead.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Na d'èi boe ca dhèu sa mai pamako ne,<bt>She doesn't want anyone to come comfort her,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">lula ana-ana na, aad'o heka ca dhèu sa.&gt;&gt;<bt>because her children, no longer exist.&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="2:18" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yermia 31:15</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yusuf si lèpa nèti rai Masir<bt>Yusuf {collective} return from Masir land/country</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Nèbhu-nèbhu ka, dhèu aae Herodes madhe. Lod'o èèna, Yusuf si ètu Masir era. Hèia Ama Lamatua pua ana pajuu Na ca dhèu mai nèti sorga, pad'elo rèhu na mi nèngu ètu d'ara nii.<bt>Eventually then king Herodes died. At that time Yusuf (coll) was still in Masir. Then God's underling from heaven, revealed himself to him in a dream.</bt><v n="20" />Ana pajuu ne lii, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Yusuf! Kèd'i ka! Mèti ka Ana ne dènge ina Na asa Isra'el. Te dhèu dhu neo pamadhe Ana ne, madhe le.&gt;&gt;<bt>That underling spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;Yusuf! Get/Wake up! Take that Child and his mother, to Isra'el. Cuz (elaboration) the person who wanted to kill that Child, has died.&gt;&gt;</bt><v n="21" />Ropa tadèngi nare, hèia Yusuf kèd'i. Èle ka nèti si asa rai Isra'el.<bt>When he heard that, then Yusuf got/woke up. Then2 he took them to Isra'el land/country.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Te ngaa ropa Yusuf tadèngi na, Arkalaus, ana dhèu aae Herodes, dhu j'aj'i dhèu aae limuri ne ètu propensi Yudea, ka na madha'u la'e asa Yudea. Èle èèna ka, Ama Lamatua peka hari dènge ne ètu d'ara nii, na, &lt;&lt;Yusuf, èu baku pea ètu Yudea.&gt;&gt; Nèti èèna ka, lasi pea asa propensi Galilea,<bt>But when he heard that king Herodes' child Arkalaus now was now king in Yudea province, then he was afraid to go to Yudea. Then2 God told him in a dream again, saying, &lt;&lt;Yusuf, you-s don't stay/live in Yudea.&gt;&gt; That's why he went to live/stay in Galilea province,</bt><v n="23" />ètu rae Nasaret. Dènge j'ara ne lii padhai Ama Lamatua lèke tare'a, nuka sèmi ngaa dhu dhèu rèti lii padhai Na suri tèke, na &lt;&lt;Bèli-camèd'a dhèu paroa Ne, Dhèu Nasaret.&gt;&gt;<bt>in Nasaret village. With that [happening] that speaking of God's happened exactly in accord with what His spokesperson had written in.advance saying, &lt;&lt;Later they will call Him, a Nasaret Person.&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="2:23" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Markus 1:24, Lukas 2:39, Yohanis 1:45</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yohanis tuka sarani aj'a-nori dhèu<bt>Yohanis the habitual baptizer teaches (doublet) people</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 1:1-8; Lukas 3:1-18; Yohanis 1:19-28)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="3" />
      <v n="1" />Lod'o Yesus dhu kapai le, hèia Yohanis tuka sarani mulai aj'a-nori dhèu ètu era dhu dhèu pea boe ètu propensi Yudea.<bt>When Yesus was big, then Yohanis the habitual baptizer began to teach (doublet) people in a place where people didn't live, in Yudea province. [NOTE to daughter translations: some of our lgs distinguish between /besar datang/ ‘adolescence, around 13-15’ vs. /su besar/ ‘already adult’. Make sure it's the latter. The gospels tell us he was around 30 when he began his ministry.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kapai mai = teenager (like Da'i"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">kapai mai = teenager (like Da'i at 14) ;</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Na aj'a peka na, &lt;&lt;A'ari pasue! Miu hud'i mangaku aa tèke eele ku sasala-sasigo miu, ho lèpa asa Ama Lamatua. Te limuri ne dhèu aa'i-aa'i bisa j'aj'i dhèu unu Ama Lamatua.&gt;&gt;<bt>He taught, saying, &lt;&lt;Dear siblings [can extend to non-kin as a vocative]! You-pl must acknowledge/confess and leave behind your-p wrongs (doublet), in.order.to return to God. Cuz (elaboration) now, all people can become God's people.&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="3:2" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 4:17, Markus 1:15</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Uru èèna, ca dhèu nèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua, ngara na Yesaya, suri le lula-nèti Yohanis ne, aku nèngu na,<bt>Previously one of God's spokespersons named Yesaya had written about Yohanis, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Bèli-camèd'a abhu dhèu pa'oo-parodha ètu d'ara mamoo, peka na,<bt>&lt;&lt;Later there will be a person that shouts out (doublet) in a desolate place, saying, [NOTE to daughter translations: make sure word for ‘shout’ can have message, not just sound.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">&lt;Dhèu aa'i-aa'i pa'èra sèna ka tao pabe'a j'ara,<bt>&lt;All people prepare to fix/repair the road/path/way,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">ho sèmi mamai Ama Lamatua!<bt>to receive God's coming!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Tao pamola j'ara hia Ne!&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>Make straight the road/way for Him!&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="3:3" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 40:3</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />J'ara mamuri Yohanis ne, ca ropa dènge dhèu rèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua uru sèra. Mèdha-papake na tao nèti rèu badha onta. Dhari hake na nèti ka'uri badha. Nganga'a na, kabara dènge dhua nasu oni.<bt>This Yohanis' way of living was of the same type as the Lord's spokespersons from long ago. His clothing, was made from camel's hair. His belt, was made from animal skin. His food, was grasshoppers and jungle [=wild] honey.</bt><note reference="3:4" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">2 Dhèu Aae sèra 1:8</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Lod'o èèna, dhèu ae mai neo paraga dènge Yohanis. Rèngu mai nèti kota Yerusalem, nèti kabarai propensi Yudea aa'i-aa'i, dènge nèti rae-rae dhu dètu loko Yarden.<bt>At that time many people came wanting to meet Yohanis. They came from the city of Yerusalem, from among all the inhabitants of Yudea province, and from villages which were close to the Yarden river.</bt><v n="6" />Ra bhoka d'ara ra, aa mangaku sasala-sasigo aa'i-aa'i, èle ka Yohanis sarani si ètu d'ara loko Yarden.<bt>They opened their insides and confessed all their wrongs (doublet), and then Yohanis *baptised [method neutral term] them in the Yarden river.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Lod'o èèna, dhèu ae nèti partei agama Parisi dènge dhèu partei agama Saduki, lasi asa era èèna kahèi, manèngi Yohanis sarani si. Te ngaa ropa Yohanis ladhe nèdhi si, hèia na jèke si, peka na, &lt;&lt;Heeh! Miu se cakaraa mege dhu kapod'e-kabèli. Bèli-camèd'a Ama Lamatua huku mi, lula tatao miu dhu bhelu-katub'a sèra. Mage mi pangee na, miu bisa rai nèti hahuku Na.<bt>At that time, people from the Parisi religious party and the Saduki religious party also came to that place, asking Yohanis to baptise them. But when Yohanis saw them, then he scolded them, saying, &lt;&lt;Heeh! [interjections ending in /h/ carry negative or critical value] You-p here are like snakes who are habitual twisters-turners (=deceivers)! God will later judge/ punish you, because of your evil (doublet) deeds/behaviour. Don't think that you can run away/flee from His judgement/punishment.</bt><note reference="3:7" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 12:34, 23:33</note><v n="8" />De be'a risi miu lèpa sa Ama Lamatua, aa tèke eele sasala miu sèra. Èle na, tao j'ara-j'ara dhu be'a, sèmi aj'u dhu hua be'a.<bt>So (consequently), it's better that you return to God, and leave behind all your wrongs. After that, do (various) good things, like trees which produce good fruit.</bt><v n="9" />Mage mi pangee na, miu se abhu mamuri, lula j'aj'i ana-èpu Abraham. Mi sanèd'e lii ja'a, ee! Te Ama Lamatua bisa tao hadhu se j'aj'i ana-èpu Abraham kahèi.<bt>Don't think you are safe because you are Abraham's descendants. Remember/think about what I'm saying here, ee! Cuz (elaboration) God can make these rocks become Abraham's descendants too. [EXEG: NLT ‘we're safe’; TRT ‘we escape punishment’ (vs.7)]</bt><note reference="3:9" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yohanis 8:33</note><v n="10" />Baku pamud'e! Te abhu dhu kèpe mema kataka, pa'èra patue aa'i-aa'i aj'u dhu hua be'a boe, sèna ka core asa d'ara ai.<bt>Watch out! Cuz (elaboration) there is (someone) who holds the axe in preparation for wanting to cut down all the trees whose fruit is not good, and then throw them away into the fire.</bt><note reference="3:10" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 7:19</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Limuri ne, ja'a sarani miu pake èi, ho j'aj'i mi tadha dhu peka na, miu se tèke eele sasala-sasala miu. Te ngaa pe abhu ca Dhèu dhu kapai risi nèti ja'a, bèli-camèd'a mai. Masi ka j'aj'i ana pua-paleha Na, ja'a nia boe sa hèi. Èèna na, Nèngu papènu d'ara miu dènge Roh Ama Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci. Nèngu tao miu j'aj'i mola-mèci kahèi, sama sèmi dhèu pake ai ho bhubhu maruru.<bt>Now, I am baptising you-pl using water, to be a sign saying you have left behind your wrongs (doublet). But later there will be a Person who is more amazing/greater than me who will come. Even just to be his *servant (person who gets bossed around all the time), I am not appropriate/worthy. Later He will fill your insides with God2's Holy Spirit. He will also make you clean/holy (doublet), like a person uses fire to burn off rubbish. [EXEG: TRT, TN] [NOTE to daughter translations: phrase as in Mark 1:8.]</bt><note reference="3:11" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Madhutu sasuri lii Yunani asli, dhu suri, peka na, &lt;&lt;baptis dènge Roh Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci, aa ai.&gt;&gt; &lt;&lt;Baptis dènge Roh Na,&gt;&gt; sasoa na, &lt;&lt;papènu d'ara miu dènge Roh Ama Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci.&gt;&gt; &lt;&lt;Baptis ... dènge ai,&gt;&gt; sasoa na, &lt;&lt;Nèngu tao miu j'aj'i mola-mèci kahèi, sama sèmi dhèu pake ai ho bhubhu maruru.&gt;&gt;<bt>According to the original Yunani words, they write, saying, “baptis with God2's Holy Spirit, and fire.” “Baptis with His Spirit” has the meaning of, “fill your insides with God's Holy Spirit.” “Baptis... with fire” has the meaning of, “make you become clean/pure/holy like a person who uses fire to burn off rubbish.”</bt></note><v n="12" />Te Nèngu dhu nèd'u kokotai dènge laludhu ètu d'ara, ho neo tatai eele èto na. Èle èèna, Na bhori laludhu asa d'ara soka. Te ngaa èto sèra, Na dutu asa d'ara ai dhu heo robhe-robhe dhu madhe boe.&gt;&gt;<bt>Cuz (elaboration) He is holding a winnowing basket that is filled with rice, in.order.to winnow throw away the husks. Then He puts that rice into a (large) rice.storage.basket. But those husks, he throws them away into the fire which burns flaming without ever ending.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dutu = po'a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">dutu = po'a</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yohanis sarani Lamatua Yesus<bt>Yohanis *baptises the Lord Yesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 1:9-11; Lukas 3:21-22)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Lod'o èèna, Yesus puru mai nèti Galilea, la'e asa loko Yarden. Na mai sèna ka manèngi Yohanis sarani Ne.<bt>At that time Yesus came down from Galilea going to the Yarden river. He came to ask Yohanis to *baptise Him.</bt><v n="14" />Te ngaa Yohanis no'o boe. Na pab'ala peka na, &lt;&lt;Tasamia ka ja'a sarani Èu? Sale ne, sina ma? Hud'i Èu ku dhu sarani ja'a. Te èèna ka dhu ja'a parluu!&gt;&gt;<bt>But Yohanis did not want [to]. He protested saying, &lt;&lt;How can it be that I baptise You-sg? Isn't this wrong, [tag question]? It must be You who baptises me. Cuz (elaboration) that's what I need!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Te ngaa Yesus dhaa, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Pangee ia ka. Te ngaa doe ne'e, hud'i laa èu di dhu sarani Ja'a. Dènge j'ara sèmi ne'e, èdhi tao madhutu dad'èi Ama Lamatua.&gt;&gt;<bt>But Yesus spoke to him, saying, &lt;&lt;Don't worry about it. But for now, let it be that you are the one who baptises Me. In that way, we-inc follow/obey/do according to God's will.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Hud'i la j'ara ne j'aj'i, sèna"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">Hud'i la j'ara ne j'aj'i, sèna ka pamèci dènge dadèi Ama Lamatua. [TB]</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ropa tadèngi nare, ka Yohanis b'ala, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Sad'i aku Èu&gt;&gt; Hèia Yohanis sarani Yesus.<bt>When he heard that, then Yohanis responded, saying, &lt;&lt;Whatever (=mildly reluctant agreement) You want (idiomatic phrasing).&gt;&gt; Then Yohanis baptised Yesus.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Sad'i aku Èu = terserah"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">Sad'i aku Èu = terserah</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Ropa sarani èle, ka Yesus kalua nèti d'ara loko. Cag'ag'a laa, liru bhoke eele. Hèia ladhe nèdhi Roh Ama Lamatua puru mai, nuka sèmi koro j'aha dhu mai tèka mi Nèngu.<bt>After baptising [him], then Yesus came out from the river. Suddenly/unexpectedly, the sky was opened up. Then H/he (vague as to who, but grammatically tracks to Jesus) saw God's Spirit descend, like a dove/pidgin came alighting on Him. [NOTE to daughter translations: slightly diff than Mrk. Here it alights (NRSV, NLT). CEV and TB both undertranslated here.]</bt><v n="17" />Hèia ra tadèngi lii Ama Lamatua nèti dedha-liru, peka na,<bt>Then they could hear God's voice from the sky (doublet), saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Nèngu ne, Ana pasue Ja'a.<bt>&lt;&lt;He here, [is] My beloved Child.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Nèngu pakarej'e taruu d'ara Ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>He continues to please My insides.&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="3:17" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 22:2, Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 2:7, Yesaya 42:1, Mateos 12:18, 17:5, Markus 1:11, Lukas 9:35</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu aae nidhu dadugu-rariu Lamatua Yesus<bt>The king of evil.spirits' (*Satan) tempts/seduces/bothers (doublet) the Lord Yesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Lukas 4:1-13; Markus 1:12-13)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="4" />
      <v n="1" />Èle ka, Roh Ama Lamatua nèti Yesus asa d'ara mamoo, sèna ka dhèu aae nidhu sèku Ne.<bt>After that, God's Spirit took Yesus to a lonely place, and/so the king of the evil spirits tested Him (his mettle/character).</bt><note reference="4:1" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Ibrani 2:18, 4:15</note><v n="2" />Ètu era ne'e, Yesus na'a-ninu boe èpa nguru lod'o mèu-mèda. Hèia Na manganga titu kèna.<bt>At that place, Yesus did not eat-drink (fixed doublet) for 40 days nighttime-daytime [normal phrasing; keep in mind that the Muslims fasting month is only during daylight hours and they eat more during that month than in any other month.] So He became very hungry.</bt><v n="3" />Ropa Na manganga sèmi èèna, hèia dhèu aae nidhu mai sèku Ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Èu ne tare'a-re'a Ana Ama Lamatua, do? Ladhe tare'a, na, paredha hadhu se, ho j'aj'i nganga'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>While He was hungry like that, the king of the evil spirits came to test his mettle/character, saying, &lt;&lt;You really are the Child of God, right? If that's true, na, command these rocks, to become food.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Te ngaa Yesus dhaa, na, &lt;&lt;Dhu suri ètu d'ara Sasuri Mola-Mèci Ama Lamatua, peka na:<bt>But Yesus replied, saying, &lt;&lt;It is written in God's Holy Writings (= *Scriptures) saying:</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;Dhèu rai-haha mamuri mesa boe nèti nganga'a di.<bt>&lt;Humans don't live just from food alone.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Te ngaa rèngu hud'i nanene ku Lii Holo-Nori Ama Lamatua,<bt>But they must also listen to/obey God's Words (doublet),</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">aa tao madhutu dad'èi Na kahèi.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>and do/act according to His will.&gt;&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="4:4" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 8:3</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Ka dhèu aae nidhu nèti Yesus asa kota Yerusalem, kota Lamatua dhu mola-mèci èèna. Èle ka, na nèti Yesus asa era dhu dedha risi ètu Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i.<bt>Next that king of evil.spirits brought Yesus to Yerusalem city, that clean/holy city of the God2's. Then2 he took Yesus up on a very high/highest place on the Central/Main Worship House {*Temple}.</bt><v n="6" />Hèia nidhu ne, peka, &lt;&lt;Ladhe Èu ne tare'a-re'a Ana Ama Lamatua, Èu ridhu sèku asa haha nèi. Te dhu suri tèke ètu d'ara Sasuri Mola-Mèci Ama Lamatua, na,<bt>Then that evil.spirit said, &lt;&lt;If You are really God's Child, then You try and jump down to the bottom (yonder). Cuz (elaboration) it is written in God's Scriptures, saying,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pasoka = malompat ; pasoa ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">pasoka = malompat ; pasoa = malompat ; ridhu = terjun</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;Pe Ama Lamatua pua ana pajuu nèti sorga,<bt>&lt;Later God will order His underling/s from heaven,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">sèna ka j'aga Èu.&gt;<bt>to protect/guard You.&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Aa ètu d'ara Sasuri Mola-Mèci Ama Lamatua, dhu suri kahèi,<bt>In God's Holy Scriptures it is also written, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;Pe ra kanata ai ra, ho sibhe Èu,<bt>&lt;Later they will catch You with their hand/s, [NOTE to daughter translations: the TB completely missed s.t. in the Gk, all the commentaries, and most English translations here. There are actually two different OT quotes here, not one as in TB, which we've made explicit in the KM with an intervening quote margin. So I think the punctuation convention of starting the second quote after the quote margin with a capital is correct.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sibhe = tangkap dgn talapak tangan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">sibhe = tangkap dgn talapak tangan sst yg jato dari atas</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">sèna ka ngi'u Èu pèd'a boe, aa haga Èu goi lèke boe hadhu sa hèi.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>so that Your body is not hurt, and Your feet does not touch connecting to the stones either.&gt;&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="4:6" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 91:11-12</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Te ngaa Yesus b'ala, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Abhu kahèi dhu suri tèke ètu d'ara Sasuri Mola-Mèci Ama Lamatua, dhu peka na,<bt>But Yesus replied, saying, &lt;&lt;It is also written in God's Holy Scriptures, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;Ama Lamatua èèna, Lamatua èu.<bt>&lt;That God [= known referent], is your-s Lord/Master/Owner.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">De èu baku pua Ne pake koasa Na, sèna ka pad'elo bukti, peka na,<bt>So (consequently) you should not order Him to use His power to show evidence, that,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Nèngu èèna, tare'a-re'a Ama Lamatua.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>He really is God/He is really God.&gt;&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="4:7" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 6:16</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Èle èèna ka, dhèu aae nidhu ne nèti hari Yesus asa kolo ledhe dhu dedha aae. Hèia na pad'elo aa'i saraga dènge babe'a negara aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha ne.<bt>After that, the king of evil.spirits took Yesus on to the peak of a very tall mountain. Then he showed him all beauty/glory and goodness of all the nations/countries in the world.</bt><v n="9" />Ropa na pad'elo nare, hèia dhèu aae nidhu ne peka, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Sad'i Èu patitu kètu urutuu, sèna ka pahaha iisi mi ja'a, pe ja'a hia aa'i se'e se mi Èu.&gt;&gt;<bt>After showing that, then the king of evil.spirits spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;As long as You-s kneel to worship me, I will give all of these to You-sg.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Te ngaa Yesus jèke ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;He, nidhu! Pakaj'èu nèti era ne'e ne! Te Sasuri Mola-Mèci Ama Lamatua, suri na,<bt>But Yesus scolded him, saying, &lt;&lt;He, evil.spirit! Get.away from this place here! Cuz (elaboration) God's Holy Writings write that,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;Èu hud'i pahaha iisi mi Ama Lamatua,<bt>&lt;You must worship God,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">aa èu ne hud'i sab'a ku dhoka hia Nèngu di.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>and you must work only for Him alone.&gt;&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="4:10" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 6:13</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Ropa dhèu aae nidhu tadèngi lii ne, hèia na tèke eele Yesus. Te ngaa ana pajuu Ama Lamatua nèti sorga mai uri Ne.<bt>When the king of evil.spirits heard that, he left Yesus. But God's *angels (underlings) from heaven came and took care of Him.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus mulai aj'a-nori dhèu ètu Galilea<bt>The Lord Yesus begins to teach (doublet) at Galilea</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 1:14-15; Lukas 4:14-15)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Tèu èèna, dhèu aae Herodes pamaso Yohanis tuka sarani asa d'ara èmu bèdho. Ropa Yesus tadèngi, hèia Na lèpa asa Galilea.<bt>At that time2, king Herodes put Yohanis the habitual baptizer into jail. When Yesus heard that, then He returned to Galilea.</bt><note reference="4:12" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 14:3, Markus 6:17, Lukas 3:19-20</note><v n="13" />La'e asa rae Na Nasaret, èle ka la'e taruu pea ètu rae Kapernaum. Rae èèna ètu sebhe dano Galilea, ètu rai Sebulon dènge Naftali.<bt>He went to His village of Nasaret, and.then He continued on to go stay in Kapernaum village. That village is at Galilea lake's edge in the land/country of Sebulon and Naftali.</bt><note reference="4:13" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yohanis 2:12</note><v n="14" />Dènge j'ara ne, Na tao madhutu ngaa dhu dhèu nèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua, ngara na Yesaya, suri tèke, peka na,<bt>In that way, He did according to what God's spokesperson named Yesaya had written in.advance, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="15" />&lt;&lt;Rai Sebulon dènge rai Naftali<bt>&lt;&lt;Sebulon's land, and Naftali's land</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">dhu padètu dènge dano Galilea ètu sebhe haa loko Yarden.<bt>which are close to Galilea lake, on Yarden river's west side. [EXEG: see TH for discussion of why it is west here, and not east. TN rides the fence on this issue. If you take their first interpretation of Isaiah, it's on the west.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Dhèu Yahudi boe pea ètu era sèra kahèi.<bt>People who are not Yahudi people are also living there.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="16" />Rèngu dhu mamuri ètu d'ara maroga,<bt>They are living in darkness,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">te ngaa limuri ne, rèdhi le saraa.<bt>but now they have seen Light.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Aa saraa ne heo le<bt>And the light has shone</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">palème mi dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu tadhe mèka Ama Lamatua.&gt;&gt;<bt>around to all people who do not yet know God.</bt><note reference="4:15-16" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 9:1-2</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Karèi nèti lod'o èèna, Yesus mulai aj'a-nori dhèu, peka na, &lt;&lt;Miu hud'i soro kabodho aa tèke eele sasala-sasigo miu, ho mamuri ka dènge mola-mèci! Te limuri ne dhèu aa'i-aa'i bisa le j'aj'i dhèu unu Ama Lamatua.&gt;&gt;<bt>Starting from that time/day, Yesus began to teach (doublet) people, saying, &lt;&lt;You-p must turn your backs (=reject) and leave behind your wrongs (doublet), to live clean/holy (doublet) [imperative]! Cuz (elaboration) now all people can become God's person/people.&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="4:17" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 3:2</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus paroa nare dhèu sab'a dhasi dhèu èpa ho madhutu Ne<bt>The Lord Yesus summons four fishermen to follow Him</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 1:16-20; Lukas 5:1-11)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Ca tèka, Yesus kako re sebhe dano Galilea. Na paraga dènge dhèu dua dhu pa'a'ari. Èci ngara na Simon, dhu tema paroa ne, Petrus. Aa ari na, Anderias. Dua ra dhu pèku i'a ètu dano Galilea, lula dua ra dhèu sab'a dhasi.<bt>One time, Yesus was walking along the edge of Galilea lake. He met/ encountered two people [who were] elder-younger siblings. One was named Simon, often/usually called, Petrus. And his younger.sibling was named Anderias. They were cast-netting fish in lake Galilea, because the two of them were fishermen.</bt><v n="19" />Hèia Yesus paroa si, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Mai ku madhutu Ja'a! Miu biasa tenge i'a, te ngaa limuri ne Ja'a neo aj'a miu ho j'aj'i tuka tenge dhèu.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus summoned them, saying, &lt;&lt;Come and follow Me [imperative]! You usually look for fish, but now I am going to teach you-p to become people who habitually look for people.&gt;&gt; [NOTE to daughter translations: avoid wording that makes Jesus training them to be sorcerers. Make them more like recruiters to a political party. Careful that equiv of /jiwa/ isn't only in relation to dead people.]</bt><v n="20" />Ropa ra tadèngi rare, hèia dua ra tèke eele dènge ka pèku ra, lasi madhutu Yesus.<bt>When they heard that, then they two left behind their castnet, and went following Yesus.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Èle ka, Yesus kako hari ciki, hèia ladhe nèdhi ana Sabadeus, dhèu dua. A'a, ngara na Yakobis, aa ari na, Yohanis. Dua ra dhu lalau paie pèku ètu dedha koha sama-sama dènge ama ra. Hèia Yesus paroa dua ra, sèna ka madhutu Ne.<bt>After that, Yesus walked on a bit more, then He saw two of Sabadius' children. The elder.sibling's name was Yakobis, and his younger.sibling's name was Yohanis. They two were arranging/ readying their dropnet/dragnet on a boat together with their father. Then Yesus summoned them two to follow Him.</bt><v n="22" />Ropa ra tadèngi rare, hèia ra tèke eele ama dènge koha ra, lasi madhutu Ne.<bt>When they heard that, then they left behind their father and their boat, going and following Him.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus aj'a-nori dhèu, aa puri-pa'èle dhèu pèd'a<bt>The Lord Yesus teaches (doublet) people, and heals (doublet) sick people</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Lukas 6:17-19)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Èle ka, Yesus si kako palème propensi Galilea, ho Na aj'a-nori dhèu ètu d'ara èmu sabaj'a dhèu Yahudi. Na aj'a Lii Lolo Be'a Ama Lamatua, aa Na peka j'ara-j'ara tasamia, sèna ka dhèu bisa madhutu paredha Ama Lamatua. Aa Na puri-pa'èle kahèi dhèu nèti rupa-rupa papèd'a-tarègu.<bt>After that, Yesus (coll.) walked all around Galilea province, in.order.for Him to teach (doublet) people in the Yahudi people's worship houses. He taught God's Good News, and He told/explained how people can follow/ obey God's commands. And He also healed (doublet) people from their different kinds of sicknesses.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="papèda-tarègu = sakit-penyakit"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">papèda-tarègu = sakit-penyakit</Message></Annotation><note reference="4:23" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 9:35, Markus 1:39</note><v n="24" />Nèbhu boe ka, tatao Yesus ne dhèu lolo palème toke d'ai propensi Siria aa'i-aa'i. Hèia dhèu rèti dhèu ra dhu lèke rupa-rupa papèd'a asa Yesus. Dhèu se rèti kahèi dhèu dhu nidhu tao, dhu huj'u kahib'i, dènge dhu karuku. Ka Na puri-pa'èle aa'i si.<bt>Not long, then news about those deeds of Yesus, spread all around until reaching the whole of Siria province. Then people brought their people suffering from various kinds of sicknesses to Yesus. They also brought people who were afflicted/ affected with evil.spirit/s, who were crazy goat (=epileptic), and those who were lame. And He healed (doublet) all of them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="huj'u kahib'i = gila kambing"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">huj'u kahib'i = gila kambing</Message></Annotation><v n="25" />Lod'o èèna, dhèu ae-ae mai madhutu Ne. Dhèu se mai nèti propensi Galilea, aa nèti rai Canguru Kota, dhu ra peka na, <span class="Italic">Dekapolis.</span> Dhèu cahag'e mai nèti kota Yerusalem, nèti propensi Yudea, aa nèti cabèka dhimu loko Yarden.<bt>At that time very many people came following Him. These poeple came from Galilea province, and from the area of Ten Cities, which they call, saying, <span class="Italic">Dekapolis.</span> Some came from Yerusalem city, from Yudea province, and from the east side of the Yarden river.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus aj'a-nori dhèu ètu ledhe<bt>The Lord Yesus teaches (doublet) people on a/the mountain</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="5" />
      <v n="1" />Ropa Yesus ladhe nèdhi dhèu ae-ae mai madhutu Ne, hèia Na ca'e la'e asa ledhe iiki cue, ka Na madhèdi ètu èèna. Ana-ana madhutu dhu Na hag'e nare sèra, mai padètu sèna ka nanene Ne.<bt>When Yesus saw many-many people coming following Him, then He went up a small mountain, and He sat there. Those followers (*disciples) whom He had chosen/set aside (out of a group), came close to hear Him.</bt><v n="2" />Hèia Na aj'a-nori si, peka na,<bt>Then He taught (doublet) them, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu dhu tare'a-re'a abhu a'oto [\s2]<bt>People who really are fortunate/get benefit [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Lukas 6:20-23)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />&lt;&lt;Dhèu kasia, rèngu oto,<bt>&lt;&lt;Poor/unfortunate people, they are the ones who are fortunate, [EXEG: See CEG word study on Gk /makarios/ as “how fortunate you are” or “what a good state of affairs you're in in God's eyes”; “happy” may be a secondary effect, but it is not really part of the primary meaning. Compare discussion in parallel passage in Luke 6.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">lula Ama Lamatua mesa Na, ka Dhèu Aae rèngu dhu hua iia.<bt>because God Himself is their great/good King.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="4" />Dhèu dhu ètu d'ara sasusa, rèngu oto,<bt>People who are sad/in strife/difficulty, they are the ones who are fortunate,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="roe bhilu = hati ancor (duka)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">roe bhilu = hati ancor (duka) [bhilu doesn't stand alone, but together tends more towards physical than</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">lula Ama Lamatua mesa Na ka dhu pamaho'o d'ara si.<bt>because God Himself is the one who comforts their insides.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pamaho'o = comfort, hibur"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">pamaho'o = comfort, hibur</Message></Annotation><note reference="5:4" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 61:2</note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="5" />Dhèu haha oto,<bt>Low (humble, meek) people are the ones who are fortunate,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">lula rèngu ka dhu bèli-camèd'a sèmi rare mèngi-nale aa'i-aa'i dhu Ama Lamatua moa tèke.<bt>because they are the ones who will receive all the blessings (doublet) which God has promised.</bt><note reference="5:5" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 37:11</note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="6" />Dhèu dhu d'ara kateme dènge Ama Lamatua, rèngu oto,<bt>People whose are whole-hearted for God, they are the ones who are fortunate,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">lula èèna na, Nèngu ka dhu hia si ngaa dhu ra neo.<bt>because later He is the one who (will) give them what they are desiring.</bt><note reference="5:6" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 55:1-2</note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="7" />Dhèu dhu pad'elo rasa kasia mi dhèu leo, rèngu oto,<bt>People who show mercy/pity to other people, they are the ones who are fortunate,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">lula èèna na, Ama Lamatua kasia rèngu kahèi.<bt>because later God will be merciful to them as well.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="8" />Dhèu dhu d'ara mola-mèci, rèngu oto,<bt>People whose insides are clean-pure/holy (doublet), they are the ones who are fortunate,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">lula èèna na, rèngu unu ra ladhe rèdhi Ama Lamatua.<bt>because later they themselves will see God.</bt><note reference="5:8" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 24:3-4</note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="9" />Dhèu dhu tema padame dhèu, rèngu oto,<bt>People who often restore relationships between people, they are the ones who are fortunate,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">lula èèna na Ama Lamatua ka dhu peka na, &lt;Rèngu se'e ka, ana Ja'a.&gt;<bt>because later God is the one who says, &lt;These here are My children.&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="10" />Dhèu dhu pasae j'aj'èra, lula ra madhutu Ama Lamatua, rèngu oto,<bt>People who shoulder.carry suffering because they follow God, they are the ones who are fortunate,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">lula Lamatua mesa Na ka, Dhèu Aae rèngu dhu hua iia.<bt>because God2 Himself is their great/good King.</bt><note reference="5:10" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">1 Petrus 3:14</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Ladhe dhèu leo paj'èra miu, lula miu madhutu Ja'a, miu oto kahèi. Ladhe dhèu padhai kaked'u miu, aa lole pa'ele iie kolongara miu, miu oto kahèi.<bt>If/when other people cause you-pl suffering because you follow Me, you are also fortunate. If/when people speak untruths about you, and speak ruining your good name/reputation, you are also fortunate.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kaked'u = omong sonde batul"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">kaked'u = omong sonde batul</Message></Annotation><note reference="5:11" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">1 Petrus 4:14</note><v n="12" />Masi ka sèmi èèna, te ngaa miu hud'i pakasee iisi aa pakarej'e d'ara, lula Ama Lamatua dhu sadia nare le pala dhu ae hia miu ètu sorga. Te ngaa sanèd'e! Mesa boe miu di dhu dui j'aj'èra sèmi èèna, te lod'o uru sèra dhèu dhu paj'èra le kahèi dhèu rèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua.&gt;&gt;<bt>Even though it is like that, nevertheless you must refresh yourselves and make your insides happy, because God is already prepared to give you many things in heaven. But remember! You are not the only ones to experience suffering like that, cuz (elaboration) long ago people were also causing suffering to God's spokespeople.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pakasee iisi = sukacita, rasa segar"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">pakasee iisi = sukacita, rasa segar</Message></Annotation><note reference="5:12" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">2 Sejara nèti Isra'el dènge Yahuda 36:16, Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 7:52</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu dhu madhutu Lamatua Yesus, nuka sèmi masi dènge saraa [\s2]<bt>People who follow the Lord Yesus are like salt and light [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 9:50; Lukas 14:34-35)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />&lt;&lt;Ladhe èdhi d'èi sèna ka nganga'a j'aj'i be'a, na, èdhi tao ku masi. Sèmi èèna kahèi dènge dhèu dhu mamuri ètu rai-haha ne, rèngu parluu miu. Te ngaa ladhe masi sèro heka, gaguna na, ngaa? Dhoka core eele di ètu j'ara, ho dhèu j'èli ne.<bt>&lt;&lt;If we-inc want to make food good/tasty, then we need to put salt first. It's like that also with people who live in this world, they need you-p. But, if that salt is no longer potent, na, what is it's use? Just throw it out on the road/path for people to step on.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hèu gèmu = rasa harum (bau)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">hèu gèmu = rasa harum (bau)</Message></Annotation><note reference="5:13" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Markus 9:50, Lukas 14:34-35</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Miu hud'i mamuri ku sèmi labhu kahèi, sèna ka dhèu ae bisa ladhe rèdhi miu dènge be'a. Miu hud'i heo lo'a-lo'a ku, nuka sèmi kota ètu kolo ledhe, dhu dhèu aa'i-aa'i ladhe rèdhi ne.<bt>You-p also must live like a lamp, so that many people can see you well. You must shine clearly/brightly, the same as a city which is on top of a mountain, which all people can see.</bt><note reference="5:14" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yohanis 8:12, 9:5</note><v n="15" />Ladhe dhèu paheo labhu iiki, ra saguru boe ne dènge èru rai, te ngaa ra padhèdi labhu ne ètu era dedha, ho pasaraa aa'i d'ara èmu.<bt>If/when people light small lamps, they don't put it inside a clay pot. But they place that lamp in a high place, so it can shine/give light to the entire inside house.</bt><note reference="5:15" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Markus 4:21, Lukas 8:16, 11:33</note><v n="16" />Miu hud'i mamuri ku sèmi èèna. Mamuri miu hud'i saraa ku, sèna ka dhèu leo ladhe rèdhi mamuri miu dhu be'a. Ropa dhèu ladhe rèdhi mamuri miu sèmi èèna, ra ded'e padedha-dedha kolongara Ama Lamatua, peka na, &lt;Ira ii! Ama miu ètu sorga, kapai titu kèna, nga!&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>You-p also must live like that. Your lives must shine, so that other people can see your good lives. When they see your lives like that, they will lift/exalt/praise God's name/reputation, saying, &lt;Ira ii! [+positive amazement] That Father of yours in heaven, [is] really amazing, nga! [=particle conveying positive speaker attitude]&gt;&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="5:16" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">1 Petrus 2:12</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Mamai Lamatua Yesus, sèna ka pamèci atora Ama Lamatua [\s2]<bt>The coming of the Lord Yesus is to make complete God's regulations/law [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />&lt;&lt;Mage miu pangee na, mamai Ja'a asa rai-haha ne, sèna ka tao eele atora Ama Lamatua dhu pangèd'u mi Musa. Aa baku pangee na, Ja'a pusi-pahae boe dènge ngaa dhu uru èèna, dhèu rèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua peka tèke le. Te mamai Ja'a ne, sèna ka pamèci j'ara aa'i-aa'i, nuka sèmi mia dhu ra peka tèke.<bt>&lt;&lt;You-p shouldn't think that, My coming into this world, was in.order to get rid of God's regulations which He gave to Musa. And don't think I'm not concerned with (doublet) what long ago God's spokesperson have spoken in.advance. Cuz (elaboration) My coming here, is to make complete everything like all the things which they spoke about in.advance.</bt><v n="18" />Nèti èèna ka, nanene paie-iie! Liru dènge rai-haha bisa mèka laho aa'i, ladhe aa'i-aa'i j'aj'i mèka madhutu atora Ama Lamatua. Masi ka ca katèd'a èèna ka, bisa boe ele nèti atora se.<bt>Because of that, listen carefully! Sky and earth will not yet be completely destroyed, if everything has not yet happened according to God's regulations. Even just one tiny mark, cannot disappear from these regulations.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="katèda = titik"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">katèda = titik</Message></Annotation><note reference="5:18" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lukas 16:17</note><v n="19" />Nèti dhèu unu Ama Lamatua aa'i-aa'i, ladhe abhu dhu sisu atora Ama Lamatua, lula na pangee, na, &lt;Atora ne, ana iiki-iiki di, de gaguna na aad'o!&gt; Hèia na aj'a sèmi èèna kahèi mi dhèu leo, pe Ama Lamatua ètu sorga, tao ne j'aj'i mi ca dhèu ana iiki. Te ngaa bagi mi dhèu dhu tao madhutu aa'i atora Ama Lamatua, hèia na aj'a-nori dhèu leo sèmi èèna, bèli-camèd'a Ama Lamatua pakab'ua ne.<bt>From among all of God's people, if there are those who violates God's regulation/s, because he thinks, saying, &lt;This regulation here, is small/insignificant and doesn't have any use!&gt; And.then he teaches like that to other people, later God in heaven will make him become a small/unimportant/insignificant person. But, for people who do/act according to all of God's regulations, and.then he teaches (doublet) like that to other people, later God will honour/value him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="masi ka ciki oo'e èèna ka,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">masi ka ciki oo'e èèna ka,</Message></Annotation><v n="20" />Parcaya la Ja'a! Miu hud'i mamuri mola, risi nèti mese agama dènge dhèu partei agama Parisi sèra. Ladhe aad'o, na, miu bisa boe j'aj'i dhèu unu Ama Lamatua.&gt;&gt;<bt>Believe Me! You must live straight/righteous, more than those religion teachers and Farisi religious party people. If not, then you can not become God's person.&gt;&gt; [EXEG: Ex. Summ.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Ladhe miu mamuri mola boe, risi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">Ladhe miu mamuri mola boe, risi nèti mese agama dènge dhèu partei agama Parisi se, na, miu bisa boe j'aj'i dhèu unu Ama Lamatua.&gt;&gt;</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus aj'a-nori dhèu sèna ka baku panasa [\s2]<bt>The Lord Yesus teaches (doublet) people to not be angry at each other [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Lukas 12:57-59)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />&lt;&lt;Miu dhu me'a le atora Musa dhu hia mi bèi-baki èdhi, peka na, &lt;Baku pamadhe dhèu, te dhèu cee dhu pamadhe dhèu nèngu lèke huku.&gt;<bt>&lt;&lt;You-p already know Musa's regulation which he explained beforehand to our-inc ancestors, saying, &lt;Don't kill people, cuz (elaboration) whoever kills people, later s/he will be afflicted with punishment.&gt;</bt><note reference="5:21" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 20:13, Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 5:17</note><v n="22" />Te ngaa Ja'a peka dènge miu sèmi ne'e: baku panasa, te dhèu cee dhu nasa dènge a'ari na, èèna na nèngu lèke huku. Dhèu dhu jèke a'ari na, ka peka na, &lt;Èu bod'o kabao!&gt; pe nèngu la'e dhaa asa dhèu heka-dhèu heka agama. Aa dhèu cee dhu jèke a'ari na, &lt;Goa, ee!&gt; nèngu lèke huku ètu ai naraka.<bt>But I want to explain to you like this: don't get reciprocally mad at each other, cuz (elaboration) whoever gets mad at his sibling/relative, later he will be afflicted with punishment. A person who blurts out angrily at his sibling, saying, &lt;You water-buffalo brain (slow-witted)!&gt; later s/he must account (for his actions) to the religious elders. And whoever blurts out angrily at his sibling, saying, &lt;(You) stupid/idiot, ee!&gt;, s/he will be afflicted with punishment in the fires of hell. [NOTE to daughter translation: Translate the meaning, not the words. Find local metaphors for “stupid fool”.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />De ladhe èu dhu mèti mèdha persembahan hia Ama Lamatua, te ngaa èu sanèd'e, na, abhu a'ari dhu nasa era dènge èu,<bt>So (consequently), if you-sg are bring a offering to God, but you remember that there is a sibling that is still angry with you, [EXEG: not reciprocal anger here, but a brother offended at you (regardless of whether you have issues with him/her or not). All sources.]</bt><v n="24" />tèke eele uuru ku mèdha persembahan sèra. Hèia lamu padame ku dènge a'ari mu, èle, na heka mai hia persembahan se asa Ama Lamatua kèna.<bt>leave that offering first. Then go make reciprocal peace with your sibling first, after that only then come give that offering to God.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Ladhe ca dhèu neo tao lii langu dènge èu, be'a risi lamu lai-lai ho padame dènge ne. Ladhe aad'o, dhèu ne nèti èu asa hakim. Hèia hakim saraka èu sa polisi, ka ra pamaso èu asa d'ara bèdho.<bt>If there is a person who wants to make a litigation/dispute with you-s, it's better you go quickly to make reciprocal peace first. If not, that person will take/bring you to the judge (assimilated loan). Then the judge will hand you over to the police (assimilated loan), and they will put you into jail.</bt><v n="26" />Ja'a pasanèd'e tare'a-re'a mi èu ne! Èèna na èu pea taruu ètu d'ara bèdho, toke b'ae aa'i mèu-mèu kèlu-g'ètu èu sèra.&gt;&gt;<bt>I am really reminding/warning you here! Later you will remain continually in jail until you have completely paid off all of your debts (doublet).&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus aj'a-nori dhèu, sèna ka baku tao j'ara makae [\s2]<bt>The Lord Yesus teaches (doublet) people to not do shameful things (sexually) [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />&lt;&lt;Miu dhu me'a le atora Musa, dhu peka na, &lt;Baku bersina.&gt;<bt>&lt;&lt;You-p already know Musa's regulation which says, &lt;Don't commit.adultery.&gt;</bt><note reference="5:27" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 20:14, Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 5:18</note><v n="28" />Te ngaa Ja'a neo peka na, sèmi ne'e: dhèu dhu ladhe nèdhi dhèu bhèni èci, hèia d'ara na neo j'unu pa'èci dènge ne, na, dhèu mone ne bersina le dènge bhèni ne ètu d'ara na.<bt>But I want to tell like this: a person who looks/stares at a woman, and.then his insides desire to sleep together (euphemism for sex) with her, na, that man has already committed.adultery with that woman in his insides.</bt><v n="29" />Ladhe èu tao sala pake musi madha g'ana èu, na, ed'o eele ne. Te be'a risi èu maso sorga dènge musi madha cabèka di, aa baku ra pèci mu asa d'ara ai naraka dènge musi madha dua-dua.<bt>If you do wrong using your right eye, na, gouge it out throw it away. Cuz (elaboration) it's better you enter heaven with just your one eye, and they don't throw you away into the fires of hell with both your eyeballs.</bt><note reference="5:29" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 18:9, Markus 9:47</note><v n="30" />Aa ladhe èu tao sala dènge kacui-aai g'ana èu, poro eele kacui-aai ne. Te be'a risi èu maso sorga dènge kacui-aai cabèka di, aa baku ra pèci mu asa d'ara ai naraka dènge kacui-aai dhu kateme iisi.&gt;&gt;<bt>And if you do wrong using your right hand, well, cut off throw away that hand. Cuz (elaboration) it's better you enter heaven with just your one hand, and they don't throw you away into the fires of hell with both your hands complete.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="calaa = satu batang"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">calaa = satu batang</Message></Annotation><note reference="5:30" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 18:8, Markus 9:43</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus aj'a-nori dhèu ho baku pa'ia-pa'ela [\s2]<bt>The Lord Yesus teaches (doublet) to not divorce (doublet) [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 19:9; Markus 10:11-12; Lukas 16:18)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />&lt;&lt;Miu dhu me'a le atora Musa, na, &lt;Dhèu dhu pa'ia dènge dhèu èmu-kamali na, nèngu hud'i hia ku sasuri pa'ia mi bhèni èèna.&gt;<bt>&lt;&lt;You-p already know Musa's regulation, saying, &lt;A person who divorces his spouse, na, he must give a divorce letter to that woman.&gt;</bt><note reference="5:31" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 24:1-4, Mateos 19:7, Markus 10:4</note><v n="32" />Te ngaa Ja'a peka sèmi ne'e: ladhe abhu dhèu dhu ia eele dhèu èmu na, te ngaa bhèni ne tao nèdhi boe j'ara makae, hèia bhèni ne leo hari èmu, na, dhèu èmu uuru èèna ka dhu tao nèngu j'aj'i bersina. Aa ladhe abhu dhèu mone dhu leo nare bhèni dhu dhèu èmu na ia eele, na, rèngu dua ra bersina kahèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>But I tell like this: if there is a person who divorces his spouse, whereas that woman has never done shameful things (sexually), then that woman remarries, na, the first husband is the one who causes her (indirectly) to commit adultery. And if there is a man who marrys the/a woman whose spouse has divorced her, na, the two of them have committed adultery as well.&gt;&gt; [DISCOURSE: ellipsed proposition “and she remarries” See Ex. Summ. TN, TRT (unanimous).][EXEG: Gk uses “porneia” and “moicheuw”, so try to reflect that difference as in KM.][NOTE to daughter translations: this is complicated. It only works if you get the connectors right.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="èci èèna ka nèngu peka na"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">èci èèna ka nèngu peka na dhèu èmu na ad'u j'ara makae. Aa ladhe dhèu mone leo nare hari bhèni ne, rèngu dua ra kako sale le èèna.&gt;&gt;</Message></Annotation><note reference="5:32" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 19:9, Markus 10:11-12, Lukas 16:18, 1 Korintus 7:10-11</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus aj'a-nori j'ara soo-subha [\s2]<bt>The Lord Yesus teaches (doublet) about making oaths (doublet) [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="33" />&lt;&lt;Miu dhu me'a le atora Musa dhu na hia mi bèi-baki èdhi, peka na, &lt;Ladhe èu pajaji pake lii soo-subha, dhu ale kolongara Ama Lamatua, na, èu dhu pa'èki le dènge soo-subha èèna.&gt;<bt>&lt;&lt;You-p already know Musa's regulation which he told to our-inc ancestors, saying, &lt;If you make a promise using an oath (doublet) mentioning God's name/reputation, na, you are tied/bound to that oath.&gt;</bt><note reference="5:33" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Atora nèti Ama-ama Agama 19:12, Sensus 30:2, Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 23:21</note><v n="34" />Te ngaa Ja'a peka sèmi ne'e: ladhe èu neo pajaji, na, mage mu j'oka subha. Baku subha dènge ngara sorga, lula sorga èèna era pea Ama Lamatua.<bt>But I tell (you) like this: if/when you want to make a promise, na, don't do it by swearing an oath. Don't oath using heaven's name, because heaven, is God's residing place.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="era pea-palu'u = tempat berdiam"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">era pea-palu'u = tempat berdiam</Message></Annotation><note reference="5:34" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yakobis 5:12, Yesaya 66:1, Mateos 23:22</note><v n="35" />Mage subha pake ngara rai-haha, lula rai-haha ne, era bane haga Ama Lamatua. Aa mage subha pake ngara Yerusalem, lula Yerusalem èèna, kota nèti Dhèu Aae Kapai.<bt>[CHECK footrest] Don't oath using the earth's name, because earth is God's footpad. And don't oath using Yerusalem name, because Yerusalem is the Big/Important/Great King's city.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="j'aj'èli = injakan ; era bane"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">j'aj'èli = injakan ; era bane haga = place to prop feet</Message></Annotation><note reference="5:35" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 66:1, Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 48:3</note><v n="36" />Baku subha pake ngara kab'a kètu miu. Te miu dènge boe koasa ho paredha rèu kètu miu, sèna ka ca loa sa j'aj'i mèdhi do j'aj'i pudhi.<bt>Don't oath with/by your-p head/s. Cuz (elaboration) you-p do not have power/authority to command the hari on your head, so even one strand of hair becomes black or becomes white. [Matthew must have listened to Michael Jackson? NOTE to daughter translations: Make sure that /kapala/ here is linked to body, not head of social group (which could be implied by context above).]</bt><v n="37" />De ladhe miu neo pajaji, dhu peka oo, na, peka la &lt;oo&gt; di. Te ngaa ladhe aad'o, na, peka la, &lt;aad'o&gt; di. Ladhe miu peka risi nèti èèna, sèra sa j'aj'aj'i nèti nidhu.&gt;&gt;<bt>So (consequently), if you want to make a promise saying yes, then just tell saying, &lt;yes&gt;. But if not, then say &lt;not&gt;. If you say more than that, its origins are from evil.spirit/s.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="o = affirmative"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">o = affirmative</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus aj'a-nori sèna ka baku b'ala bhabhelu dènge bhabhelu, te ngaa hud'i b'ala dènge j'ara lalau-lalo'o dhu be'a risi hari [\s2]<bt>The Lord Yesus teaches (doublet) to not reciprocate evil with evil, but (one) must reciprocate and serve even better [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Lukas 6:29-30)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="38" />&lt;&lt;Miu dhu me'a le atora Musa, dhu peka na, &lt;Ladhe dhèu cee dhu pa'ele iie musi madha miu, na, pa'ele iie kahèi musi madha na. Aa ladhe abhu dhèu dhu pakabhui eele ngutu èu, na, pakabhui eele ngutu na kahèi.&gt;<bt>&lt;&lt;You-p already know Musa's regulation, saying, &lt;If a person wrecks your eyes, na, wreck his eye as well. And if a person knocks out your tooth/teeth, na, knock out his tooth/teeth also.&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="cèru = dig out ; pakabhui"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">cèru = dig out ; pakabhui eele = knock out, pull out (from a blow) ; if a dentist does it, = bete eele ngutu = cabut gigi</Message></Annotation><note reference="5:38" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 21:24, Atora nèti Ama-ama Agama 24:20, Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 19:21</note><v n="39" />Te ngaa Ja'a peka dènge miu sèmi ne'e: baku b'ala bhabhelu dènge bhabhelu. Ladhe dhèu tèb'e ripi èu cabèka, na hud'i laa, na tèb'e hari ripi dhu leo.<bt>But I tell you like this: don't reciprocate evil with evil. If a person slaps your one side check, na, permit it so he slaps your other cheek as well.</bt><v n="40" />Ladhe dhèu neo tenge lii langu dènge èu, ho neo nare kodho èu, na, hia ne kodho pana èu kahèi.<bt>If a person wants to have a litigation/ argument with you, in.order to take your shirt, na, give away your jacket (hot shirt) as well.</bt><v n="41" />Ladhe sordad'u ca dhèu laka-seti èu ho pasae mèdha na kako d'ai ca kilometer, na, èu pasae mèti kaj'èu na toke dua kilometer.<bt>If an army person forces you to walk carrying his thing/s one kilometre, na, carry take [it] on the distance until two kilometres. [EXEG: Gk lexeme implies compelled by a soldier, as in NLT &amp; CEV.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="CHECK ALL: laka-seti"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">CHECK ALL: laka-seti</Message></Annotation><v n="42" />Ladhe dhèu neo manèngi nare mèdha èu èci, na, hia la. Aa ladhe dhèu neo pija mèdha èu, na, hia la.&gt;&gt;<bt>If a person wants to request something you might have, na, just give it. And if a person wants to borrow something of yours, na, just give it.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pija = pinjam"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">pija = pinjam</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus aj'a-nori, sèna ka sue dhèu dhu tèka d'ara dènge èdhi [\s2]<bt>The Lord Yesus teaches (doublet) to love people who hate us-inc [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Lukas 6:27-28, 32-36)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="43" />&lt;&lt;Miu tadèngi le, dhu peka na, &lt;Sue la a'ari èu, aa nasa la dènge dhèu dhu nasa dènge èu.&gt;<bt>&lt;&lt;You-p have heard (people) say, &lt;Love your sibling, and be angry with people who are angry with you.&gt; [NOTE: no Dhao lexeme for hate, but many similar words, so we have to fish on a context by context basis for the best fit.]</bt><note reference="5:43" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Atora nèti Ama-ama Agama 19:18</note><v n="44" />Te ngaa Ja'a peka sèmi ne'e: èu hud'i sue ku dhèu dhu nasa dènge èu, aa manèngi ho Lamatua hia mèngi-nale mi dhèu dhu paj'èra èu.<bt>But I tell like.this: you must love people who are angry with you, and request so that God2 gives blessing to people who cause suffering to you.</bt><v n="45" />Ladhe èu tao sèmi èèna, èu pad'elo, na, èu ana Ama ètu sorga. Lula Nèngu ka tao madha lod'o hia dhèu dhu be'a, dènge dhèu dhu bhelu. Na papuru èj'i hia dhèu dhu tao madhutu paredha Na, aa mi dhèu dhu lab'a paredha Na kahèi.<bt>If you do like.that, well, you show that, you are Father in heaven's child. Because He made/makes the sun (shine) for good people, and for evil people. He also sends down rain for people who do according to his command/s, and for people who oppose his command/s.</bt><v n="46" />De ladhe èu sue dhoka dhèu dhu sue èu, èu ngee na Ama Lamatua hud'i b'ala hia èu mèngi-nale, do? Aad'o! Te dhèu bhelu kahèi ne'a sue angalai na, dhu sue nèngu.<bt>So (consequently), if you only love people who love you, you think God has to reciprocate with blessing to you, right {do = tag question}? No! Cuz (elaboration) an evil person also loves his friends who love him.</bt><v n="47" />De ladhe èu me'a dhoka hia lii maho'o mi angalai èu, na, kolo-karisi na ngaa? Te dhèu dhu parcaya boe Ama Lamatua, re'a ad'u-ue j'ara sèmi èèna kahèi.<bt>So (consequently), if you only know how to give (kind)greeting to your friend, na, what is that greatness/advantage of that? Cuz (elaboration) people who do not believe God also act (doublet) like that.</bt><v n="48" />De sanèd'e, ee! Ama mu ètu sorga sue dhèu aa'i-aa'i. De èu hud'i tao madhutu ku sèmi èèna kahèi!&gt;&gt;<bt>So remember, ee! Your Father in heaven loves all people. So (consequently) you must also do/act like that!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bhera boe = tidak anak tirikan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">bhera boe = tidak anak tirikan = biga boe</Message></Annotation><note reference="5:48" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Atora nèti Ama-ama Agama 19:2, Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 18:13</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus aj'a, sèna ka soru-bara dhèu-dhèu susa [\s2]<bt>The Lord Yesus teaches to help (doublet) (various) people in difficulty [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="6" />
      <v n="1" />Yesus aj'a taruu, peka na, &lt;&lt;Sanèd'e! Mage mi madhutu atora agama di, sèna ka dhèu pad'iri miu. Te ladhe miu tao sèmi èèna, Ama miu ètu sorga b'ala boe rui-j'aj'èra miu.<bt>Yesus continued to teach saying, &lt;&lt;Remember! Don't just (blindly) follow religion's regulations, in order that people praise you-p. Cuz (elaboration) if you do like that, your Father in heaven will not reciprocate you with any reward (idiom: bones of suffering).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="padiri = puji = koa"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">padiri = puji = koa</Message></Annotation><note reference="6:1" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 23:5</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="2" />Ladhe miu neo soru-bara dhèu kasia, mage lami palolo asa mia-mia. Te ladhe miu se tao sèmi èèna, miu ca ropa dènge dhèu dhu padhai lii leo, tao leo. Dhèu sèmi sèra, d'èi lasi karihu asa d'ara èmu sabaj'a ho dhèu koa si, peka na, &lt;Ira ii! Dhèu ne maj'èni madhutu atora agama, nga!&gt; Ja'a peka mola-mola kèna! Dhèu dhu tema sèmi rare lii koa-kad'iri nèti dhèu, rèngu se abhu le pala ra.<bt>If you-p want to help (doublet) poor/pitiful/unfortunate people, don't go talking about it all over the place. Cuz (elaboration) if you do like.that, you are of the same type as people who say one thing and do another (=hypocrites). People like them like to go strolling out to the worship houses so that people will praise them, saying, &lt;Ira ii! [+positive, impressed] This person is so diligent to follow religious regulations, nga!&gt; [+impressed] I'm speaking straight (=telling the truth)! People who like to receive the praises (doublet) of people, they have already gotten/obtained their reward/compensation.</bt><v n="3" />De ladhe miu neo soru-bara dhèu dhu dènge boe ngaa-ngaa, mage mi palolo kahèi!<bt>So (consequently), if you-p want to help (doublet) people who have nothing (=poor), don't go around telling anyone!</bt><v n="4" />Dènge sèmi èèna, dhèu ètu rai-haha ne re'a boe. Te ngaa Ama miu ètu sorga dhu ne'a ngaa dhu miu tao pahuni. Pe Nèngu ka dhu b'ala hia miu berkat ae-ae.&gt;&gt;<bt>By doing like that, people in this world won't know. But your Father in heaven knows what you are doing in secret there. Later He will reciprocate you with many-many blessings2 (assimilated loan).&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus aj'a dhèu sabaj'a [\s2]<bt>The Lord Yesus teaches people to pray [\s2] [NOTE to daughter translations: because local languages often don't distinguish directionality between learning/teaching, make sure “people” is object to avoid reading of “Jesus learns to pray” :-) ]</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Lukas 11:2-4)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />&lt;&lt;Lod'o miu sabaj'a, miu baku tao nuka sèmi dhèu dhu padhai lii leo, tao leo. Dhèu se d'èi lasi asa j'ara dhu dhèu ae-ae, aa titu ètu d'ara èmu manèngi-mangaj'i ho dhèu koa-kad'iri si, peka na, &lt;Dhèu se, dhèu mola-mèci!&gt; Te ngaa nanene pabe'a-be'a! Dènge rèngu abhu koa sèmi èèna, rèngu sèmi rare le pala ra.<bt>&lt;&lt;When you-p pray, don't make yourself like the people who say one thing and do another. These people like to go out on the street/s where there are many people, and stand in the worship house/s, so that people praise (doublet) them, saying, &lt;These people are clean/holy (doublet) people!&gt; But listen carefully! By obtaining praise like that, they have already received their reward/compensation.</bt><note reference="6:5" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lukas 18:10-14</note><v n="6" />Te ngaa miu baku sèmi èèna. Ladhe miu manèngi-mangaj'i, lami asa d'ara kama ho bèdho babèdho na. Èle èèna, heka mi sabaj'a mau-mau hia Ama mi ètu sorga. Masi ka dhèu leo rèdhi boe, te ngaa Ama miu ladhe nèdhi. Bèli-camèd'a Na b'ala hia miu berkat ae-ae.<bt>But you-p should not do/be like.that. If/when you pray, go into a/the room to shut the door. And only then pray quietly to your Father. Even if other people do not see, nevertheless your Father sees. Later He will reciprocate giving to you many-many blessings.</bt></p>
    <fig path="HK-LB\LB00271C.tif" rtfFormat="width:5.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left">Dhèu Yahudi sabaj'a<bt>A Yahudi person prays</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Ladhe miu sabaj'a, baku padhai lii dhu dènge boe kolo-kapua. Te dhèu dhu tadhe boe Ama Lamatua sabaj'a sèmi èèna ka. Rèngu pangee, na, Ama Lamatua d'èi nanene lii manèngi ra dhu madhera lola-lola èèna.<bt>If/when you-p pray, don't speak words that have no purpose/no basis (doublet). Cuz (elaboration) people who do not know God pray like.that. They think that God likes to hear those prayers/requests of theirs which are really long (=roughly equivalent to 'mile long prayers')</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="madhera lola-lola = \lf Max"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">madhera lola-lola = \lf Max</Message></Annotation><v n="8" />Mage mi madhutu j'ara rèngu sèra! Te masi ka miu dhae manèngi mèka ngaa-ngaa nèti Ama mi ètu sorga, te ngaa Nèngu dhu ne'a mema le, ngaa dhu miu parluu.<bt>Don't act doing the same as them! Cuz (elaboration) even if/though you still have not yet requested anything from your Father in heaven, nevertheless He already knows in.advance what you need.</bt><v n="9" />De ladhe sabaj'a, na, madhutu la conto sèmi ne'e:<bt>So (consequently), if/when praying, na, follow an example like.this:</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;Ama ètu sorga! Kolongara Ama dhu mola-mèci.<bt>&lt;Father in heaven! Father's (=your) name/reputation is clean/holy (doublet).</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Hud'i laa dhèu aa'i-aa'i, ded'e padedha-dedha kolongara Ama dhu kapai èèna.<bt>May all people lift up high the name/reputation of Father's which is amazing/great.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="10" />Hud'i laa Ama j'aj'i Dhèu Aae mi dhèu aa'i-aa'i!<bt>May Father become King for all people!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Hud'i laa dhèu aa'i-aa'i, tao madhutu paredha Ama ètu rai-haha ne,<bt>May all people follow/obey Father's commands here on earth,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">nuka sèmi ana pajuu Ama, tao madhutu paredha Ama ètu sorga.<bt>the same as Father's underlings (*angels) follow/obey Father's commands in heaven.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="11" />Ama, hia la ji'i nganga'a-nganginu dhu d'ai bèli-bèli.<bt>Father, give us food (doublet) which is enough everyday. [NOTE to daughter translations: TB and Indonesian liturgical Lord's Prayer misses Gk /epiousios/ “daily”.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="12" />Ji'i manèngi, ho Ama saku eele aa'i sasala-sasigo ji'i,<bt>We request that Father wipe away our various wrongs (doublet),</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">nuka sèmi ji'i kahèi pabhèlu eele sasala dhèu dhu ra tao mi ji'i.<bt>the same as we-exc also completely forget people's wrongs which they do to us.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="13" />Ama, j'aga la ji'i, sèna ka ji'i baku tao bhabhelu.<bt>Father, guard/take.care. of us, so that we don't do evil.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bhabhae = halangi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">bhabhae = halangi</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Aa pakaj'èu la ji'i nèti koasa nidhu,<bt>And save/reescue/distance us, from evil.spirit's power/authority.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">[Te Ama ka Dhèu Aae dhu koasa kapai risi eele.<bt>[Cuz (elaboration) Father is the King who is most powerful.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Aa Ama ka dhu mèd'u paredha, toke d'ai mia-mia la'e.<bt>And Father is the one who holds rule/governing forever (literary).</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Sabaj'a ji'i d'ai sange ne'e ka, Ama. Amin.]&gt;<bt>Our prayer is just up to there, Father. Amin.]&gt;</bt><note reference="6:13b" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Ètu d'ara sasuri lii Yunani dhu uru èèna, ra suri tabha boe kalimat ètu d'ara kurung ne.<bt>The oldest Greek language writings don't write adding this last sentence (loan) in parentheses (loan) here.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Te ngaa sanèd'e, ee! Ladhe miu pabhèlu eele sasala dhu dhèu tao mi miu, èèna na Ama mi ètu sorga saku eele sasala-sasigo miu kahèi.<bt>But remember, ee! If/when you completely forget people's wrongs that they did to you-p, later your Father in heaven will also wipe away your wrongs (doublet).</bt><v n="15" />Te ngaa ladhe miu mo'o boe pabhèlu eele sasala dhu dhèu tao mi miu, bèli-camèd'a Ama mi bhèlu boe sasala miu kahèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>But if you don't want to completely forget people's wrongs against you, later your Father also will not forget your wrongs either.&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="6:14-15" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Markus 11:25-26</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus aj'a-nori j'ara-j'ara puasa [\s2]<bt>The Lord Yesus teaches (doublet) about fasting [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />&lt;&lt;Ladhe miu manèngi-mangaj'i aa puasa, mage mi tao rèhu susa, nuka sèmi dhèu dhu padhai lii leo, tao leo. Te ra ad'u-ue j'ara èèna, ho dhèu pad'iri si, peka na, &lt;Dhèu se'e se, dhèu mola-mèci!&gt; Te ngaa sanèd'e, ee! Dènge sèmi rare koa-kad'iri sèmi èèna, na, rèngu abhu le pala ra.<bt>&lt;&lt;If you-p pray (doublet) and fast (loan), don't make your face troubled/sad, like the people who say one thing and do another. [NOTE: Q: When do people "not eat"? A: When they are angry at their wives. :-) So Arabic loan used to carry sense of fasting as a religious activity--the whole country is effected by Muslim fasting month.] Cuz (elaboration) they do like that for people to praise2 them, saying, &lt;These people are holy/clean (doublet) people!&gt; But remember, ee! By accepting praise (doublet) like.that, they have already received their reward/compensation.</bt><v n="17" />Te ngaa ladhe miu puasa, lèu pamèu-mèu rèhu mi, aa sageri paie kètu miu!<bt>But if/when you-p fast, wash your faces really clean, and comb your hair well!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lèu1 = cuci muki ; lèu2"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">lèu1 = cuci muki ; lèu2 = tengah laut yg dalam ; sageri = sisir (kk &amp; kb)</Message></Annotation><v n="18" />De ladhe dhèu rèdhi miu, re'a boe na, miu dhu puasa. Te ngaa Ama miu ne'a. Pe Na pala hia miu mèngi-nale ae-ae.&gt;&gt;<bt>So (consequently), when people see you, they will not know that you are fasting. But your Father knows. Later He will reciprocate/reward you with many-many blessings.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus aj'a j'ara-j'ara pakaboko mèdha-panyau ètu sorga [\s2]<bt>The Lord Yesus teaches ways of gathering wealth (doublet) in heaven [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Lukas 12:33-34)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />&lt;&lt;Miu baku sab'a taruu, ho dhodhoka pakaboko mèdha-panyau ae-ae ètu rai-haha ne di. Te hub'u dènge rutu pa'ele iie aa'i si. Aa dhèu mana'u mai pa'ele iie era tatèka mèdha-panyau, aa mana'u rèti si.<bt>&lt;&lt;Don't keep working in.order.to only gather lots of wealth (doublet) here on this earth. Cuz (elaboration) moths/ wood.boring.insects and rust will later destroy/ruin them all. And stealers will also come dismantle the storage place of the wealth (doublet) and steal it away.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hub'u = fufuk, bor kayu ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">hub'u = fufuk, bor kayu ; rutu = karat ; dhèu mana'u = thief</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hub'u "><Message author="Chuck" created="2009-11-25 01:01:15Z" status="Anyone">ana cangèpi = makan pakaian, semua, ekor bentuk ke gunting, bites humans too;</Message></Annotation><note reference="6:19" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yakobis 5:2-3</note><v n="20" />Te ngaa be'a risi miu maj'èni sab'a, sèna ka pakaboko mèdha-panyau ae-ae ètu sorga. Te ètu era nèi, abhu boe hub'u dènge rutu dhu pa'ele iie si, aa abhu boe dhèu mana'u, ho mai mana'u rèti.<bt>But it's better you-p work diligently to gather lots of wealth (doublet) in heaven. Cuz (elaboration) there (yonder), there are no moths and rust to destroy/ruin things, and there are no stealers to come steal it away.</bt><v n="21" />Te ladhe miu tèka mèdha-panyau miu ètu era mia, na, tatu d'ara miu ètu èèna kahèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>Cuz (elaboration) if you-p store your wealth wherever, na, surely your insides are also there.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Lula ètu era mia mèdha-panyau miu,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">Lula ètu era mia mèdha-panyau miu, tatu dara miu ètu èèna kahèi.&gt;&gt;</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus aj'a j'ara-j'ara mamuri ètu d'ara saraa [\s2]<bt>The Lord Yesus teaches ways of living in the light [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Lukas 11:34-36)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />&lt;&lt;Musi madha dhèu, nuka sèmi labhu dhu pasaraa d'ara ra. Ladhe musi madha na mèu, nèngu madhutu j'ara mamuri dhu hua iia, èci èèna ka dènge dhèu dhu kako ètu d'ara saraa.<bt>&lt;&lt;A person's eye, is like a lamp which lights up his insides (=seat of emotions and character). If his eye is clear, s/he follows the good life path, the same as a person who walks in the light. [EXEG: Just a note to alert you all to an emerging exegesis that we're not following yet, but is gaining discussion and support. “with a good/clear eye” is a Hebrew idiom meaning “generous”. These days the Red Cross goes around Israel saying, “Give with a good eye.”]</bt><v n="23" />Te ngaa ladhe musi madha na ahu, nèngu bisa boe kako madhutu madha j'ara mola, nuka sèmi dhèu dhu gogo ai lae-lae ètu d'ara maroga. De ladhe saraa ètu d'ara miu j'aj'i maroga, na miu mamuri d'ara maroga kahèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>But if his eye is hazy/blurred then, he can not follow the straight path/way, like a person who walks groping around in the dark. So (consequently), if that light which is in your-p insides has become dark, na, you-p also live in the dark.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gogo ai lae-lae = jalan raba-raba"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">gogo ai lae-lae = jalan raba-raba</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus aj'a-nori dhèu ho baku pangee mamuri ne tasa mera mia [\s2]<bt>The Lord Yesus teaches (doublet) people to not keep thinking (worry about) how you're going to live [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Lukas 16:13, 12:22-31)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />&lt;&lt;Dhèu bisa boe sab'a hia dua lamatua, lula èèna na nèngu d'èi risi ca dhèu di. Bisa kahèi nèngu madhutu lamatua èci, aa pusi-pahae boe dhu leo. Nèti èèna ka, èu bisa boe peka na, &lt;Ama Lamatua èèna, Lamatua ja'a,&gt; ladhe èu tao doi-dhari j'aj'i mi lamatua èu.<bt>&lt;&lt;A person cannot work for two bosses/masters, because he will later like one boss more. It can also be that he follows/obeys the one boss, but he doesn't care.about/pay.attention to the other. Because of that, you-s cannot say, &lt;God is my Boss/Master,&gt; if you have made money be your-s boss/master.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Nèti èèna ka, Ja'a peka dènge miu sèmi ne'e: baku bhute pangee, na, ja'a mamuri tasa mera mia, ku'a-kinu ngaa, pake ngaa? Miu pangee na, mamuri ne dhoka ta'a-tinu, di? Aa ngi'u ne, dhoka pake mèdha-papake, di? Aad'o sèmi èèna.<bt>That's why I tell like this: don't be all pre-occupied/ fussed.over.details thinking/worrying, how am I going to live, what will I eat-drink (doublet)? What will I wear? Do you think that living is only about us-inc eating-drinking? And the body is only just for wearing clothes? It's not like that.</bt><v n="26" />Ladhe ku manu-bhui dhu lela ètu talora liru. Rèngu bhute rèdhi boe sèla hini, dènge puu-g'ètu, ho tèka nganga'a ètu d'ara soka. Te ngaa Ama miu ètu sorga piara manu-bhui sèra taruu. Tatu Nèngu kab'oi miu risi eele nèti rèngu. De ngee pabe'a-be'a. Te Ama Lamatua pakab'ua miu risi nèti manu-bhui sèra.<bt>Have a look at the birds which fly in the sky. They don't get all fussed/pre-occupied planting seeds and picking/harvesting (doublet), in.order.to store food in the (large) storage.baskets. But your-p Father in heaven cares for/raises/looks after the birds continually. Surely He also can care for2/provide for you-p even more. So (consequently), think carefully. Cuz (elaboration) God values/puts.a.price.on you-p, more than those birds.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="soe-soka = bakul-lumbung (small-gigantic baskets) ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">soe-soka = bakul-lumbung (small-gigantic baskets) ; kaboi = piara (like paron sapi)</Message></Annotation><v n="27" />Ladhe dhèu titu ètu madha tèru, ho na bhute dènge lalau ngi'u na, nèngu bisa pamadhera hari ngi'u na, do? Bisa boe!<bt>If a person stands in front of a mirror, then he fusses/gets pre-occupied with himself/his body, can he lengthen his body any more, [tag question]? He can't! [NOTE to daughter translations: CHECK collocations. Taller? or longer?]</bt><v n="28" />Ladhe bisa boe, na, nga tao ka miu bhute dènge pangee hari mèdha-papake? Lami ladhe ku hela bunga dhu muri tab'a ètu d'ara pad'a sod'a. Rèngu manyèru boe hèngu, aa manènu boe sig'i sa hèi.<bt>If not, na, why do you-p get.all.fussed/preoccupied thinking about clothes again? Go try and look at the flowers that live wild in the (remote) field. They don't spin thread, and don't weave cloth either.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="muri tab'a = tumbu liar ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">muri tab'a = tumbu liar ; hui (w/animals) ; hela bunga</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="29" />Te ngaa sanèd'e ku la! Mèdha-papake dhèu aae Soleman dhu kab'ua risi, saraga na bisa boe segi saraga hela bunga ne.<bt>But remember this (=dwell on it)! King Soleman's fanciest/most expensive clothes, their beauty cannot beat/conquer/overcome those flower's beauty.</bt><note reference="6:29" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">1 Dhèu Aae sèra 10:4-7, 2 Sejara nèti Isra'el dènge Yahuda 9:3-6</note><v n="30" />Te Ama Lamatua taru kira mi bunga dhu muri dhoka doe ne'e, aa bèli madhe, ho dhèu core asa d'ara ai. Ladhe Na tao sèmi èèna, tatu Nèngu papake miu risi eele nèti hela bunga sèra. De tasamia ka miu parcaya pa'èra boe mi Nèngu?<bt>Cuz (elaboration) God pays attention to flowers which live only today, then tomorrow die, so people throw them into the fire. If He does like that, surely He will also clothe you-p better than those flowers. So (consequently), how is it that you don't strongly believe/trust in Him?</bt><v n="31" />De baku mi pangee na, &lt;Ji'i neo nga'a ngaa?&gt; do, &lt;Neo nginu ngaa?&gt; do, &lt;Neo pake ngaa?&gt;<bt>So, you shouldn't be thinking/worrying, &lt;What will we eat?&gt; or, &lt;What will we drink?&gt; or, &lt;What will we wear?&gt;</bt><v n="32" />Dhèu dhu parcaya boe Ama Lamatua, rèngu sab'a loe boe ho neo abhu aa'i-aa'i se. Te ngaa miu baku tao sèmi èèna, te Ama miu ètu sorga dhu ne'a aa'i le, ngaa-ngaa dhu miu parluu.<bt>People who do not believe in God, they work endlessly to try to get/ obtain all those things. But you shouldn't do like that, cuz (elaboration) your-p Father in heaven already knows everything that you need.</bt><v n="33" />Te ngaa miu hud'i pakako uuru ku sasab'a Na, aa hud'i madhutu ku paredha Na, heka Na hia miu aa'i-aa'i dhu miu parluu.<bt>But you(pl) must carry.out His work first, and must follow/obey His commands first, only then He will give you all the things which you need.</bt><v n="34" />De baku bhute pangee, na, bèli miu parluu ngaa. Te bèli èèna dènge bhabhute unu na. Sasusa lod'o doe ne'e, èle ètu doe ne'e kahèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>So (consequently), don't get all fussed/pre-occupied thinking about what you-pl need tomorrow. Cuz (elaboration) tomorrow has it's own pre-occupations yet again. Today's difficulties are already enough/sufficient for now.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus aj'a, sèna ka baku galaa dhèu [\s2]<bt>The Lord Yesus teaches to not criticize/accuse people [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Lukas 6:37-38, 41-42)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="7" />
      <v n="1" />&lt;&lt;Miu baku galaa dhèu, sèna ka Ama Lamatua baku pasala miu kahèi.<bt>&lt;&lt;Don't criticize/accuse people, so that God doesn't blame/accuse you-pl either.</bt><v n="2" />Ladhe miu nile dhèu sèmi mia, pe Ama Lamatua nile miu sèmi èèna kahèi. Ladhe miu ige sasala dhèu sèmi mia, bèli-camèd'a Ama Lamatua ige sasala miu sèmi èèna kahèi.<bt>However you evaluate people, later God will also evaluate you like that too. However you count/keep track of people's wrongs, later2 God will also count your wrongs like that too.</bt><v n="3" />Masi ka sasala dhèu ciki oo'e èèna ka, èu bhèlu boe. Te ngaa sasala èu dhu kapai, èu pame'a boe ciki sa. Èci èèna ka dènge èu ladhe mèdhi ahu ca katèd'a ètu d'ara madha angalai èu, te ngaa abhu agarii aae ca laa dhu pa'abhe nare musi madha èu, dhu èu me'a more boe.<bt>Even though a person's wrongs are teeny-weeny/insignificantly small, you don't/won't forget (it/them). But your own big/great/significant wrongs, you not even aware of them in the smallest way. That is like you see a tiny speck of dust in the eye of your friend/companion, but there is a huge post/beam blocking your own eyeball, which you aren't even aware of.</bt><v n="4" />Nga tao ka èu bani peka na, &lt;Angalai! Mai ho ja'a tiu eele ahu nèti d'ara madha èu&gt;. Aa te ngaa èu mesa mu bisa boe mèdhi ngaa-ngaa, lula agarii aae dhu hutu nare musi madha mu.<bt>Why do you dare say, &lt;Friend! Come here so I can dab away the dust in your eye&gt;. Whereas you yourself cannot see anything, because of the great beam/post that is covering over your eyeball.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Masi ka èu mesa mu mèdhi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">Masi ka èu mesa mu mèdhi boe ngaa-ngaa, lula nèti agarii aae dhu hutu nare musi madha mu, nga tao ka èu bani peka na, &lt;Angalai! Mai ho ja'a tiu eele ahu nèti dara madha èu&gt;.</Message></Annotation><v n="5" />Heeh! Èu ne, mema dhèu dhu padhai lii leo, tao leo! Tao eele uuru ku agarii nèti musi madha èu, heka ladhe mèdhi ahu ca katèd'a ètu d'ara madha angalai mu, sèna ka èu bisa tiu eele ahu ne kèna.<bt>Heeh! [+critical, negative] You really are a person who says one thing and does another! Take away the beam from your own eye first, only then can you see the tiny speck of dust in your friend's eye so you can dab away that dust.</bt><note reference="7:2" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Markus 4:24</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Baku aj'a j'ara Lamatua dhu mola-mèci mi dhèu dhu d'èi pahahe dhèu. Lula dhèu sèra nuka sèmi busa pakadhi, dhu ra kabèli mai kadhi hari miu. Rèngu sèra goa sama sèmi hahi kahèi. Ladhe dhèu hia ne mutiara dhu kab'ua, na pusi boe! Te ne'a dhoka j'èli palaho di.&gt;&gt;<bt>Don't teach clean/holy (doublet) thing/s about God2 to people who like to belittle/humiliate others. Because those people are like vicious dog/s who later comes back to bite/attack you. They are also stupid like pigs. If a person gives an expensive pearl (loan--known to these sea-dwellers), na, he doesn't care! Cuz (elaboration) he only knows to just step all over it destroying it.&gt;&gt; [NOTE to daughter translations: Gk chiasmus here unravelled. Use pearls if it works. NOTE also still implicit the double whammy that pigs and dogs are not kosher for Jews.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pakadhi = bagigi ; pasobhu ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">pakadhi = bagigi ; pasobhu = pemburu</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus aj'a-nori, ho baku loe manèngi-mangaj'i [\s2]<bt>The Lord Yesus teaches (doublet) to not stop praying [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Lukas 11:9-13)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p" />
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="7" />&lt;&lt;Ladhe miu sabaj'a,<bt>&lt;&lt;If/when you-p pray,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">baku loe manèngi mi Lamatua;<bt>don't stop requesting to God2:</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">te èèna na, Na hia.<bt>cuz (elaboration) later He will give [what you ask].</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ladhe patangi-tenge;<bt>If [you] search continually (doublet);</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">pe Na pad'elo j'ara.<bt>later He will show the path/way.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ladhe kad'eu taruu babèdho;<bt>If [you] knock continually; [NOTE to daughter translations: in many local cultures, knocking is done by theives checking to see if anyone is home. Even in the cities, calling out is the norm, especially if the person is known to the household.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kad'eu "><Message author="Chuck" created="2009-11-25 01:55:56Z" status="Anyone">knock</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">pe Na bhoke.<bt>later He will open the door.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="8" />Te dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu loe boe manèngi mi Lamatua,<bt>Cuz (elaboration) all people who do not stop requesting from the Lord,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">èèna na ra sèmi rare.<bt>later [they] recieve.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Dhu patangi-tenge,<bt>Those who search continually (doublet),</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">pe ra abhu.<bt>later they will get/obtain.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Dhu kad'eu taruu,<bt>Those who knock continually,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">pe Na bhoke èmu.<bt>later He opens the door (lit. house).</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Miu pangee sèku! Ladhe ana manèngi roti, tatu ama na hia boe ne hadhu, si?<bt>Have a think (=mild imperative)! If a child requests bread, surely his father won't give a rock, right?</bt><v n="10" />Do, ladhe ana manèngi i'a, ama na hia boe mege, sina ma?<bt>Or, if the child requests fish, the father doesn't give a snake, obviously!</bt><v n="11" />Ama mi ètu sorga, mema d'ara Na hua iia titu kèna! De ladhe dhèu rai-haha dhu bhelu-katub'a sèmi miu, me'a hia mèdha dhu be'a mi ana miu, ngaa hari Ama mi! Tatu Na bagi hia miu ngaa dhu miu manèngi.<bt>Your-p Father in heaven has very good insides/character! So (consequently), if humans who are evil (doublet) like you, know how to give things which are good to your children, even more so your Father! He certainly will give what you request.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />De, ngaa dhu èu neo dhèu leo tao mi èu, na, èu hud'i tao sèmi èèna kahèi hia nèngu. Lula ne'e ne ka, j'aj'i mi kapua nèti aa'i-aa'i dhu Musa dènge dhèu rèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua dhu peka-padhai karèi nèti uru ka.&gt;&gt;<bt>So (consequently), what you-s want another person to do for you, na, you must do like that for him also. Because this here is the foundation of all that which Musa and God's spokespersons have taught (doublet) in.advance from long ago.&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="7:12" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lukas 6:31</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus pakasame j'ara dhu susa aa hèb'a kota dhu kob'o [\s2]<bt>The Lord Yesus compares the difficult ways and a door/gate which is narrow [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Lukas 13:24)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />&lt;&lt;Ladhe dhèu neo maso sorga, nèngu hud'i maso ku re hèb'a kota dhu kob'o. Te ngaa mage-mage, oo! Abhu kahèi j'ara leo dhu mud'a, aa hèb'a dhu taleo, dhu dhèu ae-ae lasi re èèna. Te j'ara sèmi èèna ka dhu lere dhèu asa naraka, ka ra cèri eele nèti Ama Lamatua.<bt>&lt;&lt;If a person wants to enter heaven, he must walk passing through the city door/gate which is narrow. But be careful, oo! There is also another path/way which is easy and a door which is wide, which many people go by on. Cuz (elaboration) paths/ways like.that are the ones which lead people to hell, so they are separated off/cut off from God. [EXEG: Gk is word for ‘perish’, see note at John 3:16.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kob'o = sempit ; taleo ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">kob'o = sempit ; taleo = lebar</Message></Annotation><v n="14" />Dhèu dhu neo maso sorga, hud'i madhutu ku j'ara dhu susa, aa maso re hèb'a dhu kob'o. Te, masi ka dhèu ciki di dhu kako re j'ara èèna, te ngaa j'ara dhu kob'o èèna ka, dhu nèti dhèu asa Lamatua.&gt;&gt;<bt>People who want to enter heaven must follow that path which is difficult and enter by that door which is narrow. Cuz (elaboration) even though only a few people who walk by that way, nevertheless that narrow way is the one which brings people to God2.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua aj'a dhèu, sèna ka baku tao madhutu dhèu kapod'e-kabèli [\s2]<bt>The Lord teaches people to not follow the decievers (doublet) [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Lukas 6:43-44)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />&lt;&lt;Baku pamud'e dènge dhèu dhu tema kapod'e-kabèli, dhu d'èi padedha iisi, peka na, rèngu se dhèu rèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua. Te rèngu tao ngi'u ra be'a nuka sèmi kahib'i-kalèbho. Te ngaa rèngu se dhèu bhelu-katub'a, èci èèna ka dènge busa hui dhu mai kadhi kahib'i-kalèbho.<bt>&lt;&lt;Be careful of the con.artists who lift/praise themselves, saying, they are God's spokesperson. Cuz (elaboration) they make themselves pretending to be good like sheep (doublet). However they are evil (doublet) people, the same as a forest/wild dog who comes to eat sheep (doublet).</bt><v n="16" />Tasamia ho miu bisa tadhe dhèu dhu kapod'e sèmi sèra? Ladhe la nèti tatao rèngu. Èèna sèmi dhèu ladhe rèdhi hua, hèia tadhe dènge ana aaj'u ne. Hua dhu be'a, mai boe nèti aj'u dhu karehe.<bt>How can you-p know/recognize those pretending people? Just look at what they do. The same as when a person looks at fruit, then knows/recognises its tree. Fruit that is good, does not come out of a tree which is bad/rotten.</bt><v n="17" />Te aj'u dhu be'a ladhe d'ai hua, hua na be'a kahèi. Te ngaa aj'u dhu karehe ladhe na hua, hua na karehe kahèi.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) a tree which is good, when it fruits, its fruit is also good. But a tree which is bad/rotten, when it fruits, its fruit is also bad/rotten.</bt><v n="18" />Abhu ètu mia, aj'u dhu be'a, hua na karehe, aa aj'u dhu karehe, hua na be'a?<bt>Where would you find a good tree whose fruit is bad, and bad trees whose fruit is good?</bt><v n="19" />Aj'u dhu hua na karehe, tatu ra patue eele, ho core asa d'ara ai.<bt>A tree which produces bad fruit, certainly they cut it (down/off) in.order.to. throw it away into the fire.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="patue = tebang"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">patue = tebang</Message></Annotation><note reference="7:19" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 3:10, Lukas 3:9</note><v n="20" />Sèmi èèna kahèi dènge rèngu dhu rèti lii padhai kapod'e-kabèli sèra. Miu tadhe si nèti tatao ra.&gt;&gt;<bt>Like that also with those pretending/deceptive spokespersons. You-p can recognise them from their deeds/behaviour/character.&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="7:20" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 12:33</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus lole dhèu dhu ale dhoka kolongara Ama Lamatua ètu hèb'a di [\s2]<bt>The Lord Yesus tells about people who just mention God with their mouth only [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Lukas 13:25-27)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />&lt;&lt;Èèna na abhu dhèu dhu paroa Ja'a, na, &lt;Lamatua!&gt; Te ngaa rèngu dhoka ale ètu hèb'a di. Bèli-camèd'a Ama Lamatua ètu sorga tule eele si. Te dhodhoka dhèu dhu d'èi tao madhutu dad'èi Nèngu di, dhu Na sèmi nare rèngu j'aj'i dhèu unu Na.<bt>&lt;&lt;Later there will be people who call Me, saying, &lt;Lord/Master!&gt; But they only mention/call with just mouth. Later God in heaven will reject them. Cuz (elaboration), only just people who truly follow His will, whom He recieves/accepts to become His people. [NOTE to daughter translations: Repetition of vocative is not natural in these lgs.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hèb'a "><Message author="Chuck" created="2009-11-25 03:02:47Z" status="Anyone">kolo-panyoro = bibir</Message></Annotation><v n="22" />Pe ropa d'ai èle rai-haha ne, dhèu ae mangaku, peka na, Ja'a ne Lamatua rèngu. Aa dènge lii solo-mako, ra peka na, &lt;Lamatua! Ji'i se la'a pakako a'aj'a Lamatua ètu mia-mia, babège nidhu dènge kolongara Lamatua, aa tao tadha-tadha malaa pake koasa nèti Lamatua.&gt;<bt>Later when at the day at end of the world, many people will acknowledge, saying, I here am their Lord/Master. They will plead (doublet) with Me, saying, &lt;Lord/Master! We-ex have gone to carry out Lord's (=your) teaching everywhere, expelling evil.spirits using Lord's name/reputation, and done all sorts of amazing sings (*miracles) using Lord's power.&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Masi ka rèngu solo-mako Ja'a sèmi èèna, te ngaa èèna na Ja'a peka dènge rèngu, na, &lt;Miu se, cee? Ja'a tadhe boe miu, te miu mamuri boe madhutu dad'èi Ama Lamatua. De mi pakaj'èu ka nèti ne'e!&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>Even though they keep trying to persuade Me like that, nevertheless I will tell them, saying, &lt;Who are you-p? I don't know you, cuz (elaboration) you don't live according to God's will. So (consequently), get away from here (imperative)!&gt;&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="7:23" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 6:9</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus aj'a lula-nèti dhèu dhu d'èlu-mèu, aa dhèu dhu goa [\s2]<bt>The Lord Yesus teaches about wise/smart people and stupid people [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Lukas 6:47-49)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />&lt;&lt;Dhèu dhu mai nanene Ja'a, hèia ra tao madhutu lii padhai Ja'a, rèngu se nuka sèmi dhèu dhu d'èlu-mèu, dhu patitu èmu ra ètu dedha hadhu kapua.<bt>&lt;&lt;People who come to listen to Me, then do according to what I say, they are like a smart/wise person who erected/built his house on rock.</bt><v n="25" />Nèbhu boe, ka èj'i aae mai toke èi lala, aa ngèlu aae lèke èmu ne. Te ngaa èmu ne guri boe, lula patitu ètu dedha hadhu kapua.<bt>Soon big rain comes until it floods, and strong winds also bash his house. But that house does not collapse, because it stands on top of the stone base.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="uli sea = puting beliung"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">uli sea = puting beliung</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Dhèu dhu mai nanene Ja'a, te ngaa tao boe madhutu lii padhai Ja'a, nèngu ne èci èèna ka dènge dhèu goa dhu patitu èmu na ètu dedha salae.<bt>A person who comes to listen to Me, but does not do according to what I say, he is like a stupid person who erects/builds his house on top of sand.</bt><v n="27" />Nèbhu boe, ka èj'i aae mai toke èi lala. Ngèlu aae lèke èmu ne kahèi. Hèia èmu ne guri eele, toke laho teb'o-teb'o.&gt;&gt;<bt>Soon big rain comes down until it floods. Strong winds also bash his house. Then that house collapses until it completely destroyed.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="laho teb'o-teb'o = \lf Max"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">laho teb'o-teb'o = \lf Max</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu malaa-maloha lula nanene lii padhai Lamatua Yesus<bt>People are amazed (doublet) hearing what the Lord Yesus is saying</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Ropa Yesus padhai lii nare, hèia dhèu aa'i-aa'i ra malaa-maloha, lula nanene a'aj'a Na,<bt>When Yesus finished speaking, then all the people were amazed (doublet) hearing his teaching,</bt><v n="29" />te Nèngu ne'a mèu isi nèti a'aj'a ne. Na aj'a-nori sèmi boe mese agama sèra.<bt>cuz (elaboration) He really knew/understood that teaching's contents. He taught (doublet) not like their religion teachers (*scribes).</bt><note reference="7:28-29" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Markus 1:22, Lukas 4:32</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus puri-pa'èle ca dhèu pèd'a kusta<bt>The Lord Yesus heals (doublet) a person with leprosy (assimilated loan) disease</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 1:40-45; Lukas 5:12-16)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="8" />
      <v n="1" />Lod'o Yesus puru nèti ledhe, hèia dhèu ae-ae lasi madhutu Ne.<bt>When Yesus came down from the mountain, then many people followed Him.</bt><v n="2" />Kabèdhi laa, ca dhèu dhu pèd'a kusta mai paraga dènge Ne. Hèia na patitu kètu urutuu ètu madha Yesus, ho manèngi, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Lamatua! Sue ku ja'a la! Ladhe mo'o, na, puri ku papèd'a ja'a ne, sèna ka dhèu madenge ia ka dènge ja'a, aa ja'a bisa hari sabaj'a ètu d'ara èmu manèngi-mangaj'i.&gt;&gt;<bt>Unexpectedly, a person sick with leprosy came to meet with Him. He knelt before Yesus to request, saying, &lt;&lt;Lord/Master! Love/pity me! [=normal way of asking for help] If (you) want, na, heal this sickness of mine, so that people are not repulsed with me anymore, and2 I can worship again in the house of prayer.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Ropa tadèngi nare, hèia Yesus j'ole kacui-aai Na ka Na g'ag'e dhèu ne, hèia Na lii, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a ko'o! Èu èle kèna!&gt;&gt; Kabèdhi la, èi papèd'a dhèu ne èle dènge ka.<bt>When [He} heard that, then Yesus extended his hand, then He touched that person and He spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;I do want to! You are well now!&gt;&gt; Unexpectedly/suddenly that person's illness disappeared right away.</bt><v n="4" />Hèia Yesus peka dènge ne, &lt;&lt;Sanèd'e paie! Èu èle le nèti papèd'a-tarègu, te ngaa baku èu lolo dènge dhèu èci sa. Aa èu hud'i madhutu ku atora Musa. De lamu asa ama agama ho na parisa ngi'u èu, sèna ka ne'a na èi papèd'a mu ele le, tare'a, do dhae. Èle na, èu hia persembahan tadha makasi, sèna ka dhèu re'a, na, èu ne èle tare'a-re'a le nèti papèd'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus told him, saying, &lt;&lt;Remember (this) well! You are healed from your disease (doublet), but don't tell anyone. And you must follow Musa's regulation first. So (consequently), go to the head of religion (*priest), in.order.for him to examine your body, so that he can know if your sickness has truly disapppeared, or not yet. Then you give an offering as a sign of thanks, so that people know that you are really healed from disease.&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="8:4" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Atora nèti Ama-ama Agama 14:1-32</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus puri-pa'èle ana sab'a èci nèti komedhaa sordad'u Roma<bt>The Lord Yesus heals (doublet) a Roma army commander's worker</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Lukas 7:1-10)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Èle èèna, hèia Yesus maso asa d'ara rae Kapernaum. Ètu era ne'e, komedhaa sordad'u Roma ca dhèu, mai manèngi ho Yesus soru-bara ne, aku nèngu na,<bt>After that, then Yesus entered into Kapernaum village. In that place, there was a Roma army commander who came to request Yesus help (doublet) him, saying,</bt><v n="6" />&lt;&lt;Ama! Ana sab'a ja'a ca dhèu, pèd'a aae, ka na j'èra titu kèna ètu èmu. Na bisa boe puru nèti era j'unu na.&gt;&gt;<bt>&lt;&lt;Father! One of my workers is severely sick, and he is suffering greatly at home. He cannot get down from [his] bed.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Ka Yesus dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Oo! Pe Ja'a dhiu puri-pa'èle ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>Yesus replied, saying, &lt;&lt;Good/OK! Later I will go heal (doublet) him.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Te ngaa komedhaa ne b'ala, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Ama roca ia ka mai asa èmu ja'a, lula ja'a nia boe sèmi Ama asa d'ara èmu ja'a. Sad'i Ama ku peka dhoka lii ca hèb'a di nèti ne'e, tatu ana sab'a ja'a ne èle dènge nèti papèd'a.<bt>[CHECK roca here] But that commander reciprocated, saying, &lt;&lt;Father! Father (=you) doesn't need to get all tired coming to my house, because I am not worthy to recieve Father in my house. As long as Father just speaks a word from here, surely that worker of mine will be healed right away from his ailment. [EXEG: TN points out that “not worthy” could be from 1) spiritual awareness (he is a sinner); 2) social sensitivity (he is a gentile, and doesn't want to ask a Jew to violate religious norms by coming into his house); or 3) both. So don't force the first reading.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="samuri = healed (Michael not know)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">samuri = healed (Michael not know)</Message></Annotation><v n="9" />Ja'a ke'a j'ara ne, lula ja'a dènge dhèu paredha dedha kahèi, dhu dènge koasa ho paredha ja'a. Aa ja'a dènge koasa kahèi, sèna ka paredha sordad'u ja'a sèra. Ladhe ja'a pua, peka na, &lt;Lamu sa nèi!&gt; tatu na la'e dènge. Aa ladhe ja'a peka, &lt;Mai asa ne'e!&gt; tatu na mai. Aa ladhe ja'a paleha dhèu sab'a ja'a, peka na, &lt;Sab'a ne'e!&gt; tatu na tao madhutu. De sad'i Ama ku lii di, tatu ana sab'a ja'a èèna, èle dènge nèti papèd'a na.&gt;&gt;<bt>I understand this matter, because I am a person with people commanding above me too, who have power/authority to command me. And I also have power/authority to order my soldiers. If I order, saying, &lt;Go yonder!&gt; surely he goes immediately. Adn if I say, &lt;Come here!&gt; surely he comes. And if I order3 my worker, saying, &lt;Do this!&gt; surely he does accordingly. So (consequently), as long Father just speaks, surely that worker of mine, will be healed straight away from his sickness/ailment.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Ropa Yesus tadèngi nare, hèia Na malaa. Ka Na padhai lii dènge dhèu ae sèra, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Nèbhu nare sange ne'e, Ja'a dhae paraga kèdhi mèka dènge ca dhèu sa nèti dhèu Yahudi dhu lèka èra sama sèmi dhèu Roma ne!<bt>When Yesus heard that, He was amazed. And2 He spoke to those many people, saying, &lt;&lt;All this time, I have not yet ever met even one Yahudi person who believes as strongly as this Roma person!</bt><v n="11" />Nanene paie-iie! Te bèli-camèd'a dhèu leo rai kara ae-ae, nuka sèmi dhèu Roma ne, mai nèti haa, nèti dhimu, ho madhèdi ra'a-rinu mei èci dènge Abraham, Isak dènge Yakob ètu d'ara èmu Ama Lamatua ètu sorga.<bt>Listen carefully! Cuz (elaboration) later there will be many outsiders/foreigners (*gentiles) like this Roma person here, who come from the west and from the east [RL natural order] to sit eat a feast at the same table with Abraham, Isak, and Yakob in God's house in heaven.</bt><note reference="8:11" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lukas 13:29</note><v n="12" />Masi ka Lamatua dhu hag'e nare le dhèu Yahudi, sena ka j'aj'i dhèu unu Na, te ngaa ae ka dhu pusi-pahae boe Ne. Èèna na, Lamatua tule eele si asa era dhu maroga kiu-kiu. Ètu era ne'e, ra tangi roma iisi d'ara pèd'a, aa ra j'èra titu kèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>Even though God2 has chosen Yahudi people to become His people, nevertheless there are many who don't pay attention to/aren't concerned with/ignore Him. Later2 He will reject throw them away to a very dark place. In that place they will cry in grief with great suffering.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="maroga kiu-kiu = \lf Max @@"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">maroga kiu-kiu = \lf Max @@</Message></Annotation><note reference="8:12" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 22:13, 25:30, Lukas 13:28</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Padhai lii nare, hèia Yesus peka dènge komedhaa ne, &lt;&lt;Lèpa ka. Te ana sab'a èu èèna èle le, madhutu sèmi parcaya èu ne.&gt;&gt; Ka lod'o dhu Na padhai èèna, ana ne èle dènge ka.<bt>Finishing speaking like.that, then Yesus told that commander, saying, &lt;&lt;Go on home (=polite imperative). Cuz (elaboration) your worker is healed, in accord with your belief.&gt;&gt; And at that time which He was speaking, that worker was healed straight away. [EXEG: TN “at that very hour: This does not refer to an hour of sixty minutes. It means that he was healed at the very same time that Jesus said these words.”] [NOTE to daughter translations: if this guy is high rank should Yesus address him as Lu or Pak? Be natural, don't force Malay etiquette.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Ka dara ciki oo'e èèna kahèi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">Ka dara ciki oo'e èèna kahèi = in a short time</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus puri-pa'èle dhèu pèd'a ae-ae<bt>The Lord Yesus heals (doublet) many sick people</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 1:29-34; Lukas 4:38-41)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Ca tèka, Yesus la'e asa èmu Petrus. Na ladhe nèdhi ina dhèu èmu Petrus dhu j'unu ètu dedha koi, dhu pèd'a maringi-sagoro.<bt>One time Yesus went to Petrus' house. He saw Petrus' spouse's mother sleeping on the bed, cuz (elaboration) she had a fever.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="j'unu "><Message author="Chuck" created="2009-11-25 03:59:59Z" status="Anyone">implies lying down, whereas bhèj'i implies actually sleeping</Message></Annotation><v n="15" />Ka Yesus kèpe kacui-aai na, hèia ina ne èle nèti papèd'a na. Hèia na kèd'i, ka la'e lalau nganga'a hia Yesus si.<bt>Yesus held her hand, then that elder.woman's was healed of her sickness/ailment. Then she got up, and went take care of/serve food to Yesus them (collective).</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Ropa lod'o oe cèna, hèia dhèu sèra mai rèti dhèu rèngu dhu nidhu tao. Hèia Na paredha nidhu se, peka na, &lt;&lt;Eee, nidhu! Rai pakaj'èu nèti ne'e!&gt;&gt; Hèia nidhu se kalua dènge ka. Na puri-pa'èle kahèi dhèu aa'i-aa'i nèti papèd'a-tarègu ra.<bt>When the sun was about to go down, then people brought their people who were afflicted by evil.spirits. Then He ordered those evil.spirits, saying, &lt;&lt;Eee, evil.spirits! Get away from here!&gt;&gt; Then those evil.spirits came out right away. He also healed (doublet) all people of their (various) diseases (doublet).</bt><v n="17" />Na tao j'ara se, ho pamèci dènge lii dhèu nèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua, ngara na Yesaya, dhu suri tèke le, peka na,<bt>He did these things, to fulfill what God's spokesperson Yesaya had written ahead of time, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Na puri-pa'èle papèd'a-tarègu èdhi.<bt>&lt;&lt;He heals (doublet) our-inc sicknesses (doublet).</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Aa pasae nare j'aj'èra èdhi.&gt;&gt;<bt>And He shoulder.carries our suffering.&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="8:17" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 53:4</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu dhu neo madhutu Lamatua Yesus hud'i madhutu ku dènge d'ara kateme<bt>People who want to follow the Lord Yesus must follow whole-heartedly</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Lukas 9:57-62)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Èle èèna ka, Yesus nèdhi dhèu ae-ae mai kalibhu rare Ne. Hèia Na peka dènge ana-ana madhutu Na, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Mai pakèd'i lati asa cabèka dano.&gt;&gt;<bt>After that, Yesus saw many people come gather/crowd around Him. So He ordered his followers, saying, &lt;&lt;Come let's go acroos to the lake's other side.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kalibhu = rong ame, kelilingi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">kalibhu = rong ame, kelilingi</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Hèia mese agama ca dhèu mai, padhai lii dènge Ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama Mese! Sad'i Ama asa mia èèna ka, ja'a bera-bera dènge Ama!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then a religion teacher came speaking with Him, saying, &lt;&lt;Father Teacher! Wherever Father (=You) goes, I want to accompany with Father!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Ka Yesus dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Be'a kahèi do! Te ngaa sanèd'e. Dhèu rai-haha aa badha-manu aa'i-aa'i, dhu dènge era pea-palu'u. Busa hui lèpa asa ro'a na. Manu-bhui la'e asa rèd'a na. Te ngaa Ja'a Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a ne dènge boe era pea-palu'u. Nanèlu ho bane kètu dènge boe kahèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>But Yesus responded, saying, &lt;&lt;That's good! But remember. All humans and animals (doublet) have their own living/staying (doublet) places. A forest/wild dog returns to his hole. A bird goes to his nest. But I, this Ideal/Prototypical Human, have no staying-living place. A place to pad my head, I don't even have either.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="badha-manu = animal kingdom ; pea-palu'u"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">badha-manu = animal kingdom ; pea-palu'u = perdiaman ; rèd'a = next (birds) ; nanèlu = bantal (kapok)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Èle ka, dhèu èci hari mai peka dènge Yesus, na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Ja'a neo madhutu Ama, te ngaa hud'i ja'a ladhe-leru ku ina-ama ja'a. Ladhe ama ku madhe, ho padhane kore, heka ja'a madhutu kèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then another person, came to speak with Yesus, saying, &lt;&lt;Father! I want to follow Father, but allow me to take care of (doublet) my parents first. When my father dies, and I have buried him, then I will follow.&gt;&gt; [EXEG: see discussion in TN. Favours father not dead and managing things over a period of time.] [NOTE to daughter translations: try to reflect this on-going business in the lexical choice in next to last sentence.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Te ngaa Yesus padhai lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e! Hud'i laa dhèu leo dhu parcaya boe Lamatua padhane dhèu madhe. Te ladhe èu neo madhutu Ja'a, na, madhutu la dènge d'ara kateme!&gt;&gt;<bt>But Yesus spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;It's like.this! Allow it so that people who don't believe in God2 bury dead people. Cuz (elaboration) if you want to follow Me, na, you must follow whole-heartedly!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus pamau ngèlu aae<bt>The Lord Yesus makes a noisy wind (=storm) calm</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 4:35-41; Lukas 8:22-25)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Èle èèna ka, Yesus ca'e asa dedha koha, palere dènge ana-ana madhutu Na.<bt>After that, Yesus got on the boat, together with His followers.</bt><v n="24" />Ropa rèngu ètu talora dano era, Yesus bhèj'i. Kaca'a laa, ngèlu aae mai. Naha aae tèb'e koha ne, toke èi maso asa d'ara.<bt>When they were still in the middle of the lake, Yesus slept. Suddenly, a noisy wind (=storm) came. Waves beat against the boat, to the point that water entered in. [NOTE to daughter translations: Read entry for ‘Galilea’ in electronic version of Kamus Alkitab to discuss size of lake. CHECK: some lgs distinguish between ‘ombak’ “normal waves” and ‘gelombang’ “big waves (dangerous)”.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lèu = sea"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">lèu = sea</Message></Annotation><v n="25" />Ropa ladhe rèdhi sèmi èèna, hèia ana madhutu se lasi parèi Yesus, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Ama! Kèd'i ku la! Bara ku ji'i, te èdhi molo madhe aa'i ti kèna!&gt;&gt;<bt>When they saw that, then the followers went to wake up Yesus, saying, &lt;&lt;Father! Father! Wake up! Help/save (doublet) us-exc, cuz (elaboration) we-inc are all about to die drowning here!&gt;&gt; [NOTE: spiritual “salvation” word doesn't work here in this context, so we can't force that. This is how they would ask to be rescued.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Soru"><Message author="Chuck" created="2009-11-25 04:37:46Z" status="Anyone">In this context of asking for rescue, soru (without bara)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Hèia Yesus dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Wee! Nga tao ka miu se madha'u sèmi ne'e ne? Miu parcaya boe Ja'a, do?&gt;&gt; Ka Na kèd'i. Èle ka Na kai ngèlu dènge naha ètu d'ara dano ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Mau ka!&gt;&gt; Hèia naha dènge ngèlu mau dènge ka.<bt>Then Yesus replied, saying, &lt;&lt;Wee! How come you-p are afraid like this here? Don't you believe/trust in Me, [tag question]?&gt;&gt; Then He got up. Then2 He forbade that wind and waves in the lake, saying, &lt;&lt;Quiet!&gt;&gt; Then3 the waves and wind became calm/quiet straight away.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Ka ana madhutu Yesus se malaa-maloha. Ra papeka na, &lt;&lt;Ira ii! Cee ka Dhèu ne'e ne? Tasamia ka Na bisa paredha ngèlu dènge naha, ka madhutu dad'èi Na?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus' underlings were amazed (doublet). They said to each other, &lt;&lt;Ira ee [+amazement]! Who is this Person? How can it be that He can command the wind and waves so that they follow/obey His will?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus pa'èle dhèu dua dhu nidhu tao<bt>The Lord Yesus heals two people who are affected by evil.spirits</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 5:1-20; Lukas 8:26-39)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Nèbhu boe ka rèngu d'ai cabèka dano, ètu rai Gad'ara.<bt>Not much longer, then they arrived at that lake's other side, in the Gadara</bt><note reference="8:28" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Sasuri lii Yunani dhu be'a risi, suri <span class="Italic">Gad'ara</span> ètu Mateos. Sasuri cahag'e dhu suri <span class="Italic">Gergesa,</span> aa cahag'e dhu leo suri <span class="Italic">Gerasa</span>.<bt>The best Yunani language writings write <span class="Italic">Gadara</span> in Mateos. There are some other writings which write <span class="Italic">Gergesa</span>, and some others which write <span class="Italic">Gerasa</span>. [NOTE: see Morris, Carson, CEV, NRSV, NLT.]</bt></note>Ètu era nèi, abhu dhèu dua dhu nidhu tao. Rèngu pea ètu era ro'a dhèu madhe. Dua ra se'e bhelu titu kèna, toke abhu boe ca dhèu sa hèi dhu bani kako re era èèna. Ropa rèdhi Yesus mai, hèia<bt>land/country. In that place there were two people who were afflicted with evil.spirits, who lived in rock holes in the place of dead people. The two of them were very evil, to.the.point.that there was not a single person who dared walk by/via that place. When they saw Yesus come, then</bt><v n="29" />ra pa'oo, peka na, &lt;&lt;We, Ana Ama Lamatua! Nga tao ka Èu mai gagu ji'i se? Masi ka d'ai mèka lod'o ho hia hahuku mi ji'i, te ngaa Èu mai le ho neo paj'èra ji'i!&gt;&gt;<bt>they yelled, saying, &lt;&lt;We, God's Child! Why have You come to bother us-ex? Even though the time to punish us has not yet arrived, nevertheless You already want to torment/torture/ persecute us-ex.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="30" />Kaj'èu boe ètu era èèna, abhu hahi canau dhu nyuu rai, tenge nganga'a.<bt>Not far from that place, there were a herd of pigs nozzling through the dirt hunting for food.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nyuu rai = can be for"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">nyuu rai = can be for food, making a wallow, or making a place to sleep</Message></Annotation><v n="31" />Hèia nidhu se manèngi Yesus, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe babèga eele ji'i, na, pua la ji'i maso asa d'ara hahi sèi!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then those evil.spirits requested Yesus, saying, &lt;&lt;If you're going to evict us, na, order us-ex to enter into those pigs yonder!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="32" />Hèia Yesus paredha nidhu se, peka na, &lt;&lt;Lami ka!&gt;&gt; Hèia nidhu kalua tèke eele dhèu dua se, lasi maso asa d'ara hahi deo sa. Ka hahi se rai paceb'a re sebhe ledhe ka manahu asa d'ara dano, hèia ra cèna, ka madhe aa'i si.<bt>Then Yesus ordered the evil spirits, saying, &lt;&lt;Go on!&gt;&gt; Then those evil.spirits came out leaving those two people, going and entering into those aforementioned pigs. Then2 those pigs ran helter-skelter down the edge/slope of the mountain into the lake, rhen they all died drowning.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="paceb'a =batasiram"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">paceb'a =batasiram</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pasoka "><Message author="Chuck" created="2009-11-25 05:41:55Z" status="Anyone">malompat</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="33" />Ropa ladhe rèdhi sèmi èèna, dhèu madhenga hahi, rai lasi asa d'ara rae, hèia ra lolo ngaa dhu j'aj'i ne.<bt>When they saw that, then the guards of the pigs ran home to the village, and they told what had happened.</bt><v n="34" />Ropa tadèngi rare, dhèu ae lasi asa era èèna. D'ai nèi, ra rèdhi Yesus. Hèia ra pakaseti Yesus, ho pakèd'i nèti rae rèngu ne.<bt>When they heard that, many people came out to that place. Arriving there, they saw Yesus. Then they pressured Yesus to leave their village (‘village’ can include all associated lands).</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus puri-pa'èle dhèu karuku ca dhèu<bt>The Lord Yesus heals (doublet) a lame person</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 2:1-12; Lukas 5:17-26)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="9" />
      <v n="1" />Èle èèna, Yesus si ca'e hari koha, lèpa asa ca bèka dano. Ka rèngu puru ètu kota Na.<bt>After that, Yesus (coll.) got back in the boat, returning to the lake's other side. And they disembarked at His own city. [NOTE to daughter translations: Gk uses /polis/ ‘city’ here. In Mrk we also used city for Capernaum and other larger population centres.]</bt><v n="2" />Ètu era ne'e dhèu j'èru rèti angalai ra dhu karuku asa Yesus. Ropa ladhe nèdhi, Yesus ne'a le, na, rèngu parcaya Ne, peka na, Nèngu bisa puri-pa'èle angalai ra. Hèia Na peka dènge dhèu karuku ne, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ana! Pa'èra d'ara èu! Te Ja'a saku eele le sasala èu.&gt;&gt;<bt>In that place people who carried [s.t. bulky/sick person] brought their friend who was lame to Yesus. When [He] saw that, Yesus knew they were believing in Him, saying/that He could heal (doublet) their friend. Then He spoke with that lame person, saying, &lt;&lt;Child/Underling! Strengthen your insides (=Be encouraged)! Cuz (elaboration) I have have wiped away your wrongs.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Te ngaa ètu era èèna, abhu pèri-pèri mese agama Yahudi dhu tadèngi lii padhai Yesus èèna. Ka ra nasa, hèia ra papeka, na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu ne'e ne bani titu kèna peka sèmi èèna! Dhodhoka Ama Lamatua di dhu bisa abho sasala-sasigo dhèu. Te ngaa lii padhai Dhèu ne tao iisi Na sama sèmi Ama Lamatua sa. Nèngu ne pahaha Ama Lamatua!&gt;&gt;<bt>But in that place there were several Yahudi religion teachers, who heard what Yesus said. Then were angry, then2 they spoke to each other, saying, &lt;&lt;This person is very bold speaking like that! Only God alone is the one who can *forgive people's wrongs (doublet). But that speaking of this Person, makes Himself the same as God. With that he has slandered/blasphemed/belittles God!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Te ngaa Yesus ne'a d'ara rèngu. Nèti èèna ka Na lii, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Nga tao ka miu se pangee, na, Ja'a ne pahaha Ama Lamatua?<bt>But Yesus knew their insides. Therefore He spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;Why do you think that I here, have slandered/blasphemed/belittled God?</bt><v n="5" />Mia ka dhu mud'a risi? Ladhe Ja'a peka dènge dhèu karuku ne, &lt;Ja'a saku eele le sasala èu,&gt; do, Ja'a peka na, &lt;Kèd'i, ho lèpa ka.&gt;<bt>Which is easier? If I tell this lame person here saying, &lt;I wipe away your wrongs,&gt; or I say, &lt;Get up, and go home.&gt; [NOTE to daughter translations: Compare with Mark 2:9-10, in case you've come up with a clearer structure for your local audience, but retain the differences in the two gospels.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="karad'a = usungan tampa orang mati"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">karad'a = usungan tampa orang mati (Michael thinks people don't know this)</Message></Annotation><v n="6" />Ladhe na kèd'i dènge ka, miu heka mèdhi, na, Ja'a ne Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a. Te Ja'a dènge hak ho abho sasala dhèu.&gt;&gt;<bt>If he gets up straight.away, then you-p will see that I here, am the Ideal/Prototypical Human. Cuz (elaboration) I have the right to forgive people's wrongs.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia Yesus paredha dhèu karuku ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Kèd'i ka! Ded'e mèti ka karad'a èu, ho lèpa ka!&gt;&gt;<bt>[CHECK /karad'a/] Then Yesus ordered that lame person, saying, &lt;&lt;Get up! Pick up your stretcher and return home!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="karad'a "><Message author="Chuck" created="2009-11-25 05:55:13Z" status="Anyone">stretcher, pallet; one young UNS not know (Dhao based) [Lena knows]</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Ka dhèu karuku ne kèd'i, hèia na lèpa dènge ka.<bt>So that lame person got.up, and he returned home straightaway.</bt><v n="8" />Ropa ladhe rèdhi, hèia rèngu aa'i-aa'i ra malaa-maloha. Hèia ra ded'e padedha-dedha kolongara Ama Lamatua, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama Lamatua, kapai risi eele! Na hia koasa kapai sèmi ne'e, hia mi dhèu rai-haha.&gt;&gt;<bt>When they saw that, then they were all amazed. Then they lifted up high/exalted God's name/reputation, saying, &lt;&lt;God is really awesome/great! He has given big/great/ awesome power/authority like this to humans.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus paroa Mateos ho madhutu Ne<bt>The Lord Yesus summons Mateos to follow Him</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 2:13-17; Lukas 5:27-32)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Èle ka Yesus la'e nèti era èèna, hèia ladhe nèdhi ca dhèu roro doi bea dhu sab'a ètu kantor bea. Ngara dhèu ne, Mateos. Hèia Yesus gale ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Mai madhutu Ja'a!&gt;&gt; Ropa tadèngi nare, hèia Mateos kèd'i dènge ka, la'e madhutu Yesus.<bt>After that, Yesus walked from that place, and He saw a tax collector who was working at the tax office. His name was Mateos. Then Yesus invited [invokes hand signal] him, saying, &lt;&lt;Come follow Me!&gt;&gt; When he heard that, then Mateos got.up straight.away and went following Yesus. [NOTE to daughter translations: this is a kios or pos, not a full kantor. See if you can reflect that.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Ka Mateos nèru Yesus si lasi ra'a-rinu asa èmu na. Na nèru kahèi mone aanga-angalai na dhèu roro bea sèra, aa tamu dhu leo kahèi, ho ra'a-rinu dènge rèngu.<bt>Then2 Mateos invited Yesus (coll.) to go eat (doublet, gives more sense of ‘dine’) at his house. He also invited his tax collector friends, and other guests too, to come eat (doublet) together with them. [NOTE to daughter translations: Gk has ‘and sinners’ in both vs. 10 &amp; 11. But to force it here skews the focus and implies this reflects Jesus' attitude, whereas in the story it is those in vs.11 that have the issue with them. So we've undertranslated it here to not skew the focus.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Te ngaa abhu pèri-pèri dhèu nèti partei Parisi, mai ka'ugu ètu madha ana-ana madhutu Yesus, peka na, &lt;&lt;Nga tao ka mese miu madhèdi na'a-ninu dènge dhèu-dhèu dhu guna boe se, nuka sèmi dhèu roro bea dènge angalai ra dhu bhelu-katub'a sèra?&gt;&gt;<bt>But there were several people from the Farisi party, who came complaining to Yesus' underlings saying, &lt;&lt;Why does your-p teacher sit eating (doublet) together with useless people, like those tax collectors and their evil friends?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ka'ugu = comel"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">ka'ugu = comel</Message></Annotation><note reference="9:10-11" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lukas 15:1-2</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Te ngaa Yesus peka dènge rèngu, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu pèd'a parluu dote-matarii, te ngaa dhèu dhu pèd'a boe parluu boe.<bt>But Yesus told them, saying, &lt;&lt;Sick people need a doctor, but people who are healed, don't need one.</bt><v n="13" />Be'a risi lami parisa paie-iie Lii Holo-Nori Ama Lamatua. Te uru èèna, Na pua Hosea, ca dhèu nèti lii padhai Na, dhu suri peka na,<bt>It's better if you-p go home to carefully examine God's Words. Cuz (elaboration) previously He ordered His spokesperson Hosea to write saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;Dad'èi Ja'a nuka,<bt>&lt;My desire is for,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">dhèu-dhèu Ja'a hud'i pasue ku èci dènge èci, aa pad'elo rasa kasia.<bt>My people to love each other and show mercy/pity.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ladhe ra tao boe madhutu sèmi èèna, na,<bt>If they don't do that, na,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">badha korban rèngu dhu rèti hia Ja'a,<bt>those animal sacrifices of theirs which they bring to give to Me,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">dènge boe kab'ua.&gt;<bt>don't have any meaning/value.&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ne'e ne ka dhu Ama Lamatua peka tèke le. Nèti èèna ka, Ja'a mai boe ho uri dhèu dhu pangee na, rèngu dhèu mola, te ngaa Ja'a mai sèna ka ladhe-leru dhèu dhu laku-laku boe.&gt;&gt;<bt>That is what God has said before. Because of that, I did not come to take.care.of people who consider themselves straight/righteous, but I came to take.care.of2 people who are not good/counted (considered worthless).&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Lula mamai Ja'a ne, lalau boe"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">Lula mamai Ja'a ne, lalau boe dhèu dhu ra pangee na ngi'u ra mola, te ngaa mamai Ja'a sèna ka ladhe-leru dhèu-dhèu dhu sala</Message></Annotation><note reference="9:13" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 12:7, Hosea 6:6</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu karèi, nga tao ka ana madhutu Lamatua Yesus puasa boe<bt>People ask why the Lord Yesus' underlings do not fast</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 2:18-22; Lukas 5:33-39)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Èle èèna ka, ana madhutu Yohanis tuka sarani sèra, mai sa Yesus. Dhèu se karèi, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ji'i dhu madhutu Yohanis tema puasa. Aa dhèu Parisi puasa kahèi. Te ngaa tasamia ka ana madhutu Ama sèra loe boe ra'a-rinu? Rèngu re'a boe puasa, do?&gt;&gt;<bt>After that, Yohanis the habitual baptizer's *disciples (underlings) came to Yesus. They asked, saying, &lt;&lt;We-ex who follow Yohanis usually/often fast. And Parisi people also fast. But why do Father's underlings repeatedly eat-drink all the time? They don't know how to fast, right?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Te ngaa Yesus dhaa dènge lii pakasame, na, &lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e: ladhe pesta kab'i, tamu sèra puasa boe, te ngaa ra'a toke bècu. Ladhe pengantin mone dènge rèngu era, aa'i-aa'i ra ra'a-rinu palere-lere. Te ngaa ladhe dhèu leo rai rèti ka pengantin mone ne, hèia mone aanga-angalai Na, d'ara ra susa, de heka ra puasa kèna.<bt>But Yesus responded to them, using a comparison, saying, &lt;&lt;It's like this: if/when there is a wedding feast, the guests don't fast, but they eat until satisfied/full. If/when the bridegroom is still there with them, they all eat festively together. But if/when other people capture run off with that bridegroom, then his friends feel troubled first, so (consequently) only then do they fast.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pengantin mone = bridegroom"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">pengantin mone = bridegroom</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Dhèu bisa boe rare bèla hiu ca èta, ho kalape mi kodho dhui dhu mae. Te ropa base kodho ne, bèla hiu dhu kalape la'a deo na karuku, na kodho deo na asa mae aae.<bt>People do not take a piece of new cloth, in.order.to patch it onto a old shirt which is ripped. Cuz (elaboration) later when they wash that shirt, that aforementioned new cloth patch will shrink, and that old shirt will rip even more.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />J'ara sèmi èèna kahèi, dènge dhua dhu heka rèti mai nèti kapua, bisa boe bhori asa d'ara sabha dhui. Te aad'o na sabha ne madhore, hèia dhua bhori eele asa rai la'e. De dhua dhu hiu hud'i bhori ku asa d'ara sabha hiu, sèna ka dua ra be'a taruu!&gt;&gt;<bt>Like that also, with palmwine they've just taken (=tapped) people don't pour it into old/decaying palmwine containers. Cuz (elaboration) surely that palmwine container will crack/leak, and the palmwine will all trickle out. So (consequently), new palmwine must be poured into palmwine containers which are new, in.order.that the two of them both continue to be good!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="soli soo-soo = pour out"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">soli soo-soo = pour out</Message></Annotation><note reference="9:17" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Sasuri lii Yunani dhu uru èèna, peka na, &lt;&lt;baku isi èi anggor hiu asa d'ara tas ka'uri dhui, ho baku d'ai na mae.&gt;&gt;<bt>The original Greek language writings say, “don't fill new grape.wine into old skin bags, , so that it doesn't crack and tear.”</bt></note>[Dènge sèmi ne'e, Yesus nori si, peka na, a'aj'a Na dhu hiu, baku pakihu dènge a'aj'a dhu dhui.]<bt>[With that Yesus taught them that His new teaching should not be mixed with old teaching/s.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus puri-pa'èle ina ca dhèu dhu pèd'a dhèu bhèni, aa pamamuri hari ana bhèni ca dhèu<bt>The Lord Yesus heals (doublet) a woman who is sick with a woman's sickness, and brings back to life a young girl</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 5:21-43; Lukas 8:40-56)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Ètu d'ara Yesus padhai lii era dènge ana madhutu Yohanis sèra, hèia kapala nèti èmu manèngi-mangaj'i mai paraga dènge Ne. Ka na patitu kètu urutuu ètu madha Yesus. Hèia na manèngi, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama, ee! Sue ku ja'a la! Te ana bhèni ja'a heka madhe kèna. De lati ho Ama bane ai mi ana ne, sèna ka na mamuri hari.&gt;&gt;<bt>[CHECK /bane/] While Yesus was still talking with Yohanis' underlings, then a head of a worship house (*synagogue) came to meet with Him. And he knelt before Yesus. And he asked, saying, &lt;&lt;Father, ee! Pity/love me (normal =Please help)! Cuz (elaboration) my daughter just died. So (consequently) let's go so Father (=You) place hand/s on the child, so she can live again.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bane "><Message author="Chuck" created="2009-11-25 06:28:06Z" status="Anyone">Can touch, not just hover</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Ropa Na tadèngi, hèia Yesus dènge ana madhutu Na, madhutu dènge ka dhèu deo na.<bt>When He heard, then Yesus and his underlings went straight.away with that person.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20-21" />Ètu talora j'ara, ca dhèu ina kako la'e madhutu si. Bhèni ne lèke papèd'a bhèni, dhu loe boe ciki sa d'ai canguru dua tèu kèna. Na pangee, na, &lt;&lt;Sad'i ja'a gai lèke kodho Yesus di, tatu èi papèd'a ja'a ne èle.&gt;&gt; Nèti èèna ka, na ara padètu la'e, hèia na gai lèke suu kodho Yesus.<bt>In the middle of the road/way/ journey, there was a mother/woman who walked following them. This woman had a female sickness that had not stopped a little for already 12 years. She was thinking that, &lt;&lt;As long as I can just touch Yesus' robe/shirt, surely my disease/infirmity/ ailment will disappear.&gt;&gt; That's why she went forward and approached then touched the edge of Yesus' robe/shirt.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Yesus dhu ne'a, hèia Na kabib'a, ladhe sa ina ne. Ka Na lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ina, ee! Pa'èra la d'ara èu. Te, lula èu parcaya Ja'a tare'a-re'a, nèti èèna ka èu èle nèti papèd'a.&gt;&gt; Hèia bhèni ne èle dènge ka.<bt>Yesus knew/felt [it], then He turned his face, to see that woman. Next, He spoke saying, &lt;&lt;Mother, ee! [+term of affection, for non-family; Gk daughter doesn't work here] Strengthen your insides. [=be encouraged] Cuz (elaboration), because you really believe in Me, that's why you are healed of your disease.&gt;&gt; Then, that woman became well/healed straight away.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Èle ka, Yesus si lasi taruu asa èmu nèti kapala èmu manèngi-mangaj'i èèna. D'ai era nèi, maso la'e asa d'ara, hèia Na ladhe nèdhi dhèu dhu tema karihu musiik mamadhe, dènge dhèu ae dhu tangi d'ara pèd'a.<bt>After that, Yesus (coll.) walked on to that head of worship house's house. Arriving there, [He] entered inside and saw the (habitual/professional) death music performers, and many people crying in grief. [EXEG: NLT, CEV, TRT, TN]</bt><v n="24" />Te ngaa Yesus peka dènge ra, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ae eele ka tangi, aa lami ka èmu miu! Te ana ne madhe boe, dhoka na bhèj'i di.&gt;&gt; Te ngaa dhèu se mari dènge pakapengo hèb'a mi Yesus.<bt>But Yesus told them, saying, &lt;&lt;Stop crying, and go to your-pl homes (=imperative)! Cuz (elaboration) this child is not dead, she is only just sleeping.&gt;&gt; But these people laughed with bent mouths (=ridicule) at Yesus.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mari pakapengo panyoro ; mari dènge"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">mari pakapengo panyoro ; mari dènge pakapengo hèb'a</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Èle ka, dhèu se aa'i-aa'i lasi asa li'u. Ka Yesus maso asa d'ara kama ana bhèni ne. Na kèpe ai ana ne, hèia ana ne mamuri dènge ka.<bt>After that, those people all left. Then2 Yesus entered into that girl's room. He held/took the child's hand, and then that child lived straight.away.</bt><v n="26" />Ropa ladhe rèdhi j'ara ne, ka dhèu mulai palolo lème ètu kabarai ra, lula-nèti ngaa dhu Yesus tao ne.<bt>When they saw that, then2 people began to tell all around their district (vague scope, but defined by inhabitants), about what Yesus had done there/to her.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus puri-pa'èle dhèu bèdhu dhèu dua<bt>The Lord Yesus heals (doublet) two blind people</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Èle, hèia Yesus kako taruu. Ètu talora j'ara, abhu dhèu bèdhu dhèu dua dhu madhutu Ne. Dua ra rodhe, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ana-èpu dhèu aae Daud! Sue ku ji'i la!&gt;&gt;<bt>Afterwards then Yesus walked on. In the middle of the way/journey, there were two blind people following along after Him. The two of them were yelling out, saying, &lt;&lt;King Daud's descendant! Love/Pity us!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Ropa Yesus maso asa d'ara èmu cue, dhèu bèdhu se lasi paraga dènge Ne. Ka Yesus karèi dua ra, peka na, &lt;&lt;Miu se lèka tare'a-re'a, na, Ja'a ne dènge koasa ho puri-pa'èle miu, sèna ka bisa ladhe mèdhi, do?&gt;&gt;<bt>When Yesus entered into a house, those blind people came to meet with Him, Then Yesus asked the two of them, saying, &lt;&lt;Do you-p really believe2 that I have the power to heal (doublet) you, so that you can be able to see, [+tag]?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia dua ra dhaa, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama karèi ia ka, te ji'i dhu lèka mema-mema le.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then the two of them answered saying, &lt;&lt;Father (=You) don't ask anymore (=idiomatic way to say of course, you don't even need to ask), cuz (elaboration) we-exc already really believe2.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="29" />Ropa tadèngi lii dhaa dua ra, hèia Yesus g'ag'e musi madha ra, ka Na peka na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe sèmi èèna, na, j'aj'i ka madhutu parcaya miu.&gt;&gt;<bt>When [He] heard the response of the two of them, then Yesus touched their eyes, and He spoke saying, &lt;&lt;If it's like.that, na, may it happen according to your-pl belief.&gt;&gt;</bt><v n="30" />Yesus padhai lii èle, hèia dua ra ladhe rèdhi dènge ka. Te ngaa Yesus pasanèd'e si, peka na, &lt;&lt;Baku miu peka dènge ca dhèu sa, ngaa dhu j'aj'i le!&gt;&gt;<bt>Yesus finished speaking like.that, then the two of them were able to see straight.away. But Yesus reminded/warned them, saying, &lt;&lt;Don't tell even one person what has happened!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Te ngaa dhèu se taha rare boe d'ara ra. Ka ra kako palème kabarai èèna, lole dènge dhèu aa'i-aa'i, tatao Yesus mi rèngu dua ra.<bt>But these people couldn't restrain/ control their insides. Then2 they went all.around that area/district telling everyone that which Yesus had done to/for the two of them.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus puri-pa'èle dhèu lii aad'o<bt>The Lord Yesus heals (doublet) a voiceless person</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="32" />Ropa dhèu bèdhu se lasi, dhèu rèti dhèu leo hari èci asa Yesus. Dhèu ne bisa boe padhai lii, lula nidhu tao ne.<bt>When those blind people left, people brought another person to Yesus. That person could not talk, because he was afflicted by evil.spirit/s. [EXEG: Gk is not clear if it is 1) can't make a sound with voice, or 2) can make a sound but can't speak. Some local lgs distinguish. 2nd is safe choice. (Most don't address this explicitly, but implied by all sources).]</bt><v n="33" />Ropa ladhe nèdhi, hèia Yesus paredha nidhu kalua nèti dhèu lii aad'o ne. Nidhu èèna kalua, ka dhèu ne padhai lii dènge ka. Hèia dhèu ae ètu era èèna malaa, ka ra peka na, &lt;&lt;Ira ii! Èdhi dhèu Yahudi paraga tèdhi mèka madha j'ara sèmi ne'e ne!&gt;&gt;<bt>When [He] saw that, then Yesus ordered that evil.spirit/s to come out of that voiceless person. That evil.spirit came out, then2 that person could speak/converse straight away. Then many people in that place were very amazed, and they said, &lt;&lt;Ira ii! [+positive amazement] We-inc Yahudi people have never encountered anything like this before!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="34" />Te ngaa dhèu Parisi ka'uu, peka na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu aae nidhu ka dhu hia Ne koasa, sèna ka Na bisa babège eela nidhu.&gt;&gt;<bt>But the Parisi people complained, saying, &lt;&lt;The king of evil.spirits is the one who gives Him power so He can expel evil.spirit/s.&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="9:34" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 10:25, 12:24, Markus 3:22, Lukas 11:15</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus taha nare boe d'ara, ropa ladhe nèdhi dhèu ae sèra<bt>[CHECK sense] Lord Yesus cannot restrain [His] insides, seeing many people</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="taha nare boe dara = 1)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">taha nare boe dara = 1) rasa kasian, 2) mara</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="35" />Èle èèna ka, Yesus kako palème kota-kota dènge rae-rae, sèna ka aj'a-nori dhèu ètu d'ara èmu sabaj'a sèra. Na aj'a dhèu nèti Lii Holo-Nori Ama Lamatua, aa j'ara tasamia rèngu bisa j'aj'i dhèu unu Ama Lamatua. Na puri-pa'èle kahèi dhèu nèti papèd'a-tarègu ra.<bt>After that, Yesus went around to the (various) cities and villages, to teach (doublet) people in their houses of worship. He taught people from/about God's Words, and how they could become God's people. He also healed (doublet) people from their (various) diseases/infirmities (doublet). [EXEG: TN notes: Gk. disease: The literal Greek means “those who were sick.” sickness: The Greek here literally means “those who were weak.” This refers to those who were weak because they were sick. Unfortunately TB translate second literally, leading teams who look at it to think they are emotionally or socially weak. It's just a doublet saying the same thing na! Translate as various sorts of diseases.][NOTE to daughter translation: omit last clause if it skews the focus. The meaning of the Gk is already covered in the previous clause.]</bt><note reference="9:35" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 4:23, Markus 1:39, Lukas 4:44</note><v n="36" />Ropa Yesus ladhe nèdhi dhèu ae se, hèia Na taha nare boe d'ara, lula dhèu se re'a heka tao sèmi ngaa sa. Te rèngu nuka sèmi kahib'i-kalèbho dhu dènge boe dhèu madhenga.<bt>When Yesus saw those many people, then He could not restrain His insides, because the people did not know what to do. Cuz (elaboration) they were like sheep who do not have a shepherd. [EXEG: NRSV, NLT, CEV, etc. TB unfortunately says “lelah” which throws some teams off. The English gloss “helpless” is much better, reflecting the Gk sense of being oppressed and without guidance. The TN display is disappointing in going in the same direction as the TB. Follow the KM here.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="roe capa lèpa = sangat lelah,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">roe capa lèpa = sangat lelah, lemah, tidak berdaya</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ula dhèu se roe capa lèpa,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">ula dhèu se roe capa lèpa, re'a heka tao sèmi ngaa sa, nuka sèmi kahib'i-kalebho dhu dènge boe dhèu madhenga.</Message></Annotation><note reference="9:36" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Sensus 27:17, 1 Dhèu Aae sèra 22:17, 2 Sejara nèti Isra'el dènge Yahuda 18:16, Yeskial 34:5, Sakaria 10:2, Markus 6:34</note><v n="37" />Èle ka, Yesus padhai lii dènge ana madhutu Na, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu ae se, nuka sèmi nganga'a ae-ae ètu d'ara oka-tedhe. Masi ka nganga'a ae titu kèna, te ngaa dhèu sab'a d'ai boe ho puu-g'ètu, sèna ka tèke asa d'ara gud'a.<bt>Then Yesus spoke with His underlings, saying, &lt;&lt;These many people here, are like food in the fields (doublet). [NOTE: this is how you refer to food-crops in Dhao.] Even though the food is much/alot, nevertheless the workers are not sufficient/ enough to harvest (doublet) it, to store it in the warehouse (assimilated loan). [EXEG: Gk is ambiguous if the harvest is in one field, or in many fields. Err on the side of the latter, with the picture of a wealthy landowner who has to manage the challenging task of harvesting from many fields in scattered locations.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="isi rai = hasil ; gud'a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">isi rai = hasil ; gud'a = gudang</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Dhèu ae se, èci èèna ka"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">Dhèu ae se, èci èèna ka dènge oka-tedhe dhu isi rai ra ae titu kena. Masi ka isi rai ae, te ngaa dhèu sab'a dai boe, ho puu-g'ètu sèna ka tèke asa dara gud'a.</Message></Annotation><note reference="9:37-38" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lukas 10:2</note><v n="38" />Nèti èèna ka, miu hud'i manèngi ku mi Lamatua oka, sèna ka Na tabha hari dhèu sab'a, ho lasi puu-g'ètu isi oka se.&gt;&gt;<bt>Because of that, you-p must request that field/'s Master/Lord/Owner, so He sends even more workers, so they can go harvest (doublet) the contents of his fields.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus hag'e nare ana madhutu Na canguru dua dhèu<bt>The Lord Yesus chooses/sets aside (from a group of similar things) His underlings 12 people</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 3:13-19; Lukas 6:12-16)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="10" />
      <v n="1" />Èle ka, Yesus paroa ana madhutu Na, sèna ka mai pakaboko. Hèia Na hia si koasa ho babège eele nidhu aa puri-pa'èle dhèu nèti papèd'a-tarègu ra.<bt>After that, Yesus called/summoned his underlings (*disciples) to come gather together. Then He gave them power/authority to expel evil.spirit/s and to heal (doublet) people from all kinds of sicknesses (doublet).</bt><v n="2" />Ana madhutu Na dhu Na pua sèra, dhèu canguru dua, nuka:<bt>His 12 underlings whom He commissioned, are: [EXEG: Gk uses ‘disciple’ in vs.1, but ‘apostle’ in vs.2; we keep disciple for referent tracking, but use verbal form ‘commission’ to resonate with /dhèu pua-paleha/ ‘apostle’.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Partama, ngara na Simon (dhu dhèu tema paroa ne, &lt;Petrus&gt;),<bt>The first [is] named Simon (whom usually people refer.to/call, saying, &lt;Petrus&gt;),</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">dènge ari na, Anderias,<bt>with his younger sibling Anderias,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Yakobis,<bt>Yakobis,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">dènge ari na, Yohanis (dua ra ana Sabadeus),<bt>with his younger sibling Yohanis (these two are Sabadius' children).</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">
      <v n="3" />Pelipus,<bt>Pilipus,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Bertolomeos,<bt>Bartolomeos.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Tomas,<bt>Tomas,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Mateos (dhèu roro doi bea),<bt>Mateos (the tax collector).</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Yakobis dhu leo (nuka ana Alpius),<bt>Yakobis (that is, Alpius' child),</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Tadius,<bt>Tadius,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">
      <v n="4" />Simon (nèti partei politik Selot),<bt>Simon (from the Selot political party),</bt><note reference="10:4" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Partei Selot ne, tenge j'ara ho neo mardeka nèti paredha Roma. Ra pangare partei ne &lt;Patriot&gt; kahèi.<bt>This Selot party, was looking for a way for them to be independent (loan) from Roma's government. They also named this party 'Patriot'.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">dènge Yudas Iskariot (dhu èèna na pahie Yesus).<bt>and Yudas Iskariot (who later sold away [=betrayed] Yesus).</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus pua ana madhutu Na, lasi pakako sasab'a-la'a Na<bt>The Lord Yesus sends/commisions His underlings to go carry out His work</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 6:7-13; Lukas 9:1-6)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5-6" />Èle èèna ka, Yesus pua ana madhutu Na canguru dua dhèu sèra, aa paredha si, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a pua miu lami asa dhèu èdhi dhèu Yahudi sèra, lula ae nèti rèngu dhu madhutu boe j'ara mamuri Ama Lamatua dènge mola. Rèngu cakaraa kahib'i-kalèbho dhu sala j'ara. Nèti èèna ka, baku lami asa dhèu Yahudi boe, nuka sèmi dhèu Samaria.<bt>After that, Yesus sent/commissioned his 12 underlings and He commanded, saying, &lt;&lt;I'm sending/commissioning you-p to go to our-inc Yahudi people, because many of them do not truly follow God's straight/right life way. They are like sheep who have lost their way/path. Because of that, don't go to non-Yahudi people, such as the Samaria people.</bt><v n="7" />Lami peka dènge dhèu Isra'el èdhi sèra, na, &lt;Ne'e ne, d'ai lod'o kèna, sèna ka dhèu aa'i-aa'i ra bisa j'aj'i dhèu unu Ama Lamatua.&gt;<bt>Go tell our-inc Isra'el people, saying, &lt;The time has now arrived, so that all people can become God's people.&gt;</bt><v n="8" />Aa lami puri-pa'èle dhèu pèd'a, pamamuri hari dhèu madhe, pa'èle dhèu kusta, aa babège eele nidhu. Ama Lamatua hia le miu ae-ae, te ngaa Na manèngi hari boe ca ana maa sa. De lami ka ho pala pa'ae-ae mi dhèu leo, te ngaa mage mi manèngi hari ngaa-ngaa kahèi.<bt>And go heal (doublet) the sick people, make the dead people live again, heal the leprosy people, and expel evil.spirit/s. God has already given much to you-pl, and/but He doesn't ask anything in return. So (consequently), now go give a great much to other people, but you don't need to ask anything in return from them either. [EXEG: Gk here has no object so seems to leave open the possibility that demons could be cast out of places as well as people. If your lg requires an object, use people; otherwise leave it vague as Gk.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ca ana maa sa = satu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">ca ana maa sa = satu remi sa</Message></Annotation><v n="9" />Pakèd'i dènge ai hua. Baku mèti doi,<bt>Leave with empty hand (=don't take anything). It's not necessary to/don't take money,</bt><v n="10" />gee j'ara, mèdha silu, salapa, do tatea. Te dhèu hud'i hia ku dhèu sab'a, ngaa dhu pantas ho ra bisa mamuri.<bt>travel.food, clothes to change (= extra clothes), footwear, or walking.stick. Cuz (elaboration) people must give workers, what is appropriate for them to be able to live.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gee j'ara = bakal"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">gee j'ara = bakal</Message></Annotation><note reference="10:10" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">1 Korintus 9:14, 1 Timotius 5:18</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Ladhe miu maso asa d'ara kota do rae èci, na, miu hud'i tenge ku dhèu dhu neo sèmi rare miu. Hèia miu pea ètu èmu èèna, toke miu pakèd'i tèke eele era èèna.<bt>If/when you enter into a city, or, a village, na, you-p must look for people/person who wants to receive you. Then, stay in that house, until you depart leaving that place.</bt><v n="12" />Ladhe miu maso asa d'ara èmu dhèu, peka la dènge rèngu, &lt;Saloom! Lamatua hia miu mèngi-nale.&gt;<bt>If/when you enter into someone's house, speak to them, &lt;Peace {|iSaloom|r} [common Christian greeting in Indonesia giving contrast to Islamic ‘salamu aleikum’]! The Lord give blessing/s to you-p.&gt;</bt><v n="13" />Ladhe dhèu ètu d'ara èmu ne, sèmi rare miu dènge be'a, na, miu manèngi sèna ka Lamatua hia si berkat. Te ngaa ladhe ra ro'o boe sèmi rare miu, na, Lamatua hia boe rèngu berkat.<bt>If people/person in that house recieve you well, na, you ask that God2 give blessing to them. But if they don't receive you, na, God2 also does/will not give blessing to them.</bt><v n="14" />Ladhe dhèu ro'o boe nanene lii padhai miu, mi kalua nèti èmu èèna, do kota èèna, hèia miu caro eele ahu nèti haga miu, sèna ka j'aj'i mi tadha, peka na, ladhe ro'o boe nanene, pe rèngu d'ui rare pala ra.<bt>[CHECK kahaku] If people/person does not want to listen to you, go out from that house, or that city, then brush off throw away the dust from your feet/leg, to be a sign, saying, if they don't want to listen, later they will bear their own portion (risk, punishment). [EXEG: See Acts, Morris.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kahaku = kabás ; kahèku ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">kahaku = kabás ; kahèku = kipas (kb, kk) ; juku = dorong, tolak</Message></Annotation><note reference="10:14" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 13:51</note><v n="15" />Bèli-camèd'a, lod'o Ama Lamatua huku dhèu ètu rai-haha ne'e, tatu Na pabia mi dhèu Sodom dènge Gomora dhu uru èèna bhelu titu kèna. Te ngaa sanèd'e! Èèna na, Nèngu huku bia risi hari mi dhèu dhu ro'o boe sèmi rare miu!&gt;&gt;<bt>Later when God judges/punishes humans on this world, surely He will be more severe to those prior time Sodom and Gomora people who were so very evil. But remember! Later He will punish even more severely people who do not want to accept/recieve you!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pabia = kasi barát"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">pabia = kasi barát</Message></Annotation><note reference="10:7-15" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lukas 10:4-12, Mateos 11:24, Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 19:24-28</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus pasanèd'e ana madhutu Na, èèna na rèngu dui j'aj'èra [\s2]<bt>The Lord Yesus reminds/warns His underlings [that] later they will experience suffering [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 13:9-13; Lukas 21:12-17)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />&lt;&lt;Sanèd'e paie! Te Ja'a pua miu ne, èci èèna ka Ja'a patabuli kahib'i-kalèbho asa talora aae busa hui. Nèti èèna ka, ngangee miu hud'i sèmi mege dhu d'èlu-mèu. Aa d'ara mi hud'i mola ku nuka sèmi koro j'aha dhu ne'a boe tenge lii langu.<bt>&lt;&lt;Remember well! Cuz (elaboration) I send/commission you-p here as if I was releasing sheep into the middle of wild dogs. Because of that, your thinking must be like snakes who are clever. And your insides also must be straight (=honest) like dove/pidgeon birds who don't know how to create issues/disputes.</bt><note reference="10:16" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lukas 10:3</note><v n="17" />Te ngaa baku pamud'e! Te bèli-camèd'a dhèu paj'èra miu, sama sèmi busa hui kadhi pamadhe kahib'i-kalèbho. Èèna na, rèngu nuni rèti miu asa era parisa lii langu agama. Aa dhèu hake paparu miu ètu d'ara èmu sabaj'a.<bt>But be careful! Cuz (elaboration) later people will mistreat you-p, like wild dogs bite to death sheep. Later they will drag take you into the place for examining religious litigations. And people will whip/hit/swing.at you in their worship house(s).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hake paparu = beat repeatedly"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">hake paparu = beat repeatedly</Message></Annotation><v n="18" />Pe rèngu ère rèti miu asa madha gubernur dènge dhèu aae, lula miu madhutu Ja'a. Te ngaa miu hud'i pake lod'o sèra, ho peka-padhai dènge ra Lii Lolo Be'a nèti Ja'a. Dènge j'ara ne'e, dhèu dhu tadhe boe Ama Lamatua tadèngi kahèi kolongara Ja'a ne.<bt>Later2 they will drag2 take you to face/report.to governor/s and king/s, because you follow Me. But you must use that time/opportunity to tell My Good News to them. In that way, people who do not know God also will be able to hear about My name/reputation.</bt><v n="19" />Te ngaa ladhe rèngu nuni rèti miu sèmi èèna, mage miu madha'u, peka na, &lt;Èèna na, ja'a peka tasamia?&gt; Do, &lt;Ja'a neo dhaa peka sèmi ngaa?&gt; Baku j'aj'i mi ngangee, te ladhe d'ai lod'o na, Ama mi ètu sorga ka dhu peka dènge miu, nèti j'ara mia ka dhu miu hud'i peka-padhai.<bt>But if/when they drag take you like.that, you don't need to be afraid, saying, &lt;Later how should I talk?&gt; Or, &lt;I am going to respond saying what?&gt; Don't become thinking/worried, cuz (elaboration) when the time comes, your Father in heaven will tell how you must speak.</bt><v n="20" />Lod'o èèna, ngaa dhu miu padhai, mai boe nèti d'ara miu unu mi, te Roh Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci èèna ka dhu aj'a-nori ètu d'ara miu, sèna ka miu padhai sèmi ngaa sa.<bt>At that time,. what you say does not come from you-pl yourselves, cuz (elaboration) God2's Holy Spirit is the one who teaches/instructs (doublet) you what to say.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Aa Roh Na dhu Mola-Mèci Na,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">Aa Roh Na dhu Mola-Mèci Na, ka dhu aj'a-nori miu se padhai lii.</Message></Annotation><note reference="10:17-20" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Markus 13:9-11, Lukas 12:11-12, 21:12-15</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Sanèd'e, te bèli-camèd'a ètu d'ara èmu cue, ladhe abhu ca dhèu parcaya Ja'a, èèna na a'ari nèngu mesa na, ka dhu tenge j'ara ho pamadhe ne. Aa ladhe ana ka dhu parcaya, èèna na ama na ka dhu pamadhe ne. Ladhe ina-ama ka dhu parcaya, bèli-camèd'a ana-ana ra ka dhu pamadhe si.<bt>Remember, cuz (elaboration) in the future within one house, if there is a person who believes in Me, later his/her own sibling/s are the ones who will look for a way to kill him/her. And if a child is the one who believes, later [it will be] his/her father who kills him/her. If the mother-father (=parents) believe, later [it will be] their own children who kill them.</bt><note reference="10:21" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Markus 13:12, Lukas 21:16</note><v n="22" />Sanèd'e! Te bèli-camèd'a dhèu aa'i-aa'i tèka d'ara dènge miu, lula miu parcaya Ja'a ne. Te ngaa dhèu dhu taha taruu, èèna na Ama Lamatua hia ne mamuri.<bt>Remember! Cuz (elaboration), later all people will hate/want revenge on you-p, because you believe in Me. But the person who endures continually, God will save him/her.</bt><note reference="10:22" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 24:9, 13, Markus 13:13, Lukas 21:17</note><v n="23" />Ladhe dhèu paj'èra miu ètu d'ara kota cue, rai lami asa kota leo! Lèke kèna! Ja'a ne Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a. Bèli-camèd'a ropa miu palème aa'i mèka kota-kota ètu Isra'el, te ngaa Ja'a dhu lèpa hari mai le èèna.<bt>If people mistreat you-p in one city, run/flee to another city. That true! I here am The Ideal/Prototypical Human. Later you=p still will not have finished travelling around to all the Isra'el cities, nevertheless I will already have returned/come back.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Biasa dhèu pakab'ua ca dhèu mese risi nèti ana sakola na sèra. Aa dhèu pakab'ua ca dhèu lamatua risi nèti ènu na sèra.<bt>People normally respect a teacher more than his pupils. And people respect a master/owner more than his slaves.</bt><note reference="10:24" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lukas 6:40, Yohanis 13:16, 15:20</note><v n="25" />Ladhe ana sakola mèu sama sèmi mese na, nèngu pangee na d'ai le. Aa ladhe ènu d'èlu-mèu sama sèmi lamatua na, nèngu ngee na d'ai le.<bt>If a pupil has studied to the same skill as his/her teacher, s/he feels enough/ satisfied. And if a slave has studied (doublet) to the same as his/her master/owner, s/he also feels enough/satisfied.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">De sanèd'e paie! Ladhe dhèu paroa lamatua èmu, peka na, &lt;Èu ne, Baalsebul, dhèu aae nidhu!&gt; tatu isi èmu na abhu kolongara dhu karehe risi hari.&gt;&gt;<bt>So (consequently) remember well! If people have called a house owner/master, saying, &lt;You here, are Balsebul, that is the king of evil.spirits!&gt; surely his household will also get an even worse name/reputation yet.&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="10:25" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 9:34, 12:24, Markus 3:22, Lukas 11:15</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Baku madha'u dènge dhèu rai-haha, te Ama Lamatua ka dhu sanoro miu [\s2]<bt>Don't fear humans, cuz (elaboration) God is the one guarding/protecting you [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Lukas 12:2-7)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />&lt;&lt;De miu baku madha'u dènge dhèu dhu lab'a miu. Te, ngaa dhu dhèu tao pahuni, bèli-camèd'a dhèu aa'i-aa'i ladhe rèdhi.<bt>&lt;&lt;So (consequently), you-p don't need to be afraid of people who oppose you. Cuz (elaboration) what people do in secret, later all people will get to see [it].</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sanoro = jaga, lindungi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">sanoro = jaga, lindungi</Message></Annotation><note reference="10:26" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Markus 4:22, Lukas 8:17</note><v n="27" />Ngaa dhu Ja'a aj'a-nori le miu mesa mi, miu hud'i lami lole ku mi dhèu aa'i-aa'i. Aa ngaa dhu Ja'a paholo le dènge miu, miu se hud'i lami peka ku palème era.<bt>What I have taught (doublet) you alone/by.yourselves, you must go tell all people. And what I have told quietly, you must go tell [it] all around in all places.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="paholo = bisik"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">paholo = bisik</Message></Annotation><v n="28" />Baku madha'u dènge dhèu rai-haha, te rèngu bisa dhoka pamadhe ngi'u aae dhèu di, te ngaa bisa boe pa'ele iie samanga. Nèti èèna ka, miu hud'i madha'u ku dènge Ama Lamatua, te dhoka Nèngu di dhu dènge koasa ho pamaso ngi'u aae dhèu dènge samanga kateme, asa d'ara dhasi ai dhu heo na loe boe ciki sa.<bt>Don't be afraid of humans, cuz (elaboration) they can only just kill a person's body, but they cannot destroy a person's soul/spirit/life force. Because of that, you-p must be afraid of God, cuz (elaboration) He alone [is the one] who has the power/authority to put a person's body and his spirit/soul into the sea/ocean of fire which burn unceasingly.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="saruru = manyala kecil hampir padam"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">saruru = manyala kecil hampir padam</Message></Annotation><v n="29" />De pa'èra d'ara miu. Dhèu pahie ana mangungu ètu d'ara pasa dènge kab'ua ciki oo'e di. Te ngaa ci'u sa bisa boe madhe, ladhe Ama mi ètu sorga no'o mèka.<bt>So (consequently) strengthen/encourage your insides (=be encouraged). People sell sparrow-like birds [local variety, similar size and behaviour] in the market for only the very cheapest price. But there is not even one tail [counter for birds] who dies, if your-p Father in heaven does not yet want/allow.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ana mangungu = burung pipit, small,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">ana mangungu = burung pipit, small, lots of them, eat grain and grass seed (finch?)</Message></Annotation><v n="30" />Ama miu ètu sorga dhu loe boe ladhe-leru miu, toke j'ara-j'ara dhu ana iiki-iiki. D'ai rèu kètu ètu kab'a kètu miu, Na ige nare aa'i hèi.<bt>Your-p Father in heaven also does not cease to attend/watch over (doublet) you-p down to the smallest matter. Even your hair strands number on your head, He has counted them all.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="patae = stare, mata tidak berkedip"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">patae = stare, mata tidak berkedip</Message></Annotation><v n="31" />De baku madha'u! Lula Ama Lamatua pakab'ua miu risi nèti ana mangungu aa'i-aa'i ra.&gt;&gt;<bt>So (consequently), don't be afraid. Because God values you more than all those sparrow-like birds.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Baku makae mangaku Lamatua Yesus [\s2]<bt>Don't be embarrassed to acknowledge the Lord Yesus [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Lukas 12:8-9)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="32" />Hèia Yesus tuhu hari lii padhai Na, peka na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu dhu bani mangaku Ja'a ètu madha dhèu ae ètu rai-haha ne, pe Ja'a kahèi mangaku nèngu ètu katanga madha Ama Ku ètu sorga, peka na, &lt;Nèngu ne dhèu Ja'a.&gt;<bt>Then Yesus continued speaking, saying, &lt;&lt;The person who dares acknowledge Me in front of many people on earth here, later I also will acknowlege knowing him in front of My Father in heaven, saying, &lt;He here is My person.&gt;</bt><v n="33" />Te ngaa dhèu dhu pasili Ja'a ètu madha dhèu ae, peka na nèngu tadhe boe Ja'a, bèli-camèd'a Ja'a peka dènge Ama Ku ètu sorga kahèi, na, &lt;Ja'a tadhe boe dhèu ne'e.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>But the person who deny.knowing Me in front of many people, saying he/she doesn't know/recognise Me, later I also will tell My Father in heaven, saying, &lt;I don't know/recognise this person.&gt;&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="10:33" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">2 Timotius 2:12</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus mai nèti boe dame, te ngaa patao-palaha [\s2]<bt>The Lord Yesus does not come to bring peace, but dissension (doublet) [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Lukas 12:51-53, 14:26-27)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="34" />&lt;&lt;Mage mi pangee na, Ja'a ne mai kèti dame asa rai-haha ne. Te mamai Ja'a ne, sèna ka dhèu rai-haha ne èci lab'a èci.<bt>&lt;&lt;You-p don't/shouldn't think that, I came to bring peace to this world. Cuz (elaboration) My coming is so humans oppose each other.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dadame = kb"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">dadame = kb</Message></Annotation><v n="35" />Ja'a mai asa rai-haha ne, madhutu ngaa dhu dhèu rèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua peka tèke èèna,<bt>I came to this world following that which God's spokepersons had said ahead of time, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;Èèna na, ana mone lab'a ama na,<bt>&lt;Later male child will oppose his father,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">ana bhèni lab'a ina na,<bt>female child will oppose her mother,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">aa bhèni dhèu èmu ana na, lab'a ina nèti dhèu èmu na,<bt>and female child-in-law will oppose her mother-in-law,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="36" />te isi èmu mae-manyèla, lula èci lab'a èci.&gt;<bt>cuz (elaboration) a household itself will tear-destroy (doublet), because one opposes another.&gt;</bt><note reference="10:35-36" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mika 7:6</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="37" />De dhèu dhu neo madhutu Ja'a tare'a-re'a, nèngu hud'i sue ku Ja'a, <span class="Italic">risi</span> nèti aa'i-aa'i, risi nèti ina-ama na, aa risi nèti ana niki na. Ladhe aad'o, na, nèngu nia boe j'aj'i dhèu unu Ja'a.<bt>So (consequently), the person who really/truly wants to follow Me, he must love Me <span class="Italic">more</span> than everything; more than his mother-father (= class of parents), and more than his children. If not, na, s/he is not worthy of being My person.</bt><v n="38" />Te dhèu dhu neo madhutu Ja'a, te ngaa d'èi boe pasae j'aj'èra, nèngu nia boe j'aj'i dhèu unu Ja'a.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) the person who wants to follow Me, but doesn't want to shoulder.carry (=experience) suffering, s/he is not worthy/appropriate to be/become My person.</bt><note reference="10:38" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 16:24, Markus 8:34, Lukas 9:23</note><v n="39" />Dhèu dhu sadia madhe lula na madhutu Ja'a, bèli-camèd'a nèngu abhu mamuri taruu dènge Ama Lamatua. Te ngaa dhèu dhu dhoka neo mamuri hia ngi'u nèngu unu na, èèna na, mamuri na ele iia d'ara!&gt;&gt;<bt>The perosn who is ready/prepared to die because s/he follows Me, later s/he will get to live continually (OR get continual life) with God. But the person who only wants to live just for him/her.self, later that life of his/hers, will disappear/be lost pointlessly/without effort!&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="10:39" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 16:25, Markus 8:35, Lukas 9:24, 17:33, Yohanis 12:25</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Bèli-camèd'a Ama Lamatua b'ala ngaa dhu dhèu tao [\s2]<bt>Later God will reciprocate what people do [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 9:41)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="40" />&lt;&lt;Dhèu dhu sèmi nare miu dènge be'a, nèngu sèmi nare Ja'a kahèi. Aa dhèu dhu sèmi nare Ja'a, nèngu kahèi sèmi nare Ama Lamatua dhu pua Ja'a mai.<bt>&lt;&lt;The person who receives/accepts you well, s/he also receives/accepts Me. And the person who receives/accepts Me, s/he also receives/accepts God who sent/commissioned Me.</bt><note reference="10:40" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Markus 9:37, Lukas 9:48, 10:16, Yohanis 13:20</note><v n="41" />Dhèu dhu sèmi nare dhèu nèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua, lula na padhue-padhai Lii Holo-Nori Ama Lamatua, pe Lamatua b'ala nèngu sama sèmi Na b'ala mi ca dhèu nèti lii padhai Nèngu. Aa dhèu dhu sèmi nare ca dhèu d'ara mola, lula dhèu èèna madhutu tare'a-re'a dad'èi Ama Lamatua, pe Lamatua b'ala nèngu sama sèmi Na b'ala mi ca dhèu d'ara mola.<bt>The person who receives/accepts God's spokesperson, because that spokesperson is talking (doublet) about God Words/Message, later God will reciprocate/reward him/her the same as God reciprocates/rewards a spokesperson of His. And the person who receives/accepts a straight/righteous person, because that person is truly following God's will, later God will reciprocate him/her the same as God reciprocates a straight/ righteous person. [EXEG: “in the name of” = because he has the rank of, because he belongs to me; see word study for “name” (CEG-PPT)]</bt><v n="42" />Dhèu dhu sèmi nare ca dhèu dhu haha d'ai seli, lula nèngu madhutu Ja'a, tatu Ama Lamatua b'ala ne. Masi ka dhèu hia èi hua ca galaa di, tatu Ama Lamatua bhèlu boe ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>The person who receives the lowest/most insignificant person because s/he follows Me, surely God will reciprocate him/her. Even if it is only just gives one glass of plain/empty water (=plain water not tea or anything in it), certainly God will not forget him/her.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="èi hua ca galaa = aer"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">èi hua ca galaa = aer kosong</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yohanis tuka sarani pua ana madhutu na lasi asa Lamatua Yesus<bt>Yohanis the habitual baptizer sends his followers to go to the Lord Yesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Lukas 7:18-35)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="11" />
      <v n="1" />Ropa Yesus hia nare lii moa mi canguru dua ana madhutu Na, hèia Na la'e kako palème rae-rae ètu rai èèna, sèna ka aj'a dhèu ètu sèra. Aa Na peka-padhai Lii Lolo Be'a Ama Lamatua.<bt>When Yesus finished giving instructions to those 12 followers of His, then He went all.around the villages in that land/country, to teach people and tell God's Good News.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="2" />Lod'o èèna, Yohanis ètu d'ara bèdho. Ropa na tadèngi j'ara aa'i-aa'i dhu Yesus tao, hèia na pua ana madhutu na ho lasi karèi Yesus, peka na,<bt>At that time, Yohanis was in jail. When he heard all the things which Yesus did, then he ordered his followers to go ask Yesus, saying,</bt><v n="3" />&lt;&lt;Ama Lamatua dhu pajaji tèke le karèi nèti uru ka, na, Nèngu neo pua Kristus mai, sèna ka pala mamuri mi èdhi dhèu Yahudi. Ama ne, Kristus, do? Do, èdhi hud'i mate hari ku dhèu leo?&gt;&gt; Ka lasi karèi Yesus.<bt>&lt;&lt;God has promised beforehand from long ago, that, He is going to send Kristus to come to save us-inc Yahudi people. Father (=You, having John call Yesus Father is showing greater respect than just their kinship relationship calls for) here are Kristus, [tag question]? Or, must we-inc wait for yet another person?&gt;&gt; So they went and asked Yesus.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Ropa tadèngi nare, hèia Yesus dhaa, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Miu se tadèngi le, aa mèdhi unu mi dènge madha. De lèpa ho lami peka dènge Yohanis, aa'i-aa'i dhu j'aj'i, nuka sèmi ngaa dhu dhèu nèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua, Yesaya, suri tèke le, peka na:<bt>When [He] heard that, then Yesus replied, saying, &lt;&lt;You-p have heard and have seen with your eyes. So (consequently) go back to report to Yohanis, saying, everything has happened just like what God's spokesperson Yesaya has written ahead of time, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">
      <v n="5" />Dhèu bèdhu, ladhe rèdhi.<bt>Blind people, can see. [NOTE to daughter translations: If possible, get a rhythm going here in vs.5. No translations seem to put this in quotes.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Dhèu karuku, kèd'i kako.<bt>Lame people, get up (and) walk.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Dhèu pèd'a kusta, ka'uri ra milu hari.<bt>Leprosy sickness people, their skin is smooth again.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="milu = licin"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">milu = licin</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Dhèu katele-katipa, bisa tadèngi.<bt>Deaf people (doublet), can hear again.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Dhèu madhe, mamuri hari.<bt>Dead people, live again.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Dhèu unu aad'o, nanene Lii Lolo Be'a.<bt>Poor people, hear Good News.</bt><note reference="11:5" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 35:5-6, 61:1</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />De sèmi ne'e: lami peka dènge Yohanis, bèli-camèd'a nèngu abhu a'oto, ladhe na parcaya Ja'a taruu. Nèti èèna ka, Ama Lamatua hia mèngi-nale mi dhèu dhu parcaya Ja'a pa'èra-èra!&gt;&gt;<bt>So (consequently), it's like this: go tell Yohanis, later he will be fortunate if he believes continually in Me. That is why God gives blessing/s to the person who believes strongly/firmly in Me!&gt;&gt; [EXEG: LN] [NOTE: TB missed the meaning of the two key Gk words in this verse.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Ropa ana madhutu Yohanis se lèpa, hèia Yesus peka dènge dhèu ae se, lula-nèti Yohanis ne, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Lod'o miu neo paraga dènge Yohanis ètu d'ara pad'a sod'a, miu pangee, na, neo paraga dènge dhèu dhu sèmi ngaa sa? Tatu boe, miu paraga dènge dhèu dhu roe aala-aala, nuka sèmi kalai èèu dhu bhabheu madhutu ngèlu di!<bt>When Yohanis' underlings had gone back/home, then Yesus spoke with many people about Yohanis, saying, &lt;&lt;When you-p went to meet with Yohanis in that lonely field over there, what kind of human did you think you would meet? Surely you would not go there to meet a person who is soft/pliable, like bamboo which sways back and forth just following the wind!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="roe aala-aala = sangat lemah, talalu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">roe aala-aala = sangat lemah, talalu noe (org yg iko arus) ; kalai èèu = bambu @@ PHONOLOGY ; hahed'u = sway, bounce (like carrying on a pole)</Message></Annotation><v n="8" />Aa tatu boe miu mèdhi dhèu dhu pake mèdha-papake dhu kab'ua aae, te dhèu sèmi èèna era pea na dhodhoka ètu d'ara èmu dhèu aae di!<bt>And surely you would not go there to see a person who wears/wore expensive clothing, cuz (elaboration) people like that only just live in kings' houses!</bt><v n="9" />De lami ladhe dhèu sèmi ngaa sa ètu nèi? Mi pangee na, miu lami tenge dhèu nèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua! Tare'a! Te nèngu ne, ca dhèu nèti lii padhai Lamatua dhu kapai risi.<bt>So (consequently), what kind of person did you go see there (remote)? Did you think you were going to find God's spokeperson? Correct! But he there is God2's spokesperson who is the greatest.</bt><v n="10" />Te ètu d'ara sasuri Ama Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci èèna, dhu suri tèke le lula-nèti Yohanis ne, peka na,<bt>Cuz (elaboration) the Scriptures have written beforehand about Yohanis, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;Nanene! Ja'a pua dhèu Ja'a,<bt>&lt;Listen! I am sending/commissioning My person,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">sèna ka bhoke j'ara hia Èu.&gt;<bt>to go open the path/road/way for You.&gt;</bt><note reference="11:10" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Meliaki 3:1</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Nanene paie! Ètu rai-haha ne, abhu boe ca dhèu sa dhu kapai risi nèti Yohanis ne. Te ngaa nèti dhèu rai-haha aa'i-aa'i dhu mangaku Ama Lamatua sama sèmi Dhèu Aae, dhèu dhu haha d'ai seli èèna ka, nèngu dhu kapai risi nèti Yohanis.<bt>Listen carefully! In this world, there is not a single person, who is greater than Yohanis. But among all the people who acknowledge God as King, the person who is the lowest/most insignificant is already more great than Yohanis.</bt><v n="12" />Karèi nèti Yohanis pakako sasab'a na, d'ai sange ne'e ne, abhu dhèu ae-ae dhu j'aj'i le dhèu unu Ama Lamatua. Te ngaa abhu dhèu leo dhu pangee sala, peka na rèngu hud'i pamusu ku, sèna ka laka-seti dhèu ho j'aj'i dhèu unu Ama Lamatua.<bt>Starting from Yohanis beginning to carry out his work until now, there are many people who have entered becoming God-owned. But there are yet other people who think wrongly, saying, they must war/fight to force people to become God's people. [EXEG: M Crofts Consultant Notes.]</bt><v n="13" />Toke d'ai lod'o mamai Yohanis tuka sarani, èdhi dhèu Yahudi dhu tema madhutu atora Musa, dènge atora dhèu rèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua leo sèra.<bt>Until Yohanis the habitual baptizer's arrival, we-inc Yahudi people normally lived following Musa's regulations and God's spokespersons' regulations.</bt><note reference="11:12-13" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lukas 16:16</note><v n="14" />De parcaya la Ja'a! Yohanis ne, nuka Elia, dhu dhèu rèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua, peka mema le lula-nèti mamai na.<bt>So (consequently), just believe Me! This Yohanis is (like) Elia whom God's spokespersons have told about his arrival ahead of time.</bt><note reference="11:14" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Meliaki 4:5, Mateos 17:10-13, Markus 9:11-13</note><v n="15" />De dhu neo me'a mèu, hud'i nanene ku paie-iie!<bt>So (consequently), those who desire to understand well must listen well!</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Ja'a neo hia lii pakasame, sèna ka miu me'a, rupa sèmi mia ka dhèu taa limuri ne. Te rèngu se cakaraa dènge ana-ana dhu madhèdi ètu d'ara pasa. Rèngu dhu pa'oo-parodha dènge angalai ra, peka na,<bt>I want to give an example/comparison so that you-p know, what kind of humans people nowadays are. Cuz (elaboration) they are like children who are sitting around at the market. They are calling out (doublet) back and forth with their friends, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="17" />&lt;Ji'i aa'i-aa'i mi tiu sakino dènge karej'e-karae,<bt>&lt;We-exc blow flutes really joyously (doublet),</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">te ngaa miu roge-ledho boe.<bt>but you-p don't dance (doublet).</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Hèia ji'i sod'a lii beke dhèu madhe,<bt>Then we sing mournful song/s for the dead,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">te ngaa miu tangi boe.&gt;<bt>but you don't cry.&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Miu se sama sèmi ana iiki dhu re'a boe roca. Lod'o Yohanis mai, nèngu d'èi puasa, aa ninu boe èi anggor. Te ngaa dhèu peka na, &lt;Nèngu, nidhu tao!&gt;<bt>You(pl) here are like small children who can't be pleased/satisfied. When Yohanis came, he liked to fast and didn't drink wine. But people said, &lt;He is affected by evil.spirit/s!&gt;</bt><v n="19" />Te ngaa Ja'a, Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a ne, mai le. Ja'a puasa boe, aa kinu èi anggor. Te ngaa dhèu peka na, &lt;Nèngu èèna, dhèu gagoo-gagehu! Dhèu tema mahu bia! La'e pa'angalai dènge dhèu roro bea! Pa'èci dènge dhèu dhu laku-laku boe. Nèngu dhu ne'a boe makae!&gt; Te ngaa mi patadhe lii padhai Ja'a ne! Mamèu Ama Lamatua èèna, cèu ètu d'ara mamuri dhèu unu Na.&gt;&gt;<bt>But now I, the Ideal/Prototypical Human, have come. I do not fast and I drink wine. But people say, &lt;He is a gluttonous person (doublet)! And a heavy drunkard! He goes and makes friends with tax collectors! He joins together (=associates) with the worthless nobodies. He knows no shame! [carries the idea of lost his sense of his social position/responsibility and thrown away social norms]&gt; But you just note My words! God's cleverness/intelligence/wisdom is made visible/obvious in the lives of His people.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gagoo-gagehu = rakus, balalas"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">gagoo-gagehu = rakus, balalas</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu dhu d'èi boe sèmi rare Lamatua Yesus<bt>People who do not want to receive/accept the Lord Yesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Lukas 10:13-15)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Èle èèna ka, Lamatua Yesus pasanèd'e dhèu-dhèu dhu pea ètu pèri-pèri rae. Na tao le tadha-tadha malaa ae risi ètu nèi, te ngaa ro'o boe ae eele nèti sasala ra, ho madhutu j'ara mamuri Ama Lamatua dhu mola.<bt>After that, the Lord Yesus began to remind/warn people who were living in several villages. He had already done the most of various kinds of miracles there, but they did stop from/repent of their wrongs to follow God's life way which is straight/ true/right.</bt><v n="21" />Yesus jèke si, peka na, &lt;&lt;Heh! Miu dhèu Korasin, aa miu dhèu Betsaida! Mate unu miu! Bèli-camèd'a pasae mere mamadhe-mamopo! Ja'a tao le rupa-rupa tadha malaa ètu katanga madha miu, te ngaa miu mo'o boe parcaya Ama Lamatua. Masi ka miu dhèu Yahudi dhu peka na, miu tadhe Lamatua, te ngaa ladhe sèmi tadha malaa dhu Ja'a tao se'e ètu kota Tirus dènge kota Sidon, tatu nèbhu nare sange ne'e, dhèu-dhèu ètu sèra èle le ho'a, aa tèke eele le sasala-sasigo ra ho madhutu Ama Lamatua. Aa tatu ra pake le bèla mèdhi, dènge tao ahu mi kètu ho j'aj'i mi tadha, na, rèngu manyasa nèti sasala ra. Masi ka dhèu Tirus dènge dhèu Sidon sèra dhèu Yahudi boe, dhu mangaku na, tadhe Lamatua.<bt>Yesus scolded them, saying, &lt;&lt;Heh! [+critical] You Korasin people and Betsaida people! Watch.out! Later you-p will carry/experience disaster/misfortune (doublet)! I have done various miracles in front of you, but you-p do not want to believe in God. Even though you-p are Yahudi people, who say you know God2. However, if perchance [+hypothetical] those miracles which I have done were in Tirus city and Sidon city, certainly after all this time people there would have repented already and have left their wrongs (doublet) to follow God. And they also would surely wear dark/black (grieving) clothes, and put dust on top of their heads to be a sign saying they regret their wrongs. Even though these Tirus people and Sidon people are not Yahudi people who acknowledge knowing God2.</bt><note reference="11:21" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 23:1-18, Yeskial 26:1--28:26, Yoel 3:4-8, Amos 1:9-10, Sakaria 9:2-4</note><v n="22" />Ja'a monya boe! Bèli-camèd'a mèdhi unu mi! D'ai lod'o dhu Ama Lamatua pama'ète lii langu dhèu aa'i-aa'i ra, hahuku dhèu Tirus dènge dhèu Sidon samaa risi nèti hahuku miu.<bt>I'm not lying! Later you-p will see for yourselves! At the day/time when God decides all people's cases/litigations, Tirus people and Sidon people's judgement/punishment will still be lighter/more lenient than your judgement/punishment.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="samaa = ringan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z" status="Anyone">samaa = ringan</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Miu dhèu Kapernaum! Mage-mage, ee! Mage mi pangee, na, Ama Lamatua paca'e miu lami asa sorga. Aad'o! Èèna na Lamatua pèci mi asa d'ara naraka! Ladhe sèmi tadha-tadha malaa dhu Ja'a tao ètu rae miu dhu j'aj'i uuru le ètu kota Sodom, tatu Ama Lamatua parluu boe labhu pakèpu kota èèna. Te ladhe dhèu Sodom rèdhi tadha malaa se, tatu ra rai eele le nèti bhabhelu-katub'a ra.<bt>You Kapernaum people! Watch out, ee! Don't think that God will take you up to enter into heaven. No! Later the Lord will throw you away into hell! If perchance [+hypothetical] those various miracles which I did in your village, had happened before in Sodom city, God would certainly not have needed to have burned up that city there. Cuz (elaboration) if Sodom people had seen those miracles, surely they would have left behind their evil (doublet).</bt><note reference="11:23" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 14:13-15, Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 19:24-28</note><v n="24" />Tare'a! Pe mèdhi unu mi! Ladhe d'ai ka lod'o Ama Lamatua pama'ète lii langu dhèu aa'i-aa'i, hahuku dhèu Sodom samaa risi nèti hahuku miu se!&gt;&gt;<bt>True! Later you will see for yourselves! When arrives the day/time when God decides all people's cases/litigations, Sodom people's judgement/punishment will still be far more light/lenient than your judgement/punishment!&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="11:24" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 10:15, Lukas 10:12</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus gale dhèu sèna ka madhutu Ne, ho Na pa'èra hari si<bt>The Lord Yesus invites people to follow Him, so they can become strong again</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Lukas 10:21-22)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Ropa padhai lii nare, hèia Yesus sabaj'a, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Ama dhu j'aj'i Lamatua ètu dedha-liru dènge rai-haha. Ja'a manèngi makasi ae-ae, lula Ama pahuni pamèno-mèno j'ara-j'ara dhu Ama hia huku mi dhèu-dhèu dhu pangee na, rèngu d'èlu-mèu, aa dhu padedha iisi ra. Te ngaa Ama bhoke patalele j'ara se'e aa'i-aa'i mi dhèu haha dènge dhu pahaha iisi ra.<bt>After finishing speaking, then Yesus prayed, saying, &lt;&lt;Father! Father (=You) are Lord/Master in heaven and on earth. I give many thanks, because Father has truly hidden the matters/ways of Father punishing people who consider themselves smart/wise/knowledgable, and who elevate themselves (=proud, arrogant). But Father has revealed all these things to the low (=insignificant) people, and the people who humble themselves.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pamèno-mèno = sekeras-kerasnya ; patalele -"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">pamèno-mèno = sekeras-kerasnya ; patalele - terbuka lebar/luas</Message></Annotation><v n="26" />Tare'a, Ama! Te sèmi èèna ka, dhu pakarej'e d'ara Ama!&gt;&gt;<bt>It's true, Father! Cuz (elaboration) things like that are what makes Father's insides happy!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Ropa sabaj'a nare, hèia Yesus peka dènge dhèu-dhèu ètu sèra, na, &lt;&lt;Nanene paie-iie! Ama Ku ètu sorga pangèd'u le koasa aa'i-aa'i mi Ja'a ne. Dhu tadhe mèu Ja'a, dhoka Ama ku di. Aa dhu tadhe mèu Ama, dhoka Ana Na, nuka Ja'a ne. Aa Ja'a hag'e kore dhèu leo, sèna ka peka dènge ra, ho rèngu tadhe mèu Ne kahèi.<bt>After finishing praying, then Yesus psoke to the people there, saying, &lt;&lt;Listen carefully! My Father in heaven has given/entrusted all power/authority to Me. The one who knows Me well, is only just Father. And the one who knows Father well, is only just His Child, which is Me. And I choose other people, in.order.to tell them, so that they can also know Him well.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kabhili = pili"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">kabhili = pili</Message></Annotation><note reference="11:27" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yohanis 3:35, 1:18, 10:15</note></p>
    <fig path="HK-LB\HK00019C.tif" rtfFormat="width:7.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left">Sapi luku<bt>Yoked cows pulling plow</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Miu aa'i-aa'i mi dhu roe lula sab'a bia, mai madhutu Ja'a! Aa miu aa'i-aa'i mi dhu pasae bia, mai la asa Ja'a!<bt>You all who are tired/weary of working hard, come follow Me! You all who shoulder.carrying heavy problems, come here to Me!</bt><v n="29" />Ladhe miu sèmi mere a'aj'a Ja'a, ho kako palere-lere dènge Ja'a, na, èdhi ca ropa dènge sapi dua ngi'u dhu nuni kataka pare rai èci. Te Ja'a ne, d'ara hua iia, aa lii mako. Ladhe miu madhutu Ja'a, miu j'aj'i èra hari.<bt>If you receive/ accept My teaching in.order to walk accompanying Me, na, we-inc are like two bodies (=counter for animals) of cows who are pulling together one plow. Cuz (elaboration) I here, have good insides (=kindhearted, generous), and am kind/gentle/gracious. If you follow Me, na, you will become strong again.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kataka = kapak ; kataka pare"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">kataka = kapak ; kataka pare rai = pacul, bajak</Message></Annotation><note reference="11:29" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yermia 6:16</note><v n="30" />Lula a'aj'a Ja'a, carui boe. Aa paredha Ja'a, bia boe kahèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>Because My teaching is not difficult/impossible. And My commands, are not heavy either.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu pasisu dènge Lamatua Yesus lula-nèti lod'o ae sasab'a<bt>People criticize/at odds with the Lord Yesus about the day of stopping work (*Sabbath)</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 2:23-28; Lukas 6:1-5)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="12" />
      <v n="1" />Ca lod'o, lèke dènge ae sasab'a dhèu Yahudi, Yesus dènge ana-ana madhutu Na dhu kako re karasa oka dhèu. Ana madhutu Na manganga, hèia ra g'ètu are-gandum ka ra'a noo-noo.<bt>One time/day, occuring on the Yahudi people's day of stopping work, Yesus and His followers were walking along by someone's garden. His followers were hungry, so they hand.stripped rice-wheat (generic-specific) grainheads and ate as they walked along.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ra'a noo-noo = eat as you"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">ra'a noo-noo = eat as you walk</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Ètu èèna, abhu pèri-pèri dhèu nèti partei agama Parisi dhu madhutu pa'èra ad'a dhèu Yahudi ra. Ropa ladhe rèdhi ana madhutu Yesus se tao sèmi èèna, hèia ra kai Ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ana madhutu Mu, g'ètu gandum lèke dènge lod'o ae sasab'a-la'a! Rèngu baku tao sèmi ne'e! Te tatao ne sisu atora èdhi.&gt;&gt;<bt>There, there were several people from the Parisi religious party who followed strongly their Yahudi customs. When they saw Yesus' folowers do like.that, then they scolded/rebuked Him, saying, &lt;&lt;Your {Mu = somewhat disrepectful -- but appropriate to this context} followers are picking wheat on the day of stopping work! They should not do like.that! Cuz (elaboration) that behaviour violates our-inc regulations.&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="12:1" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 23:25</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3-4" />Te ngaa Yesus b'ala, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Tasamia, ee? Miu teko bhèlu lii lolo Daud, si? Daud dènge ana-ana madhutu na dhu manganga titu kèna. Hèia na maso asa d'ara Paleo Manèngi-Mangaj'i Ama Lamatua, ka nare roti dhu ama agama hia le mi Lamatua, ka rèngu ra'a. Te ngaa dhu bisa ra'e roti se dhodhoka ama agama sèra. Dhèu leo bisa boe. Èle ka Daud si ra'a, te ngaa ca dhèu sa pasala boe si. Miu nuka sèmi dhèu dhu baca mèdhi boe sasuri Lii Holo-Nori Ama Lamatua!<bt>But Yesus responded, saying, &lt;&lt;How is it? You haven't forgotten that story of Daud's, [+tag]? Daud and his followers' were very hungry. Then he entered into God's Worship Tent (*Tabernacle), and took the bread which the religion heads (*priests) had already given to God2, and they ate. But the ones who could eat that bread were only just the religion heads. Other people weren't allowed. Then grandfather Daud (coll.) ate [it], but no one accused/blamed them. You-pl are as if you have never read the Scriptures!</bt><note reference="12:3-4" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">1 Samuel 21:1-6, Atora nèti Ama-ama Agama 24:9</note><v n="5" />Te ètu d'ara sasuri èèna, suri kahèi nèti sasab'a ama agama Yahudi sèra, ètu d'ara èmu sabaj'a, lèke dènge lod'o ae sasab'a. Te ngaa rèngu sala boe ngaa-ngaa.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) those writings it is also written about the work of the *priests (religion heads) in the worship house, falling on the day/s of stopping work/rest. But they are doing nothing wrong.</bt><note reference="12:5" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Sensus 28:9-10</note><v n="6" />Nanene! Uru èèna, èmu sabaj'a ka dhu kab'ua, te ngaa limuri ne abhu dhu kab'ua risi, nuka Ja'a ne, Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a.<bt>Listen! Previously, [it was] the worship house that was important/valuable, but now there is something even more important/valuable, that is Me, the Ideal/Prototypical Human.</bt><v n="7" />Ètu d'ara Sasuri Mola-Mèci Ama Lamatua, Na peka na, &lt;Dad'èi Ja'a sèmi ne'e: dhèu Ja'a sèra hud'i pad'elo ku rasa kasia èci dènge èci. Ladhe ra tao boe madhutu j'ara ne, na, badha korban dhu rèngu rèti hia Ja'a, dènge boe kab'ua.&gt; De ladhe miu me'a mèu sasoa nèti lii padhai Lamatua ne, tatu miu pasala boe ana madhutu Ja'a se. Te ra tao boe sala ngaa-ngaa!<bt>In the Scriptures, God says, &lt;My will/desire is like this: My people must show mercy/pity to each other. If they don't do like that, na, those animal offerings of theirs which they bring to Me, do not have any meaning/value at all.&gt; So (consequently), if you truly understand that speaking of God2's, surely you will not accuse my followers of wrong. Cuz (elaboration) they have not done anything wrong!</bt><note reference="12:7" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 9:13, Hosea 6:6</note><v n="8" />Te Ja'a ne, Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a. Ja'a ka dhu dènge hak ho pama'ète, peka na, dhèu bisa sab'a ngaa, lèke dènge lod'o ae sasab'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>Cuz (elaboration) I here am the Ideal/Prototypical Human. I am the One who has right/ authority to decide what people may do/work on the day of stopping work/rest.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua puri-pa'èle dhèu, lèke dènge lod'o ae sasab'a-la'a<bt>The Lord Yesus heals a person, on the day of stopping work</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 3:1-6; Lukas 6:6-11)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Èle ka Yesus tèke eele era èèna, la'e asa d'ara èmu sabaj'a ra.<bt>After that Yesus left that place, going to their worship house.</bt><v n="10" />Ètu ne'e, abhu mone ca dhèu dhu kacui-aai madhe cabèka. Dhèu Parisi sèra dhu tenge-tenge j'ara ho pasala Yesus, ladhe sèmi Na puri-pa'èle dhèu dhu kacui-aai madhe cabèka ne, lèke dènge lod'o ae sasab'a. Hèia ra karèi Ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Madhutu atora agama èdhi, dhèu bisa puri-pa'èle dhèu, lèke dènge lod'o ae sasab'a-la'a, do aad'o?&gt;&gt;<bt>At there, there was a man whose hand/arm was dead on one side. Those Parisi people kept wanting to find a way to accuse/blame Yesus, if perchance [+hypothetical] He healed (doublet) that person whose arm was dead on one side, on the day of stopping work/rest. Then they asked Him, saying, &lt;&lt;According to our-inc religious regulations, can people heal (doublet) people on the day of stopping work, or not?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Hèia Yesus dhaa, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe kahib'i-kalèbho ci'u manahu asa d'ara ro'a, lèke dènge lod'o ae sasab'a, dhèu unu na mai name nare, sina ma?<bt>Then Yesus replied, saying, &lt;&lt;If a sheep (singular) fell into a hole on the day of stopping work, its owner would come lift up take out that sheep, wouldn't he {I expect you to agree with me}?</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="name = tarek kasi kaluar (not"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">name = tarek kasi kaluar (not inflected)</Message></Annotation><note reference="12:11" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lukas 14:5</note><v n="12" />De Ama Lamatua sue dhèu rai-haha, risi nèti dhèu unu kahib'i-kalèbho deo na. Nèti èèna ka, dhèu bisa tao j'ara dhu be'a lèke dènge lod'o ae sasab'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>So (consequently), God loves humans, more than that aforementioned sheep owner. Because of that, people can do good things on the day of stopping work.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Ka Na lii dènge dhèu dhu ai madhe cabèka na, &lt;&lt;J'ole kacui-aai èu mai!&gt;&gt; Hèia, na j'ole kacui-aai dhu madhe èèna, kaca'a la èle dènge ka, sama dènge kacui-aai dhu iia èèna.<bt>Next Yesus spoke with that person whose arm was dead on one side, &lt;&lt;Stretch out your arm this way!&gt;&gt; Then he extended that dead arm of his, and that arm was good straight away, the same as his arm on the other side.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Ropa dhèu Parisi se rèdhi sèmi èèna, hèia ra nasa titu kèna. Èle ka ra kalua tèke eele èmu sabaj'a ne, hèia lasi pare'a, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Èdhi hud'i tenge ku j'ara, sèna ka pamadhe Ne!&gt;&gt;<bt>When they saw that, those Parisi people were furious. Then3 they left that worship house (lexically leans toward ‘stalked out’), then they went to seek mutual agreement [with each other], saying, &lt;&lt;We-inc must find a way to kill Him!&gt;&gt; [EXEG: NLT, CEV]</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ama Lamatua dhu pili nare Yesus, sèna ka sab'a hia Ne<bt>[It is ] God who chose Yesus to work for Him</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Te ngaa Yesus dhu ne'a ngangee rèngu dhu karehe ne, nèti èèna ka la'e asa era leo. Dhèu ae madhutu Ne, hèia Na puri-pa'èle dhèu dhu pèd'a aa'i-aa'i.<bt>But Yesus knew that evil plan/thinking of theirs, that's why He went to another place. Many people followed Him, then He healed (doublet) all their sicknesses.</bt><v n="16" />Te ngaa Na kai si, peka na, &lt;&lt;Mage lami palolo kahèi dènge dhèu leo lula-nèti Ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>But He forbade them, saying, &lt;&lt;You-p may not tell other people about Me.&gt;&gt;</bt><v n="17" />Nèngu tao sèmi èèna, madhutu sèmi lii padhai Ama Lamatua dhu peka le mi dhèu nèti lii padhai Na, ngara na Yesaya, dhu suri tèke, na,<bt>He did like.that following that which God had already told His spokesperson Yesaya, who had written beforehand, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="18" />&lt;&lt;Ladhe ku laa! Nèngu ne, Dhèu pajuu-paleha Ja'a, dhu Ja'a hag'e kore le.<bt>&lt;&lt;Look! Here he is, My servant (doublet) whom I have chosen. [NOTE: don't capitalise needlessly in OT quotes -MC]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Ja'a sue Ne,<bt>I love Him,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">aa d'ara Ja'a karej'e taruu dènge Ne.<bt>and My insides are continually happy with Him.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Èèna na, Ja'a pangèd'u Ne Roh Ja'a,<bt>Later I will give2 My Spirit to Him,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">ho la'e aj'a-nori dhèu nèti suku aa'i-aa'i<bt>to go teach (doublet) people from all ethnic groups</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">lula-nèti j'ara mamuri Ja'a dhu mola.<bt>about My life path/way which is straight/just.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="19" />Nèngu ne, ne'a boe tèb'a kakara.<bt>He does not beat his chest (=be arrogant)</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Nèngu ne, ne'a boe padedha iisi.<bt>He does not lift himself up (=be arrogant).</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="20" />D'ara Na hua iia.<bt>He has a good2 insides (=kindhearted, generous).</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Dhu ne'a boe paj'èra dhèu.<bt>He doesn't cause difficulty/trouble to people.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Aj'u dhu oe padhe, Na lèku eele boe.<bt>Wood/stick/tree which is almost broken, He doesn't break it all the way.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="padhe = pata (result) ; lèku"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">padhe = pata (result) ; lèku = pata (kk)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Labhu dhu saruru, Na tiu pamadhe boe.<bt>A lantern which is almost flickering out, He doesn't blow it out.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="saruru = amper padam"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">saruru = amper padam</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Na loe boe aj'a-nori dhèu, toke dhèu aa'i-aa'i tao madhutu j'ara mamuri dhu mola nèti Ama Lamatua.<bt>He continually teaches (doublet) people, until eventually all people follow God's life path/way which is straight/just.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="21" />Dhèu nèti suku aa'i-aa'i èèna na parcaya Ne, lula re'a na, Nèngu ne, cee.&gt;&gt;<bt>People from all tribes/races will believe in Him, because they know who He is.&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="12:18-21" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 42:1-4</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Mese agama sèra peka na, dhèu aae nidhu ka dhu hia Yesus koasa<bt>Religious teachers say the king of evil spirits is the one who gives Yesus power/authority</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 3:20-30; Lukas 11:14-23)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Ca tèka, rèti asa Yesus ca dhèu dhu nidhu tao toke bèdhu aa ele lii. Hèia Yesus pa'èle ne dènge babège eele nidhu nèti dhèu ne'e. Ka dhèu ne bisa nèdhi, aa bisa padhai lii.<bt>Then one time, people brought to Yesus a person who was afflicted by evil.spirit/s until he was blind and could not speak. Then Yesus healed him, and expelled away that evil.spirit. Then2 that person could see and could speak.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rèti ca dh"><Message author="From Merge" created="2009-11-27 09:42:49Z" status="Anyone">Merge Conflict: Original was "dhèu rèti ca dhèu dhu nidhu tao toke bèdhu aa ele lii, asa Yesus"; Ours was "rèti ca dhèu dhu nidhu tao toke bèdhu aa ele lii, asa Yesus"; Theirs was "dhèu rèti asa Yesus ca dhèu dhu nidhu tao toke bèdhu aa ele lii"</Message></Annotation><v n="23" />Dhèu ae se, ropa rèdhi sèmi èèna, hèia ra malaa-maloha. Ra papeka na, &lt;&lt;Nèngu ne'e, ele boe ana-èpu Daud, dhu dhèu rèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua suri tèke karèi nèti uru ka! Nèngu ne'e, tatu Dhèu dhu èdhi mate tae-tae èèna!&gt;&gt;<bt>Those many people, when they saw that, then they were amazed (doublet). They conversed (w/each other), saying, &lt;&lt;Probably He here is Daud's descendant (doublet) whom God's spokespersons have written about from long ago. He here is surely that Person whom we-inc have been waiting and waiting for!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Te ngaa ropa dhèu Parisi tadèngi rare, hèia ra ro'o boe parcaya. Ka ra papeka, na, &lt;&lt;Wee! Dhèu ne bisa babège nidhu, lula dhèu aae nidhu Baalsebul ka dhu pangèd'u Na koasa.&gt;&gt;<bt>But when the Parisi people heard that, then they did not want to believe/accept [it]. And they spoke to each other, saying, &lt;&lt;Wee [+NEG]! This person can expel evil.spirit/s, because evil.spirits' king Balsebul is the one who gives2 that power/authority to Him.&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="12:24" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 9:34, 10:25</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Te ngaa Yesus ne'a lii padhai dhèu Parisi se. Hèia Na peka dènge dhèu se'e, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Lii padhai miu ne, lèke boe! Ladhe ètu d'ara rai cue, ana kabarai na patao-palaha, tasa mera mia ho rai ne bisa taha! Sèmi èèna kahèi, ladhe dhèu ètu d'ara kota èci, do d'ara èmu cue, èci patao dènge èci, tatu ra mae-manyèla, toke laho mae-mae, si!<bt>But Yesus knew that speaking of the Parisi people. And He told them, saying, &lt;&lt;That speaking of yours, is not right/correct! If inside one political.unit/country, the masses/citizens attack (doublet) each other, how can it be that that political.unit still can endure! Like that also, if people in one city, or in one house, are at odds with each other, surely they will be divided/fractioned (doublet) until they are completely destroyed!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="padhai-padhue = consultation aiming towards consensus"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">padhai-padhue = consultation aiming towards consensus</Message></Annotation><v n="26" />De ladhe nidhu pamusu dènge nidhu, aa palab'a èci dènge èci, tatu dhèu aae ra nèd'u paredha nèbhu boe!<bt>So (consequently), if evil.spirits are at war/fighting with evil spirits, and keep opposing each other, surely their king cannot hold power/rule much longer anymore.</bt><v n="27" />Sanèd'e paie! Dhèu miu re'a kahèi babège eele nidhu. Ra pake koasa nèti nidhu, do? Aad'o! De miu baku padhai lii ore dhu peka na, Ja'a pake koasa nidhu, ho babège eele nidhu. Pe dhèu miu unu mi ka dhu pama'ète, peka na, ngaa dhu miu galaa ne, lèke boe j'ara.<bt>Remember well! Your-p people also know how to expel evil.spirits. Do they use power from evil.spirits? No! So (consequently) you don't talk groundlessly/haphazardly/aimlessly, saying, I am using evil.spirits' power to expel evil.spirits. Later your very own people will be the ones who decide that what you accuse there, is not right/correct.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bata = usir"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">bata = usir</Message></Annotation><v n="28" />Te ngaa ladhe Ja'a tare'a-re'a babège eele nidhu pake koasa nèti Roh Ama Lamatua, èèna pad'elo na, Lamatua èèna tare'a-re'a Dhèu Aae dhu ètu le katanga madha miu.<bt>But if I truly expel evil.spirits using God's Spirit's power/authority, that shows that it is God2 who is truly King is right in front of your noses.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="29" />Ladhe dhèu neo lasi mana'u èmu dhèu èci dhu èra, nèngu hud'i èki-karadhe uuru ku dhèu lamatua èmu ne. Heka na mana'u nèti mèdha-panyau na sèra.<bt>If someone wants to come steal things in a strong person's house, he must completely tie up (doublet) that house-owner first. After that, only then he can steal away that person's thing/s.</bt><note reference="12:29" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Dènge sèmi èèna, Yesus peka na, Nèngu èra risi nèti dhèu aae nidhu, dhu ra paroa na &lt;Baalsebul&gt;.<bt>With that, Yesus told saying, He was stronger than the evil.sprit's king, whom they usually called ‘Balsebul’.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="30" />Sanèd'e, ee! Te dhèu dhu pa'èci boe dènge Ja'a, nèngu pamusu dènge Ja'a. Aa dhèu dhu soru-bara boe Ja'a ètu d'ara sab'a-la'a, nèngu ne'a dhoka pa'iu dhèu di.<bt>Remember, ee! Cuz (elaboration) the person who is not united/joined with Me, he is enemies with Me. And the person who does not help out (doublet) in My work, he there is only just making chaos (inciting people against each other, as in a cock fight).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pa'iu-pa'èki = ; pa'iu = ba'adu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z" status="Anyone">pa'iu-pa'èki = ; pa'iu = ba'adu</Message></Annotation><note reference="12:30" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Markus 9:40</note><v n="31" />De nanene paie-iie lii padhai Ja'a ne! Ama Lamatua dhu sadia saku eele sasala-sasigo dhèu. Ladhe dhèu padhai lii pakarehe kolongara dhèu leo, Ama Lamatua sadia abho ne era. Te ngaa ladhe abhu dhèu dhu bani padhai pakarehe Roh Ama Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci, Ama Lamatua saku eele boe sasala na èèna.<bt>So (consequently), listen carefully to this speaking of Mine! God is ready/prepared to wipe away people's wrongs (doublet). If people speak evil/ruining other people's name/reputation, God is still prepared to forgive him. But if there is someone who dares speak ruining/evil about the Clean/Holy Spirit of God's, God will not wipe away that sin of his.</bt><v n="32" />Ladhe dhèu pakarehe Ja'a, Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a ne, Ama Lamatua sadia saku eele sasala na. Te ngaa cee ka dhu bani padhai lii pahahe Roh Ama Lamatua, te ngaa Ama Lamatua saku eele boe sasala na, masi ka toke dai mia-mia la'e!&gt;&gt;<bt>If someone speaks evil about Me, the Ideal/Prototypical Human here, God is prepared to wipe away his wrong. But whoever dares to speak belittling/slandering God's Spirit, nevertheless [+contrary to expectation] God will not wipe away that wrong of his, even until forever going [svc]!&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="12:32" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lukas 12:10</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Aj'u dènge hua na<bt>A tree and its fruit</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Lukas 6:43-45)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="33" />Hèia Yesus padhai lii taruu dènge dhèu Parisi se, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ngee paie-iie! Aj'u dhu be'a, hia hua dhu be'a. Te ngaa aj'u dhu karehe, hia hua dhu karehe. Nèti hua na, dhèu bisa tadhe aj'u ne, be'a do karehe.<bt>Then Yesus continued talking with those Parisi people, saying, &lt;&lt;Think carefully! A tree which is good produces fruit which is good. But a tree which is bad/rotten produces fruit which is bad/rotten. Because from its fruit, people can know/recognise whether that tree there is good or bad/rotten.</bt><note reference="12:33" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 7:20, Lukas 6:44</note><v n="34" />Te ngaa miu se ca ropa dènge mege, dhu ne'a dhoka kapod'e-kabèli di! Miu me'a boe padhai lii dhu be'a. Lula ngaa dhu tèke ètu d'ara, èèna ka dhu kalua mai nèti d'ara hèb'a na.<bt>But you here are like snakes who only know how to be twisters-turners (=deceivers)! You cannot speak of things which are good. Because whatever is stored.away in a person's insides, that is what later comes out of his/her mouth.</bt><note reference="12:34" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 3:7, 23:33, 15:18, Lukas 3:7, 6:45</note><v n="35" />Dhèu be'a, tatu lii padhai na be'a, lula ètu d'ara na abhu j'ara dhu be'a. Te ngaa dhèu bhelu, tatu lii padhai na karehe, lula ètu d'ara na dhu pènu dènge bhabhelu-katub'a.<bt>A good person, surely says what is good, because there are various good things stored in his insides. But an evil person, surely says what is evil/rotten, because there are evil (doublet) things filling up his insides.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="36" />Lèka la lii Ja'a ne! Te bèli-camèd'a lod'o èle rai-haha, Ama Lamatua parisa lii langu dhèu aa'i-aa'i. Lod'o èèna, dhèu èci-èci ka hud'i dhaa lii-lii nèngu dhu dènge boe kolo-kapua.<bt>Believe2 Me! Cuz (elaboration) later the end.of.the.world comes, God will examine all people's cases/litigations. At that time each/every person must respond/account for his/her words which do not have any purpose-reason (doublet; lit. tip-base).</bt><v n="37" />De mage-mage! Te bèli-camèd'a èèna, Ama Lamatua dadoo lii-lii miu sèra, aa pama'ète peka na, miu lèke huku do, aad'o.&gt;&gt;<bt>So (consequently) be careful! Cuz (elaboration) later God will weigh/consider your words, and decide whether you will be punished, or not.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dadoo = timbang, tatai"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">dadoo = timbang, tatai</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu manèngi sèna ka Lamatua Yesus pad'elo tadha malaa<bt>People request the Lord Yesus to show evidence</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 8:11-12; Lukas 11:29-32)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="38" />Ropa tadèngi lii padhai Yesus sèmi èèna, hèia pèri-pèri mese agama dènge dhèu Parisi, peka dènge Yesus, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama Mese! Ji'i neo ngèdhi tadha malaa èci, sèna ka j'aj'i mi tadha, peka na, koasa Ama, tare'a nèti Ama Lamatua.&gt;&gt;<bt>When they heard Yesus' speaking like that, there were several religion teachers and Parisi people who spoke with Yesus, saying, &lt;&lt;Father Teacher! We-exc want to see a miracle, as a sign that Your power really is from God.&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="12:38" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 16:1, Markus 8:11, Lukas 11:16</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="39" />Te ngaa Yesus jèke si, peka na, &lt;&lt;Weh! Miu dhèu taa limuri ne, mo'o boe madhutu Ama Lamatua! Miu se me'a dhodhoka ad'u-ue bhelu-katub'a di! Masi ka miu manèngi tadha malaa, te ngaa Ja'a tao boe. Lula uru èèna, Lamatua hia le tadha malaa re Yunus, dhèu nèti lii padhai Na. Èèna d'ai le!<bt>But Yesus scolded them, saying, &lt;&lt;Weh! [+negative] You people nowadays, don't want/like to follow/obey God! You want only to just do evil (doublet)! Even though you request miracles, nevertheless I won't do [them]. Because previously God2 already gave miracle/s by way of His spokesperson Yunus. That is enough!</bt><note reference="12:39" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 16:4, Markus 8:12</note><v n="40" />Yunus pea tèlu mèu-tèlu mèda ètu d'ara kabake i'a aae ci'u. Sèmi èèna kahèi dènge Ja'a, Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a ne. Bèli-camèd'a Ja'a kahèi ètu d'ara ro'a dhèu madhe, tèlu mèu-tèlu mèda.<bt>Yunus stayed three days, three nights [hyperbole/literary way of talking about historical/momentous events regardless of precision] inside the big fish's stomach/abdomen. That's similar to Me, this Ideal/Prototypical Human. Later I will stay three days, three nights in the rock hole/grave of the dead people.</bt><note reference="12:40" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yunus 1:17</note><v n="41" />Ladhe d'ai lod'o èle rai-haha ne, Lamatua j'aj'i hakim. Aa dhèu Niniwe se titu j'aj'i sakasii ho galaa miu, peka na, &lt;Miu aa'i-aa'i se, goa!&gt; Uru èèna, ropa dhèu Niniwe sèra tadèngi lii padhai Yunus, dhèu nèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua, hèia ra tèke eele sasala ra. Te ngaa miu sèmi boe èèna. Masi ka limuri ne, abhu le Dhèu ètu talora aae miu, dhu kapai risi nèti Yunus, nuka Ja'a ne. Te ngaa miu se pusi-pahae boe Ja'a ciki sa hèi.<bt>Later at the end.of.the.world, God2 will be judge (loan). And the Niniwe people will stand to be witness (assimilated loan) accusing you, saying, &lt;You all here are stupid/idiots!&gt; Previously, when those Niniwe people heard God's spokesperson Yunus, then they left behind their sins. But you don't/won't. Even though now there is a Person in your midst who is more amazing/impressive/ greater than Yunus, that's Me here. But you don't want to care.about/pay.attention.to (doublet) Me even a little bit.</bt><note reference="12:41" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yunus 3:5</note><v n="42" />Pe, ètu d'ara lod'o èle rai-haha ne, ladhe Lamatua j'aj'i hakim, bhèni aae Syeba nèti balèu, j'aj'i sakasii kahèi. Na paj'uj'u ai na mi miu, ho na galaa miu aa'i-aa'i dhu ana loo-limuri ne, peka na, &lt;Miu aa'i-aa'i mi, goa!&gt; Uru èèna, bhèni aae ne mai nèti rai kaj'èu ho neo nèdhi unu na mamèu dhèu aae Soleman. Te ngaa limuri ne, abhu ca Dhèu ètu talora aae miu dhu kapai risi nèti dhèu aae Soleman, nuka Ja'a ne. Te ngaa miu pusi-pahae boe Ja'a ciki sa hèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>Later at the end of the world, when God2 is judge, queen of Syeba from the south will also be a witness. She will point her finger at you-pl to accuse all of you who live nowadays, saying, &lt;You all here are stupid/idiots!&gt; Previously, that queen came from a far away land/country to see with her very own eyes king Soleman's skill/cleverness. But now there is a Person in your midst who is more amazing/impressive/greater than king Soleman, that's Me here. But you don't want to care. about/pay.attention.to (doublet) Me even a little bit.&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="12:42" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">1 Dhèu Aae sèra 10:1-10, 2 Sejara nèti Isra'el dènge Yahuda 9:1-12</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Nidhu lèpa hari asa dhèu dhu na pea nèdhi uru èèna<bt>The evil.spirit returns again to the person where he had once lived</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Lukas 11:24-26)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="43" />&lt;&lt;Ladhe babège eele nidhu nèti ca dhèu, nidhu ne la'e pea asa era dhu kaliu, ho j'aj'i mi era ae iisi na. Te ngaa abhu boe era dhu mèci ho na pea kalili.<bt>&lt;&lt;If an evil.spirit is expelled out of a person, that evil.spirit goes to live in a lonely place to look for a stopping/resting place. But he doesn't find a place that fits/is.appropriate for him to reside long-term.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kaliu = sunyi ; pea kalili="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">kaliu = sunyi ; pea kalili= tinggal tetap</Message><Message author="Chuck" created="2009-12-02 04:04:25Z" status="Anyone" /></Annotation><v n="44" />Hèia na pangee, peka na, &lt;Abhu boe era dhu be'a sèmi nèi, hua iia ja'a lèpa hari asa dhèu dhu uru èèna ja'a pea.&gt; Ka la'e hari asa era nèngu uru èèna. Na ladhe na, era ne mèu bia, aa dhu lalau rare pabe'a-be'a.<bt>Then he thinks, saying, &lt;&lt;There is no place better than that (remote in time/space/reference), [so] it's better I return again to that previous person where I stayed.&gt; And he returns to that previous place. He sees that place there, already clean and well-arranged.</bt><v n="45" />Hèia nidhu ne la'e paroa nare angalai na dhèu pidhu dhu bhabhelu ra risi nèti nèngu. Ka lasi pea ètu d'ara dhèu ne, hèia aa'i-aa'i ra kakeho ne. De limuri ne, mamuri dhèu ne asa ele iie-iie. Sèmi èèna kahèi lèke mi dhèu bhelu-katub'a taa limuri ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then that evil.spirit goes to call/summon his seven friends who are more evil than him. Next they go to stay inside that person, and they all gang.up on him. So (consequently) now that person's life is even more ruined. So it will also happen to/effect evil people in these times/era.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="madahu = 1) loosen up (tights"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">madahu = 1) loosen up (tights clumps of cotton) 2) karoyok, 3) swear at s.o.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kakeho "><Message author="Chuck" created="2009-11-26 02:05:06Z" status="Anyone">= stir up, mix up; make a mess of</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhu tare'a-re'a j'aj'i a'ari Lamatua Yesus<bt>The Lord Yesus' real family</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 3:31-35; Lukas 8:19-21)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="46" />Lod'o èèna, Yesus padhai lii era dènge dhèu ae. Hèia ina dènge ari Na sèra, mai neo paraga dènge Ne. Rèngu titu ètu li'u, ka ra pua dhèu lasi paroa Ne.<bt>At that time, Yesus was still conversing with many people. Then his mother and His younger.siblings came wanting to meet with Him. They stood outside (the house) and told someone to go call Him.</bt><v n="47" />Hèia dhèu mai peka dènge Ne, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Ina dènge ari Ama ètu li'u nèi. Rèngu neo paraga dènge Ama.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then the person came told Him, saying, &lt;&lt;Father! Father's (=Your) mother and younger.siblings are outside there. They want to meet with Father.&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="12:47" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Abhu sasuri lii Yunani cahag'e dhu suri boe ayat 47 ne.<bt>There are some Yunani language writings which do not carry this verse 47. [TEXT: see TH and TRT. Majority accepts this verse.]</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="48" />Ka Yesus peka dènge ra, &lt;&lt;Cee ka ina Ku, aa cee ka a'ari Ja'a dhu tare'a-re'a?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus said to them, &lt;&lt;Who is my real mother, and who are my real siblings (unmarked for relative age)?&gt;&gt;</bt><v n="49" />Hèia Na paj'uj'u asa dhèu-dhèu dhu madhutu Ne, ka Na lii, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Rèngu se'e se ka, ina dènge a'ari Ja'a.<bt>Then He pointed at the people who were following Him, and spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;These here are My mother and My siblings.</bt><v n="50" />Te dhèu dhu tao madhutu dad'èi Ama Ku ètu sorga, rèngu ka ina Ku aa a'ari Ja'a dhu tare'a-re'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>Cuz (elaboration) people who do according to My Father in heaven's will, they are My real family/siblings.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus hia lii pakasame nèti dhèu sèle hini ètu rupa-rupa rai<bt>The Lord Yesus gives an example/comparison about a person who plants seed in all.sorts.of soil/dirt</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 4:1-9; Lukas 8:4-8)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="13" />
      <v n="1" />Lod'o èèna kahèi, Yesus kalua nèti èmu èèna, la'e madhèdi asa sebhe dano Galilea.<bt>That day then Yesus went out of that house, to go sit at lake Galilea's edge.</bt><v n="2" />Hèia dhèu ae-ae mai lingu rare Ne. Ka la'e madhèdi asa dedha koha cue, dhu panahu ètu era èèna, ho aj'a dhèu sèra. Dhèu aa'i-aa'i ètu dae sèra nanene Ne.<bt>Then very many people came crowding around Him. Then He got up and went to sit on a boat which was anchored there, in.order.to teach the people. All those people on the land could hear Him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dae = darat, tepi pantai, shore"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">dae = darat, tepi pantai, shore</Message></Annotation><v n="3" />Hèia Na aj'a madha j'ara ae-ae mi rèngu pake lii pakasame. Na lole, peka na, &lt;&lt;Abhu ca dhèu sab'a oka-tedhe, dhu ceb'e hini ètu d'ara oka na.<bt>Then He taught alot of things/issues to them using examples/ comparisons. He storied, saying, &lt;&lt;There was person who went to work his/her garden/field/s (doublet), who scatter/sprinkle/broadcast seed in his garden/field.</bt><v n="4" />Ropa na ceb'e hini se, abhu dhu lèke ètu j'ara. Hèia manu-bhui mai, ka tutu ra'e aa'i hini se.<bt>When s/he scattered those seeds, there were some which fell on the path/road. Then birds came, and completely pecked up all those seeds.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Te ngaa hini cahag'e lèke ètu rai dhu dènge hadhu. Hini se muri malai, lula abhu rai ciki di.<bt>But there were some seeds which fell on the stony land. Those seeds sprouted quickly, because that land/soil was thin. [EXEG: Gk. conjunction here is /dia/ interpreted as a causal “because”, or “since”. If we were writing it ourselves, we probably wouldn't connect it that way, but here we're trying to reflect the Gk. The thought is that thin soil over rocks heats more quickly and triggers the growth process more quickly.]</bt><v n="6" />Te ngaa ropa lod'o rea, hèia ana aaj'u se kamale, ka mango eele si. Te amo ra marèma boe ètu d'ara rai.<bt>But when the sun rose, then those sprouts withered, and dried up (implication from serial verb construction - completely, hence died). Cuz (elaboration) their roots could not go down deep into the soil.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Abhu hini cahag'e dhu lèke ètu era j'u'u padhudhu. Hèia j'u'u padhudhu se hèlu pamadhe aa'i si.<bt>There were some other seeds which fell in the middle of thorny grass. Then that thorny grass pinched/grabbed/squeezed killing all of them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hèlu = 1) coil, 2) twist"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">hèlu = 1) coil, 2) twist around s.t.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Te ngaa abhu hini cahag'e lèke ètu rai isi. Hini se muri, ka ra kapai toke hua-hela. Abhu dhu tèlu nguru hari, abhu dhu èna nguru hari, aa abhu dhu d'ai cangasu hari.<bt>[CHECK common phrasing] But there were some other seeds which fell on the fertile land/soil. Those seeds sprouted, and then they grew until they produced yield. There were some which returned a yield thirty times, there were some sixty times, and there were some even up to a hundred times.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bèb'a = berkembang biak (hewan dan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">bèb'a = berkembang biak (hewan dan manusia)</Message></Annotation><note reference="13:2" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lukas 5:1-3</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Cee dhu dènge ro'a dhilu, na nanene paie-iie!&gt;&gt;<bt>Whoever has earholes, na, listen carefully!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Nga tao ka Lamatua Yesus d'èi aj'a pake lii pakasame<bt>The Lord Yesus explains why He like to teach using examples/comparisons</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 4:10-12; Lukas 8:9-10)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Èle èèna ka, ana madhutu Yesus mai karèi Ne, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Nga tao ka Ama aj'a dhèu ae pake lii pakasame?&gt;&gt;<bt>Afterwards Yesus' followers came to ask Him, saying, &lt;&lt;Why does Father (=You) teach many people using examples/comparisons?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Hèia Yesus dhaa, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Lula miu se neo me'a tare'a-re'a paredha Ama Lamatua, nèti èèna ka Ja'a peka mema sasoa nèti lii pakasame ne. Te ngaa mi dhèu leo, Ja'a aj'a pake lii pakasame.<bt>Then Yesus replied, saying, &lt;&lt;Because you-pl really want to understand God's commands, that's why I tell you straightaway the meaning of those examples. But for other people, I teach using examples.</bt><v n="12" />Te dhèu dhu tare'a-re'a neo re'a dad'èi Ama Lamatua, pe Lamatua hia ne asa ne'a ae. Te ngaa dhèu dhu pusi-pahae boe dad'èi Lamatua, pe Lamatua tao ne asa tabha goa.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) people who really wants to know God's will, later God2 will enable him/her to understand even more. But the person who doesn't have a concern for (doublet) God2's will, later God2 will make him/her increasingly stupid. [NOTE to daughter translations: try to reflect “increasingly wise... increasingly stupid”]</bt><note reference="13:12" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 25:29, Markus 4:25, Lukas 8:18, 19:26</note><v n="13" />Ja'a aj'a-nori si pake dhoka lii pakasame di, lula:<bt>I teach (doublet) them using only examples, because:</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;Rèngu rèdhi le,<bt>&lt;They have seen,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">te ngaa ro'o boe re'a.<bt>but don't want to know/understand.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Rèngu tadèngi le,<bt>They have heard,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">te ngaa ra pusi-pahae boe.&gt;<bt>but don't care (doublet).&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Rèngu se cakaraa dènge dhèu dhu Yesaya suri mema le. Yesaya èèna, nuka dhèu nèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua, dhu suri, na,<bt>They there are the same as people whom God's spokesperson Yesaya wrote about, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;Miu èèna na tadèngi,<bt>&lt;Later you-p will hear,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">te ngaa miu pakatele dhilu.<bt>but you deafen your ears.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Miu èèna na ladhe mèdhi,<bt>Later you will see,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">te ngaa mo'o boe pame'a ngaa dhu j'aj'i le.<bt>but you will not want to understand what happened.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="15" />Lula d'ara dhèu se'e adhu sèmi hadhu,<bt>Because these people's insides are hard like rock,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">ra pakatele dhilu ra,<bt>they deafen their ears,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">aa ra pabèdhu musi madha ra.<bt>they make their eyes blind.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">De hud'i rèngu sène, sèna ka ro'a dhilu ra katele-katipa,<bt>So (consequently), just leave/allow it so their ear-holes (idiomatic) become deaf (doublet),</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="katele-katipa = tuli kabekek (KM)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">katele-katipa = tuli kabekek (KM)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">aa soro tèke si, sèna ka musi madha ra bèdhu sèmi èèna.<bt>and just leave/allow2 it so their eyeballs (idiomatic) become blind just like that,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Hud'i laa, ho Ja'a puri-pa'èle ia ka si,<bt>Let it be, so I don't need to heal (doublet) them,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">lula rèngu pusi-pahae boe Ja'a.&gt;<bt>because they don't care/have.concern for (doublet) Me.&gt;</bt><note reference="13:14-15" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 6:9-10</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Te ngaa miu se, oto! Lula miu ladhe mèdhi dènge musi madha, aa tadèngi dènge ro'a dhilu miu unu mi.<bt>But you here, are fortunate! Because you have seen with your own eyeballs, and you have heard with your own earholes.</bt><v n="17" />Parcaya la Ja'a! Uru èèna, dhèu rèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua, dènge dhèu dhu d'ara mola, d'ara ra neo rèdhi ngaa dhu limuri ne miu ladhe mèdhi, te ngaa bisa boe. D'ara ra neo kahèi tadèngi ngaa dhu limuri ne miu tadèngi le, te ngaa bisa boe.&gt;&gt;<bt>Believe Me! Previously God's spokesperson/s and people who had straight insides (=righteous people) were yearning/longing to see what you have now seen, but they could not. They also yearned/longed to hear what you have now heard, but they could not.&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="13:16-17" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lukas 10:23-24</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus peka sasoa lii pakasame nèti hini<bt>The Lord Yesus tells the meaning of that example about seeds</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 4:13-20; Lukas 8:11-15)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Ropa padhai lii nare, hèia Yesus peka dènge ra, &lt;&lt;De mi nanene ka sasoa nèti lii pakasame deo na.<bt>After finishing speaking like.that, then Yesus told them, saying, &lt;&lt;So (consequently) listen to that recent example's meaning.</bt><v n="19" />Hini dhu lèke ètu j'ara, nuka dhèu dhu nanene Lii Holo-Nori nèti Ama Lamatua nèd'u paredha, te ngaa nèngu ne'a iia boe. Hèia dhèu aae nidhu mai parame nare Lii Holo-Nori nèti d'ara dhèu ne.<bt>The seed which fell on that road, are like a person who hears Words/Message/Instructions about God's ruling/governing, but he doesn't really understand [it]. Then the evil.spirit's king comes and snatches away those Words from that person's insides.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Hini dhu ceb'e lèke ètu rai dhu pènu dènge hadhu, nuka dhèu dhu nanene Lii Holo-Nori Ama Lamatua, hèia na sèmi nare dènge d'ara karej'e.<bt>The seed which fell on that stony land, is like a person who hears God's Words, then he accepts them with happy insides.</bt><v n="21" />Te ngaa Lii Holo-Nori ne, amo na marèma boe. Nèti èèna ka, nare boe nèbhu ètu d'ara dhèu ne. Ropa dhèu leo paj'èra ne lula na sèmi nare Lii Holo-Nori ne, ka dhèu ne kèpe pa'èra heka a'aj'a sèra.<bt>But those Words/Message its roots are not deep. That's why it doesn't last long in that person's insides. When other people cause trouble for him, because he accepted those Words, that person does not hold strongly to those teachings anymore (implication: easily abandons them).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="juku = tolak"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">juku = tolak</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Aa hini dhu lèke ètu talora aae j'u'u padhudhu, nuka dhèu dhu nanene Lii Holo-Nori. Te ngaa nèngu bhute dènge rupa-rupa j'ara, ho pakarej'e mamuri na. Hèia bhabhute se'e ka seti eele Lii Holo-Nori ne nèti d'ara nèngu, toke dènge heka kab'ua.<bt>And the seed which fell in the middle of that thorny grass, is like the person who has heard those Words/Message. But he/she is too preoccupied with many things to please his own life. Then all those busy-nesses, elbow out those Words from his/her insides, to the point that it doesn't have any more value/worth.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Te ngaa hini dhu lèke ètu rai isi, nuka dhèu dhu pasa paie dhilu na, sèna ka sèmi nare Lii Holo-Nori, aa tao madhutu dad'èi Lamatua. Hèia na tao j'ara-j'ara dhu be'a, sama sèmi hini dhu muri toke kapai, ka na hua ae-ae. Abhu dhu tèlu nguru hari, abhu kahèi èna nguru hari, aa abhu dhu d'ai cangasu hari.&gt;&gt;<bt>But the seed which fell on that fertile land/soil, is like the person who fastens his/her ears (=pays attention) in.order.to recieve that Word/Message, and to follow God2's will. Then he does (various) good things, like that seed which grew until it was big/mature, then bore much fruit/crop. There are some who returned thirty times, and also some forty times, and some even up to a hundred times.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus hia lii pakasame nèti j'u'u ètu talora aae oka<bt>The Lord Yesus gives an example about grass in the middle of the garden</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Yesus lolo hari lii pakasame èci, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Paredha Ama Lamatua ne, nuka sèmi abhu ca dhèu la'e ceb'e hini dhu be'a ètu d'ara oka na.<bt>Yesus told another example, saying, &lt;&lt;That governing/ruling of God's is like a person who scatters good seeds in his garden. [LEX: for ‘seed’ here defaults to grain types]</bt><v n="25" />D'ara mèda èèna, ropa dhèu aa'i-aa'i bhèj'i luu, hèia dhèu bhelu mai, ka na ceb'e lamusi j'u'u ètu d'ara oka ne.<bt>At night, when everyone is sleeping soundly, then evil people come, and scatter seeds of wild grass inside that garden.</bt><v n="26" />Ropa hini ètu d'ara oka ne d'ai hua-hela, hèia dhèu sab'a se, ladhe rèdhi j'u'u dhu muri palere-lere dènge hini se.<bt>When the seeds in that garden begin to produce crop/yield, then his workers see wild grass is growing together with those seeds/crops there.</bt><v n="27" />Ka lasi peka dènge lamatua oka ne, aku rèngu na, &lt;Ama! Ca hari ni ji'i sèle hini dhu be'a ètu d'ara oka ama, si? Nga tao ka muri mai pab'ali dènge j'u'u ae-ae?&gt;<bt>Then2 they go tell that garden's master/owner, saying, &lt;Father! Earlier we-exc planted seeds which are good in father's garden, right? So why now are we getting back a lot of grass?&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Lamatua oka ne dhaa, peka na, &lt;Èèna tatao nèti dhèu bhelu.&gt;<bt>That owner replied, saying, &lt;That, is evil person/s' work.&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia dhèu sab'a se peka, aku rèngu na, &lt;Ama, ji'i la'a ko'o eele j'u'u sèi, do?&gt;<bt>Then his workers suggested, saying, &lt;Father, should we go dig.up throw away that grass, ok?&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ko'o (2) = tofa (doesn't inflect)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">ko'o (2) = tofa (doesn't inflect)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="29" />Te ngaa na b'ala, peka na, &lt;Hud'i laa, te ladhe miu ko'o eele j'u'u se, ana nganga'a èdhi se lèke bete kahèi.<bt>But he responded, saying, &lt;Let it be, cuz (elaboration) if/when you dig.up that grass, later our-inc food plants will also get pulled up.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bete = cabut, also pull out"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">bete = cabut, also pull out plants</Message></Annotation><v n="30" />Hud'i rèngu sène ra muri palere-lere toke hèru puu-g'ètu. Pe d'ai lod'o na, ja'a peka dènge dhèu sab'a se, na, &lt;&lt;Miu pakaboko uru ku j'u'u sèra. Hèia èki si ca èki-ca èki ho tunu eele si. Èle ku, heka ta pakaboko isi oka kèna, sèna ka pamaso asa d'ara babesi.&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>[CHECK ta] Just leave it so they grow together until the harvest season. Later at that time, I will tell workers, saying, &lt;&lt;You gather first that wild grass. Then tie it in into individual wads, to burn it up. After that then let's gather the good harvest, and put it in the (large) store.house.&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ta = ti = èdhi ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">ta = ti = èdhi ; babesi = lumbung ukuran besar</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus pake lii pakasame nèti lamusi dhu ana iiki<bt>The Lord Yesus gives an example about seed which is very small</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 4:30-32; Lukas 13:18-19)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Èle, ka Yesus peka hari, na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a pake hari lii pakasame èci, sèna ka miu me'a tasamia Ama Lamatua j'aj'i Dhèu Aae mi dhèu ae-ae. Dhèu unu Na sèra, mulai nuka sèmi lamusi dhu ana iiki titu kèna, dhu dhèu sèle ètu d'ara oka na.<bt>After that, Yesus spoke again, saying, &lt;&lt;I add one more example, so you can understand how God becomes King to so many people. His people, start out like very tiny seed which a person plants in his/her garden.</bt><v n="32" />Masi ka lamusi ne ana iiki d'ai seli, te ngaa ladhe na muri mai, j'aj'i aj'u dhu kapai aae ètu d'ara oka ne. Toke manu-bhui tao rèd'a ètu dadana-dadana na.&gt;&gt;<bt>Even though that seed is the extremely small/tiny, nevertheless when it lives/grows/sprouts, it becomes a tree which is the largest/greatest in the garden. To the point that birds come make nests in its branches.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus pake lii pakasame nèti ragi<bt>The Lord Yesus gives an example about yeast (assimilated loan)</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Lukas 13:20-21)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="33" />Yesus peka hari lii pakasame èci, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu-dhèu unu Ama Lamatua, èci èèna ka dènge ragi dhu bhèni èci nare, pab'ali dènge tarigu ca sak.<bt>Yesus added another example, saying, &lt;&lt;God's people are also like yeast which a woman takes and mixes with a sack of flour.</bt><note reference="13:33" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Sasuri lii Yunani suri, peka na, &lt;&lt;tarigu tèlu σάτα (<span class="Italic">sata</span>)&gt;&gt;. <span class="Italic">Sata</span> èci, pe d'ai 12 liter. Tèlu <span class="Italic">sata</span>, pe d'ai 36 liter, nuka tarigu ca sak.<bt>Yunani language writings say, “three σάτα (sata) of flour”. One <span class="Italic">sata</span>, is approximately 12 litres. Three <span class="Italic">sata</span>, are approximately 36 litres, or, one sack of flour.</bt></note>Hèia roti ne ca'e toke kapai, lula ragi dhu ciki oo'e deo na.&gt;&gt;<bt>[CHECK juu] Then that bread raises until big, because of that very little bit of yeast.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sak = sack ; juu ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">sak = sack ; juu = (bread) raise</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus pake lii pakasame, ho aj'a dhèu nèti j'ara-j'ara hiu dhu dhèu re'a mèka<bt>The Lord Yesus uses an example to teach new things which people have never yet been known</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 4:33-34)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="34" />Yesus aj'a dhèu ae dènge lii lolo rupa-rupa. Lii padhai Na, aa'i-aa'i se, dhodhoka pake lii pakasame di.<bt>Yesus taught many people by using various stories. All of that speaking of his, just only used examples/comparisons.</bt><v n="35" />Na aj'a sèmi èèna, sèna ka madhutu sèmi lii nèti dhèu rèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua dhu suri tèke, peka na,<bt>He taught like.that in accord with what God's spokesperson had written beforehand saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Pe Ja'a aj'a-nori pake lii pakasame.<bt>&lt;&lt;Later I will teach (doublet) using examples.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Pe Ja'a lole j'ara-j'ara dhu dhèu tadèngi rèdhi mèka,<bt>Later I will tell (various) things which people have not yet ever heard,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">karèi nèti Lamatua paj'aj'i rai-haha toke d'ai sange ne'e.&gt;&gt;<bt>beginning from when God2 made this world until now.&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="13:35" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 78:2</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus peka sasoa nèti j'u'u dhu muri ètu talora aae oka<bt>The Lord Yeus tells the meaning of that example about wild grass in the middle of the garden</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="36" />Èle ka, Yesus lèpa èmu tèke eele dhèu ae sèra. Hèia ana madhutu Na sèra mai manèngi, na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Peka ku dènge ji'i sasoa nèti lii pakasame j'u'u deo sa!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then, Yesus went home, leaving those many people. Then His followers came and asked Him, saying, &lt;&lt;Father! Please explain to us-exc that recent/earlier example about wild grass's meaning (imperative)!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="37" />Ka Yesus dhaa, na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu dhu ceb'e hini dhu be'a èèna, nuka Ja'a, Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a ne.<bt>Then Yesus replied, saying, &lt;&lt;The person who scattered that seed which is good, that is Me, the Ideal/Prototypical Human.</bt><v n="38" />Aa oka èèna, nuka rai-haha ne. Hini dhu be'a èèna, nuka dhèu-dhèu dhu j'aj'i le ana-èpu Ama Lamatua. Aa j'u'u sèra, nuka ana pajuu nèti dhèu aae nidhu.<bt>And that garden is this world. That good seed there is people who have become God's family. And that wild grass there is evil.spirit's king's servants/emissaries.</bt><v n="39" />Aa dhèu bhelu dhu mai ceb'e lamusi j'u'u, nuka dhèu aae nidhu. Aa lod'o puu-g'ètu èèna, nuka d'ai èle rai-haha ne. Dhèu sab'a dhu pakaboko isi oka se, nuka ana pajuu Ama Lamatua nèti sorga.<bt>And that evil person who comes to scatter those grass seeds is the evil.spirits' king. And that harvest season is the end.of.the.world. The workers who gather that harvest are God's underlings from heaven (*angels).</bt><v n="40" />Ropa d'ai èle rai-haha ne, ra oru rare j'u'u se ho tunu pakèpu si.<bt>At the end of the world, they gather up that grass to burn it up.</bt><v n="41" />Te Ja'a, Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a ne, bèli-camèd'a pua ana pajuu nèti sorga mai. Rèngu èèna na pakaboko dhèu-dhèu dhu pusi-pahae boe madhutu paredha Ama Lamatua. Aa rèngu oru rare kahèi dhèu-dhèu dhu dadugu-rariu dhèu leo, sèna ka baku madhutu paredha Lamatua.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) I, this Ideal/Prototypical Human, later will sent underlings from heaven. Later they will gather all the people who do not care about (doublet) following God's commands. And they also will gather2 the people who tempt/bother (doublet) other people, to not follow God2's commands.</bt><v n="42" />Èèna na ra core dhèu bhelu-katub'a aa'i-aa'i se asa d'ara ai naraka, nuka sèmi j'u'u dhu ai na'e pakèpu si. Ètu nèi, dhèu se rasa j'èra titu kèna, aa tangi d'ara ma'ète mae-mae loe boe ciki sa.<bt>Later they will throw away all those evil people into hell fire, the same as that grass that was burned up in the fire. There they will feel great suffering and cry wailing without stopping.</bt><v n="43" />Te ngaa dhèu dhu mamuri mola madhutu dad'èi Ama Lamatua, rèngu pea taruu dènge Ama Dhèu Aae ra ètu sorga. Ètu nèi, dhèu se ha'a-ha'a, hèti-hèti, nuka sèmi madha lod'o. De dhèu dhu neo tadhe mèu Ja'a, pasa dhilu paie-iie!&gt;&gt;<bt>But people who live straight/righteous according to God's will, they will stay/live continually with their Father King in heaven. There, they shine clearly like the sun. So (consequently), people who want to know/understand Me, fasten your ears carefully!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ha'a-ha'a = bersinar ; hèti-hèti ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">ha'a-ha'a = bersinar ; hèti-hèti = bersinar2</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus pake lii pakasame nèti mèdha dhu kab'ua aae<bt>The Lord Yesus gives an example about a thing which is very expensive</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="44" />Yesus tabha hari lii pakasame èci, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu dhu neo tadhe mèu Ama Lamatua nèd'u paredha, rèngu nuka sèmi dhèu dhu neo abhu mèdha kab'ua aae, dhu dhèu huni tèke ètu d'ara rai cakasib'i. Ka dhèu ne la'e kèi, hèia na abhu mèdha ne, nèti èèna ka na karej'e-karae. Èle èèna ka, na dhènu hari mèdha deo na. Hèia na lèpa hari lai-lai, la'e pahia aa'i mèdha-panyau na. Ka la'e hèli nare rai ne, sèna ka na unu mèdha dhu kab'ua aae deo na.&gt;&gt;<bt>Yesus added an example again, saying, &lt;&lt;People who want to understand God2's rule/government, they are like finding/encountering an incredibly expensive thing which someone has hidden in a piece/plot of land. That person goes digging, and s/he finds that thing there, and that's why s/he is very happy (doublet). Then s/he burys again that aforementioned thing. And s/he goes home quickly, to completely sell off all of his/her wealth/possessions. Next, s/he goes to buy that land, so that s/he can actually possess that expensive/valuable thing.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kèi = gali ; dhènu ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">kèi = gali ; dhènu = kubur</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus hia lii pakasame nèti mutiara dhu kab'ua aae<bt>The Lord Yesus give an example about a pearl which is very expensive</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="45" />Yesus tuhu hari lii pakasame, peka na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu dhu neo tadhe mèu Ama Lamatua nèd'u paredha, èci èèna kahèi dènge dhèu d'aga ca dhèu dhu d'ara na neo abhu mutiara dhu kab'ua aae titu kèna. Èle ka, na patangi-tenge mutiara ho neo hèli.<bt>Yesus added another example/comparison, saying, &lt;&lt;People who want to recognise/understand God2's rule/government, are like a merchant who wants to obtain pearls (loan) which is/are very expensive/valuable. So he keeps hunting for pearl to buy.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dag'a = dagang"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">dag'a = dagang</Message></Annotation><v n="46" />Ropa na rage mutiara cue dhu be'a titu kèna, hèia na lèpa lai-lai, sèna ka pahia aa'i mèdha-panyau na. Hèia la'e tihe mutiara ne, sèna ka j'aj'i mi unu na.&gt;&gt;<bt>When he comes upon a pearl that is very good, then he goes home quickly, to completely sell off all of his wealth/possessions. Then he goes and buys (pays in full) that pearl, so that he/she could actually own it.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tihe = bayar lunas"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">tihe = bayar lunas</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus pake lii upama nèti dhèu puu i'a nèti pèku<bt>The Lord Yesus gives an example about sorting a [fish]net</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="puu = select out, one by"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">puu = select out, one by one</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="47" />Yesus peka hari, na, &lt;&lt;Paredha Ama Lamatua, nuka sèmi pèku èci dhu dhèu sab'a dhasi lasi lolo ètu d'ara dano. Ka pèku ne lèke rupa-rupa i'a.<bt>Yesus spoke again, saying, &lt;&lt;God's rule/governmentis like a drag.net/dropnet which fishermen go release/spread.out in the lake. Then that net gets all.kinds of fish. [EXEG: Gk “large body of water”. NRSV goes to “sea”; CEV and TN Display go to “lake”; CONTEXT: Jesus mob are still hanging around Galilee, so we go with lake.]</bt><v n="48" />Ropa pèku ne pènu dènge i'a, dhèu pèku se ded'e rèti asa dedha nebhe. Hèia ra madhèdi kabhili i'a nèti pèku ne. I'a dhu be'a, ra tao asa d'ara kalera. Te ngaa i'a dhu karehe, ra core eele.<bt>[CHECK collocation of /soe/ with fish] When that net is full of fish, then the fishermen come and take it up, to bring it to the beach. Then they sit and sort the fish from the net. The fish which are good, they put into basket/s. But the fish which are not good, they throw away.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nebhe = pantai (extends inland to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">nebhe = pantai (extends inland to foreshore) ; dae = focuses on edge of water &amp; land ; kalera = tampat ikan di pinggang</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="49" />Èci èèna ka, ladhe d'ai lod'o èle rai-haha ne. Èèna na ana pajuu Lamatua mai nèti sorga, sèna ka hag'e eele dhèu dhu d'ara mola nèti dhèu bhelu-katub'a.<bt>It will be like that also, at the end of the world. Later God's underlings will come from heaven, and separate out the people who are evil (doublet) from the people who have straight insides.</bt><v n="50" />Dhèu dhu bhelu-katub'a aa'i-aa'i ra, core si asa d'ara ai naraka. Ètu nèi, rèngu heka re'a j'aj'èra, aa loe boe tangi roma iisi.&gt;&gt;<bt>They will throw away all those evil (doublet) people into hell fire. There (remote), they will then feel great suffering and cry wailing without ever stopping.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus aj'a lula-nèti a'aj'a dhu dhui, dènge a'aj'a dhu hiu<bt>The Lord Yesus teaches about old teachings, and new teachings</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="51" />Ropa padhai lii nare, hèia Yesus karèi ra, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Miu me'a aa'i ngaa dhu Ja'a peka-padhai se, do?&gt;&gt;<bt>After finishing speaking like.that, then Yesus asked them, saying, &lt;&lt;Do you understand everything which I have spoken (doublet) just now, [tag question]?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ra dhaa peka na, &lt;&lt;Nge'a, Ama!&gt;&gt;<bt>They replied saying, &lt;&lt;We-exc understand, Father!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="52" />Hèia Yesus b'ala, peka na, &lt;&lt;Be'a! Te mese agama aa'i-aa'i dhu re'a tare'a-re'a Lii Holo-Nori Lamatua dhu suri tèke karèi nèti uru èèna, ka ra kèpe pa'èra a'aj'a Ja'a, na, rèngu ca ropa dènge lamatua èmu dhu d'èi bhoke gud'a na, ho pad'elo mèdha-panyau na dhu dhui, dènge mèdha-panyau na dhu hiu.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus responded, saying, &lt;&lt;Good/Ok! Cuz (elaboration) each religious teacher who truly studies/learns God2's Words which have been written beforehand from long ago, then he also holds firmly to My teachings now, na, s/he like a house owner/master who likes to open up his storehouse to show/display his old wealth/possessions, together with his new wealth/possessions.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="NRSV: And he said to them,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z" status="Information">NRSV: And he said to them, “Therefore every scribe who has been trained (lit. having become a disciple) for the kingdom of heaven is like the master of a household who brings out of his treasure what is new and what is old.”</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu Nasaret ro'o boe sèmi rare Lamatua Yesus<bt>Nasaret people reject (do not want to accept) the Lord Yesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 6:1-6; Lukas 4:16-30)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="53" />Ropa Yesus aj'a nare dhèu ae sèra, pake lii pakasame, hèia la'e, tèke eele era èèna,<bt>When Yesus had finished teaching many people using examples, then He walked/traveled leaving that place,</bt><v n="54" />ho lèpa asa rae Na. D'ai nèi, maso la'e asa d'ara èmu sabaj'a, ho aj'a-nori dhèu. Dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu tadèngi lii padhai Na malaa-maloha. Ka ra papeka, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ira ii! Dhèu ne d'èlu-mèu titu kèna, nga! Na sakola ètu mia ne? Tasamia ka Na bisa tao tadha malaa se'e?<bt>to go home to His village. There, He entered into the worship house to teach (doublet) people. All the people who heard Him, were amazed (doublet). They conversed with each other saying, &lt;&lt;Ira ii! [+impressed] This person's skill/knowledge is great! Where did he go to school? How is it that He can do those miracles?</bt><v n="55" />Nèngu ne dhoka Ana nèti ca dhèu tuka aj'u di. Èdhi patadha be'a dènge ina Na Maria; aa dènge ari Na aa'i-aa'i, nuka Yakobis, Yusuf, Yudas dènge Simon.<bt>He here is only just a carpenter's child. We-inc know well His mother Maria; and all His younger siblings, that is Yakobis, Yusuf, Yudas and Simon.</bt><v n="56" />Èdhi tadhe ana hèni Na kahèi, te èdhi pea ètu d'ara rae cue! De Na abhu mamèu Na nèti mia? Aa Na abhu koasa kapai ne nèti cee hari?&gt;&gt;<bt>We-inc also know His sisters, cuz (elaboration) we-inc all live in one/the same village! So (consequently), where did He that great skill/knowledge of His from? And He got that great power of His, from who else?&gt;&gt;</bt><v n="57" />Nèti èèna ka, dhèu se kacèki, toke ra ro'o heka nanene lii padhai Na.<bt>That's why they were jealous/irritated/upset, to the point that they did not want to listen to what He had to say anymore.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kacèki = kakodok, jengkel"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">kacèki = kakodok, jengkel</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Te ngaa Yesus peka dènge ra, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Mema tare'a! Dhèu d'èi risi pakab'ua dhèu nèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua dhu mai nèti era leo, te ngaa ra pakab'ua boe dhèu nèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua dhu mai nèti rae rèngu unu ra.&gt;&gt;<bt>But Yesus told them, saying, &lt;&lt;It's really true! People like to give more respect to God's spokespeople who come from other places, but they don't want to respect God's spokespeople who come from their own village.&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="13:57" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yohanis 4:44</note><v n="58" />Lula d'ara ra adhu, toke ra parcaya boe Yesus, nèti èèna ka Na tao tadha malaa ae boe ètu d'ara rae Na.<bt>Because their insides were hard, to the point that they did not want to believe Yesus, that is why He did not do many miracles in His village.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ra pare pamadhe Yohanis tuka sarani<bt>They cut killing Yohanis the habitual baptizer</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 6:14-29; Lukas 9:7-9)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="14" />
      <v n="1" />Tèu èèna, dhèu aae Herodes nèd'u paredha ètu propensi Galilea. Nèngu ne dhu tadèngi le kahèi rupa-rupa j'ara lula-nèti Yesus.<bt>At that time, king Herodes held government in Galilea province. He had also heard various kinds of news about Yesus.</bt><v n="2" />Na peka dènge dhèu sab'a na sèra, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ele boe Yesus ne, nuka Yohanis tuka sarani, dhu ca hari ni ja'a pua dhèu poro rare kètu na. Limuri ne, na mamuri hari le! Nèti èèna ka, na abhu koasa, tao tadha-tadha malaa sèra.&gt;&gt;<bt>He told his workers, saying, &lt;&lt;Perhaps this Yesus here, is Yohanis the habitual baptizer who previously I ordered to cut off his head. Now he lives again! That's why he has power to do those (various) miracles.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Dhèu aae Herodes peka sèmi èèna, lula uru èèna nèngu dhu tao lii langu dènge Yohanis, toke na kèpe Yohanis aa pamaso asa d'ara bèdho. J'aj'aj'i lii langu ne, sèmi ne'e ka: dhèu aae Herodes leo nare dhèu èmu ari na Pelipus, ngara na Herodias. Aa te ngaa Pelipus dènge Herodias dhae pa'ia-pa'ela mèka.<bt>King Herodes spoke like that, because previously he was having an argument/litigation with Yohanis, to the point that he captured/arrested and put Yohanis into jail. The origins of that litigation is like this: king Herodes had married his younger.sibling Pilipus' wife, named Herodias. However in actual fact, Pilipus and Herodias had not yet divorced (doublet).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pagalaa = saling melapor di pemerintah"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">pagalaa = saling melapor di pemerintah</Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Nèti èèna ka, Yohanis kai ne pahari-pahari, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama dhèu aae, baku paleo èmu dènge dhèu èmu ari mu. Te j'ara ne, pamèci boe dènge ad'a èdhi dhèu Yahudi!&gt;&gt;<bt>That's why Yohanis scolded over and over, saying, &lt;&lt;Father king may not marry your younger.sibling's wife. Cuz (elaboration) that matter violates our-inc Yahudi custom!&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="14:3-4" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lukas 3:19-20; Atora nèti Ama-ama Agama 18:16, 20:21</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Te ngaa Herodes dale boe lii kai na, hèia leo nare Herodias. Madhutu iia-iia na, Herodes neo pamadhe Yohanis tuka sarani. Te ngaa na madha'u dènge dhèu ae sèra, lula ra parcaya na, Yohanis ne, ca dhèu nèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua. Nèti èèna ka, na pua dhèu sab'a na pamaso Yohanis asa d'ara bèdho.<bt>But Herodes did not want to pay.attention to his objections, and he married Herodias anyway. According to the truth (=in actual fact), Herodes wanted to kill Yohanis the habitual baptizer, but he was fearful of the many people, because they believed that, that Yohanis was God's spokesperson. That's why he ordered his workers, to put Yohanis in jail.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bege = kuatir, takut (Lena not"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">bege = kuatir, takut (Lena not know)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Te ngaa nèbhu-nèbhu, hèia Herodes tao pesta hari jadi na. Lod'o èèna, ana bhèni nèti bhèni aae Herodias la'e roge ètu madha tamu se. Na roge be'a titu kèna, toke d'ara Herodes karej'e bia.<bt>But eventually then Herodes had his birthday feast. At that time the daughter of queen (=normal term for king's wife) Herodias went to dance in front of the guests. That dancing of hers was really nice to the point that it made Herodes' insides heavily happy (=very).</bt><v n="7" />Na roge nare, hèia Herodes paroa ne, ka na peka, &lt;&lt;Èu neo manèngi hadia ngaa nèti ja'a, na peka la! Te èèna na ja'a hia èu. Ja'a leko boe-monya boe. Aa ja'a subha dènge kolongara Ama Lamatua.&gt;&gt;<bt>The dancing finished then Herodes called her and said, &lt;&lt;What ever gift you want to ask from me, just say it! Cuz (elaboration) later I will give it to you. I'm not lying (doublet). And I oath/swear using God's name.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Ropa na tadèngi dhèu aae peka sèmi èèna, hèia ina na kakèj'i ne. Nèti èèna ka, ana ne la'e peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Ja'a manèngi kètu nèti Yohanis tuka sarani. Tèke ne mi d'ara dula, ho rèti mai asa ne'e hia ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>Hearing the king' speaking like.that, then her mother poked (=persuaded) her. That's why she went to request, saying, &lt;&lt;Father! I request Yohanis the habitual baptizer's head. Put it on a tray, and bring it here giving it to me.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kakèj'i = buju-buju ; dula ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">kakèj'i = buju-buju ; dula = dulang ; dula2 = kotor ; dadula = anak yg tidak suka makan, tidak ada nafsu makan, atau pili-pili makanan</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Ropa tadèngi lii manèngi ana bhèni ne, hèia d'ara Herodes roe dènge. Te ngaa nèngu bisa boe ère nare hari lii subha na, te tamu aa'i-aa'i dhu tadèngi le. Nèti èèna ka, na madhutu dhoka dad'èi ana bhèni ne di.<bt>Hearing that girl's request like.that, then Herodes ínsides became weak/soft right.away (=discouraged/dismay). But he could not pull back his oath, cuz (elaboration) all the guests had heard it. That's why he just followed that girl's will.</bt><v n="10" />Ka na paredha dhèu lasi poro rare kètu Yohanis ètu d'ara bèdho.<bt>Next he commanded people to go cut off Yohanis head in jail.</bt><v n="11" />Ropa ra poro rare, hèia ra tèke mi d'ara dula ho rèti lasi hia mi ana bhèni ne. Ropa ana bhèni ne sèmi nare dula, hèia nèti asa ina na.<bt>They cut off Yohanis' head, then they put it on a tray, to bring and give to that girl. She received that tray, then she took it to go give it to her mother.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Lod'o ana madhutu Yohanis se tadèngi, ka mai rare ngi'u aae na, ho lasi padhane. Èle ka, lasi peka dènge Yesus j'ara dhu j'aj'i ne.<bt>[CHECK if object needed for “heard”] When Yohanis' followers heard, then they came and took his corpse, to go bury [it]. Then they went to report that matter to Yesus.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus panga'a lèmi riho risi dhèu<bt>The Lord Yesus feeds five thousand people plus</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 6:30-44; Lukas 9:10-17; Yohanis 6:1-14)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Lod'o Yesus tadèngi ngaa dhu j'aj'i mi Yohanis, hèia Nèngu dènge ana-ana madhutu Na tèke eele era èèna. Hèia ra ca'e koha, ho lasi asa era dhu dhèu pea boe, sèna ka ra ae rare ciki. Te ngaa dhèu ae ladhe rèdhi koha Yesus si dhu oro-oro re sebhe dano. Ka dhèu se mai nèti rae-rae, kako karohe-karohe re dedha rai. Nèti èèna ka, dhèu se d'ai uuru nèti Yesus si.<bt>[CHECK should last clause have /nèti/?] When Yesus heard what had happened to Yohanis, then He and His followers left that place. Then they got into a boat to go to a place where people didn't live, in.order.to stop a little (=rest). But many people saw Yesus (coll.) boat going along the lake's edge. Then people came out from villages, and walked quickly along a land path/road. That's why these people arrived ahead of Yesus (coll.).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="karohe-karohe = malai"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">karohe-karohe = malai</Message></Annotation><v n="14" />Ropa Na puru nèti dedha koha, hèia nèdhi dhèu ae-ae dhu mate le Nèngu. Ka Na rasa kasia mi rèngu. Hèia Na puri-pa'èle papèd'a-tarègu ra.<bt>When He got out of the boat, then He saw those great many people were waiting for Him. Then2 He felt pity for them. Then He healed (doublet) their sicknesses (doublet). [EXEG: Gk “great crowd” (which later turns out to be in the thousands)]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />D'ai lod'o nihia, hèia ana madhutu Na, peka dènge Ne, &lt;&lt;Ama! Hua iia Ama pua dhèu se, sèna ka lasi hèli nganga'a ètu rae-rae dhu padètu ètu se'e. Te lod'o nihia le! Ètu ne'e nganga'a aad'o.&gt;&gt;<bt>When it was late.afternoon/evening, then His followers came and told Him saying, &lt;&lt;Father! It's better that Father tells all these people so they go buy food in the villages near here. Cuz (elaboration) it's already late.afternoon/evening now! Here there is no food.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nganga'a ngaa-ngaa aad'o @@ PHONOLOGY"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">nganga'a ngaa-ngaa aad'o @@ PHONOLOGY</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Te ngaa Yesus b'ala si, peka na, &lt;&lt;Baku! Miu ka dhu panga'a si.&gt;&gt;<bt>But Yesus replied, saying, &lt;&lt;It's not necessary. You-p are the ones who feed them&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Te ngaa ra dhaa, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ira ee, Ama! Ji'i se dènge boe ngaa-ngaa, ho panga'a dhèu ae-ae sèmi ne'e ne. Ji'i tao tasamia? Te abhu dhoka roti lèmi bua di, aa i'a dua ngi'u di!&gt;&gt;<bt>But they replied, saying, &lt;&lt;Ira ee, Father! [+consternation] We-exc don't have anything to feed as many people as this. What are we going to do? Cuz (elaboration) there is only just five breads and two fish!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Te ngaa Yesus lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;Oo! Be'a kèna. Mèti ku mai!&gt;&gt;<bt>But Yesus spoke saying, &lt;&lt;Yes! That's good. Bring it here!&gt;&gt;</bt><v n="19" />Ka Na pua dhèu se aa'i-aa'i ra madhèdi kaboko ètu dedha j'u'u. Èle èèna ka, Yesus nare roti lèmi bua dènge i'a dua ngi'u sèra. Hèia Na ladhe asa dedha, ho manèngi makasi mi Ama Lamatua. Èle ka, Na pamae roti se, hèia j'ole asa ana madhutu Na, sèna ka ra papala mi dhèu se aa'i-aa'i ra.<bt>Next He ordered all those people to sit in groups on top the grass. Afterwards Yesus took those five loaves of bread, and those two bodies of fish (bread and fish counters). Then He faced upward to give thanks to God. After that, He broke that bread, and extended it to His followers, for them to go divide it to all those people. [NOTE to daughter translations: discuss with team merits of streamlining /ame itu roti deng itu ikan dong/ or keeping /ame itu roti lima bua, deng itu ikan dua ekor/. The Gk has it, and retaining the fuller (but reduntant) info may enhance the power of the miracle.]</bt><v n="20" />Ka dhèu se ra'a toke bècu. Ra'a rara, hèia ana madhutu se pakaboko rare dhu ata, pènu canguru dua soe.<bt>[CHECK /ra'a rara/] Afterwards then they all ate until satisfied. After eating then, they went to gather up the leftover food, until filling twelve <span class="Italic">(soe</span>) baskets. [NOTE to daughter translations: Just like in Mark, the Gk here uses different terms for the baskets after feeding the 5,000, than after feeding the 4,000 (Matt. 15:37). Although LN says we can't be sure of the relative sizes, some sources way the Gk term for basket used for the 4,000 is slightly larger than the one here. Most of our lgs have lexical terms that can reflect this difference. KM doesn't. Both should be able to be picked up and carried, so avoid the gigantic storage baskets.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ata = sisa ; hahake ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">ata = sisa ; hahake = soe dhu kapai</Message></Annotation><v n="21" />Dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu ra'a se, dhèu mone pe d'ai lèmi riho sa, iga mèka dhèu bhèni dènge ana iiki.<bt>All the people who got to eat there, [were] approximately five thousand men, not yet counting the women and children.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ana iiki = children ; ana"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">ana iiki = children ; ana niki ra = their children</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus kako re dedha èi<bt>The Lord Yesus walks on top water</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 6:45-52; Yohanis 6:16-21)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Ropa dhèu aa'i-aa'i se ra'a rare, hèia Yesus pua ana madhutu Na ca'e koha, sèna ka lasi uru asa cabèka dano. Te ngaa Nèngu ètu èèna era, sena ka pua dhèu se lèpa.<bt>They all finished eating, then Yesus ordered His followers to go get in the boat, for them to go on ahead to the lake's other side. But He still stayed there, to order those people to go.home.</bt><v n="23" />Ropa rèngu lèpa aa'i mèu-mèu, hèia Yesus ca'e la'e asa ledhe èci, ho sabaj'a. Toke mèda, Nèngu mesa Na ètu èèna era.<bt>When they all had gone home, then Yesus went up on top of a mountain to pray. When it was night, He was still alone in that place.</bt><v n="24" />Lod'o èèna, koha ana madhutu Na d'ai le talora aae dano. Te ngaa rèngu tuku d'ai madhe, lula ngèlu nèti madha, aa naha kapai tatèb'e koha ra.<bt>At that time, His followers' boat had arrived into the middle of the lake. But they were paddling extremely hard, because the wind was from the front, with big waves striking their boat.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tatèbe = pukul"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">tatèbe = pukul</Message></Annotation><v n="25" />Oe d'ai mèu, hèia Yesus la'e madhutu si. Te ngaa Nèngu dhu kako re dedha èi.<bt>[When it was] almost light, then Yesus went following them. But He was walking on top of the water.</bt><v n="26" />Ropa ladhe rèdhi, ana madhutu se cag'ag'a, hèia ra padhai dènge lii madha'u, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Heeh! Nidhu kèna!&gt;&gt;<bt>When they saw that, those followers were very startled. They spoke fearfully, saying, &lt;&lt;Heeh! There's an evil spirit there!&gt;&gt; [EXEG: Gk. /phantasma/ ‘apparition’; but this is how the RL talks when they see an apparition.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Te ngaa Yesus lii dènge ra, peka na, &lt;&lt;Miu baku madha'u! Te Ja'a ne, Yesus! Mau-mau la!&gt;&gt;<bt>But Yesus spoke immediately to them, saying, &lt;&lt;You-p don't be afraid! Cuz (elaboration) I here am Yesus! Settle down!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Ropa ra tadèngi lii ne'e, hèia Petrus peka na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe Ama kèna, pua la ja'a kako re dedha èi ne, dhiu asa Ama.&gt;&gt;<bt>Hearing like.that, then Petrus spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;If that is Father (=You), order me to walk on top of the water to go to Father.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="29" />Ka Yesus dhaa peka na, &lt;&lt;Mai ka!&gt;&gt; Hèia Petrus puru nèti dedha koha, la'e re dedha èi, asa Yesus.<bt>Then Yesus replied saying, &lt;&lt;Come here!&gt;&gt; Then Petrus got out of the boat to go on top of the water to Yesus.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ridhu = lompat"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">ridhu = lompat</Message></Annotation><v n="30" />Te ngaa ropa Petrus rasa na ngèlu aae, hèia na madha'u bia. Ka na mulai cène, hèia na pa'oo, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ira oo, Ama, ee! Soru ku ja'a la!&gt;&gt;<bt>But when Petrus felt there was strong wind, then he was terrified. He began to sink, then he yelled, saying &lt;&lt;Aduu, Father! [+in strife or grief] Help me!&gt;&gt; [NOTE to daughter translations: Make it natural to the context. Don't force the spiritual reading of “save”.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Yesus j'ole dènge ka kacui-aai Na, ka kèpe nare Petrus. Hèia Yesus padhai lii, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Petrus, ee! Nga tao ka d'ara èu kajari? Èu parcaya èra boe mi Ja'a, do?&gt;&gt;<bt>Yesus extended His hand quickly and took hold of Petrus. Then Yesus spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;Petrus, ee! Why are you doubting (branched insides)? Don't you believe in Me [tag question]?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bèdhi-bèdhi = bounce up and down,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">bèdhi-bèdhi = bounce up and down, duk-dak (takut)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="32" />Ka dua ra ca'e lasi asa dedha koha, hèia ngèlu mau dènge.<bt>The two of them got up into the boat, then the wind calmed down right.away.</bt><v n="33" />Ropa rèdhi sèmi èèna, ana madhutu Na koa-kio padedha-dedha Ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ira ii! Ama ne, mema tare'a-re'a Ana Ama Lamatua!&gt;&gt;<bt>Seeing like.that, then His followers praised (doublet) Him, saying, &lt;&lt;Ira ii [+amazement]! Father here is really truly God's Child!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus puri-pa'èle dhèu-dhèu pèd'a ètu Genesaret<bt>The Lord Yesus heals (doublet) sick people in Genesaret</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 6:53-56)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="34" />Ropa rèngu d'ai cabèka dano, hèia ra puru lasi asa dedha nebhe nèti rae Genesaret.<bt>When they arrived at the other side of the lake, then they got down/disembarked at Genasaret village's beach.</bt><v n="35" />Lod'o ra puru èèna, dhèu ae dhu tadhe le. Hèia dhèu pa'oo, peka na, &lt;&lt;Wee! Yesus mai le!&gt;&gt; Ra rai lasi peka palème, hèia dhèu rèti dhèu pèd'a aa'i-aa'i.<bt>When they disembarked, many people recognised (them). Then they began to yell, saying, &lt;&lt;Wee! Yesus has come!&gt;&gt; They ran to tell all around, and people brought all their sick people.</bt><v n="36" />Ra manèngi sèna ka ra goi lèke kodho Yesus. Te ra pangee na, &lt;&lt;Sad'i dhèu pèd'a goi lèke suu kodho Na, tatu dhèu se èle dènge nèti papèd'a ra.&gt;&gt; Ka dhèu dhu pèd'a aa'i-aa'i se goi kodho Yesus, ka ra èle dènge nèti papèd'a.<bt>They requested that they could touch Yesus' robe/clothes. Cuz (elaboration) they thought, saying, &lt;&lt;As long as sick people touch just the edge of Yesus' robe/clothes, surely they will be healed straight away from their sickness.&gt;&gt; And all the sick people who touched that robe of Yesus, were healed straight.away from their sickness.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu rai-haha tao atora, ho gati eele paredha Ama Lamatua<bt>Humans make their regulations to replace away God's commands</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 7:1-13)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="15" />
      <v n="1" />Ca tèka, dhèu Parisi dènge mese agama ca nau mai nèti Yerusalem, ho paraga dènge Yesus.<bt>One time, a group of Parisi people and religion teachers come from Yerusalem to meet with Yesus.</bt><v n="2" />Dhèu Parisi kèpe pa'èra ad'a Yahudi rèngu. Lod'o rèngu tadèngi, na, ladhe ana madhutu Yesus ra'a-rinu dhu j'amo boe kacui-aai madhutu ad'a ra, hèia ra nasa. Ka rèngu mai ho pasala Yesus, peka na, &lt;&lt;Nga tao ka ana madhutu Èu se ra'a-rinu j'amo uuru boe ai? Èèna na, sisu le ad'a bèi-baki èdhi!&gt;&gt;<bt>Parisi people hold tightly to their Yahudi customary law (adat). When they heard that Yesus' follwers ate (doublet) without washing their hands according to their customary law, then they got upset/angry. Then2 they came and accused Yesus saying, &lt;&lt;Why do Your followers eat, but not wash their hands first? That there violates our-inc ancestors' custom!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Te ngaa Yesus dhaa, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Miu se, dhèu dhu padhai lii leo tao leo! Miu d'èlu-mèu lab'a paredha Ama Lamatua, sèna ka madhutu ad'a tatao nèti bèi-baki miu di.<bt>But Yesus replied, saying, &lt;&lt;You here are people who say one thing and do another! You are clever/skilled at opposing God's commands, in.order.to follow only your ancestor's customs.</bt><v n="4" />Te Ama Lamatua paredha, peka na, &lt;Pakab'ua ina-ama miu.&gt; Aa peka hari, na, &lt;Ladhe ca dhèu padhèd'a aapa ina do ama na, hud'i huku pamadhe ne.&gt;<bt>Cuz (elaboration) God has commanded, saying, &lt;&lt;Honor your mother-father [RL order for naturalness].&gt;&gt; And add again, saying, &lt;If a person curses3 his mother or father, must give him the death sentence [GRAMM: a kind of agentless passive wannabe].&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="padhèda aapa = maki"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">padhèda aapa = maki</Message></Annotation><note reference="15:4" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 20:12, 21:17, Atora nèti Ama-ama Agama 20:9, Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 5:16</note><v n="5-6" />Ama Lamatua aj'a sèmi èèna ka, te ngaa miu aj'a leo. Miu peka na, &lt;Ca dhèu parluu boe pake mèdha-panyau na, sèna ka soru-bara ina-ama na, masi ka rèngu ètu d'ara j'aj'èra, ladhe na pamoa le neo hia mèdha ne asa Lamatua&gt; Te ngaa dènge aj'a sèmi èèna, miu core eele le paredha Ama Lamatua, ho gati dènge atora unu miu.<bt>God teaches like.that, but you teach different. You say, &lt;A person doesn't need to use his thing/possession to help (doublet) his/her mother-father, even if/though they are in great difficulty, if s/he has already promised to give that thing to God2.&gt; But by teaching like.that, you have thrown out God's commands, and replaced it with your own regulations.</bt><v n="7" />Nèti èèna ka, deo na Ja'a dhu peka le, miu se, dhèu dhu padhai lii leo tao leo! Èèna na, nuka sèmi Yesaya, dhèu nèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua, dhu suri tèke, peka na,<bt>That's why earlier I said, you here, are people who say one thing and do another! That is like what God's spokesperson Yesaya wrote ahead of time about you from long ago! Cuz (elaboration) the Lord used him to write, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="8" />&lt;Abhu dhèu dhu koa-kio Ja'a,<bt>'There are people who *praise (doublet) Me,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">dhoka dènge hèb'a di, te ngaa dènge boe d'ara.<bt>only just with [their] mouth/s, but not with [their] insides.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="9" />Masi ka rèngu tao sèmi èèna, te ngaa parcuma.<bt>Even if/though they do like that, its just fruitless/pointless (loan).</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Ra pusi-pahae boe Ja'a,<bt>They don't care.about/pay.attention.to (doublet) Me,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">te rèngu sèra pahae dhoka atora dhèu rai-haha di.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>cuz (elaboration) they only just care about following humans' regulations.&gt;&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="15:8-9" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 29:13</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">J'ara-j'ara karehe mai nèti d'ara dhèu<bt>Evil matters come out of people's insides</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 7:14-23)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Èle èèna ka, Yesus paroa dhèu leo ètu èèna, ka Na aj'a si, peka na, &lt;&lt;Pasa dhilu pabe'a-be'a, sèna ka miu bisa me'a mèu!<bt>After that, Yesus called/summoned other people there to teach them, saying, &lt;&lt;Fasten your ears well, so.that you can understand clearly!</bt><v n="11" />Ngaa dhu maso asa d'ara hèb'a, pakaj'alu boe dhèu. Te ngaa dhu mai nèti d'ara hèb'a, èèna ka dhu pakaj'alu dhèu.&gt;&gt;<bt>What enters into a person's mouth, doesn't make a person dirty/defiled. But what comes out of a person's mouth, that is what makes a person dirty/defiled.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Èle ka, ana madhutu Na mai karèi Ne, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama me'a, do? Dhèu Parisi se d'ara pèd'a ropa tadèngi lii padhai Ama.&gt;&gt;<bt>After that, Yesus' followers came to ask Him, saying, &lt;&lt;Father knows, right? Those Parisi people were offended hearing that speaking of Father's.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Te ngaa Yesus dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama Ku ètu sorga, èèna na core eele dhèu dhu aj'a madhutu boe dad'èi Na. Èèna nuka sèmi dhèu ko'o eele j'u'u dhu na d'èi boe.<bt>But Yesus responded, saying, &lt;&lt;My Father in heaven later will throw out people who do not teach following His will. That is like a person digs-pulls up plants which he does not want.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="patue = tebang ; ko'o ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">patue = tebang ; ko'o = tofa</Message></Annotation><v n="14" />De baku pusi-pahae dènge dhèu Parisi sèi! Te rèngu ca ropa dènge dhèu bèdhu dhu pakako dhèu bèdhu. Èèna na ra manahu palere-lere asa d'ara ro'a lasi.&gt;&gt;<bt>So (consequently), you shouldn't be.concerned (=strong dismissal) (doublet) with those Parisi people! Cuz (elaboration) they there are like blind people who lead blind people. Later they will fall together into a hole.&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="15:14" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lukas 6:39</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Ka Petrus lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama, lole ku dènge ji'i la, sasoa nèti lii pakasame deo na!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then2 Petrus spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;Father, please tell us that earlier example's meaning!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Yesus b'ala, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Miu me'a mèka kahèi?<bt>Yesus replied, saying, &lt;&lt;You also still don't understand?</bt><v n="17" />Sasoa na sèmi ne'e: ngaa dhu èdhi ta'a, maso asa d'ara hèb'a, la'e taruu asa kabake, èle èèna kalua hari la'e asa d'ara kakus.<bt>It's meaning is like.this: that which we-inc eat, enters into the mouth, continues into the stomach, and afterwards comes out again into the toilet (loan). [EXEG: see Gk. ‘latrine’.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kakus (loan, but widely used)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">kakus (loan, but widely used)</Message></Annotation><v n="18" />Te, ngaa dhu mai nèti d'ara hèb'a, èèna ka dhu pakaj'alu dhèu, toke Ama Lamatua madenge dènge ne, aa d'èi boe pa'èci dènge ne.<bt>But that which comes out of the mouth, that is what makes a person dirty/defiled, to the point that God is also repugnated by him, and does not want to join with him. [EXEG: last explicating implications of ‘defiled’; see CEV]</bt><note reference="15:18" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 12:34</note><v n="19" />Te j'ara-j'ara karehe, ae ka dhu mai nèti d'ara dhèu! Nuka sèmi: ngangee dhu bhelu, pamadhe dhèu, bersina, tao j'ara makae dènge dhèu dhu dhèu èmu nèngu boe, mana'u, sakasii kapod'e-kabèli, dènge pakarehe kolongara dhèu.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) many evil things come out of people's insides! Like: thinking evil, killing people, adultery, shameful things with a person who is not his/her spouse (defaults to sexual), stealing, deceiving witness [Morris], and slander someone's name/reputation.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mana'u pagogo-pagero = curi sebagai profesi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">mana'u pagogo-pagero = curi sebagai profesi</Message></Annotation><v n="20" />J'ara-j'ara se'e ka dhu pakaj'alu dhèu. Te ngaa ladhe dhèu dhoka ra'a j'amo boe ai madhutu ad'a, èèna sala boe ngaa-ngaa.&gt;&gt;<bt>It's matters/issues like these which make people dirty/defiled. But if people just eat without washing their hands according to custom, that is not a problem.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus soru-bara ca dhèu ina dhu Yahudi boe<bt>The Lord Yesus helps (doublet) a mother/woman who is not a Yahudi person</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 7:24-30)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Èle èèna ka, Yesus tèke eele era ne'e, kako la'e asa kota Tirus dènge kota Sidon.<bt>Afterwards then Yesus left that place, to go to the city of Tirus and the city of Sidon. [EXEG: ‘territory of’ explicit - implicit, MTTs preference]</bt><v n="22" />Ètu nèi, abhu ina ca dhèu dhu j'aj'aj'i na nèti rai ne'e. Nèngu dhèu Yahudi boe. Ropa na tadèngi nare Yesus mai le asa ne'e, hèia la'e manèngi, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ana-èpu dhèu aae Daud! Sue ku ja'a la! Te ana bhèni ja'a, lèke nidhu tao. Kasia ku ji'i la! Te na j'èra d'ai seli.&gt;&gt;<bt>There (remote), there was a mother/woman who originated/came.from that area/region. She was not a Yahudi person. When she heard that Yesus was there, she came there and asked, saying, &lt;&lt;King Daud's descendant! Love/pity me! (=help me) Cuz (elaboration) my daughter is afflicted by an evil.spirit. Have pity/mercy on us-exc! Cuz (elaboration) she is suffering greatly.&gt;&gt; [EXEG: a native from that area, Canaanite see CONNOT M. Crofts]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Te ngaa Yesus mau-mau, aa dhaa boe ngaa-ngaa ciki sa. Hèia ana madhutu Na mai peka dènge Ne, &lt;&lt;Ama, ina ne pa'oo-parodha loe boe. Be'a risi Ama babège eele ne nèti ne'e!&gt;&gt;<bt>But Yesus was quiet, and didn't answer anything. Then His followers came to report to Him, saying, &lt;&lt;Father, this woman here keeps on yelling disruptively (doublet). It's better Father evicts her from here!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="oe sèmi pane'a boe sa ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">oe sèmi pane'a boe sa = seperti sonde mau tau</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Hèia Yesus dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama Lamatua pua Ja'a mai, ho soru-bara dhèu èdhi dhèu Yahudi, lula rèngu kako sala j'ara, nuka sèmi kahib'i-kalèbho dhu re'a heka j'ara. Te Na pua boe Ja'a sèna ka soru-bara dhèu leo.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus replied, saying, &lt;&lt;God ordered/sent Me to come help (doublet) our-inc Yahudi people, because they have lost their way, like sheep which no longer know the way. He didn't order/send Me to come help (doublet) other (categories of) people.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Te ngaa ina ne mai padètu-dètu asa Yesus. Ka na patitu kètu urutuu dènge lii manèngi, &lt;&lt;Ama! Sue ku ja'a la!&gt;&gt;<bt>But that woman came closer to Yesus. And she knelt and requested, saying, &lt;&lt;Father! Love/pity me. (= help me)&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Te ngaa Yesus core lii padhai Na, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Pantas boe tare nganga'a nèti ana-ana, ka hia mi busa.&gt;&gt; [Dènge lii dhu pacele, sasoa na, Yesus hud'i soru-bara uuru ku dhèu Yahudi Nèngu unu Na, heka bisa ladhe-leru dhèu leo kèna.]<bt>But Yesus threw language out (= spoke indirectly in 'code'/ with double meaning), saying, &lt;&lt;It's not appropriate to take food from the children, then give it to the dogs.&gt;&gt; [With indirect speech meaning that Yesus must help (doublet) His own Yahudi people first, only.then can serve (doublet) other (categories of) people.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Ana-ana se'e, hud'i ra'a uuru ku,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">Ana-ana se'e, hud'i ra'a uuru ku, heka dhu sisu core hia busa.&gt;&gt; (Dènge lii dhu pacele, peka na, Yesus hud'i soru-bara ku dhèu Yahudi Na, heka ladhe-leru dhèu leo kèna).</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Te ngaa ina ne b'ala, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Tare'a Ama! Te ngaa busa dhu mate mema ètu ro'a mei. Rèngu ra'a kahèi nganga'a dhu bèbhe eele nèti d'ara pega ana sèra.&gt;&gt; [Sasoa na, ropa ana-ana ra'a, busa kahèi abhu ra'a. Masi ka Yesus soru-bara dhèu unu Na, te ngaa Nèngu hud'i ladhe-leru dhèu Yahudi boe kahèi.]<bt>But that woman responded, saying, &lt;&lt;True, Father! But the dogs have been waiting under the table. They also eat food that falls from the children's dishes.&gt;&gt; [Meaning, when the children eat, the dogs also get to eat. Even though Yesus helps (doublet) His own people, nevertheless He also must look.after (doublet) non-Yahudi people.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Ropa tadèngi nare, ka Yesus peka na, &lt;&lt;Ira ii! Ina parcaya Ja'a tare'a-re'a! De lèpa ka, lula ngaa dhu ina manèngi èèna, j'aj'i le!&gt;&gt; Èle èèna ka, na lèpa, ka na ladhe nèdhi ana na dhu èle le nèti papèd'a na.<bt>Hearing like.that, then Yesus told saying, &lt;&lt;Ira ii! [+impressed] Mother (=you) truly believes in Me! So (consequently) go on home, because what mother requested there, has already happened!&gt;&gt; Then she went home, and she saw her child had already been healed from her sickness.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus puri-pa'èle dhèu ae nèti papèd'a ra<bt>The Lord Yesus heals (doublet) many people from their sicknesses</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="29" />Èle ka, Yesus dènge ana-ana madhutu Na tèke eele era ne'e, hèia ra kako madhutu re sebhe dano Galilea. Ka ra ca'e asa ledhe cue, hèia Yesus madhèdi ho aj'a-nori si.<bt>After that, Yesus and His followers left that place, and they walked along Galilea lake's edge. Next they went up a mountain, and Yesus sat down to teach (doublet) them.</bt><v n="30" />Èle èèna ka, dhèu ae-ae mai asa Yesus. Ra rèti dènge dhèu haga roe cabèka, dhèu bèdhu, dhèu karuku, dhèu lii aad'o, dènge dhèu-dhèu dhu pèd'a leo kahèi. Ra pamadhèdi dhèu pèd'a se padètu-dètu dènge haga Yesus. Ka Na puri-pa'èle si.<bt>Then many-many people to Yesus. They brought their people with drag/weak feet, blind people, lame people, people who could not talk, and various people with other sicknesses. They placed those sick people near Yesus' feet. Then He healed (doublet) them.</bt><v n="31" />Ropa ladhe rèdhi, hèia dhèu ae se malaa. Ra papeka na, &lt;&lt;Ira ii! Malaa titu kèna, nga! Dhèu haga roe cabèka, bisa kako èra hari. Dhèu bèdhu, bisa rèdhi. Dhèu karuku, bisa kako. Aa dhèu lii aad'o, bisa padhai lii! Se'e se, tatu tatao Ama Lamatua. Aa Lamatua èèna ka, dhu uru-uru sèra bèi-baki èdhi pahaha iisi mi Nèngu.&gt;&gt;<bt>Seeing like.that, then those many people, were amazed. They spoke with each other, saying, &lt;&lt;Ira ii! [+impressed] Incredibly amazing, nga! People with drag foot, can walk strongly again. Blind people, can see. Lame people can walk. And people who can't talk, now can converse! These things are surely God's workings/doings. And that God2, is the one whom our-inc ancestors worshiped long ago.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus panga'a èpa riho dhèu<bt>The Lord Yesus feeds four thousand people</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 8:1-10)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="32" />Lalu eele pèri-pèri lod'o, hèia Yesus paroa ana madhutu Na, ka Na peka, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a rasa kasia dènge dhèu ae-ae se. Abhu dhu mai nèti era kaj'èu, ra pakaboko ètu ne'e tèlu lod'o kèna, toke gee ra èle aa'i le. Be'a risi baku hia si lèpa dènge kabake manganga. Mage dhoka ra bèbha ètu talora j'ara.&gt;&gt;<bt>After several days, then Yesus called/summoned His followers and said, &lt;&lt;I feel pity on these many-many people here. There are those who have come from far, they have gathered already three days, to the point that there is no more trialfood. It's better they don't be allowed to go home with empty stomachs. May it not be that they faint in the middle of the road/journey.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gee = bakal"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">gee = bakal</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="33" />Te ngaa ana madhutu Yesus dhaa, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Era ne'e kaj'èu nèti rae. Tatu, èdhi bisa boe panga'a tare dhèu ae-ae sèmi se'e.&gt;&gt;<bt>But Yesus' followers replied, saying, &lt;&lt;Father! This is place is far from village/s. Surely we-inc can't feed this many people.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="34" />Te ngaa Yesus karèi si, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Roti miu pèri bua?&gt;&gt;<bt>But Yesus asked them, saying, &lt;&lt;How many fruit of bread do you have?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ra dhaa, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Dhoka pidhu di, dènge i'a pèri ngi'u di!&gt;&gt;<bt>They replied, saying, &lt;&lt;Just seven, with a few bodies of fish!&gt;&gt; [NOTE counters for bread and fish.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="35" />Ka Yesus pua dhèu se'e madhèdi ètu rai.<bt>Then2 Yesus ordered those people to sit on the ground.</bt><v n="36" />Hèia nare roti pidhu bua dènge i'a sèra, ka Na manèngi makasi mi Ama Lamatua. Ka Na pamae roti se, hèia Na j'ole asa ana madhutu Na, sèna ka ra papala mi dhèu aa'i-aa'i sèra.<bt>Then He took those seven loaves of bread with the fish, to give thanks to God. Then He broke those preads, then He handed it out to His followers, for them to go divide it out to all those people.</bt><v n="37" />Hèia aa'i-aa'i ra'a toke bècu. Ka ra kaboko rare nganga'a dhu ata, pènu pidhu soe hahake.<bt>Then they all ate until satisfied. Then, they gathered up the extra food, seven (hahake) baskets full. [NOTE to daughter translations: compare with Matt. 14:20. This should be a slightly larger type of basket here than there.]</bt><v n="38" />Dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu ra'a se, dhèu mone ele boe d'ai èpa riho dhèu sa. Dhae ige mèka bhèni dènge ana iiki sèra.<bt>All the people who ate there, approximately four thousand males. [That] does not yet count adding women and children.</bt><v n="39" />Èle ka, Yesus pua dhèu ae-ae sèra lèpa. Hèia Na ca'e asa dedha koha, ho lasi asa rai Magadan.<bt>After that, Yesus ordered those many people to go home. Then He got into a boat for them to go to Magadan area/land/country.</bt><note reference="15:39" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Rai ne, dhèu re'a boe ètu mia. Abhu sasuri lii Yunani cahag'e dhu leo, dhu suri, peka na, &lt;Magdala&gt;. Abhu cahag'e hari dhu suri, peka na, &lt;Magdalan&gt;.<bt>Where this place is, isn't clear to people. There are other Yunani language writings that write, saying, ‘Magdala’. There are still some others which write, saying, ‘Magdalan’.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu Parisi dènge dhèu Saduki neo pamanahu Lamatua Yesus<bt>Parisi people and Saduki people want to make the Lord Yesus fall (=make him make a mistake)</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 8:11-13; Lukas 12:54-56)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="16" />
      <v n="1" />Ca tèka, pèri-pèri dhèu Parisi dènge dhèu Saduki, mai paraga dènge Yesus. Rèngu neo pakarèi dènge Ne, sèna ka tenge j'ara neo pamanahu Yesus. Nèti èèna ka, ra manèngi sèmi ne'e ka, &lt;&lt;Ama! Tao ku tadha malaa, sèna ka j'aj'i tadha, dhu peka na, Ama abhu koasa nèti Ama Lamatua.&gt;&gt;<bt>One time, several Parisi people and Saduki people came to meet with Yesus. They wanted to debate with Him, in.order.to make Him fall (socially/intellectually/morally). Because of that they requested Him, saying, &lt;&lt;Father! Do a miracle, as a sign that Father has obtained power from God.&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="16:1" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 12:38, Lukas 11:16</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="2" />Te ngaa Yesus b'ala, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe èdhi tèdhi liru mea ropa lod'o cèna, èdhi te'a, na, &lt;Bèli èj'i mai boe.&gt;<bt>But Yesus responded, saying, &lt;&lt;If we see the sky's colour is red when the sun sinks, we-inc know that, &lt;Tommorow [it's] not going to rain.&gt;</bt><v n="3" />Aa ladhe lod'o rea, aa liru mèdhi, na èdhi te'a, na, &lt;Doe ne'e, oe èj'i.&gt; De ladhe miu bisa patadhe mere tadha ètu liru sèmi sèra, nga tao ka miu bisa boe patadhe mere sasoa nèti tadha-tadha jaman?<bt>And if the sun rises with the sky is dark, we-inc know that, &lt;Today [it's] going to rain.&gt; So (consequently), if you can recognise signs in the sky like those, why can you not recognise the meaning/significance of signs of the age/times (loan)?</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="oe èj'i = it's about to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">oe èj'i = it's about to rain</Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Miu dhèu lod'o limuri ne, me'a dhodhoka ad'u-ue bhabhelu di! Miu pusi-pahae boe Ama Lamatua! Masi ka miu manèngi tadha malaa, te ngaa Ja'a dale boe tao. Lula uru èèna, Lamatua dhu tao le tadha malaa re Yunus, ca dhèu nèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua. De èèna d'ai le!&gt;&gt; Ropa padhai lii nare, hèia Yesus tèke eele si.<bt>You people nowadays, only know just how do to evil! You don't care about (doublet) God! Even if you request amazing sign/s (*miracle/s), nevertheless I won't give [them]. Because previously God2 has already given amazing signs using His spokesperson Yunus. So (consequently), that's already enough!&gt;&gt; After finishing speaking like.that, then Yesus went away leaving them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dale "><Message author="Chuck" created="2009-11-26 06:47:04Z" status="Anyone">sonded mau, pusi boe, sonde toe</Message></Annotation><note reference="16:4" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 12:39, Lukas 11:29</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus aj'a, na, baku pamud'e dènge tatao dhèu Parisi dènge dhèu Saduki<bt>The Lord Yesus teaches, saying, be careful with the Parisi people and the Saduki people's behaviour/deeds/character</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 8:14-21)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Ropa Yesus si lasi asa ca bèka dano, hèia ana madhutu Na, heka sanèd'e, na, rèngu rèti boe roti tao gee j'ara.<bt>When Yesus (coll.) were going to the other side of the lake, then His followers remembered that they had forgotten to bring bread for their travel.food.</bt><v n="6" />Tadèngi rèngu padhai lii sèmi èèna, hèia Na peka na, &lt;&lt;Miu baku pamud'e dènge ragi dhèu Parisi dènge dhèu Saduki.&gt;&gt;<bt>Hearing them speak like.that, then He told [them] saying, &lt;&lt;You-p must be careful with the Parisi people and the Saduki people's yeast.&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="16:6" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lukas 12:1</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Ropa tadèngi rare, hèia ana madhutu Na bingu, ka ra peka, &lt;&lt;Na peka ngaa nèi? Ele boe ne'a na, èdhi tèti boe roti, sina ma?&gt;&gt;<bt>Hearing like that, then His followers were confused. They spoke to each other and said, &lt;&lt;What is He speaking about there? Probably He knows that we didn't bring bread, [tag question]?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Te ngaa Yesus ne'a ngangee rèngu. Ka Na padhai lii, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Wee, miu seli-kolane, nga! Nga tao ka miu padhue dhoka roti di! Miu parcaya boe Ja'a, do?<bt>But Yesus knew their thinking. So He spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;Wee, You are too much, nga! Why are you talking about bread! You don't believe/trust Me, [tag question]?</bt><v n="9" />Miu dhae me'a iia mèka koasa Ja'a, do? Te lod'o Ja'a pamae lèmi bua roti ho panga'a lèmi riho dhèu sèra, dhu sisa, miu pakaboko mere pèri soe?<bt>Do you still not understand My power, [tag question]? Cuz (elaboration) that day when I broke up those five loaves of bread to feed those five thousand people, how many <span class="Italic">soe </span>baskets did you gather of that excess/left.over?</bt><note reference="16:9" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 14:17-21</note><v n="10" />Aa tasamia hari dènge roti pidhu bua dhu Ja'a panga'a èpa riho dhèu sèra? Abhu pèri soe hahake dhu miu pakaboko nèti dhu ra'a risi sèra?<bt>Then what about again those seven breads which I divided out to those four thousand people? How many <span class="Italic">hahake </span>baskets did you collect of that excess/left.over? [NOTE to daughter translations: Gk uses 2 different words for basket for 2 different incedents. If possible, use normal size for 5,000 and larger size for 4,000, as in Mark.]</bt><note reference="16:10" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 15:34-38</note><v n="11" />Nga tao ka miu mo'o boe me'a dènge lii padhai Ja'a deo na? Ja'a padhue-padhai boe lula roti. Te Ja'a neo pasanèd'e miu, sèna ka miu baku pamud'e dènge tatao dhèu Parisi dènge dhèu Saduki. Te lii aj'a-nori ra bisa ère rare dhèu ae, nuka sèmi ragi dhu tao roti j'aj'i kapai.&gt;&gt;<bt>Why do you not understand those words of Mine earlier? I wasn't talking (doublet) about bread. Cuz (elaboration) I want/ed to remind/warn you, so that you are careful of the Parisi people and the Saduki people's behaviour/deeds/ character. Cuz (elaboration) their teaching (doublet) can pull/influence many people, the same as yeast makes the bread to become big.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Ropa Yesus padhai lii sèmi èèna, hèia heka rèngu re'a kèna, na Nèngu peka boe roti. Te ngaa Na padhue-padhai nèti a'aj'a dhu sale nèti dhèu Parisi dènge dhèu Saduki.<bt>When Yesus spoke like.that, only then did they understand that He was not talking about bread. But He was talking about the Parisi people and the Saduki people teachings which are wrong.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Petrus mangaku, peka na, Lamatua Yesus èèna, Kristus<bt>Petrus acknowledges that the Lord Yesus is Kristus</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 8:27-30; Lukas 9:18-21)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Èle, hèia Yesus si lasi asa rai dhu padètu dènge kota Kaisarea Pilipi. Ètu talora j'ara, Na karèi ana madhutu Na, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Madhutu lii papeka dhèu, Ja'a, Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a ne, cee?&gt;&gt;<bt>After that, then Yesus (coll.) went to the region/land near the city of Kaisarea Pilipi. In the middle of the road/journey (Mark 8:27) He aked His followers, saying, “According to people's talk, they say, I, the Ideal Human, am who?” [EXEG: vs.13 must also have people - Son of Man, then vs. 15 you - Me. (see Morris). “on the journey” from Mark 8:27.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Ra dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Abhu dhu peka na, Ama ne, Yohanis tuka sarani dhu mamuri hari. Cahag'e peka na, ele boe Ama ne, Elia. Cahag'e hari ale na, Yermia. Ladhe aad'o, na, ca dhèu leo nèti dhèu rèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua uru-uru sèra.&gt;&gt;<bt>They answered, saying, &lt;&lt;There are those who say Father here, is Yohanis the habitual baptizer who is alive again. Others say, probably Elia. Yet others mention Yeremia. If not (those), na, one of God's other spokespersons from long ago.&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="16:14" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 14:1-2, Markus 6:14-15, Lukas 9:7-8</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Ka Yesus karèi hari si, &lt;&lt;Ladhe madhutu miu mesa mi, Ja'a ne, cee?&gt;&gt;<bt>Next Yesus asked them again, saying, &lt;&lt;If according to your ownselves, I here, am who?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Hèia Simon Petrus dhaa, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama ne, Kristus, nuka Dhèu dhu uru èèna Ama Lamatua pajaji tèke ho neo hia mai! Aa Ama ne, Ana Ama Lamatua dhu mamuri toke d'ai mia-mia!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Simon Petrus answered, saying, &lt;&lt;Father here, is Kristus, that is that Person whom long.ago God promised to send! And Father (=you) here, are the Child of the God who lives continually!&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="16:16" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yohanis 6:68-69</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Èle èèna ka, Yesus lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;Simon, ana Yunus! Èu ne, oto kapai! Te nèti boe dhèu rai-haha dhu peka lii ne'e dènge èu. Te ngaa Ama Ku ètu sorga ka peka dènge èu.<bt>Then3 Yesus said, &lt;&lt;Simon, Yunus' child! You-s here are really fortunate! Cuz (elaboration) it is not humans who told this matter to you. But My Father in heaven who told you.</bt><v n="18" />Nanene, ee! Karèi nèti deo ne'e ne, Ja'a pangare èu, &lt;Petrus&gt;. Dhu sasoa na, hadhu.<bt>Listen, ee! Beginning from now I want to name you, &lt;Petrus&gt;. Its meaning is, stone.</bt><note reference="16:18" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Yesus tao lii pacele ètu ne'e. Te lii Yunani peka na, Πέτρος (<span class="Italic">Petros,</span> nuka, ngara dhèu), aa πέτρᾳ (<span class="Italic">petra,</span> nuka, hadhu).<bt>Yesus is making a word play here. Cuz (elaboration) the Yunani language says, Πέτρος (<span class="Italic">Petros</span>, that is, a person's name), and πέτρᾳ (<span class="Italic">petra</span>, that is, rock).</bt></note>Lula parcaya èu, èra sèmi hadhu, èèna na èu j'aj'i era padhèdi nèti dhèu-dhèu Ja'a dhu parcaya. Masi ka rèngu abhu j'aj'èra toke madhe, te ngaa rèngu taha taruu.<bt>Because your belief is strong like stone, later you will become a setting on place (foundation) for My believing people (=believers = church). Even if they experience suffering to the point of dying, they will endure continually.</bt><v n="19" />Ja'a èèna na hia èu hak, sèna ka èu uri dhèu-dhèu Ja'a, nuka sèmi èu mèd'u gagoe sorga. Te, ngaa dhu èu kai ètu rai-haha, èèna na Lamatua kai ètu sorga kahèi. Dènge ngaa dhu èu hia isin ètu rai-haha ne, Lamatua hia le isin ètu sorga kahèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>I will later give right/authority to you to manage/arrange/oversee My people, like as if you held heaven's key. Cuz (elaboration) that which you forbid on earth, God2 also forbids in heaven. And that which you give permission on earth, God2 has already also permitted in heaven.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gagoe = kunci (kb) ; goe"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">gagoe = kunci (kb) ; goe = kunci (kk)</Message></Annotation><note reference="16:19" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 18:18, Yohanis 20:23</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Padhai lii nare sèmi èèna, ka Yesus kai si ho rèngu baku peka dènge dhèu, na, Nèngu ne, Kristus.<bt>After speaking like.that, then Yesus forbade them to not tell any one that He was Kristus.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus peka j'ara mamadhe dènge mamuri hari Na<bt>The Lord Yesus tells about His death and His living again</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 8:31--9:1; Lukas 9:22-27)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Karèi nèti lod'o èèna, Yesus peka dènge ana madhutu Na sèra, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a hud'i laku ku asa Yerusalem. Te ngaa ètu nèi, Ja'a abhu j'aj'èra ae-ae, nèti dhèu heka-dhèu heka ad'a, kètu agama Yahudi dènge mese agama sèra. Èèna na ra pamadhe Ja'a, te ngaa camèd'a èèna, Ja'a mamuri hari.&gt;&gt;<bt>Beginning from that time, Yesus told His followers, saying, &lt;&lt;I must go to the city of Yerusalem. But there (remote), I will get/experience lots of suffering from the traditional elders, the *chief priests, and the religion teachers. Later they will kill Me, but on the day.after.the.next.day, I will live again.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Ropa Yesus padhai lii nare, hèia Petrus ère nare Yesus asa karasa, ka na kai, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama, baku padhai lii sèmi èèna! Tatu Ama Lamatua soro tèke boe j'ara ne j'aj'i!&gt;&gt;<bt>Yesus told like that, then Petrus pulled Him away to the side to scold [him] saying, &lt;&lt;Father, don't speak like.that! Surely God would not allow that to happen!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Te ngaa lii padhai Petrus ne, madhutu boe dad'èi Lamatua. Nèti èèna ka, Yesus kabib'a, ka jèke ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Heh! Pakaj'èu nèti ne'e! Lii padhai èèna nèti dhèu aae nidhu! Èu baku bhabhae Ja'a! Èu ne dhodhoka pangee madhutu dad'èi dhèu rai-haha di, te ngaa madhutu boe dad'èi Ama Lamatua!&gt;&gt;<bt>But that speaking of Petrus', did not follow God2's will. That's why Yesus turned back and scolded2 him, saying, &lt;&lt;Heh! [+rebuke] Get away from here! That speaking is from the king of evil.spirit/s! You don't hinder/ obstruct Me! You only think according to human's will/desire, not according to God's will/desire!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bhabhae = halangi (DUP, active) ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">bhabhae = halangi (DUP, active) ; bhae = halangi</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Èle èèna ka, hèia Yesus aj'a ana madhutu Na sèra, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu dhu neo madhutu Ja'a, nèngu hud'i taha taruu ku bèli-bèli! Nèngu hud'i pa'uru ku dad'èi Ama Lamatua, aa pabhèlu eele dad'èi nèngu unu na. Masi ka dhèu neo pamadhe ne, nèngu hud'i madhutu Ja'a taruu, sama sèmi dhèu pasae aj'u palolo-palèbha na, la'e asa era mamadhe na.<bt>After that, Yesus taught His followers, saying, &lt;&lt;The person who wants to follow Me, s/he must endure following continually every day! S/He must prioritise God's will, and completely forget his own will. Even if people want to kill him/her, s/he must just follow Me continually, like a person shoulder.carrying his/her *cross to his place of dying.</bt><note reference="16:24" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 10:38, Lukas 14:27</note><v n="25" />Te dhèu dhu sadia madhe lula na madhutu Ja'a, bèli-camèd'a nèngu abhu mamuri taruu dènge Ama Lamatua. Te ngaa dhèu dhu d'èi dhoka mamuri hia ngi'u aae na di, èèna na mamuri nèngu ele iie d'ara!<bt>Cuz (elaboration) the person who is prepared to die because s/he follows Me, later s/he will be able to live continually with God. But the person who only wants to live for just his/her own self, later2 that life of his/hers, will disapper just like that!</bt><note reference="16:25" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 10:39, Lukas 17:33, Yohanis 12:25</note><v n="26" />Nanene paie-iie! Ladhe èu abhu aa'i isi rai-haha ne, te ngaa ladhe Lamatua core eele èu, a'oto na ètu mia? Masi ka èu pasae mèti aa'i isi rai-haha ne, èu bisa boe pasilu dènge samanga èu!<bt>Listen carefully! If you obtain all of the world's contents, but God2 rejects you, where is the benefit? Even if you shoulder.carry bringing all the world's contents, you cannot exchange [it/them] for your soul!</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Ja'a peka mema dènge miu j'ara aa'i-aa'i ra, lula Ja'a ne, Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a. Bèli-camèd'a Ja'a mai hari dènge dadedha nèti Ama Ku, palere-lere dènge ana pajuu Na nèti sorga. Lod'o èèna, pe Ja'a b'ala mi ca dhèu-ca dhèu madhutu tatao ra.<bt>I tell you all these things beforehand, because I here, am the Ideal/ Prototypical Human. Later I will come back again with My Father's high-ness/glory, together with His underlings from heaven. At that time later I will reciprocate/reward to each person according to what s/he has done.</bt><note reference="16:27" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 25:31, Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 62:12, Roma 2:6</note><v n="28" />Sanèd'e paie! Nèti miu aa'i-aa'i se, bèli-camèd'a abhu cahag'e dhu madhe boe, toke ra rèdhi Ja'a, nuka Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a ne, j'aj'i Dhèu Aae dhu kèd'u paredha.&gt;&gt;<bt>Remember [this] well! From all of you here, later there will be some people who do not die, until the time/when they get to see Me, the Ideal Human, as a King who rules/governs.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ama Lamatua pad'elo dadedha Lamatua Yesus<bt>God shows the high-ness/glory of the Lord Yesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 9:2-13; Lukas 9:28-36)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="17" />
      <v n="1" />Èle èna lod'o, ka Yesus paroa Petrus, Yakobis dènge ari na Yohanis, sèna ka lasi asa ledhe dhu dedha èci, ho pea mesa ra ètu nèi.<bt>After six days, then Yesus called/summoned Petrus, Yakobis and his younger.sibling Yohanis, for them to go up on top of a tall mountain, so.that they would be alone there (remote).</bt><v n="2" />D'ai nèi, ra ladhe na, rupa Yesus leko-leo. Rèhu Na kaha'a nuka sèmi madha lod'o, aa mèdha-papake Na j'aj'i pudhi kale'e.<bt>Arriving there (remote), they saw Yesus form/shape had become different. His face shone like the sun, and His clothes had become blazing/bright white.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kaha'a = bersinar, cahaya"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">kaha'a = bersinar, cahaya</Message></Annotation><v n="3" />Kaca'a la, rèngu ladhe rèdhi Yesus dhu padhai lii dènge Musa dènge Elia.<bt>Unexpectedly, they saw Him conversing with Musa and Elia.</bt><v n="4" />Hèia Petrus bingu, ka na padhai lii leli, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Ji'i karej'e titu kèna ètu era ne'e ne! De be'a risi ji'i patitu paleo tèlu bua. Cue hia Ama, cue hia Musa, aa cue hari hia Elia.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Petrus became confused, to.the.point.that he spoke recklessly/without.basis saying, &lt;&lt;Father! We-exc are really happy in this place! So (consequently) it's better if (=how about if) we make three huts/shelters/tents. One for Father, one for Musa, and one more for Elia.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Lod'o Petrus padhai lii sèmi èèna era, cag'ag'a laa, ra'i-liru puru mai sarimu nare rèngu. Hèia rèngu malaa-maloha tadèngi lii èci dhu kalua nèti d'ara ra'i-liru ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Nanene! Yesus ne, Ana pasue Ja'a. Nèngu ne'e ka dhu pakarej'e taruu d'ara Ja'a. Nanene Ne paie-iie!&gt;&gt;<bt>When Petrus was still talking like.that, suddenly/unexpectedly a cloud came down and covered over/blanketed them. Then they were surprised (doublet) hearing a voice come out of the cloud, saying, &lt;&lt;Listen! Yesus here, is My beloved Child. He always/regularly makes My insides happy. Listen carefully to him!&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="17:1-5" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">2 Petrus 1:17-18, Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 22:2, Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 2:7, Yesaya 42:1, Mateos 3:17, 12:18, Markus 1:11, Lukas 3:22, Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 18:15</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Ropa tadèngi lii ne, hèia ana madhutu Na madha'u titu kèna, ka ra bèbha sagèb'a ètu rai.<bt>Hearing like.that then that those followers were extremely afraid, and they fell flat on their faces. [EXEG: TB lexical choice is misleading here. Gk doesn't imply a posture for worshipping.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sagèb'a = matono ; baa-baa ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">sagèb'a = matono ; baa-baa = kaku</Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Te ngaa Yesus mai gai si, ka Na peka na, &lt;&lt;Mi kèd'i ka, baku madha'u!&gt;&gt;<bt>But Yesus came finger.flicking them and He said, &lt;&lt;You-p get up. Don't be afraid!&gt;&gt;</bt><v n="8" />Ka ana madhutu se boti kètu ra, te ngaa ra ladhe rèdhi heka dhèu èci sa ètu era èèna, dhoka Yesus di.<bt>Then2 the followers lifted their faces, but they could not see anyone there, only just Yesus.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Èle ka, ra puru nèti ledhe ne. Hèia Yesus kai si, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ngaa dhu heka ladhe mèdhi deo na, mage peka dènge dhèu èci sa kahèi! Te Ja'a Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a ne, hud'i madhe uuru ku. Èle èèna, ladhe Ja'a mamuri hari, heka miu lole dènge dhèu kèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>After that, they started to go down from that mountain. Then Yesus forbade them, saying, &lt;&lt;What you saw earlier there, don't tell anyone else! Cuz (elaboration) I, this Ideal/Prototypical Human, must die first. Then, later if/when I already live again, only.then you can tell people.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Hèia ra karèi Ne, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama ne mema Kristus, te ngaa Elia ètu mia? Te mese agama se aj'a, peka na, Elia hud'i mai uuru ku, èle èèna, heka Kristus mai kèna. Te ngaa madhutu Ama, tasamia?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then they asked Him, saying, &lt;&lt;Father here, is really Kristus, but where is Elia? Cuz (elaboration) those religion teachers teach, saying, Elia must come first, only.then Kristus comes. But according to Father, how.is.it?&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="17:10" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Meliaki 4:5</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Ka Yesus dhaa, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Mema lèke. Elia hud'i mai uuru ku, ho bhoke j'ara hia Kristus.<bt>And Yesus answered, saying, &lt;&lt;That's actually true! Elia must come first to open the path for Kristus.</bt><v n="12" />Nanene paie! Elia mai le, te ngaa dhèu tadhe boe ne. Rèngu paj'èra ne, madhutu dad'èi ra. Sèmi èèna kahèi, bèli-camèd'a rèngu paj'èra Ja'a, Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>Listen well! Elia has already come, but people did not know/recognise him. They caused difficulty to him, according to their desires/will. Like that also, later they do to Me, this Ideal/Prototypical Human.&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="17:12" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 11:14</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Ropa ra tadèngi rare, ana madhutu Na heka re'a, na, Elia dhu Yesus peka ne, nuka Yohanis tuka sarani.<bt>After hearing like that, then His followers came to realise that the Elia whom Yesus was talking about there, was Yohanis the habitual baptizer.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus pa'èle ana èci dhu nidhu tao<bt>The Lord Yesus heals a child who is afflicted with evil.spirit/s</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 9:14-29; Lukas 9:37-43a)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Èle ka, ropa rèngu lèpa, paraga dènge dhèu ae dhu mate le. Hèia ama ca dhèu mai patitu kètu urutuu, ka na manèngi Yesus,<bt>After that, when they had returned, they met many people who waiting for them. Then a father came kneeling to request help from Yesus,</bt><v n="15" />na peka, &lt;&lt;Ama! Sue ku ana ja'a la! Te nèngu dhu huj'u kahib'i, aa na j'èra titu kèna. Ladhe èi papèd'a ne cèu, na bèbhe sa d'ara èi, do d'ara ai. Ama sue ku la!<bt>saying, &lt;&lt;Father! Love/pity my child! (=Help) Cuz (elaboration) he has crazy goat sickness (=epilepsy), and he is suffering greatly. If/when that sickness appears, he falls in water or in fire. Please help, Father!</bt><v n="16" />Ana ne, ja'a kèti le asa ana-ana madhutu Ama ku, te ngaa ra tao rare boe ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>I have already brought this child to Father's followers, but they could not do anything (successfully) for him.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Ropa Na tadèngi sèmi èèna, hèia Yesus jèke ana madhutu Na sèra, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Heh! Miu se seli-kolane! Ja'a aj'a le miu pahari-pahari, te ngaa miu me'a mèu boe. Aa miu parcaya boe Ja'a dènge d'ara kateme. Ja'a hud'i mate hari ku miu, d'ai pèri lod'o? Mèti ana èèna mai!&gt;&gt;<bt>Hearing like.that, then Yesus spoke angrily to His followers, saying, &lt;&lt;Heh! [+negative] You guys are too much! I have taught you over and over, but you don't understand well. And you don't believe in Me wholeheartedly! I have to be patient with you until when?! Bring that child here!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Hèia, rèti ana ne, ka Yesus babège eele nidhu nèti ana ne'e. Ka nidhu rai tèke eele ne, hèia ana ne èle dènge ka.<bt>Then they brought that child, then2 Yesus expelled that evil.spirit out of that child. Then2 that evil.spirit fled leaving behind that child, and he was healed straight.away.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Èle èèna ka, ropa Yesus mesa Na dènge ana madhutu sèra, ka ra karèi Ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Nga tao ka ji'i bisa boe babège ngare nidhu deo na?&gt;&gt;<bt>After that, when Yesus was alone together with His followers, they asked Him, saying, &lt;&lt;Father! Why could we-exc not (successfully - implied by SVC) expel that evil.spirit earlier?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Ka Yesus dhaa, na, &lt;&lt;Miu babège mere boe, lula miu parcaya boe dènge d'ara kateme. Sanèd'e! Ladhe miu parcaya Ja'a tare'a-re'a, masi ka ciki oo'e èèna ka sama sèmi lamusi ana iiki-iiki èci,<bt>Yesus replied, saying, &lt;&lt;You couldn't (successfully) expel that evil.spirit, because you don't believe wholeheartedly. If you truly believe in Me, even if only just a tiny bit,</bt><note reference="17:20" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Lamatua Yesus pakasame parcaya dhèu dènge lamusi dhu ana iiki-iiki èci. Ètu ayat ne'e, kapai lamusi dhu panting, te ngaa jenis lamusi panting boe. Alkitab lii Idhonesia ètu ne'e, peka na, &lt;biji sesawi&gt;, te ngaa abhu masala ae dènge tafsiran èèna.<bt>The Lord Yesus is comparing a person's faith/belief with a very tiny seed. Here, it is the size of the seed which is important, but the kind/type of seed is not important. The Indonesian Bible here says, ‘seed of Chinese cabbage [in a form not found in most dictionaries]’, but there are several problems with that interpretation.</bt></note>miu bisa paredha ledhe èci, peka na, &lt;Hee ledhe, hari sa nèi, lamu!&gt; Tatu na hari kahèi. De miu bisa tao ngaa èèna ka, sad'i parcaya dènge d'ara kateme.<bt>you can order a mountain, saying &lt;Hee mountain! Move over there!&gt; Surely it will move. So (consequently), you can do anything, as long as (you) believe whole-heartedly.</bt><note reference="17:20" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 21:21, Markus 11:23, 1 Korintus 13:2</note><v n="21" />[Te ngaa sanèd'e! Nidhu sèmi se'e se, mema bhelu titu kèna. Ladhe miu sabaj'a boe aa puasa boe, ho manèngi mi Ama Lamatua, na, miu babège mere boe nidhu sèmi sèra.&gt;&gt;]<bt>[But remember! Evil.spirits like these are excessively evil. If you-p don't pray and fast in.order.to request help from God, na, you can't expel an evil.sprit like that.&gt;&gt;]</bt><note reference="17:21" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Sasuri lii Yunani dhu be'a risi aa dhu uru tèka, suri boe ayat 21 ne.<bt>The best and oldest Yunani language writings don't write this verse 21.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus peka dua hari kèna, lula-nèti mamadhe Na<bt>The Lord Yesus talks a second time about His death</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 9:30-32; Lukas 9:43b-45)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Ca lod'o, Yesus dènge ana madhutu Na dhu pakaboko ètu propensi Galilea. Na peka dènge rèngu, na, &lt;&lt;Nèbhu heka, te ra neo pahie Ja'a asa dhèu leo rai kara.<bt>One time, Yesus and His followers were gathered in Galilea province. He told them, saying, &lt;&lt;Not much longer, they will sell (=betray) Me to other (foreign) people.</bt><v n="23" />Hèia ra pamadhe Ja'a, Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a ne. Mema tare'a Ja'a madhe, te ngaa asa camèd'a Ja'a mamuri hari.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then they will kill Me, this Ideal/Prototypical Human. I will truly die, but later on the day.after.the.following.day, I will live again.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ropa ana madhutu Na sèra tadèngi lii deo na, hèia d'ara ra susa titu kèna.<bt>Hearing His talk like.that, then thier insides were very distressed.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus peka-padhai lula-nèti b'ae bea èmu sabaj'a<bt>The Lord Yesus talks (doublet) about the worship houses' tax</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Lod'o Yesus dènge ana madhutu Na lasi asa rae Kapernaum, hèia dhèu roro bea mai paraga dènge Petrus, ka ra karèi ne, na, &lt;&lt;Mese miu b'ae bea Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i do, aad'o?&gt;&gt;<bt>When Yesus and his followers arrived in Kapernaum village, then tax collectors came to meet with Petrus and asked him, saying, &lt;&lt;Does your-pl Teacher pay the *Temple tax, or not?&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="17:24" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 30:13, 38:26</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Hèia Petrus dhaa, &lt;&lt;Na b'ae!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Petrus replied saying, &lt;&lt;He pays!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ropa Petrus lepa, ka Yesus karèi dènge ka, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Simon, èu pangee ku la! Dhèu aae-dhèu aae ètu rai-haha ne abhu bea nèti cee? Nèti ana matana ra, do, nèti dhèu leo?&gt;&gt;<bt>When he went home, then2 Yesus immediately asked him first, saying, &lt;&lt;Simon, have a think. The kings of this world take/get/obtain tax from who? From their own child(ren), or from other people?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Petrus dhaa, na, &lt;&lt;Nèti dhèu leo!&gt;&gt;<bt>Petrus replied saying, &lt;&lt;From other people!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka Yesus tuhu lii padhai Na, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe sèmi èèna, ana dhèu aae di dhu b'ae boe, si?<bt>Then2 Yesus continued speaking, saying, &lt;&lt;If that's the case, the kings own child doesn't pay, right? [EXEG: See Carson for cristalogical significance of this.]</bt><v n="27" />Sèmi èèna kahèi dènge bea Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i. Te ngaa hud'i laa, sèna ka dhèu roro bea se baku nasa dènge èdhi. De be'a risi lamu madulu i'a asa d'ara dano. I'a dhu èu abhu uuru èèna, èu bhoke hèb'a na. Pe èu abhu doi iia cue. More, ho b'ae bea èdhi dua ti. Te doi ne, d'ai le bea èdhi dua ti.&gt;&gt;<bt>It's the same with the Temple tax. But, let it be, so we-inc don't make those tax collectors angry with us-inc. So (consequently), it's better if you just go fish for fish in the lake. The first fish you get, you open its mouth. Later you will find a silver money there. Take it, to go pay us two's tax. Cuz (elaboration) this money is enough to pay for the two of us-inc.&gt;&gt; [NOTE: Why does the TB say “dirham” here?? Point out to your team how bad this is from a translation perspective. It neither transliterates the Gk, nor translates it into an Indonesian word that anybody has ever known, Nobody knows where they got it!!]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="madulu = pancing"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">madulu = pancing</Message></Annotation><note reference="17:27" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Tèu mai-tèu mai, dhèu mone Yahudi sèra dhu umur 20 tèu sa dedha, hud'i b'ae bea èci dhu soru-bara j'aga mèdha-panyau dènge èmu nèti Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i (baca ètu sasuri <span class="Italic">Kalua nèti Masir</span> 30:12-16). Tèu Lamatua Yesus mamuri, ra ige bea èèna dènge doi<span class="Italic"> didrakma. Didrakma</span> cue, kab'ua na, èci èèna ka dènge dua <span class="Italic">dinari</span>. Ca <span class="Italic">dinari</span> èèna, èci èèna ka dènge gaji ca dhèu tuka d'ara ca lod'o. Ètu ayat ne'e, Yesus peka mi Petrus, aku Nèngu na, pe nèngu abhu ca doi <span class="Italic">stater</span> ètu d'ara hèb'a i'a èèna. Ca doi <span class="Italic">stater</span> kab'ua na, nuka dua <span class="Italic">didrakma</span>, do, èpa <span class="Italic">dinari</span> -- d'ai b'ae bea nèti Yesus dènge Petrus.<bt>Each year, each male Yahudi who was 20 years old and older must pay a tax to help (doublet) care for the *Temple (read in <span class="Italic">Exit from Masir</span> 30:12-16). While the Lord Yesus was alive, they counted that tax with the <span class="Italic">didrakma</span> money/coin. The value of one <span class="Italic">didrakma</span> was the same as two <span class="Italic">dinari</span>. One <span class="Italic">dinari</span> was equivalent to a worker/craftsman's wages for one day. In this verse, Yesus was telling Petrus that he would find a <span class="Italic">stater</span> money/coin in that fish's mouth. The value of one <span class="Italic">stater</span> was two <span class="Italic">didrakma s</span>, or, four <span class="Italic">dinari</span> -- enough to pay that tax for Yesus and Petrus.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ana-ana madhutu Lamatua Yesus pakarèi, na, cee ka dhu kapai risi<bt>The Lord Yesus' followers ask who is the biggest/greatest</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 9:33-37; Lukas 9:46-48)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="18" />
      <v n="1" />Lod'o èèna, ana madhutu Yesus lasi karèi Ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Nèti dhèu-dhèu unu Ama Lamatua, cee ka dhu kapai risi?&gt;&gt;<bt>At that time, Yesus' followers came to Him to ask, saying, &lt;&lt;Father! Who is the biggest/most important of God's people?&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="18:1" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lukas 22:24</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="2" />Hèia Yesus paroa nare ana iiki èci, mai patitu asa talora aae rèngu.<bt>Then Yesus called/summoned a small child, and stood him in their midst.</bt><v n="3" />Ka Na peka dènge ra, &lt;&lt;Nanene paie-iie! Dhèu dhu neo j'aj'i dhèu unu Lamatua, rèngu hud'i ub'a ngangee ra, ho j'aj'i sama sèmi ana iiki dhu ne'a boe padedha iisi.<bt>Then2 He spoke to them, saying, &lt;&lt;Listen carefully! A person who wants to become God2's person, he must change his/her thinking to become the same as a small child who does not know how to elevate (=praise) him/herself.</bt><note reference="18:3" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Markus 10:15, Lukas 18:17</note><v n="4" />Lula dhèu dhu ne'a pahaha iisi sama sèmi ana iiki ne, nèngu èèna ka dhu kapai risi ètu madha Ama Lamatua.<bt>Because the person who is lowers/humbles themself like this small child here, he there is the person who is the biggest/most important before God.</bt><v n="5" />Aa dhèu dhu sèmi nare dhèu haha nuka sèmi ana iiki ne, lula na parcaya Ja'a, na, nèngu sèmi nare le Ja'a ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>And the person who accepts/receives a low/ insignificant person like this child here, because s/he believes in Me, na, that person has received/accepted Me.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus pasanèd'e lula-nèti dhèu dhu tao dhèu leo sèna ka ra ad'u-ue sasala<bt>The Lord Yesus reminds about people who make other people do wrong</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 9:42-48; Lukas 17:1-2)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Èle èèna ka, Yesus padhai lii hari, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe abhu dhèu dhu tao ana iiki sèna ka madhutu j'ara dhu sale, toke ana ne parcaya heka Ja'a, na, mata unu na! Be'a risi dhèu èki hadhu aae cue,<bt>Then Yesus spoke again saying, &lt;&lt;If there is a person who makes a small child/unempowered person so they follow a/the path/way that is wrong, to.the.point.that s/he does not believe in Me anymore, na, watch out [language of threat/risk]! It's better (if/for) people tie a big stone</bt><note reference="18:6" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Sasuri lii Yunani suri, peka na, &lt;&lt;hadhu gili&gt;&gt; dhu ra pake ho mol are-gandum.<bt>Greek language writings write, saying, &lt;grinding stone&gt; which they use to mill wheat grain.</bt></note>mi ladha goro na, ho pacène ne asa d'ara dhasi marèma.<bt>, on his/her neck, and sink/drown him/her in the deep ocean.</bt><v n="7" />Rai-haha ne mema era dhu pènu dènge dhudhu-sete, lula abhu j'ara ae dhu pamanahu dhèu asa d'ara sasala-sasigo. Te ngaa dhèu dhu dui babia risi, nuka dhèu dhu tenge-tenge j'ara ho soro dhèu asa d'ara sasala.<bt>[CHECK metaphor] This world here is truly a place of thorns &amp; briers (=misfortune &amp; calamity), because there many things which make people fall in sin (doublet). But that people/person who carries the greatest burden/risk, is the person who looks for ways to infleunce other people to do wrong.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dhudhu-sete = duri (simbol tantangan &amp;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">dhudhu-sete = duri (simbol tantangan &amp; penderitaan)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Ladhe èu tao sala, pake kacui-aai èu, do, haga èu, na, poro eele ne! Te be'a risi èu maso asa d'ara sorga dènge ai cabèka, do, haga calaa. Mage dhoka ra core èu asa d'ara ai naraka, dènge ai do haga dhu tesa.<bt>If you do wrong using your hand/arm, or your foot/leg, na, just cut it off! Cuz (elaboration) it's better you enter heaven with a hand/arm on just one side, or a foot/leg on just one side. May it not be that they throw you into hell fire with both of your hands and feet complete.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Ladhe èu manahu asa dara sasala"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">Ladhe èu manahu asa dara sasala lula ai èu, do haga mu, na poro eele ne! Te be'a risi maso sorga dènge ai calaa, do haga cabèka, nèti ai do haga dhu tesa, te ngaa core asa dara ai naraka.</Message></Annotation><note reference="18:8" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 5:30</note><v n="9" />Ladhe èu tao sala, pake musi madha èu, na, cèru eele ne! Te be'a risi èu maso asa d'ara sorga dènge musi madha cabèka. Mage dhoka ra core èu asa d'ara ai naraka, dènge musi madha dhu tesa.&gt;&gt;<bt>If you do wrong using your eye, just gouge it out! Cuz (elaboration) it's better you enter heaven with an eye on just one side. May it not be that they throw you into hell fire with both of your eyes complete.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="cèru = cungkil"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">cèru = cungkil</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bèbhe asa dara sasala lula musi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">bèbhe asa dara sasala lula musi madha mu, na cèru eele ne! Te be'a risi èu lamu asa dara sorga dènge musi madha cabèka, nèti musi madha dhu tesa, te ngaa pèci mu asa dara ai naraka.&gt;&gt;</Message></Annotation><note reference="18:9" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 5:29</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus hia lii pakasame lula-nèti kahib'i-kalèbho ci'u dhu ele<bt>The Lord Yesus gives an example/comparison about one sheep which disappears (=the usual way to talk to about ‘losing’ st)</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Lukas 15:3-7)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Ka Yesus tuhu hari lii Na, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Sanèd'e, ee! Baku mi pahaha ana iiki sèmi se'e se. Te abhu ana pajuu Ama Lamatua nèti sorga dhu madhenga si. Aa ana pajuu se dhu lasi taruu, peka dènge Ama Lamatua ngaa-ngaa dhu j'aj'i mi ana se.<bt>Yesus spoke again saying, &lt;&lt;Remember, ee! May it not be that you-p look.disparagingly/belittle a small child/unempowered person like this. Cuz (elaboration) God has their *angels (underlings) from heaven who are watching/guarding them. And those underlings can go any time, to tell God what has happened to these children.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11-13" />Mi pangee paie-iie, te Ja'a hia lii pakasame èci sèmi ne'e ka: abhu dhèu èci dhu kahib'i-kalèbho na, cangasu ngi'u. Ca lod'o, ci'u nèti kahib'i-kalèbho se, kako sala j'ara. Madhutu ngangee miu, dhèu madhenga ne tao tasamia? Tatu na tèke eele ceo nguru ceo ngi'u sèra ètu ledhe, ho la'e tenge ci'u dhu ele ne.<bt>You think carefully, cuz (elaboration) I want to give an example like this: there was a person who had one hundred bodies (counter) of sheep. One day, one tail of sheep (counter for single one) wandered off-track/astray. According to your thinking, what must that shepherd do? Surely he/she will leave those 99 bodies of sheep on the mountain, to go look for that one tail of sheep which disappeared.</bt><note reference="18:11" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lukas 19:10</note></p>
    <fig path="HK-LB\LB00001C.tif" rtfFormat="width:5.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right">Dhèu madhenge abhu hari kahib'i-kalèbho dhu ele<bt>A shepherd finds (the) sheep which was lost</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ladhe na abhu hari, tatu na karej'e, ropa na ladhe nèdhi ci'u ne, risi nèti kahib'i-kalèbho na ceo nguru ceo ngi'u dhu ele boe sèra. [Ja'a, Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a ne, mai ho hia mamuri mi dhèu dhu kako sale nèti j'ara dhu mola.]<bt>If/when s/he finds it again, surely s/he will be happier seeing that one sheep there, than when s/he sees his 99 bodies of sheep which didn't disappear. [I, this Ideal/Prototypical Human, also came/come to *save/give life to people who have deviated from the straight/righteous path/way.]</bt><note reference="18:11-13" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Sasuri lii Yunani dhu be'a risi aa dhu uru tèka, suri boe kalimat ètu d'ara kurung ne.<bt>The Yunani language writings which are the best and the oldest don't carry/load this sentence in parentheses (loan).</bt></note><v n="14" />Te, masi ka ana iiki ca dhèu di dhu kako sala j'ara, te ngaa Ama Ku ètu sorga d'èi boe kahèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>Cuz (elaboration) even if only just one small child/unempowered person gets lost/disappears, nevertheless My Father in heaven does not like it.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus aj'a j'ara tasamia, ho èdhi pabe'a hari dènge dhèu dhu tao sala mi èdhi<bt>The Lord Yesus teaches how we-inc can be reciprocally good with people who do wrong to us</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Yesus lii hari, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe a'ari èu dhèu parcaya tao sale mi èu, na, èu mesa mu lamu paraga dènge ne. Ladhe miu dua mi mesa mi, heka èu peka sasala nèngu kèna. Ladhe na sèmi nare lii padhai èu, na, miu dua mi pabe'a hari le kèna.<bt>Yesus spoke again saying, &lt;&lt;If your sibling/fellow believer does wrong to you-sg, na, you are the one who must go meet with him/her. When the two of you are alone, only then tell his/her wrong. If s/he accepts what you say, na, the two of you are in a reciprocally good relationship again. [EXEG: NRSV, NLT, CEV, Morris.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rode = ganggu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">rode = ganggu</Message></Annotation><note reference="18:15" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lukas 17:3</note><v n="16" />Te ngaa ladhe no'o boe sèmi nare lii padhai èu, lamu paroa more angalai mu ca dhèu do dua dhèu, ho lami paraga dènge ne, sèna ka padhai lii hari. Te ètu d'ara Sasuri Mola-Mèci Ama Lamatua dhu suri tèke, peka na, &lt;Ètu d'ara lii langu èci, hud'i abhu ku dua-tèlu sakasii dhu lii èci, heka sèmi rare lii galaa ra.&gt;<bt>But if s/he doesn't want to accepts what you say, na, go get one or two of your friends/companions to go meet with him/her, so that you discuss it again. Cuz (elaboration) in the Scriptures it is written, saying, &lt;In a dispute/case/litigation, there must be two or three witnesses who say the same thing, only then can (you) accept their accusation.&gt;</bt><note reference="18:16" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 19:15</note><v n="17" />Te ngaa ladhe no'o boe nanene lii miu, lami lole dènge juma'at. Aa ladhe na d'èi boe nanene lii juma'at kahèi, tao ne nuka sèmi ca dhèu dhu tadhe boe Lamatua. Ladhe aad'o na, cap ne nuka sèmi dhèu bhelu, conto sèmi dhèu roro bea sèra.<bt>But if s/he still does not want to listen to you-p, go tell the congregation. And if s/he also does not want to listen to the congregation either, treat him/her like a person who does not know the Lord. If not then, consider/brand/categorise him/her like an evil person, for example tax collector/s.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Sanèd'e paie-iie lii padhai Ja'a ne! Ngaa dhu miu oro ètu rai-haha ne, èèna ka dhu Lamatua oro le ètu sorga. Aa ngaa dhu miu hia isin ètu rai-haha ne, èèna ka Lamatua hia le isin ètu sorga kahèi.<bt>Remember well My speaking! Whatever you-p forbid/block on earth, that [matter] God2 has already forbidden/blocked in heaven. And whatever you permit on earth, that [matter] God2 has already permitted in heaven too.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="oro2 = larang ; oro2 ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">oro2 = larang ; oro2 = menyusur</Message></Annotation><note reference="18:18" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 16:19, Yohanis 20:23</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Aa Ja'a peka hari, na, ladhe abhu dhèu dua dhu sabaj'a dènge d'ara èci, pe Ama Ku ètu sorga hia ngaa dhu ra manèngi.<bt>And I tell again, saying, if there are two people who pray with one insides (in accord w/each other), later My Father in heaven will give that which they ask.</bt><v n="20" />Te, ladhe abhu dua, do tèlu dhèu, pakaboko sabaj'a sama-sama, lula rèngu dhèu Ja'a, na, Ja'a ètu talora aae rèngu kahèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>Cuz (elaboration) if there are two, or three people, gathered praying together because they are My people, na, I am also in their midst.&gt;&gt; [EXEG: “in my name” here means “because they belong to me”. See my PPT word study on “name”, NLT, CEV note, TRT. etc.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Te, ladhe abhu dua, do tèlu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">Te, ladhe abhu dua, do tèlu dhèu, pakaboko sabaj'a ale kolongara Ja'a, èèna na Ja'a ètu talora aae rèngu.&gt;&gt;</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus pake lii pakasame nèti pegawi dhu hia boe abho mi angalai na<bt>The Lord Yesus gives an example about an official (assimilated loan) who doesn't forgive his friend</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Èle èèna, ka Petrus karèi Yesus, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama, ja'a neo karèi ciki. Ladhe a'ari ja'a tao sale pahari-pahari mi ja'a, èèna na d'ai pèri hari ja'a hud'i hia ne abho? D'ai pidhu hari, do?&gt;&gt;<bt>After that, Petrus came asking Yesus, saying, &lt;&lt;Father, I want to ask a little something (=polite way to say I have a question). If my sibling/fellow believer wrongs me over and over, then arriving at how many times must I give forgiveness to him/her? Up to seven times, [tag question]? [EXEG: NRSV, see also note at 8:15]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Hèia Yesus dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Aad'o! Èu hud'i abho ne pidhu kali pidhu nguru hari,<bt>Then Yesus replied, saying, &lt;&lt;No! You must forgive him/her 7 times 70 times,</bt><note reference="18:22" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Lii Yunani ètu ne'e, sasoa na bisa &lt;&lt;7 kali 70 hari&gt;&gt;. Bisa kahèi, &lt;&lt;77 hari&gt;&gt;.<bt>The Yunani language here can mean, &lt;&lt;7 times 70 times&gt;&gt;. It can also (mean), &lt;&lt;77 times&gt;&gt;.</bt></note>toke èu ige more heka.<bt>until you can't count anymore.</bt><note reference="18:21-22" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lukas 17:3-4</note><v n="23" />Miu hud'i tao ku sèmi èèna, lula Ama Lamatua nuka sèmi dhèu aae dhu ige kèlu na ètu pegawi na.<bt>You-p must do like that, because God is like a king who counts/keep track of his officials' debts.</bt><v n="24" />Ropa na ige nare, hèia na pua dhèu lasi paroa pegawi dhu pakèlu toke riho kehi.<bt>When he started to count, then he ordered his people to go call in/summon an official who was in debt to him for money, up to millions and millions.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="riho kehi = jutaan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">riho kehi = jutaan</Message></Annotation><note reference="18:24" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Alkitab lii Yunani ètu ne'e suri, peka na, &lt;&lt;10.000 τάλαντον (<span class="Italic">talanton</span>)&gt;&gt;. <span class="Italic">Talanton</span> èci, kab'ua na, sama dènge gaji dhèu sab'a 15-20 tèu. Alkitab lii Idhonesia suri, peka na, &lt;talenta&gt; ètu ne'e.<bt>The Yunani language Bible here writes “10,000 τάλαντον (<span class="Italic">talanton</span>)”. The value of one <span class="Italic">talenton</span> was a worker's wages for 15-20 years. The Indonesian Bible says ‘talenta’ here.</bt></note><v n="25" />Te ngaa pegawi ne b'ae nare boe kèlu na. Ka dhèu aae paredha, peka na, &lt;Lami pahie eele dhèu ne dènge bhèni-ana niki na aa'i-aa'i, sèna ka ra j'aj'i ènu. Aa mèdha-panyau na, pahie aa'i kahèi, ho b'ae kèlu-g'ètu na.&gt;<bt>But that official could not pay off that debt of his. Then2 the king ordered, saying, &lt;&lt;Go sell this person and his wife and all his children, so they become slaves. And sell off all his wealth/possessions in.order.to pay his debt (doublet).&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Ropa pegawi ne tadèngi nare, hèia na pabèbha iisi, ho patitu kètu urutuu ètu madha dhèu aae, ka pamako, aku nèngu na, &lt;Ira ee! Ama dhèu aae hia ja'a tebho d'ai ciki sa! Sèna ka ja'a b'ae kèlu ja'a aa'i-aa'i ra.&gt;<bt>Hearing like that then that official fell kneeling in front of the king and pleaded with him, saying, &lt;Ira ee! [+in strife] Father king give me a little bit of time. So that I will pay off all of my debts.&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pabhèba iisi = jatuhkan diri"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">pabhèba iisi = jatuhkan diri</Message></Annotation><v n="27" />Ropa tadèngi, hèia dhèu aae rasa kasia dènge ne. Ka dhèu aae pabhèlu eele aa'i mèu-mèu kèlu na, ka pua na lèpa.<bt>Hearing like.that, then that king felt pity on him. Then2 the king completely forgot (by active choice) all his debts, and sent him home.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Te ngaa ropa na d'ai li'u, hèia pegawi ne paraga dènge angalai na dhu pakèlu nèngu doi ciki di.<bt>But when that official went outside, then he met one of his friends who was in debt just a little/small money to him.</bt><note reference="18:28" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Alkitab lii Yunani ètu ne'e, suri, peka na, &lt;&lt;100 δηνάριον (<span class="Italic">deinarion</span>)&gt;&gt;. Kab'ua nèti <span class="Italic">deinarion</span> èci, nuka sèmi gaji dhèu sab'a ètu d'ara ca lod'o. De ladhe èdhi pasoro dènge 10.000 τάλαντον (<span class="Italic">talanton</span>) ètu ayat 24, na, kèlu ne dènge boe kab'ua ngaa-ngaa.<bt>The Yunani language Bible here writes, &lt;&lt;100 δηνάριον (<span class="Italic">deinarion</span>)&gt;&gt;. The value of one <span class="Italic">deinarion</span> is one worker's wage for one day. So (consequently), when compared with the 10,000 τάλαντον (<span class="Italic">talanton</span>) in verse 24, na, this debt here has no meaning/significance whatsoever.</bt></note>Ka na kèpe angalai ne, hèia pacèli ladha goro na, aa na jèke ne, aku nèngu na, &lt;Weh! B'ae ka d'ara lai-lai ne kèlu èu sèra!&gt;<bt>Next that official grabbed his friend, and strangled his neck and spoke angrily, saying, &lt;Weh! [+annoyed] Pay up your debts right now!&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="29" />Ropa angalai na tadèngi, hèia na patitu kètu urutuu, ka pamako ne, peka na, &lt;Ira ee! Angalai, ee! Hia ku ja'a tebho d'ai ciki sa! Pe ja'a b'ae kèlu ja'a sèra!&gt;<bt>Hearing like that, then his friend fell kneeling and pleaded with him, saying, &lt;Ira ee! Friend, ee! Please give me a little bit of time. Later I will return/repay my debts to you.&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="30" />Te ngaa pegawi ne peka na, &lt;Bisa boe! Ja'a mate heka panèbhu. Èu b'ae dènge ka lod'o doe ne'e kahèi!&gt; Èle ka, la'e pamaso angalai na asa d'ara bèdho, toke na b'ae aa'i kèlu na.<bt>But that official said, &lt;Can't do! I'm not going to wait any longer. You must pay immediately today!&gt; Then he threw his friend in jail, until completely paid that debt of his.</bt><v n="31" />Ropa pegawi dhu leo ladhe rèdhi ngaa dhu j'aj'i ne, hèia d'ara ra susa. Ka lasi lolo dènge dhèu aae.<bt>When the king's other officials saw what happened there, then their insides were distressed. Then2 they went to report to the king.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="32" />Ropa tadèngi nare, hèia dhèu aae ne paroa pegawi dhu ne'a boe manèngi makasi ne. Dhèu aae jèke ne, aku nèngu na, &lt;Heh, dhèu bhelu-katub'a! Lula èu ne manèngi sèna ka ja'a sue èu, nèti èèna ka ja'a pabhèlu eele le kèlu èu sèra.<bt>Hearing like that, then the king called that thankless official. (=who had lost all sense of social propriety). The king scolded him, saying, &lt;Heh, evil (doublet) person! Because you requested me to pity you, that's why I have chosen to forget your debts.</bt><v n="33" />Te ngaa, nga tao ka èu kasia boe angalai èu sa hèi, sama sèmi ja'a kasia èu ne?&gt;<bt>But why could you not have pity/mercy on your friend too, the same as I had pity/mercy on you?&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dara èu la'e kahèi. Èu sue"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">dara èu la'e kahèi. Èu sue boe angalai èu ciki sa, sèmi ja'a kasia èu ne?&gt;</Message></Annotation><v n="34" />Ka dhèu aae nasa bia dènge ne, hèia na pua pamaso dhèu ne asa d'ara bèdho, sèna ka ra paj'èra ne, toke na b'ae aa'i kèlu na sèra.&gt;&gt;<bt>That king was so severely angry with him, that he ordered them to go put that person into jail, so that they would torture him, until he completely pays off all those debts of his.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="35" />Hèia Yesus pa'èle lii pakasame Na, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama Ku ètu sorga pa'iga sèmi èèna kahèi mi dedha miu. Pe Na huku miu, ladhe miu mo'o boe pabhèlu eele sasala nèti a'ari miu dhèu parcaya sèra.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus closed His comparison story by telling, saying, &lt;&lt;My Father in heaven also counts like that for you. Later He will punish you-p, if you do not want to completely forget your sibling/fellow believer's wrongs.&gt;&gt; [EXEG: see note at 18:15]</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu Parisi tenge j'ara ho pamanahu Lamatua Yesus lula-nèti j'ara pa'ia-pa'ela<bt>By means of the matter of marriage-divorce, the Parisi people look for a way to bring down the Lord Yesus</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Thru 27 Feb 2009"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">Thru 27 Feb 2009</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 10:1-12)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="19" />
      <v n="1" />Ropa Yesus aj'a nare aa'i j'ara sèra, hèia la'e tèke eele Galilea asa propensi Yudea, ètu cabèka loko Yarden.<bt>When Yesus finished teaching all of that, then He went leaving Galilea to go to Yudea province at Yordan river's other side.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rèdha = 1) hela step (convulsions"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">rèdha = 1) hela step (convulsions from high fever), kejang karena panas tinggi (KM); 2) tarik jerat (burung) ; ana tai1 = orang yg datang numpang dgn kotong ; ana tai2 = timbangan kecil (the small weights) (kaba tai = timbangan, dacing) ; kad'o1 = saya jenguk (kunjungi) ; kad'o2 = 1) hamil, mengandung (not inflected), 2) put things in pouch or loose sarong above waistband, taruh sst pada bagian sarong yg di atas ikat pinggang</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Dhèu ae ka dhu madhutu Ne, ka Na puri-pa'èle dhèu-dhèu pèd'a ètu nèi.<bt>Many people followed Him, and He healed (various) sick people there.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Abhu pèri-pèri dhèu Parisi dhu madhutu kahèi, dhu neo pamanahu Ne. Ka ra karèi Yesus, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Madhutu atora agama èdhi, ladhe dhèu mone leo le èmu, bisa ia eele dhèu èmu na, sad'i na abhu j'ara dhu la'e asa pa'ie-pa'ela. Sèmi èèna, do?&gt;&gt;<bt>There were also several Parisi people who came wanting to make Him fall. And they asked Yesus, saying, &lt;&lt;Father! According to our-inc religious regulations, if a male has married, he may divorce his spouse, as long as there is a matter which brings the divorce (doublet). That's how it is, right?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Te ngaa Yesus b'ala si, na &lt;&lt;Miu se dhu me'a mèu agama. Te ngaa tasamia ka miu me'a boe isi Sasuri Mola-Mèci Ama Lamatua? Te ètu d'ara sasuri nèti lii lolo uru tèka, dhu suri peka na, &lt;Ama Lamatua paj'aj'i dhèu rai-haha, dhèu mone dènge dhèu bhèni.&gt;<bt>But Yesus responded to them, saying, &lt;&lt;You-p here are religious experts. But why do you not know/understand the Scripture's contents? Cuz (elaboration) in writings of the origin/beginning story, it is written saying, &lt;God made humans male and female.&gt;</bt><note reference="19:4" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 1:27, 5:2</note><v n="5" />Aa dhu suri kahèi, peka na,<bt>And it is also written, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;Nèti èèna ka, dhèu mone hud'i tèke eele ina-ama na,<bt>&lt;Because of that, a man/male must leave his mother-father,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">sèna ka la'e mamuri d'ara èci dènge dhèu èmu-kamali na,<bt>in.order.to go live one insides (=one accord) with his spouse,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">te dua ra dhu j'aj'i le èci.&gt;<bt>cuz (elaboration) the two of them have become one/united.&gt; [NOTE to daughter translations: Follow the wording you used in Gen 2:24.]</bt><note reference="19:5" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 2:24</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Nèti èèna ka, ladhe Ama Lamatua unu Na dhu hia dua ra j'aj'i le èci, na, dhèu rai-haha baku pacèri si hari!&gt;&gt;<bt>Because of that, if God himself has made the two of them to become one/united, na, humans mustn't make them separated/divorced anymore.&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Ropa tadèngi rare Yesus peka sèmi èèna, dhèu Parisi se karèi hari Ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe sèmi èèna, nga tao ka Musa peka na, dhèu bisa pa'ia-pa'ela, sad'i nèngu tao uuru ku sasuri pa'ia hia dhèu èmu na?&gt;&gt;<bt>Hearing Yesus speak like.that, then those Parisi people asked again, saying, &lt;&lt;If it's like that then, why did Musa say, a person can divorce (doublet), as long as he gives a divorce letter to his spouse first?&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="19:7" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 24:1-4, Mateos 5:31</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Hèia Yesus dhaa, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Musa soro tèke bèi-baki miu pa'ia-pa'ela dènge dhèu èmu-kamali ra, lula rèngu sèra kètu hadhu èci èèna ka dènge miu! Te ngaa lod'o Ama Lamatua paj'aj'i rai-haha ne, dad'èi Na sèmi boe èèna.<bt>Then Yesus answered, saying, &lt;&lt;Musa allowed your ancestors to divorce (doublet) their spouses, because they were stone heads (=stubborn) just like you! But when God made this world, His intent was not like.that.</bt><v n="9" />Nèti èèna ka, Ja'a pasanèd'e mema miu, ee! Ladhe bhèni ad'u uuru madha j'ara makae, dhèu èmu na bisa ia eele ne. Te ngaa ladhe ia eele bhèni ne dhu ad'u boe j'ara makae, hèia dhèu mone na leo hari dènge bhèni leo, nèngu ne tao le j'ara makae!&gt;&gt;<bt>That's why I'm reminding you directly! If the/a woman commits.adultery first, then her spouse may divorce her. But if (he) divorces a woman who doesn't /hasn't committed adultery, and the male/man marries again with another woman, then he has committed.adultery !&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="19:9" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 5:32, 1 Korintus 7:10-11</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Ropa tadèngi lii ne'e, hèia ana madhutu Na sèra, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe sèmi èèna, be'a risi baku leo-èmu.&gt;&gt;<bt>Hearing Him speak like.that, then His followers spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;If it's like.that then, it's better just not to get married.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Hèia Yesus b'ala si, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu ae ka dhu ro'o boe sèmi rare lii padhai lii Ja'a ne. Dhodhoka dhèu dhu Ama Lamatua hag'e nare si.<bt>Then Yesus responded to them, saying, &lt;&lt;Many people don't want to accept this speaking of mine. Only just people whom God sets aside/chooses. [NOTE to daughter translations: CHECK that /tunju/ in your lg doesn't imply that God superimposes singleness on some people. He calls some and enables them to remain single for ministry purposes in partnership with him.]</bt><v n="12" />Te abhu dhèu dhu leo boe èmu, lula karèi nèti rara iisi ne, nèngu sèmi èèna ka. Abhu kahèi dhu leo boe èmu, lula dhèu tao ne sèmi èèna. Aa abhu kahèi dhu no'o boe leo-èmu, lula na neo pakako sasab'a Ama Lamatua di. Dhèu dhu re'a mèu a'aj'a ne, hud'i laa nèngu sèmi dènge be'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>Cuz (elaboration) there are people who don't marry, because from birth s/he was like.that. There are also those who don't marry, because people made him like that. And there are also those who choose to not marry, because s/he only wants to carry out God's work. The person who can understand this teaching, na, let him accept it well/nicely.&gt;&gt; [EXEG: see discussion in Morris &amp; Carson. Both marriage and singleness are “approved” here; avoid making either one superior, or either one inferior.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="uku-kèdi = suanggi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">uku-kèdi = suanggi</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus hia lii mèngi-nale mi ana iiki sèra<bt>The Lord Yesus speaks giving blessing to small children</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 10:13-16; Lukas 18:15-17)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Lod'o èèna, dhèu sa'u rèti ana-ana ra asa Yesus, sèna ka Yesus tao kacui-aai Na mi rèngu, aa dènge hia lii mèngi-nale. Te ngaa ana madhutu Na kai dhèu se.<bt>At that time, people child.carried brought their children to Yesus, so that He would put hands and speak giving blessing to them. But His followers rebuked those people.</bt><v n="14" />Hèia Yesus nasa dènge ana madhutu Na, ka Na lii, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Hud'i laa ana se mai asa Ja'a! Baku bhabhae si! Te dhèu dhu sèmi rèngu se'e ka, dhu j'aj'i dhèu unu Ama Lamatua.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus got angry with His followers, and spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;Allow those children to come to Me! Don't prevent/prohibit them! Cuz (elaboration) people like them here, are the ones who are/become God's people.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bhabhae = pele"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">bhabhae = pele</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Èle èèna ka Yesus tao kacui-aai Na mi ana se, aa Na manèngi ho Ama Lamatua hia si mèngi-nale. Èle, hèia Yesus pakèd'i la'e, tèke eele era èèna.<bt>Then Yesus put hand/s on those children, and requested that God give blessing to them. After that, then Yesus walked/travelled leaving that place.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu kaja tenge j'ara, sèna ka mamuri taruu dènge Ama Lamatua<bt>A rich person looks for a way to live forever with God</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 10:17-31; Lukas 18:18-30)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Ca tèke, dhèu èci mai karèi Yesus, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama Mese! Ja'a hud'i tao ku j'ara dhu hua iia tasamia, sèna ka ke'a tare'a, na, ja'a bisa maso sorga? Te ja'a neo mamuri taruu sama-sama dènge Ama Lamatua.&gt;&gt;<bt>One time, a person came asking Yesus saying, &lt;&lt;Father Teacher! What good thing must I do so that I can truly know that I can enter heaven? Cuz (elaboration) I want to live continually together with God?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Hèia Yesus dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Nga tao ka, èu karèi Ja'a lula-nèti ngaa dhu hua iia? Dhodhoka Ama Lamatua di, dhu hua iia. Te ladhe èu neo mamuri taruu dènge Ne, na, mamuri la madhutu paredha Na.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus replied, saying, &lt;&lt;Why do you ask Me about what is good? Only God alone is good. If you want to live with Him continually, na, live following/obeying His commands.&gt;&gt; [EXEG: “keep His com...” has durative on-going sense.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Ka dhèu ne karèi hari, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Paredha dhu mia èèna?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then2 that person asked again, saying, &lt;&lt;Which command/s is that?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia Yesus b'ala ne, peka na,<bt>Then Yesus responded, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">&lt;&lt;Baku pamadhe dhèu;<bt>&lt;&lt;Don't murder people;</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">baku tao j'ara makae dènge dhèu dhu dhèu èmu boe èu;<bt>don't do shameful things (sexually) with a person who is not your spouse;</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">baku mana'u;<bt>don't steal;</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">baku j'aj'i sakasii dhu kapod'e-kabèli;<bt>don't be a twisted/deceitful (doublet) witness;</bt><note reference="19:18" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 20:13-16, Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 5:17-20</note></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">
      <v n="19" />pakab'ua ina-ama mu;<bt>give honour to your mother-father;</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">aa sue ku dhèu èu, sama sèmi èu sue ngi'u èu mesa mu.&gt;&gt;<bt>and love your people (related or associated with you) the same as you love your own self.&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="19:19" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 20:12, Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 5:16, Atora nèti Ama-ama Agama 19:18</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Dhèu ne dhaa, na, &lt;&lt;Paredha aa'i-aa'i sèra ja'a tao madhutu le. De, ngaa hari dhu kura?&gt;&gt;<bt>That person replied, saying, &lt;&lt;I have followed/obeyed all those commands. What else is still lacking?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Ropa tadèngi lii dhèu ne, hèia Yesus peka na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe èu neo madhutu aa'i dad'èi Ama Lamatua, lèpa ho pahia aa'i mèdha-panyau èu, sèna ka papala hia dhèu dhu dènge boe ngaa-ngaa sèra. Èle èèna, mai ho madhutu Ja'a. Te èèna na, Ama Lamatua pala hia èu mèdha-panyau ae-ae ètu sorga.&gt;&gt;<bt>Hearing like.that, then Yesus said, &lt;&lt;If you want to completely follow God's will/desires, go home and sell all your wealth/possessions (doublet), to divide out that money to the poor people. After that, come and follow Me. Cuz (elaboration) later God will reciprocate/reward to you lots of wealth in heaven.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Ropa na tadèngi nare lii Yesus, hèia dhèu ne lèpa dènge d'ara pèd'a laho mae-mae, lula nèngu kaja titu kèna.<bt>When he heard what Yesus said, then that person went home with sad/pained insides, because he was very rich.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Èle èèna, ka Yesus padhai lii dènge ana madhutu Na, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Lèka la Ja'a, te dhèu kaja carui titu kèna maso sorga.<bt>after that, Yesus spoke with His followers, saying, &lt;&lt;Believe2 Me, cuz (elaboration) rich people have great difficulty2 (approaching impossible) entering heaven.</bt><v n="24" />Carui èèna, nuka sèmi badha onta dhu kapai, maso la'e asa d'ara oka na re ro'a j'aj'au.&gt;&gt;<bt>That difficulty2, is like a camel (loan) animal which is big, entering into his corral through a sewing.needle's hole.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Ropa ana madhutu se tadèngi rare, rèngu malaa, hèia ra dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe sèmi èèna, cee ka dhu bisa maso sorga?&gt;&gt;<bt>Hearing like.that then, His followers were amazed/surprised, and so they replied, saying, &lt;&lt;If it's like.that then, who is it who can enter heaven?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Hèia Yesus ladhe patae si, ka Na lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe dhèu rai-haha dhu tao, mema bisa boe. Te ngaa ladhe Ama Lamatua ka dhu tao, aa'i-aa'i bisa j'aj'i!&gt;&gt;<bt>[CHECK /ad'u dara/] Then Yesus looked carefully at them, then2 He spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;If humans are the ones who do/work it, it's surely not possible. But if God is the one who does/works it, all/everything can happen!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="/Ladhe ad'u dara dhèu rai-haha, mema"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">/Ladhe ad'u dara dhèu rai-haha, mema bisa boe./ ad'u dara = initiative (= tao dara)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Hèia Petrus pasanèd'e, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Ji'i se tèke eele le mèdha-panyau ji'i aa'i-aa'i, ho madhutu Ama. De ji'i abhu ngaa?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Petrus reminded, saying, &lt;&lt;Father! We-exc have gone leaving all our wealth/possessions, in.order.to follow Father. So (consequently) what do we get?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Na dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Parcaya la Ja'a ne! Pe d'ai lod'o Ama Lamatua tao pahiu aa'i mèu-mèu, Ja'a Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a ne, madhèdi ètu dedha kadera paredha aae èèna. Lod'o èèna kahèi, miu dhu madhutu Ja'a, madhèdi kahèi ètu dedha kadera paredha canguru dua sèra, sèna ka j'aj'i hakim mi canguru dua suku èdhi dhèu Isra'el!<bt>He replied saying, &lt;&lt;Believe Me! Later if/when God makes everything become new, I, this Ideal/Prototypical Human, will sit in a big ruling chair. At that time also, you who follow Me, will also sit on 12 ruling chairs, as judges for our-inc 12 Israel clans!</bt><note reference="19:28" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 25:31, Lukas 22:30</note><v n="29" />Dhèu dhu tèke eele èmu na, a'ari na, ina-ama na, ana niki na, aa oka-tedhe na, ho madhutu Ja'a, bèli-camèd'a èèna abhu hari cangasu kali. Aa d'ai ka lod'o èle rai-haha ne, nèngu kahèi abhu mamuri taruu dènge Ama Lamatua.<bt>The person who leaves his/her house, elder-younger.siblings, mother-father, children, and his/her garden/s (doublet), in.order.to follow Me, later s/he will recieve in return up to 100 times increase. Then at the end of this world, s/he will also get to live with God continually.</bt><v n="30" />De sanèd'e paie! Madhutu ngangee Ama Lamatua, dhèu ae dhu padedha iisi na, rèngu sèra ka dhu j'aj'i mi ana iiki. Te ngaa dhèu dhu peka na, nèngu dhèu haha, aa te ngaa madhutu a'abhu Lamatua, nèngu ka dhu kapai.&gt;&gt;<bt>So (consequently) remember well! According to God's thinking, many people who elevate themselves, they are the ones who become small/insignificant. But the person who considers him/her self low (=humble), they are the ones who are big/important/significant, according to God2's thinking.&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="19:30" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 20:16, Lukas 13:30</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lii pakasame lula-nèti dhèu dhu sab'a oka anggor<bt>Example/parable about workers in the vineyard (lit. grape field)</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="20" />
      <v n="1" />Èle èèna, ka Yesus aj'a peka na, &lt;&lt;Paredha Ama Lamatua èci èèna ka dènge lii pakasame ne: abhu ca dhèu lamatua oka anggor, dhu kèd'i mad'ae aae d'ara hake èna sa. Na la'e tenge dhèu sèna ka sab'a ètu d'ara oka na.<bt>After that, Yesus taught, saying, &lt;&lt;God's ruling/governing is like this comparison story: there was a grape field/garden owner/master who went out early at six in the morning. He went to look for people to work in his field/garden.</bt><v n="2" />Na abhu dhèu sab'a, hèia rare lii èci, ho sab'e d'ara ca lod'o, bab'ae na, ca doi iia.<bt>He encountered workers, and they agreed to work one day with its payment of one silver money.</bt><note reference="20:2" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Sasuri Mola-Mèci ètu d'ara lii Yunani ètu ne, suri, peka na, &lt;&lt;ca doi <span class="Italic">dinari</span>&gt;&gt;. Kab'ua na, gaji ca dhèu tuka d'ara ca lod'o.<bt>The Yunani language Bible here writes, “one <span class="Italic">dinari</span> money”. The value of one <span class="Italic">dinari</span>, was a worker's wage for one full day.</bt></note>Dhèu se d'èi kahèi, ka lamatua oka ne pua lasi sab'a.<bt>After agreeing, then2 the owner of the field ordered them to go work.</bt><v n="3" />Pe d'ara hake ceo sa, la'e asa d'ara pasa. Ètu era nèi, nèngu paraga dènge dhèu pèri-pèri dhu madhèdi iia d'ara.<bt>At nine in the morning, he went into the market. There he met several people who were just sitting around lazily.</bt><v n="4" />Hèia na lii dènge ra, &lt;Miu se neo sab'a ètu d'ara oka ja'a, do? Pe ja'a b'ae miu madhutu kab'ua dhu lèke.&gt; Ropa tadèngi rare, ro'o kahèi, hèia lasi dènge ka sab'a.<bt>Then he told them &lt;Do you want to work in my garden [tag question]? Later I will pay you according to the value that is appropriate.&gt; Hearing like.that, they agreed, and then went immediately to work.</bt><v n="5" />D'ai lod'o titu mera sa, dènge hake tèlu lod'o nihia, lamatua oka ne la'e tenge hari dhèu sab'a.<bt>At high noon, and three in the afternoon, that field owner went to go look for workers again.</bt><v n="6" />D'ara hake lèmi lod'o nihia sa, la'e hari. Na laladhe, na, abhu dhèu dhu titu iia d'ara era. Ka na lii dènge ra, aku nèngu na, &lt;Nga tao ka karèi nèti mad'ae toke sange ne'e ne, miu se titu iia d'ara, sab'a boe ngaa-ngaa?&gt;<bt>When it was late afternoon, around five oclock, he went again. He looked all around and saw there were still people who were just standing around empty (=doing nothing). Then2 he asked them, saying, &lt;Why do you stand around empty from morning until now, and don't do any work?&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Ka dhèu se dhaa, peka na, &lt;Ama, ee! Abhu boe ca dhèu sa dhu hia ji'i sasab'a.&gt;<bt>Those people answered, saying, &lt;Father, ee! There is no one who gives us work.&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka lamatua oka ne peka, &lt;Ladhe sèmi èèna, lami sab'a asa d'ara oka ja'a!&gt;<bt>Then that master said, &lt;If that's the case, then you-p go work in my garden (imperative)!&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Toke d'ai èle jam sab'a, hèia lamatua oka ne pua madho na, peka na, &lt;Paroa dhèu sab'a se, sèna ka b'ae rui sasab'a ra èci-èci. Mulai nèti dhèu sab'a limuri tèka, toke dhèu sab'a uuru.&gt;<bt>When it was time to stop work, then that garden master called his manager/supervisor (assimilated loan) and said, &lt;Call the workers in.order.to pay each of them their work money. Start from the people who worked last, until those people who worked first.&gt;</bt><note reference="20:8" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Atora nèti Ama-ama Agama 19:13, Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 24:15</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Ka madho ne paroa uuru dhèu dhu sab'a hake lèmi nihia. Na b'ae si ca dhèu, ca doi iia.<bt>Then, that manager/supervisor called/summoned those workers who worked from five oclock in the afternoon. He paid each one of them to recieve one silver money/coin.</bt><v n="10" />Èle ka, na paroa dhèu sab'a dhu leo sèra, toke dhèu dhu sab'a mulai nèti hake èna mad'ae deo na. Dhèu se, pangee na, ele boe rèngu abhu risi nèti dhèu dhu sab'a hake lèmi nihia. Re'a boe na, rèngu abhu kahèi ca dhèu, ca doi iia.<bt>After that he called those other workers, until (reaching) the people who worked started from six oclock in the morning. These people thought that, probably they would recieve more than those people who started work at five in the afternoon. But contrary to expectation (idiomatic), they also got one silver money for each person.</bt><v n="11" />Ropa ra sèmi rare, hèia ra ka'ugu dènge lamatua oka èèna, aku rèngu na,<bt>When they received that, they grumbled to that garden master saying,</bt><v n="12" />&lt;Ira, iii! Bisa boe sèmi ne'e, ama! Rèngu dhu mai limuri tèka, dhoka sab'a ca jam di. Te ngaa ji'i dhu karèi mad'ae aae ka, sab'a toke èi kabhèsu hae! Te ngaa tasamia ka ama b'ae ji'i èci èèna ka dènge rèngu se?&gt;<bt>&lt;Ira ii! [+strife] It can't be like this, father! Those who came the very last, only worked just one hour. But we here who began early in the morning, have worked to the bone until the sweat flowed (idiom: worked hard)! But how is it that father pays us the same as them there?&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Hèia lamatua oka ne dhaa, na, &lt;Angalai! Ja'a tipu boe èu. Lula èu mesa mu mo'o kahèi sab'a ètu d'ara ca lod'o dhu bab'ae na ca doi iia. Tare'a si? De ja'a b'ae madhutu sèmi lii pama'ète èdhi dua ti, si?<bt>Then that garden master replied [NOTE: Gk is “to one of them”; here it is implicit in that what he says is all grammatically singular. I can go either way on this, as I think it can match the Kupang and Greek without making the info load too heavy. What would you like to do?] saying, &lt;Friend! I have not conned you-sg. Because you yourself agreed to work one day, with the payment one silver money. Right [tag question]? So (consequently), I paid according to the agreement between the two of us-inc, right?</bt><v n="14" />De be'a risi more doi j'aj'èra èu ho lèpa ka. Ladhe ja'a neo b'ae mi dhèu dhu sab'a limuri tèka nèti èu, èci èèna ka dènge ja'a neo b'ae èu, èèna na madhutu dad'èi ja'a.<bt>So (consequently) it would be better for you-sg to take your compensation/payment money and go on home. If I want to pay people who started working later than you the same amount that I pay you, that is up to my desires.</bt><v n="15" />Lula doi-dhari ja'a, ja'a bisa pake madhutu dad'èi d'ara ja'a. Tasamia ka, angalai nasa lula babe'a d'ara ja'a?&gt;<bt>Because my money (doublet) I can use according to my likes. How is that friend (=you) is angry because of my good insides (=kindness/generosity).&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Sèmi èèna kahèi, lod'o Ama Lamatua j'aj'i Dhèu Aae mi dhèu aa'i-aa'i. Na pala-bagi hia dhèu-dhèu unu Na, madhutu dad'èi d'ara Na. De dhèu dhu mai limuri tèka, èèna na abhu pala sama sèmi dhèu dhu mai uuru. Aa dhèu dhu mai uuru, pe na abhu pala nuka sèmi dhèu dhu mai limuri tèka.&gt;&gt;<bt>Like that also when God becomes King for all people. He will divide out to His own people according to the desires of His insides. So (consequently) a person who comes last, later s/he will get his/her share/reward the same as a person who comes first. And a person who comes first, later s/he will get his/her share/reward the same as a person who comes last.&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="20:16" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 19:30, Markus 10:31, Lukas 13:30</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus peka mema j'ara mamadhe Na d'ai ka tèlu hari kèna<bt>The Lord Yesus foretells the third time about His death</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 10:32-34; Lukas 18:31-34)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Èle ka, Yesus si mulai lasi asa Yerusalem. Ètu talora j'ara Na paroa ana madhutu Na, sèna ka rèngu mesa ra di. Ka Na lii hari, peka na,<bt>After that, then Yesus (coll.) began to go to Yerusalem. In the middle of the road/way/journey, He called His followers so they were alone with Him. Next He spoke again, saying,</bt><v n="18" />&lt;&lt;Mi nanene paie! Ne'e ne, èdhi lati asa Yerusalem. Te ngaa ètu nèi dhèu pahie Ja'a, Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a ne, asa kètu agama Yahudi dènge mese agama sèra. Èle èèna, ra huku pamadhe Ja'a.<bt>&lt;&lt;You-p listen carefully! Now we-inc are going to Yerusalem. But there (remote) they will sell Me off (=betray), the Ideal/Prototypical Human, to the *chief priests and the religion teachers. Then3 they will judge/punish Me with death.</bt><v n="19" />Hèia ra soro Ja'a asa dhèu leo rai kara dhu tadhe boe Ama Lamatua. Ka ra padhai lii pamakae Ja'a, aa ra hake paru isi Ja'a. Èle èèna, heka ra paku pamadhe Ja'a ètu aj'u palolo-palèbha. Ja'a tare'a-re'a madhe, te ngaa asa camèd'a èèna, Ja'a mamuri hari.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then they hand Me over to other (implied: foreign) people who do not know God. Then2 they will speak shaming Me/shamefully to Me. And they will whip My body repeatedly. And then they will nail Me to death on the *crossed wood. I will really die. But on the.day.after.the.next.day, I will live again.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hake paru isi = pukul ulang-ulang"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">hake paru isi = pukul ulang-ulang</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ina Yakobis dènge Yohanis manèngi sèna ka ded'e ana-ana na j'aj'i dhèu kapai<bt>Yakobis and Yohanes' mother requests to that her children be appointed as big/important people</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 10:35-45)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Hèia dhèu èmu Sabadeus palere-lere dènge ana na, Yohanis dènge Yakobis, lasi paraga dènge Yesus. Ka na patitu kètu urutuu ho neo pamako Yesus.<bt>After that, Sabadius' wife came together with her children Yakobis and Yohanis to meet with Yesus. Then2 she knelt in.order to beg/nag/coax Yesus.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Ka Yesus karèi ne, &lt;&lt;Mama neo ngaa?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus asked her saying, &lt;&lt;What does mama want?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia na dhaa, &lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e, Ama! Lod'o Ama mèd'u paredha, ja'a manèngi sèna ka Ama ded'e ana ja'a dhèu dua se rèd'u paredha sama-sama dènge Ama. Ja'a manèngi ho Ama hia ca dhèu madhèdi re baboa g'ana, aa ca dhèu re baboa kariu Ama.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then she responded, &lt;&lt;It's like.this, Father! When Father holds rule/government, I ask that Father elevate/appoint my two children here, so they also hold rule/government together with Father. I request that Father allows one on the right side, and one on Father's left side.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Ropa tadèngi lii manèngi ne, hèia Yesus peka Yakobis dènge Yohanis, na, &lt;&lt;Miu se, me'a boe ngaa dhu miu manèngi. Te bèli-camèd'a Ja'a abhu j'aj'èra ae-ae. De tasamia? Miu pangee na, miu bisa pasae kahèi j'aj'èra se, sama-sama dènge Ja'a, do?&gt;&gt;<bt>Hearing her request, then Yesus told Yakobis and Yohanis, saying, &lt;&lt;You-pl don't understand what you ask for. Cuz (elaboration) I later will get/experience much suffering. So (consequently), how about it? Do you think you also are capable of shoulder.carrying that suffering together with Me, [tag question]?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Dua ra dhaa dhu dènge boe pake ngangee, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Oo, bisa, Ama!&gt;&gt;<bt>The two of them replied without thinking, saying, &lt;&lt;Too easy, Father!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Ka Yesus lii dènge ra, &lt;&lt;Mema, èèna na miu pasae j'aj'èra kahèi sèmi Ja'a. Te ngaa bèli-camèd'a cee ka dhu madhèdi ètu baboa g'ana do kariu Ja'a, Ja'a dènge boe hak ho pama'ète. Èèna hak Ama Lamatua. Na pama'ète nare le, cee-cee ka dhu madhèdi ètu era sèra.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then2 He psoke to them, saying, &lt;&lt;True, you also will later shoulder.carry that suffering like Me. But who it is who later sits on My right and left sides, it is not My right to decide. It is God's right. He has already decided ahead.of.time, who it is who sits in those places.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Ropa ana madhutu dhèu canguru sèra tadèngi lii manèngi dua ra, hèia ra nasa.<bt>When those ten other followers heard what the two of them had asked like that, then they were angry.</bt><v n="25" />Te ngaa Yesus paroa nare si aa'i-aa'i ra, hèia Na peka, &lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e! Miu dhu me'a le, si? Dhèu aae-dhèu kapai dhu rèd'u paredha, ènyi kabarai ra toke ra bisa boe kalau sa kahèi. Aa dhèu kapai kabarai ètu rai-haha ne, dhu tadhe boe Ama Lamatua, hia paredha risi eele, toke kabarai ra abhu boe d'oa kètu ciki sa.<bt>But Yesus called them all, and He said, &lt;&lt;It's like this! You know/understand, don't you? Leaders (doublet) who hold rule/government usually press.down/oppress their populace, until they cannot move. And the heads of nations on this earth who do not know God, they give excessive commands, to the point that their populace cannot lift their heads even a little.</bt><v n="26" />Te ngaa baku miu tao sèmi èèna! De nèti miu se cee ka dhu neo j'aj'i dhèu aae-dhèu kapai, nèngu hud'i j'aj'i ku nuka sèmi ènu, sèna ka lalau dhèu leo.<bt>But you-p may not do like that! So (consequently), whoever of you wants to become a leader (doublet), he must become like a servant/slave to serve other people.</bt><note reference="20:25-26" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lukas 22:25-26</note><v n="27" />Aa cee dhu neo j'aj'i kètu, nèngu hud'i tao iisi na nuka sèmi ènu.<bt>And whoever wants to become head, he must make himself like a slave.</bt><note reference="20:26-27" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 23:11, Markus 9:35, Lukas 22:26</note><v n="28" />Nanene! Ja'a sèmi èèna kahèi. Ja'a, Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a ne, mai sèna ka ladhe-leru dhèu. Ja'a mai boe, sèna ka dhèu lalau-lalo'o Ja'a. Te mamai Ja'a ne, sèna ka soro ngi'u Ja'a kateme iisi, ho sui dhèu ae nèti sasala-sasigo ra.&gt;&gt;<bt>Listen! I am also like that. I, this Ideal/Prototypical Human, came to serve (doublet) people. I did not come in.order.that people serve (doublet) Me. Cuz (elaboration) I came to give My entire life, in.order.to *redeem many people from their wrongs (doublet).&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus puri-pa'èle dhèu bèdhu<bt>The Lord Yesus heals (doublet) blind person/people</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 10:46-52; Lukas 18:35-43)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="29" />Ka Yesus si kako taruu. Ropa rèngu kalua nèti kota Jeriko, dhèu ae dhu madhutu rèngu.<bt>Then2 Yesus (coll.) walked on. When they came out of Yeriko city, many people were following them.</bt><v n="30" />Ètu èèna, abhu dhèu bèdhu dhèu dua dhu madhèdi ètu sebhe j'ara. Ropa dua ra tadèngi na, Dhèu dhu kako re èèna, nuka Yesus nèti Nasaret, hèia ra parodha, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Ana-èpu Daud! Ji'i se dhu tatae Ama, karèi nèbhu ka! Sue ku ji'i la!&gt;&gt;<bt>There, there were two blind people who sat on the side of the road. When they heard that the Person who passed by there, was Yesus from Nasaret, then they shouted out, saying, &lt;&lt;Father! Daud's descendant (doublet)! We-inc have been waiting so long for Father! Love/pity us-exc (=help us)!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Ropa dhèu tadèngi ra parodha sèmi èèna, ka ra kai si, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Hee! Miu dua mi baku maruru!&gt;&gt;<bt>Hearing them shouting like.that, then people forbade, saying, &lt;&lt;Hee! You two don't be disruptive!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Te ngaa dua ra asa hino, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Ana-èpu Daud! Sue ku ji'i la!&gt;&gt;<bt>But they yelled even louder, saying, &lt;&lt;Father! Daud's descendant (doublet)! Love/pity us!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="32" />Ropa Yesus tadèngi lii paroa ne, hèia Na titu, ka karèi si, peka na, &lt;&lt;Miu se neo sèna ka Ja'a tao ngaa hia miu?&gt;&gt;<bt>When Yesus heard their summons, then He stood (=stopped walking) and asked them, saying, &lt;&lt;What do you want Me to do for you?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="33" />Ka dua ra dhaa, na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Hia la ji'i se bisa ngèdhi!&gt;&gt;<bt>They answered saying, &lt;&lt;Father! Allow us to be able to see!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="34" />Tadèngi lii dhaa dua ra, hèia Yesus rasa kasia. Ka Na g'ag'e musi madha ra, hèia dua ra rèdhi dènge ka. Èle ka, dua ra lasi dènge madhutu Yesus.<bt>Hearing their response, then Yesus felt pity for them. Then2 He touched their eyes, and they saw straightaway. After that, they walked following Yesus.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus maso asa d'ara kota Yerusalem nuka sèmi Dhèu Aae<bt>The Lord Yesus enters the city of Yerusalem like a King</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 11:1-11; Lukas 19:28-40; Yohanis 12:12-19)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="21" />
      <v n="1" />Ka Yesus si lasi taruu, d'ai rae Betfage, ètu sebhe ledhe Saitun.<bt>Then2 Yesus (coll.) continued on reaching a village named Betfage, on Saitun mountain's edge/slope.</bt><note reference="21:1" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Ra pangare ledhe ne &lt;Saitun&gt;, lula ètu nèi, abhu oka ae dhu dènge aj'u saitun. Rèngu biasa gili hua saitun sèna ka abhu èi mènyi na. Ledhe Saitun ne, kaj'èu nèti kota Yerusalem, pe d'ai ca kilo sa.<bt>They gave the name &lt;Saitun&gt; to that mountain, because there there were many olive tree gardens. They normally ground/pressed olives fruit to get it's oil. That Saitun mountain's distance is approximately one kilometre from Yerusalem city.</bt></note>Rae ne dhu dètu le dènge kota Yerusalem. Ètu era ne'e, rèngu ae taha. Hèia Na pua ana madhutu Na dhèu dua lasi uuru.<bt>That village was near to Yerusalem city. There they stopped momentarily/rested. Then He ordered two of His followers to go on ahead.</bt><v n="2" />Na paredha si, peka na, &lt;&lt;Dua mi lami asa rae nèi. Ladhe miu d'ai nèi, miu ladhe mèdhi keled'ei rena ci'u dènge ana na dhu ra èki ètu era èèna. Lami lècu mere ne, ho mèti mai hia Ja'a.<bt>He commanded them, saying, &lt;&lt;You two go to that village over there. If/When you arrive, you will see a female donkey animal and her offspring tied up there. Go open/untie it in.order.to pull bring [them] to Me.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lècu = buka tali (animal, boat)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">lècu = buka tali (animal, boat)</Message></Annotation><v n="3" />Te ngaa ladhe dhèu karèi miu, peka na, &lt;Nga tao ka miu ère mèti keled'ei dhèu?&gt; Mi dhaa, peka na, &lt;Lamatua neo pake ne. Ladhe pake nare, pe Na hia hari mai.&gt;<bt>But if someone asks you, saying, &lt;Why are you pulling taking someone else's donkey?&gt; You answer, saying, &lt;&lt;Lord/Master wants to use [it]. When [he] is finished using [it], later He will send [it] back here.&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Aa'i-aa'i se hud'i j'aj'i ku sama sèmi lii padhai nèti dhèu rèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua, dhu suri tèke, peka na,<bt>All this must happen, following that which God's spokesperson has written ahead.of.time, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="5" />&lt;Miu dhèu Yerusalem sèra!<bt>&lt;Hey you Yerusalem people!</bt><note reference="21:5" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Alkitab lii Yunani ètu ne'e, suri, peka na, &lt;&lt;ana bhèni nèti Sion&gt;&gt;. Sion ne, ngara leo nèti Yerusalem. De ètu ayat ne, Sakaria pake lii hini ho paj'uj'u ana kabarai kota Yerusalem.<bt>The Yunani language Bible here writes, “daughter of Sion”. Sion is another name for Yerusalem. So (consequently), here Sakaria is using refined/poetic language to designate the people of the city of Yerusalem.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Mai laladhe ku la!<bt>Come look here!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Te Dhèu Aae miu mai.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) your King is coming.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Na mai dènge pahaha iisi.<bt>He comes lowering himself (=unpretentious/humble). [NOTE to daughter translations: careful for MTT noise from TB that uses /lemah lembut/ which skews focus on kind/gentle manner, rather than humble/low status.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Na mai dhu manya'e keled'ei ngèru.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>He comes riding/mounted on a young donkey.&gt;&gt;&gt; [NOTE to daughter translations: CHECK, you might have to say keledai muda in this, if /ana/ here is closer to newborn. In verse 2 it should be OK, cuz it's in relation to the mother there.]</bt><note reference="21:5" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Sakaria 9:9</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Ka ana madhutu Na lasi ka, aa ra tao madhutu aa'i dhu Yesus moa le dènge ra.<bt>Afterwards then His followers went, and they did everything like Yesus had instructed them.</bt><v n="7" />Ère rèti keled'ei rena dènge ana na asa Yesus. Èle ka, ra hèle sig'i-kalolo, hèia Yesus manya'e, lasi asa d'ara kota.<bt>They pulled brought that female donkey and her offspring to Yesus. Then3 they put their blanket/s (doublet =word for men's traditional sarong), and He mounted on top to enter the city.</bt><v n="8" />Ropa rèngu oe d'ai d'ara kota, hèia dhèu ae ka dhu hèle sig'i-kalolo dènge salalu ra mi j'ara. Abhu kahèi cahag'e lasi pare rèu palam,<bt>When they were about to enter the city (=they had not yet got there), then many people took their blankets (doublet =men's cloth) and their sashes (=women's cloth), put them on the road. There were also those who went to cut palm leaves</bt><note reference="21:8" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">D'ara sasuri Mateos, &lt;dadana sèra&gt;. Te ngaa èdhi te'a le nèti Yohanis 12:13, peka na, rèu-rèu palam.<bt>Matthew's original writing said 'branches'. But we know from Yohanes 12:13 that it was palam leaves.</bt></note>ho ra tao ètu talora j'ara. Dènge j'ara ne'e, rèngu tao tadha dhu peka na, rèngu soru Yesus sama sèmi dhèu kapai.<bt>in.order.for them to put them in the middle of the road. In that way, they made a sign saying, they welcomed Yesus like a big/ important person.</bt><v n="9" />Abhu kahèi dhèu cahag'e dhu kako uuru nèti Yesus, aa cahag'e kako re limuri. Dhèu se pa'oo-parodha palere-lere, peka na,<bt>There were also some people who went walking ahead of Yesus, and there were those who followed from behind. Thethese people shouted out (doublet) enthusiastically (doublet), saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;<span class="Italic">Hosana!</span> Ji'i koa-kio Ama Lamatua!<bt>&lt;&lt;<span class="Italic">Hosana!</span> We-exc praise (doublet) God!</bt><note reference="21:9" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">D'ara lii Aram peka, <span class="Italic">&lt;Hosana&gt;</span>. Uru èèna, sasoa na, &lt;hia mamuri mi dhèu&gt;. Lod'o Lamatua Yesus mamuri era ètu rai-haha ne, lii ne, dhèu pake ho koa-kio Ama Lamatua.<bt>Their Aram language says <span class="Italic">&lt;Hosana&gt;</span>. Previously, its meaning says, &lt;he saves people&gt;. When the Lord Yesus was still living on this earth, that word, they usually used to praise (doublet) God.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Lula ana-èpu Daud mai le!<bt>Because Daud's descendant (doublet) has come!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <span class="Italic">Hosana!</span> Ji'i koa-kio Ama Lamatua!<bt><span class="Italic">Hosana!</span> We-exc praise (doublet) God!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Lula Ama Lamatua ka dhu pua Dhèu ne'e mai.<bt>Because God has sent/commissioned this Person to come.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <span class="Italic">Hosana!</span> Ji'i koa-kio Ama Lamatua!<bt><span class="Italic">Hosana!</span> We-exc praise (doublet) God!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Lula Ama Lamatua dhu nèd'u mema paredha ètu dedha-liru dhu dedha risi!&gt;&gt;<bt>Because God is really ruling in the very highest sky (doublet)!&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="21:9" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 118:26</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Ropa Yesus maso asa Yerusalem dènge dhèu dhu pakelu oob'a, hèia isi kabarai aa'i-aa'i ètu d'ara kota kalua mai, ka ra pakarèi, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ira ii! Cee ka dhu mai ne?&gt;&gt;<bt>When Yesus entered Yerusalem bustlingly/lively like.that, then the all the citizens of the city came out, asking each.other saying, &lt;&lt;Ira ii [+amazement]! Who is this coming?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pakelu ooba = dgn rame sekali"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">pakelu ooba = dgn rame sekali</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Dhèu ae se dhaa, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Nèngu ne, Dhèu nèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua. Ngara Na Yesus, dhèu Nasaret, nèti propensi Galilea.&gt;&gt;<bt>The many people answered, saying, &lt;&lt;He is God's spokesperson. His name is Yesus, a Nasaret person, from Galilea province.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus babège eele dhèu dhu pahia-pahèli ètu d'ara Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i<bt>The Lord Yesus evicts people who are selling-buying at the Main Prayer House</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 11:15-19; Lukas 19:45-48; Yohanis 2:13-22)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Ka Yesus si lasi taruu asa d'ara Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i Ama Lamatua. Ètu madha Èmu Manèngi-Mangaj'i ne, dhèu tao nuka sèmi pasa, ho pahia-pahèli koro j'aha dhu dhèu tema pake j'aj'i mèdha korban lod'o sabaj'a. Ropa ladhe nèdhi sèmi èèna, hèia Yesus babèga eele si nèti era èèna. Na lege eele mei-mei dhu ra pake pasilu doi, aa Na paguri eele bagu-bagu dhu ra pake pahia manu-bhui.<bt>Then Yesus (coll.) walked on, and they entered God's Main Prayer House. In that Prayer House's yard/front, people had made like a market in.order.for them to sell (doublet) dove/pidgeon birds which people comonly used as sacrifices for prayer/worship. Seeing like that then, Yesus went to expel kick them out of that place. He flung about tables which they used to change money, and turned upside down benches which they used to sell birds.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lega1 = berangkat (Lii Pacele) ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">lega1 = berangkat (Lii Pacele) ; lega2 = terangkat, ujung bangku terangkat (sit on one end and the other lifts), lege = tip up, tip over, angkat banting (meja)</Message></Annotation><v n="13" />Hèia Yesus peka dènge dhèu se'e, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu rèti lii padhai Lamatua dhu suri tèke le, peka na,<bt>Then Yesus told them, saying, &lt;&lt;The Lord's spokespeople have written saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;Ja'a patitu Èmu ne,<bt>&lt;I built this House, [NOTE: ‘build’ here indicates primary and original purpose of having the house.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">sèna ka dhèu mai manèngi-mangaj'i ètu ne'e.&gt;<bt>so that people can come pray/worship here.&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Dad'èi Lamatua sèmi èèna ka, te ngaa miu tao Èmu ne, nuka sèmi era kaboko dhèu parapo!&gt;&gt;<bt>God2's intent is like.that, but you have made this House to become robbers' gathering place!&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="21:13" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 56:7, Yermia 7:11</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Èle, ka dhèu bèdhu dènge dhèu karuku mai sa Yesus ètu Èmu Sabaj'a Ama Lamatua. Ka Na puri-pa'èle aa'i si.<bt>Afterwards then blind people and lame people came to Yesus in that Prayer House of God's. Then2 He healed them all.</bt><v n="15" />Ètu era ne'e, abhu kahèi kètu agama Yahudi dènge mese agama sèra. Ropa rèdhi Yesus tao tadha malaa, hèia ra ka'uu-kamuki. Risi-risi hari, ropa ra tadèngi ana-ana pa'oo palere-lere ètu d'ara Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i ne, dhu peka na,<bt>There, there were also *chief priests and religion teachers. When they saw Yesus doing miracles, then they complained (doublet). Even more so when they heard children yelling enthusiastically at the Prayer House, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">
      <span class="Italic">&lt;&lt;Hosana! </span>Ji'i koa-kio Ama Lamatua!<bt>&lt;&lt;<span class="Italic">Hosana!</span> We-inc praise (doublet) God!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Lula ana-èpu dhèu aae Daud mai le!&gt;&gt;<bt>Because descendant of king Daud has now come!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Ka kètu kapai se lii dènge Yesus, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Eeh! Èu tadèngi lii padhai lii ana-ana se? Èèna lèke boe!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then, those leaders told Yesus, saying, &lt;&lt;Eeh! [+critical] Do you {èu = not very respectful in this context} hear what those children are saying? It's not true/right!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kètu kapai here not dhèu kapai,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">kètu kapai here not dhèu kapai, because the latter can also mean ‘adult’, which is the probable reading in this context with children</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Te ngaa Yesus b'ala si, na, &lt;&lt;Oo, Ja'a tadèngi. Te, nga tao? Miu baca mèdhi mèka ètu d'ara Sasuri Mola-Mèci Ama Lamatua lula-nèti ana-ana dhu koa-kio Ama Lamatua, do? Te ètu d'ara sasuri èèna dhu suri, na,<bt>But Yesus answered them, saying, &lt;&lt;Yea, I hear. Why? Have you never read in the Scriptures about children who praise (doublet) God [tag question]? Cuz (elaboration) there it is written, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;Ama Lamatua dhu sadia nare le, ana rara iisi hiu, dènge ana-ana iiki,<bt>&lt;God has prepared ahead.of.time red children (=newborns) and small children,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">ho koa-kio Ne.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>so.that they prasie (doublet) Him.&gt;&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="21:16" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 8:3</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Hèia Yesus si tèke eele kota ne, lasi j'unu asa rae Betania.<bt>Then Yesus (coll.) went out leaving behind that city, going to sleep in Betania village.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus dhoo aj'u ca kapua ho hua ia ka<bt>The Lord Yesus curses a tree so it has no more fruit</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 11:12-14, 20-24)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Asa bèli mad'ae aae na, Yesus si lèpa hari asa kota Yerusalem. Te ngaa ètu talora j'ara, Nèngu manganga le.<bt>Early the next morning, Yesus (coll.) returned again to Yerusalem city. But in the middle of the road/journey, He felt hungry.</bt><v n="19" />Na ladhe nèdhi aj'u ca kapua buli sebhe j'ara dhu dhèu tema ra'a hua na.<bt>He saw a tree on the side of the road which people usually eat it's fruit.</bt><note reference="21:19" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Lii Idhonesia peka na, &lt;pohon ara&gt; nèti Yunani συκῆ <span class="Italic">(sukei).</span> Te ngaa ètu d'ara Sasuri Ama Lamatua paj'uj'u aj'u dhu dhèu biasa sèle, dènge ra'a hua na. Ètu Idhonesia re bèka dhimu, dhèu ra'a boe hua &lt;aj'u ara&gt;. De &lt;aj'u ara&gt; ètu Sasuri Ama Lamatua, sama boe dènge aj'u ara èdhi.<bt>Indonesian uses the word &lt;ara tree&gt; from the Greek term <span class="Italic">sukei</span>. But the Bible designates a tree there which people usually plant, and eat its fruit. In eastern Indonesia, people do not eat &lt;ara tree's&gt; fruit. So, &lt;ara tree&gt; in the Bible, is not the same as our-inc ara trees here.</bt></note>De la'e ka padètu-dètu dènge aj'u ne'e, ho neo ladhe sèku dhu hua le, do dhae. Te ngaa ropa d'ai kapua aaj'u ne, Na nèdhi boe hua cue sa, lula rèu heka sub'u mai kèna. Hèia Na peka mi aj'u ne, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Lula èu hia boe Ja'a hua cue sa, de èèna na èu hua heka!&gt;&gt; Ropa Na lii nare sèmi èèna, hèia aj'u ne mango dènge ka.<bt>So He went close to that tree, to try and see if there was fruit, or not yet. But when He arrived at that tree, He did not see even one fruit, because the leaves had only just begun to sprout. Then He spoke with that tree, saying, &lt;&lt;Because you did not give your fruit to Me, consequently that is why you will not have fruit again!&gt;&gt; When He finished speaking like that, then that tree dried up right.away.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="subu = muncul, (ganti daon)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">subu = muncul, (ganti daon)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Ropa ana madhutu Na ladhe rèdhi j'ara ne, hèia ra malaa. Ka ra karèi, peka na, &lt;&lt;Tasamia ka aj'u ne mango?&gt;&gt;<bt>When His followers saw that, then they were surprised/confused. They asked saying, &lt;&lt;How can it be that this tree just dried up?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Hèia Yesus dhaa, na, &lt;&lt;Nanene paie-iie! Ladhe miu lèka tare'a-re'a Lamatua, aa dènge boe d'ara kajari, miu kahèi bisa tao sama sèmi dhu Ja'a tao ne. Miu bisa tao risi hari nèti ne'e. Sèmi: miu bisa paredha ledhe pidha asa d'ara dhasi la'e. Tatu Ama Lamatua pidha eele kahèi ledhe ne nèti era na, sad'i miu parcaya Nèngu tare'a-re'a!<bt>Then He answered, saying, &lt;&lt;Listen carefully! If you believe truly in God, and don't doubt (have split insides), you can do the same as I did there. You can also do more than that. For example: you-pl could command a mountain to move into the ocean. Surely God will move that mountain from that place, as.long.as you truly believe in Him!</bt><note reference="21:21" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 17:20, 1 Korintus 13:2</note><v n="22" />Te aa'i-aa'i dhu miu manèngi nèti Ama Lamatua, èèna na miu abhu, sad'i miu parcaya Ne tare'a-re'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>Cuz (elaboration) all things which you request from God, later you will get/obtain, as long as you truly believe in Him.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Kètu agama sèra karèi Lamatua Yesus abhu hak nèti mia<bt>The chief priests query where the Lord Yesus' right/authority is from</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 11:27-33; Lukas 20:1-8)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />D'ai Yerusalem, Yesus si maso hari asa Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i. Ropa Nèngu aj'a dhèu madha j'ara Ama Lamatua, hèia kètu agama Yahudi, mese agama sèra, dènge dhèu heka-dhèu heka ad'a, mai karèi Yesus, na, &lt;&lt;Med'a na, cee ka dhu pua Èu tao maruru ètu era ne'e ne? Cee ka dhu hia Èu hak?&gt;&gt;<bt>Arriving in Yerusalem, Yesus (coll.) entered again to the Main Prayer House. While He was teaching people about the things of God, then the *chief priests, religious teachers and traditional elders came to ask Him, saying, &lt;&lt;Yesterday, who ordered You {èu = not very polite in this context} to come and make chaos here? Who gave that right/authority to You?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Te ngaa Yesus dhu ne'a, na, dhèu se dhu neo pamanahu Ne. Hèia Na b'ala, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a neo karèi miu kahèi. Miu dhaa uuru ku, heka Ja'a dhaa miu kèna.<bt>But Yesus knew they were looking for a way to make Him fall. So He replied, saying, &lt;&lt;I also want to ask you-pl [something] too. You answer Me first, only.then I will answer you.</bt><v n="25" />Lii karèi Ja'a sèmi ne'e ka: miu aa'i-aa'i mi tadhe Yohanis tuka sarani, si? Cee ka dhu hia ne hak, ho sarani dhèu? Ama Lamatua do, dhèu rai-haha?&gt;&gt;<bt>My question is like.this: you all know Yohanis, that habitual baptizer, right? Who was it who gave him the right/authority to baptize people? God or, humans?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka ra papeka isi-aanga ra, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Waa! Nara le èdhi, nga! Ladhe èdhi dhaa, peka na, &lt;Ama Lamatua ka dhu hia hak&gt;, pe Na b'ala èdhi, peka na, &lt;Ladhe sèmi èèna, nga tao ka miu parcaya boe Yohanis!&gt;<bt>Then they spoke among themselves, saying, &lt;&lt;Waa! [=Oh no!] We-inc have been trapped here, nga [protest particle sort of like ugh!] If we answer saying &lt;It's God who gave the right/authority&gt;, later He will reply saying, &lt;If that's the case, why didn't you believe Yohanis?&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="papeka isi anga ra = omong"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">papeka isi anga ra = omong dong deng dong</Message></Annotation><v n="26" />Te ngaa ladhe èdhi dhaa na, &lt;Dhèu rai-haha ka dhu hia hak&gt;, mage dhoka dhèu aa'i-aa'i patao dènge èdhi. Lula rèngu parcaya, na, Yohanis ne, dhèu nèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua.&gt;&gt;<bt>But if we respond, &lt;Humans are the ones who gave the right/authority&gt;, watch out lest the people all run.amuck at us. Because they believe that Yohanis is God's spokesperson.&gt;&gt;</bt><v n="27" />Nèti èèna ka, ra dhaa peka na, &lt;&lt;Ji'i nge'a boe.&gt;&gt;<bt>That's why they answered Yesus, saying, &lt;&lt;We-exc don't know.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia Yesus b'ala si, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe sèmi èèna, Ja'a parluu boe peka na, cee ka dhu hia Ja'a hak.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus replied, saying, &lt;&lt;If that's the case, I also don't need to tell you who gave the right/authority to Me.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lii pakasame lula-nèti ama dènge ana mone dhèu dua<bt>An example about a father and his two sons</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Yesus padhai lii taruu dènge kètu kapai sèra, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Miu pangee sèku dènge lii lolo ne. Abhu ca dhèu ama, dènge ana mone na dhèu dua. Na peka dènge ana uuru èèna, &lt;Ana, deo ne'e èu lamu sab'a asa d'ara oka.&gt;<bt>Yesus continued speaking with those leaders, saying, &lt;&lt;Have a think about this story. There was a father and his two male children. He ordered the first/oldest child, saying, &lt;Son. Today, you go work in the garden.&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="29" />Te ngaa ana ne dhaa, aku nèngu na, &lt;Eeh! Ja'a laku boe.&gt; Te ngaa nèbhu boe ka, na manyasa, ka la'e.<bt>But that child answered, saying, ‘Eeh [+frustration/objection]! I won't go.’ But soon he felt.regret, so/and he went.</bt><note reference="21:29-31" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Alkitab lii Idhonesia TB1 madhutu boe sasuri lii Yunani dhu uru tèka aa dhu be'a risi ètu ne'e.<bt>The Indonesian language Bible TB1 doesn't follow the oldest and best Yunani writings here.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="30" />Ka ama ra pua ana limuri, peka na, &lt;Deo ne'e, èu lamu sab'a asa d'ara oka.&gt;<bt>Then2 their father ordered his younger child, saying, ‘Today, you go work in the garden.’</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka ana ne dhaa, aku nèngu na, &lt;Be'a, ama! Pe ja'a laku.&gt; Te ngaa te'a boe na, nèngu dhu la'e boe.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then2 that child answered, saying, ‘Ok father. I'll go later’. But it turns out that he didn't go.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Ropa lole nare, hèia Yesus karèi dhèu se'e, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a neo karèi sèmi ne'e: nèti ana dhèu dua se, mia ka dhu tao madhutu lii paredha ama ra?&gt;&gt;<bt>After finishing telling the story, then Yesus asked them, saying, &lt;&lt;I want to ask like this: from those two children there, which one did according to his father's command?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia ra dhaa, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ana uuru!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then they answered saying, &lt;&lt;That first one!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka Na peka, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Oo. Te ngaa nanene paie, te Ja'a peka dhu lèke kèna. Te dhèu dhu miu cap, na, dhèu dhu laku-laku boe, sama sèmi dhèu roro bea, dènge bhèni kajeo, bèli-camèd'a rèngu se'e ka dhu j'aj'i uuru dhèu unu Ama Lamatua, nèti miu. Te miu dhoka sad'i dhaa di, peka na, ‘oo’ mi Ama Lamatua, te ngaa tao boe madhutu dad'èi Na.<bt>Then2 He spoke saying, &lt;&lt;Yes (colloquial). But listen carefully, cuz (elaboration) I'm telling (you) the truth. People whom you have branded/ stamped/categorised as worthless, like these tax collectors, and naughty women (whores/prostitutes), later these are the ones who will become God's people ahead of you. Cuz (elaboration) you only say ‘yea ok’ to God, but don't do according to His will.</bt><v n="32" />Uru èèna, Yohanis tuka sarani, aj'a le miu j'ara tasamia, sèna ka miu bisa mamuri mola. Te ngaa miu parcaya boe ne. Aa te ngaa ropa dhèu laku-laku boe sèra, nanene lii a'aj'a nèti Yohanis, rèngu tèke eele sasala ra, sèna ka tao madhutu a'aj'a èèna. Miu dhu me'a le. Te ngaa miu loe boe nèti ad'u-ue sasala-sasigo, ho madhutu dad'èi Ama Lamatua.&gt;&gt;<bt>Previously, Yohanis the habitual baptizer taught you, how you could live straight (=righteously). But you didn't believe him. However when worthless people heard Yohanis, they left behind their wrongs, to follow that teaching of his. You already know that. But you don't want to stop from your wrongs (doublet), to follow/obey God's will.&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="21:32" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lukas 3:12, 7:29-30</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus tao lii pakasame lula-nèti dhèu bhelu dhu seb'a oka anggor<bt>The Lord Yesus give an example about evil people who rent (share-crop) a grape garden</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 12:1-12; Lukas 20:9-19)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="33" />Yesus lole nare, ka Na lolo hari lii pakasame èci, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Abhu ca dhèu lamatua rai dhu la'e tao oka, ho sèle anggor ètu dedha rai na ca kasib'i. Ka na tao tedhe rai reo. Aa na tao bak cue era pacèli èi anggor. Dhèu ne patitu kahèi era madhenge dhu dedha aae èci. Èle, ka na hia oka ne mi dhèu seb'a, sèna ka d'ai hèru puu-g'ètu, ra pabagi èi anggor. Hèia la'e ka asa rai kaj'èu.<bt>After that, Yesus storied one example more, sayimg. &lt;&lt;There was a land owner who went to make/start a garden, in.order.to plant grape on his plot of land. Then2 he made a fence all around. And he made a tank (assimilated loan) as a place to step/squeeze the grape water/juice. He built a guarding place that was high. Afterwards he gave that garden for people to rent, so that when the harvest season arrived, they could divide out the grape water/juice. Then he left to go to a far land/country.</bt><note reference="21:33" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 5:1-2</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="34" />Ropa d'ai hèru puu-g'ètu, lamatua oka ne pua dhèu sab'a na, lasi asa dhèu seb'a se, sèna ka rare pala nèngu.<bt>When the harvest season arrived, then that garden owner sent/commissioned his workers to go to those renters, in.order.to get/take his share.</bt><v n="35" />Te ngaa dhèu seb'a oka se'e, pusi-pahae boe dènge dhèu-dhèu sab'a nèti lamatua oka ne. Abhu dhu lèke game, abhu dhu ra pamadhe, aa abhu dhu lèke pèci dènge hadhu.<bt>But those renters didn't care/pay attention to (doublet) his workers. There were some which were beaten, there were some who they killed, and some who had stones thrown at them.</bt><v n="36" />Ka lamatua oka ne pua hari dhèu sab'a na canau, ae risi nèti dhèu sab'a dhu lasi uuru sèra. Te ngaa dhèu seb'a oka se tao hari bhabhelu sèmi èèna kahèi mi dhèu sab'a se aa'i-aa'i ra.<bt>But that garden owner sent/commissioned again a group of his workers which was bigger than that first group. But those renters did evil like.that to all these workers too.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="37" />Nèbhu-nèbhu ka lamatua oka ne, pua ana d'èlu na la'e. Na pangee, na, &lt;Ladhe ja'a pua ana d'èlu ja'a la'e, tatu ra sèmi na dènge be'a, aa ra pakab'ua ne kahèi.&gt;<bt>Eventually then, that garden owner sent/commissioned his own child to go. He thought, saying, &lt;If I send my own child to go, surely they will accept him well, and they will also respect him.&gt; [with implication: do what he says]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="38" />Te ngaa ropa dhèu seb'a se ladhe rèdhi ana ne, hèia ra papeka, &lt;Wee, mi laladhe ku laa! Te mone heka nèi hia ana d'èlu na mai. Nèngu ne'e ka dhu bèli-camèd'a, unu aa'i mèdha-panyau mone heka ne. De ta pamadhe ne, sèna ka èdhi unu oka ne.&gt;<bt>But when those renters saw that child, then they spoke to each other, saying, &lt;Wee, have a look there! Cuz (elaboration) the old man has sent his own child here. He is the one who will later own/possess all the old man's wealth/possessions (doublet). So (consequently), let's kill him, so that we are the ones who own/take possession of this garden.&gt;</bt><v n="39" />Hèia kèpe rare ana ne, ka ra nuni asa li'u oka, hèia ra pamadhe ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then they captured that child, then2 dragged him outside the garden and killed him.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="40" />Ka Yesus pa'èle lii lolo Na, ka Na karèi dhèu se'e, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a neo karèi miu sèmi ne'e: ladhe lamatua oka ne lèpa mai, madhutu ngangee miu, na tao dhèu seb'a oka se tasa mera mia?&gt;&gt;<bt>[When] Yesus finished His story, He asked them, saying, &lt;&lt;I want to ask you-pl like this: if/when that garden owner comes back, according to your thinking, what will he do with those renters?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="41" />Hèia kètu kapai Yahudi sèra dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Tatu na pamadhe dhèu bhelu se aa'i-aa'i. Èle, na hia hari dhèu leo seb'a oka ne, dhu èèna na pabagi dènge be'a, ropa d'ai hèru puu-g'ètu.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then, the Yahudi leaders responded, saying, &lt;&lt;Surely he would kill all those evil people. After that, he would rent that garden out to other people, who later would rightly share the results at the harvest time/season.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="42" />Ka Yesus peka dènge ra, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ele boe miu se baca mèdhi boe, ngaa dhu suri tèke ètu d'ara Sasuri Mola-Mèci Ama Lamatua, dhu peka na,<bt>Then2 Yesus spoke with them, saying, &lt;&lt;Perhaps you have never read what is written in the Scriptures, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;Abhu hadhu cue dhu tuka hadhu core eele,<bt>&lt;There was a stone which the stone.workers rejected threw out,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">te ngaa limuri ne, j'aj'i le hadhu era padhèdi èmu!<bt>but now that stone has become the house's main support stone!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ama Lamatua mesa Na ka dhu kabhili nare, aa Na pamadhèdi hadhu ne.<bt>God himself chose it, and placed that stone.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Nèti èèna ka, èdhi ladhe na be'a titu kèna!&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>This is why we-inc see that it is so good!&gt;&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="21:42" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 118:22-23</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="43" />Èle èèna ka, Yesus tuhu hari lii padhai Na, peka na, &lt;&lt;De miu sanèd'e paie-iie. Uru èèna, Ama Lamatua hag'e nare èdhi dhèu Yahudi se, ho j'aj'i dhèu unu Na. Te ngaa, lula miu pusi-pahae boe Ja'a, èèna na Lamatua pili nare dhèu leo rai kara. Te dhèu dhu mamuri madhutu dad'èi Na, dhu nia j'aj'i dhèu unu Na.<bt>Then Yesus talked on, saying, &lt;&lt;So (consequently) you think carefully. Previously God chose us-inc Yahudi people here, to become His people. But because you do not care about/pay attention to (doublet) Me, later God2 will choose other (foreign) people. Cuz (elaboration) only people who live following His will are the ones who are worthy to become His person.</bt><v n="44" />[Ja'a peka paled'a-led'a dènge miu. Ja'a ka, hadhu padhèdi èèna. Dhèu dhu bèbhe lèke hadhu ne, èèna na nèngu laho kao-kao. Aa ladhe hadhu ne bèbhe lèke dhèu, èèna na dhèu ne laho kao-kao.]&gt;&gt;<bt>[I'm telling you clearly (no hidden meaning). I here, am that support stone there! A person who falls hitting that stone, later that person will become completely destroyed. And if that stone falls on someone, later that person will become completely destroyed.]&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="21:44" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Sasuri lii Yunani cahag'e suri boe ayat 44 ne'e.<bt>Some Yunani language writings don't write this verse 44.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="45" />Ropa kètu kapai Yahudi dènge dhèu Parisi tadèngi lii padhai Yesus, hèia re'a, na, lii ne padhèto dènge rèngu. Rèngu se ca ropa dènge dhèu seb'a oka anggor, aa dènge tuka dhu core eele hadhu era padhèdi èmu.<bt>When the *chief priests, and Parisi people heard what Yesus was saying, then they knew that He was targeting them. They were of the same type like those grape garden renters, and those stone.workers who threw away that house support stone.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="padhèto = touch with tip of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">padhèto = touch with tip of finger (sentuh dgn ujung jari)</Message></Annotation><v n="46" />De ra nasa titu kèna. Ka rèngu mulai tenge j'ara ho kèpe Ne. Te ngaa rèngu madha'u dènge dhèu ae, dhu peka na Yesus ne, Dhèu nèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua. Nèti èèna ka, rèngu bani boe tao ngaa-ngaa mi dedha Nèngu.<bt>So (consequently), they became very angry. So/then, they began to look for way/s capture Him. But they were afraid of the many people, who considered Yesus a spokesperson of God. That's why they did not dare do anything to Him.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus hia lii upama lula-nèti dhèu dhu ro'o boe lasi pesta kab'i<bt>The Lord Yesus gives an allegory about people who do not want to come to a wedding feast</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Lukas 14:15-24)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="22" />
      <v n="1" />Ka Yesus padhai lii hari dènge rèngu pake lii upama, aku Nèngu na,<bt>Then2 Yesus spoke again with them using an allegory, saying,</bt><v n="2" />&lt;&lt;Paredha Ama Lamatua èèna, nuka sèmi dhèu aae ca dhèu dhu tao pesta kab'i ana mone na.<bt>&lt;&lt;God's rule/governing, is like a king who makes a wedding feast for his male child.</bt><v n="3" />Ropa dhèu pananasu rare, hèia na pua dhèu sab'a na, sèna ka lasi peka dhèu-dhèu dhu abhu nèru, ra peka na, &lt;Mai ka, te d'ai tadha ta'a-tinu kèna.&gt; Te ngaa dhèu dhu abhu nèru se ro'o boe mai.<bt>When the cookers have finished (=feast is ready), then he sends/commissions his workers to go tell (various) people who were invited, saying, &lt;Come on, cuz (elaboration) the feast (doublet) is about to begin.&gt; But those invited people did not want to come.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Hèia dhèu sab'a se lèpa, lasi peka dènge dhèu aae. Ropa na tadèngi, hèia dhèu aae pua dhèu sab'a na dhu leo hari, aku nèngu na, &lt;Lami peka hari dènge dhèu sèra ho mai ka, te pesta neo mulai kèna. Ja'a para sapi, ka pananasu kore le dhu be'a titu kèna. Peka si mai ka, ra'a-rinu, te aa'i-aa'i tesa le.&gt;<bt>Then those workers go and reports to the king. Hearing like.that, then that king sends his other workers, saying, &lt;You-p go tell those people again to come, cuz (elaboration) the feast/party is about to begin. I have cut/slaughtered a cow (=what you say when you have a really big feast here), and cooked delicious [stuff]. Tell them to come eat (doublet), cuz (elaboration) everything is complete here.&gt;</bt><v n="5" />Dhèu sab'a se lasi peka sèmi dhu dhèu aae moa èèna. Te ngaa dhèu dhu lèke nèru se, pusi-pahae boe. Abhu dhu lasi ladhe oka ra, abhu dhu lasi era sasab'a ra,<bt>Those workers went to tell what the king had instructed. But those people who were invited did not want to know about it (doublet). Some went to check out their garden/s, some went to their work places,</bt><v n="6" />aa cahag'e hari ra kèpe rare dhèu sab'a se nèti dhèu aae ne, ho ra game toke madhe.<bt>and some others captured those workers of the king, and they beat them to death.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Ropa na tadèngi, hèia dhèu aae nasa bia. Ka na paredha sordad'u na, lasi pamadhe aa'i dhèu-dhèu dhu pamadhe dhèu sab'a na sèra. Hèia sordad'u se tunu pakèpu-ladhu ai kota ne toke mera dènge rai.<bt>Hearing like that, then that king was heavily (=severely) angry. Then2 he ordered his soldiers to go kill all those people who had murdered his workers. Then those soldiers burned (doublet) that city flat to the ground.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Èle, ka dhèu aae paroa nare dhèu sab'a dhu leo sèra, ka na peka, &lt;Pesta kab'i ne tesa aa'i le, te ngaa dhèu-dhèu dhu ja'a nèru, nia boe madhèdi ètu d'ara pesta ja'a.<bt>After that, that king called/summoned his other workers and said, &lt;&lt;The wedding feast is complete/ready, but those people whom I invited, are not worthy to sit at my feast.</bt><v n="9" />De lami ka asa j'ara oka-hoo, sèna ka nèru cee dhu sad'i miu paraga.&gt;<bt>So (consequently) you-p go out onto the busy (=main) streets, and invite just whoever you happen to meet there.&gt;</bt><v n="10" />Ka dhèu sab'a se lasi asa j'ara oka-hoo. Hèia rèti mai dhèu ae-ae dhu ra paraga ètu j'ara, sèna ka ra'a-rinu ètu pesta kab'i ne. Dhèu se'e, nuka dhèu dhu be'a dènge dhèu dhu bhelu-katub'a, mai papènu ètu era kakab'i ne.<bt>Then2 those workers went to the busy streets. They brought back many people whom they encountered there to go to that wedding feast. There were good people and evil (doublet) people who came filling up that feast place.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Ka dhèu aae la'e asa era pesta ne ladhe palème tamu sèra. Hèia ladhe nèdhi tamu ca dhèu dhu pake boe mèdha-papake pesta.<bt>Then2 that king entered into the feast place and looked all around at his guests. Then he saw a guest who was not wearing feast/party clothes.</bt><note reference="22:11" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Dhèu d'èlu-mèu cahag'e peka na, dhèu aae ne, sadia mèdha-papake pesta hia dhèu sèra dhu mai nèti mia-mia. Te ngaa dhèu èci ne'e, no'o boe pake mèdha-papake èèna. Dènge j'ara sèmi ne'e, nèngu pahahe dhèu aae dènge ana na.<bt>Some knowledgable people (experts) say that this king provided feast/party clothes for the people who came from various places. But this one person didn't want to wear those clothes. In that way, he offended/insulted the king and his offspring.</bt></note><v n="12" />Ka dhèu aae karèi ne, peka na, &lt;Hee, angalai! Èu nga tao ka mai asa ne'e pake boe mèdha-papake pesta?&gt; Te ngaa dhèu ne loo-loo sène.<bt>Then that king asked, saying, &lt;Hee friend! Why did you come here without wearing feast/party clothes?&gt; But that person was just puzzled and stupidly.speechless.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="loo=loo = tanganga (diam)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">loo=loo = tanganga (diam)</Message></Annotation><v n="13" />Hèia dhèu aae paredha dhèu-dhèu sab'a na, aku nèngu na, &lt;Uj'u haga dènge ai dhèu ne'e ne, ho core ne asa li'u la'e. Hud'i laa na tangi dènge abhu j'èra ètu era dhu maroga kiu-kiu nèi.&gt;<bt>Next that king ordered his workers, saying, &lt;Tie this person's feet and hands and pick him up throw him outside. Let him cry and suffer in the pitch dark place there (remote).&gt;</bt><note reference="22:13" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 8:12, 25:30, Lukas 13:28</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Sèmi èèna kahèi, Ama Lamatua paroa dhèu ae, te ngaa dhodhoka dhu ciki di dhu kabhili nare j'aj'i dhèu unu Na.&gt;&gt;<bt>Likewise, God also calls/summons many people, but He only chooses just a few to become His people.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus padhai lii lula-nèti j'ara b'ae bea mi dhèu paredha<bt>The Lord Yesus talks about paying tax to the government</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 12:13-17; Lukas 20:20-26)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Ropa tadèngi rare lii padhai Yesus, hèia dhèu-dhèu Parisi rare lii èci ho neo pamanahu aa galaa Ne.<bt>After hearing Yesus speaking like.that, the Parisi people agreed with each other to try and make Him fall and accuse/indict Him.</bt><v n="16" />Ka dhèu se pua dhèu rèngu palere-lere dènge dhèu-dhèu nèti partei politik Herodes, sèna ka lasi pakarèi dènge Yesus. Dhèu se koa-kad'iri Yesus, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama Mese! Ji'i nge'a d'ara Ama mola. Ama dhu me'a boe kapod'e-kabèli, aa dhu ladhe boe rèhu dhèu. Ama dhu tema aj'a-nori Lii Holo-Nori Ama Lamatua dènge boe koe-kapengo.<bt>So they ordered their people together with people from Herodes' political party to go debate with Yesus. They praised/flattered (doublet) Yesus, saying, &lt;&lt;Father Teacher! We-exc know Father's insides are straight (=you are honest/just). Father doesn't know how to twist-turn (=decieve) and doesn't choose faces (=discriminate). Father always teaches (doublet) God's Words correctly (doublet). [NOTE: on ‘Herodians’, see CEV ftn and discussion in Morris.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pakanucu also fits here (but UNS"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">pakanucu also fits here (but UNS not know)</Message></Annotation><v n="17" />Mamai ji'i ne, neo karèi j'ara èci. Madhutu atora agama Yahudi, èdhi bisa b'ae bea mi dhèu aae kapai Roma, do aad'o?&gt;&gt;<bt>Our purpose for coming is we want to ask something. According to our-inc Yahudi religious regulations, are we-inc allowed to pay tax to the Roma goverment's big king, or not?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Te ngaa Yesus ne'a mema, na, rèngu neo madulu d'ara Na, sèna ka Nèngu padhai lii lab'a dhèu paredha Roma. Hèia Yesus dhaa, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Miu mema dhèu ho'a tema! Tasamia ka miu neo pamanahu Ja'a dènge j'ara ne'e?<bt>[CHECK /dhèu ho'a tema/] But Yesus already knew they were fishing/baiting/trying.to.trap Him, so.that He would speak opposing the Roma government. Then He replied saying, &lt;&lt;You are fundamentally hypocrites [idiom to double-check]! Why are you trying to trap me with that problem/issue?</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="madulu = pancing (fish, or with"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">madulu = pancing (fish, or with words) ; dhèu ho'a tema = 1) padhai lii leo, tao leo, 2) kebiasaan</Message></Annotation><v n="19" />Pad'elo sèku Ja'a doi iia cue, dhu dhèu pake ho b'ae bea!&gt;&gt; Hèia ra pad'elo doi iia ne mi Yesus.<bt>Show Me a silver money which people use to pay tax!&gt;&gt; Then they showed a silver money/coin to Yesus.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Ka Na karèi si, &lt;&lt;Ne'e ne, rèhu cee? Aa ne'e ne, ngara cee?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then He asked them, saying, &lt;&lt;This is whose face here? And this is whose name here?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Ra dhaa, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Èèna keser, dhèu aae kapai paredha Roma.&gt;&gt;<bt>They answered, saying, &lt;&lt;That's keser, that big king of the Roma government.&gt;&gt; [NOTE: /keser/ is considered a slightly archaic term in this region for a king--from the Dutch]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia Yesus peka dènge ra, na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe sèmi èèna hia la mi dhèu paredha ngaa dhu j'aj'i hak dhèu paredha. Aa hia la mi Ama Lamatua ngaa dhu j'aj'i hak Ama Lamatua.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus told them, saying, &lt;&lt;If that's the case, you go give to the government that which the government has rights.to. And give to God that which God has rights.to.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Ropa ra tadèngi hèia rèngu aa'i-aa'i malaa, lula ngaa dhu Na peka sèra lèke tare'a-re'a. Nèti èèna ka, rèngu bisa boe abhu j'ara ho pamanahu Yesus. Hèia lasi ka tèke eele Yesus.<bt>Hearing Him answer like that, then they all were amazed, because He spoke correctly. That's why they could not find a way to trap Him. Then they walked leaving Yesus. [NOTE (CEG): I assume /ko Dia omong batúl na./ is required from UNS response. Also implied by positive semantics of Gk ‘marvelled’. See also discussion in Morris, TN, and Carson.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus aj'a lula-nèti dhèu madhe mamuri hari; aa dhèu paleo èmu ètu sorga, do aad'o?<bt>The Lord Yesus teaches about dead people living again; and people marrying in heaven, or not?</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 12:18-27; Lukas 20:27-40)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Ètu era ne'e, abhu kahèi dhèu nèti partei Saduki. Dhèu se'e ka dhu aj'a, peka na, dhèu madhe bisa heka mamuri. Lod'o èèna, dhèu se'e kahèi dhu tenge j'ara ho pamanahu Yesus. Nèti èèna ka, rèngu mai pakarèi dènge Ne, peka na,<bt>There, there were also people from the Saduki party. These people taught that dead people do not live again. That day, they also sought a way to trap Yesus. That's why they came to debate with Him, saying,</bt><note reference="22:23" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 23:8</note><v n="24" />&lt;&lt;Ama Mese! Musa dhu suri tèke le atora hia ji'i, dhu peka na: ladhe dhèu mone ca dhèu madhe tèke eele dhèu èmu na dhu dènge boe ana, na, ari nèti dhèu mone ne, hud'i leo nare hari bhèni balu ne, sèna ka abhu kolo gati madha a'a na.<bt>&lt;&lt;Father Teacher! Musa wrote leaving behind for us, this regulation that says: if a man dies leaving behind his spouse, but does not have a child, na, then that man's younger.sibling must marry that widow, in.order.to give a descendant (lit: tip) to replace his dead elder.sibling.</bt><note reference="22:24" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 25:5</note><v n="25" />Mema uru èèna Musa aj'a sèmi èèna ka. Te ngaa ji'i neo karèi sèmi ne'e: abhu ana mone dhèu pidhu dhu pa'a'ari. Ana partama leo-èmu, te ngaa madhe dènge boe kolo. Hèia ari na leo nare bhèni balu ne.<bt>It's true that previously Musa taught like that. But we-exc want to ask like this: there were seven male siblings. The first one married, but he died and did not leave a child (idomatic). Then his younger.sibling married that widow.</bt><v n="26" />Nèbhu boe ka, na madhe, dènge boe ana kahèi. Sèmi èèna kahèi dènge ari ka tèlu na; nèngu madhèdi kahèi dènge bhèni balu ne, te ngaa madhe kahèi dènge boe ana. Sèmi èèna ka toke ari na dhu limuri tèka, madhe kahèi.<bt>Not much longer he died, and also didn't have a child. Like that also with younger.sibling number three; he married2 that widow, but he also died and did not leave behind a child. Like that until the youngest younger.sibling also died.</bt><v n="27" />Ka bhèni balu ne madhe.<bt>Then2 that widow died.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />De dhu ji'i neo karèi, sèmi ne'e ne: bhèni balu ne dhu leo nèdhi dènge mone dhèu pidhu se. Bèli-camèd'a lod'o èle rai-haha ne, ropa Ama Lamatua pamamuri hari dhèu madhe sèra, na, bhèni ne j'aj'i mi dhèu èmu cee?&gt;&gt;<bt>So (consequently), what we want to ask is like this: that woman has married seven men. Later when the world ends, when2 God makes dead people live again, na, that woman will be whose spouse?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="29" />Èle èèna ka, Yesus b'ala si, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe lii pakarèi miu sèmi èèna, miu se sala kapai le! Te miu se me'a mere boe isi sasuri Ama Lamatua. Aa me'a boe kahèi koasa Na dhu kapai aae èèna.<bt>Then3 Yesus answered, saying, &lt;&lt;If you-p ask like.that, you are really wrong here! Cuz (elaboration) you don't really understand the contents of God's Writings. And you also don't really understand His power/authority which is awesome!</bt><v n="30" />Dhu lèke ka sèmi ne'e! Pe Ama Lamatua pamamuri hari dhèu nèti mamadhe ra, rèngu se paleo heka èmu, sama sèmi ana pajuu Na ètu sorga dhu leo boe èmu.<bt>What's correct is like this. Later, [when] God makes dead people live again, they will also not marry anymore, like His underlings in heaven do not marry.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Aa Ja'a neo peka kahèi, lula-nèti dhèu madhe bisa mamuri hari, do aad'o. Ètu d'ara sasuri Musa, dhu lole na, aj'u iiki ca kapua dhu ai na'e te ngaa kèpu boe. Nèti lii lolo ne, èdhi bisa te'a, na, dhèu madhe bisa mamuri hari. Te ètu d'ara sasuri èèna, Ama Lamatua peka dènge Musa, na,<bt>And I also want to talk about whether dead people can live again, or not. In Musa' writings there is a the story of the small tree which was burning but did not burn2 up. From that story, we-inc know that dead people can live again. Cuz (elaboration) in that writing God told Musa, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="32" />&lt;Ja'a ne Ama Lamatua nèti bèi-baki èu.<bt>&lt;I here am your grandfathers'/forefathers' God.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Nuka Abraham, Isak dènge Yakob.<bt>That is Abraham, Isak, and Yakob.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Rèngu aa'i-aa'i ra pahaha iisi era mi Ja'a toke d'ai sange ne'e ne.&gt;<bt>They all still worship Me until now.&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">De èdhi te'a, na, lod'o Ama Lamatua peka sèmi èèna, baki èdhi se dhu madhe nèbhu le. Te ngaa Ama Lamatua peka na, Nèngu j'aj'i Lamatua rèngu era. Nèti èèna ka, èdhi dhu te'a na, samanga rèngu dhu mamuri era, masi ka rèngu dhu madhe nèbhu le. De masi ka madhe, te ngaa ra mamuri hari. Te dhodhoka dhèu mamuri di, dhu pahaha iisi mi Ama Lamatua, dhèu dhu madhe, aad'o, si?!&gt;&gt;<bt>So (consequently), we-inc know that when God spoke like.that, those grandfathers of ours-inc had been dead a long time. But God said He was still their Lord. That's why we-inc know that their souls were/are continuing to live, even though they were dead a long time. So (consequently) even if people die, nevertheless they live again. Cuz (elaboration) only living people who worship God, not dead people, right?!&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="22:32" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 3:6</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="33" />Ropa ra tadèngi rare lii padhai Yesus ne, hèia dhèu Saduki se re'a heka b'ala. Te ngaa dhèu ae se malaa-maloha, ka ra papeka na, &lt;&lt;Ira ii! Lii padhai Dhèu ne'e ne be'a seli eele, nga!&gt;&gt;<bt>Hearing Yesus teach like that, then those Saduki people could not reply anything else. But those many people were amazed and spoke to each other saying, &lt;&lt;Ira ii [+amazement]! This Person's speaking is really awesome!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus aj'a lula-nèti paredha dhu kapai risi<bt>The Lord Yesus teaches about the command/s which are the most important</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 12:28-34; Lukas 10:25-28)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="34" />Ropa dhèu Parisi tadèngi, na, Yesus segi le dhèu Saduki, hèia ra pakaboko ho lasi pakarèi dènge Ne.<bt>When the Parisi people heard that Yesus had surpassed/overcome those Saduki people, then they gathered to debate with Him.</bt><v n="35" />Nèti rèngu se, abhu ca dhèu dhu d'èlu-mèu j'ara-j'ara agama, la'e pakarèi dènge Yesus, aku nèngu na,<bt>One of their religion experts tried to debate Him, saying,</bt><v n="36" />&lt;&lt;Ama Mese! Ja'a neo karèi sèmi ne'e ka: atora nèti ad'a dènge agama èdhi, ae d'ai seli. Paredha aa'i-aa'i dhu nèti Musa, mia ka dhu dedha risi?&gt;&gt;<bt>&lt;&lt;Father Teacher! I want to ask like.this: the regulations from our-inc tradition/custom's and religion's are very many. From all those commandments which are from Musa, which one/s is the most important?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="37" />Hèia Yesus dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Paredha dhu dedha risi ètu d'ara Sasuri Mola-Mèci Ama Lamatua suri, peka na:<bt>Then Yesus replied saying, &lt;&lt;The commandment which is most important in the Scriptures, says like.this:</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;Ama Lamatua èèna, tare'a Lamatua miu.<bt>&lt;God is your-p God2/Master.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">De miu se hud'i sue <span class="Italic">risi</span> Ne nèti ngaa aa'i-aa'i.<bt>So (consequently), you-p must love Him <span class="Italic">more</span> than everything.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Nèti èèna ka, miu hud'i sanao-maena taruu mi Nèngu,<bt>Because of that, you must always hope-depend (doublet) on Him,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">tadhe paie Ne,<bt>understand/know Him well,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">dènge sab'a pa'èra ho madhutu dad'èi Na.&gt;<bt>and work hard to follow/obey His will.&gt;</bt><note reference="22:37" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 6:5</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="38" />Ne'e ne ka, paredha dhu dedha dènge kapai risi!<bt>This command is the one that is most highest and greatest!</bt><v n="39" />Aa abhu paredha ka dua dhu peka na:<bt>And the second command says like.this:</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;Èu hud'i sue ku dhèu leo, nuka sèmi èu sue ngi'u èu mesa mu.&gt;<bt>&lt;You-s must love other people, the same as you love your own self.'</bt><note reference="22:39" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Atora nèti Ama-ama Agama 19:18</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="40" />Dua paredha se, nuka kapua nèti atora Musa dènge lii aj'a-nori aa'i-aa'i ra nèti dhèu rèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua. Dhèu tatu boe madhutu paredha leo, ladhe nèngu madhutu uuru boe dua paredha dhu dedha risi se.&gt;&gt;<bt>These two commandments here, are the tree/trunk (=root/base) of all Musa's regulations and God's spokesperson's teachings (doublet). A person surely can not follow the other commands, if he does not first follow these two higher commands here.&gt;&gt; [NOTE: last sentence following Carson, CONNOT]</bt><note reference="22:35-40" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lukas 10:25-28</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Kristus, mema tare'a ana-èpu dhèu aae Daud, te ngaa Nèngu Lamatua nèti dhèu aae Daud kahèi<bt>Kristus is truly king Daud's descendant, but He also is king Daud's Lord/Master/God2</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 12:35-37; Lukas 20:41-44)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="41" />Ropa dhèu Parisi dhu pakaboko era ètu èèna, ka Yesus karèi si, peka na,<bt>When those Parisi people were still gathered there, then Yesus asked them, saying,</bt><v n="42" />&lt;&lt;Karèi nèti uru ka, Ama Lamatua dhu padhadha tèke le, ho pua Kristus mai, sèna ka hia mamuri mi dhèu unu Na. De madhutu a'abhu miu, na, Kristus èèna ana-èpu cee?&gt;&gt;<bt>&lt;&lt;From long ago God has promised to send Kristus to save/ give life to His people. So (consequently) according to your-p thinking, na, that Kristus is whose descendant?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia ra dhaa peka na, &lt;&lt;Nèngu èèna, ana-èpu nèti dhèu aae Daud.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then they answered, saying, &lt;&lt;He is a descendant of king Daud.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="43" />Yesus lii hari, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe sèmi èèna, nga tao ka Roh Mola-Mèci èèna peka dènge dhèu aae Daud, na, nèngu paroa Kristus, &lt;Lamatua&gt;? Te Daud suri tèke na,<bt>Yesus spoke further, saying, &lt;&lt;If it's like.that then, why did the Holy Spirit tell king Daud for him to call Kristus &lt;Lord/Master&gt;? Cuz (elaboration) Daud wrote, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="44" />&lt;Ama Lamatua peka mema le dènge lamatua ja'a, na,<bt>&lt;God has told my lord/master, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">&lt;&lt;Mai ho madhèdi ètu era hua iia ne, ètu baboa g'ana Ja'a.<bt>&lt;&lt;Come and sit in the place of greatest respect/honour here, at My right side.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Te bèli-camèd'a Ja'a tao musu-musu èu sèra, pahaha iisi mi èu.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>Cuz (elaboration) later I will make your enemies, surrender/lower/ humble themselves to you.&gt;&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="22:44" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 110:1</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="45" />De nèti lii ne'e ne, èdhi te'a, na, dhèu aae Daud mesa na paroa Kristus ne, &lt;Lamatua&gt;. De ladhe dhèu peka na, Kristus dhoka ana-èpu Daud di, èèna dhae d'ai mèka. Lula Nèngu Lamatua nèti dhèu aae Daud kahèi!&gt;&gt;<bt>So (consequently), from that message/saying, we-inc know that it was king Daud himself who called Kristus, &lt;Lord/Master&gt;. So (consequently), if people say that Kristus is only just king Daud's descendant, that is not enough! Because He also was king Daud's Lord/Master!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="46" />Ropa ra tadèngi lii padhai Yesus, dhèu Parisi se nuka sèmi dhèu goa sa, te ca dhèu sa bisa boe dhaa lii Yesus. Nèti èèna ka, nèti lod'o èèna, rèngu bani heka tenge j'ara ho pakarèi Ne.<bt>Hearing Yesus' talking like.that, those Parisi people became just stupidly.speechless, cuz (elaboration) there was not a single person who could respond to Yesus. That's why from that day/time, they didn't dare try to debate Him anymore.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus pasanèd'e, sèna ka baku pamud'e dènge mese agama aa dhèu Parisi sèra<bt>The Lord Yesus reminds/warns to be careful of the religion teachers and the Parisi people</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 12:38-39; Lukas 11:43, 46; 20:45-46)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="23" />
      <v n="1" />Èle èèna ka, Yesus aj'a ana madhutu Na dènge dhèu ae leo dhu palere dènge rèngu.<bt>After that, Yesus taught His followers, together with those many other people who were together with them.</bt><v n="2" />Na peka dènge ra, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Mese agama dènge dhèu Parisi sèra abhu hak ho aj'a-nori atora Musa mi dhèu.<bt>He told them, saying, &lt;&lt;Those religion teachers and Parisi people have right/authority to teach (doublet) Musa's regulations to people.</bt><v n="3" />Nèti èèna ka, miu hud'i nanene si, aa tao madhutu lii a'aj'a ra. Te ngaa mage mi madhutu ngaa dhu ra ad'u-ue, lula rèngu mesa ra madhutu boe lii a'aj'a rèngu sèra.<bt>Because of that, you-p must listen to them and follow their teachings. But don't follow what they do, because they themselves don't do according to their own teachings.</bt><v n="4" />Rèngu laka-seti dhèu sèna ka madhutu atora agama ra dhu pabia dhèu. Te ngaa rèngu mesa ra ro'o boe soru-bara dhèu, sèna ka madhutu atora sèra.<bt>They force people to follow their religious regulations which burden/weigh down people. But they themselves don't want to help (doublet) people to follow those regulations.</bt><v n="5" />Aa'i-aa'i dhu ra ad'u-ue sèra, sèna ka dhèu koa-kad'iri si. Nuka sèmi: ètu katanga rèi ra, dhu èki dènge mèdha èci dhu suri Lii Holo-Nori Ama Lamatua, aa ètu lele aai ra kahèi. Te ngaa rèngu tao parisi hari, sèna ka dhèu padedha si, peka na, &lt;Ira ii! Dhèu se, dhèu mola!&gt;<bt>[CHECK /kalele ai/ upper arm, above elbow] Everything which they do, they do so that people will praise2 (doublet) them. For example: in a box that contains God's Words they tie/bind on their heads, and their (upper) arms. But they make theirs even bigger, so that people will elevate them up (=praise), saying, &lt;Ira ii! [+positive] These people, are straight/righteous people!&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="katanga rèi = testa ; kalele"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z" status="Anyone">katanga rèi = testa ; kalele ai = upper arm, above elbow</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lele aai"><Message author="Chuck" created="2009-11-27 07:32:37Z" status="Anyone">upper arm, above elbow (kalele ai wrong); kalele manu = chicken thigh</Message></Annotation><note reference="23:5" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 6:1, Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 6:8, Sensus 15:38</note></p>
    <fig path="HK-LB\HK00274C.tif" rtfFormat="width:4.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right">Dhèu Yahudi èki Lii Holo-Nori ètu katanga rèi<bt>A Yahudi person ties the Scripture on his forehead</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Ladhe rèngu maso asa d'ara èmu gareja, do, d'ara pesta rèngu d'èi tenge era dhu be'a risi, sèna ka dhèu ae ladhe rèdhi si.<bt>If/when they enter a worship house, or they go to a feast/party, they always look for a place which is the best, so many people will see them.</bt><v n="7" />Ladhe lasi asa d'ara pasa, rèngu d'èi dhèu pakab'ua si. Ra tenge j'ara, sèna ka dhèu pahaha iisi mi rèngu, aa d'èi dhèu paroa ra, &lt;Ama mese, dhu hua iia.&gt;<bt>If/when they go to the market, they like people to honor/respect them. They look for ways so that people will bow to them, saying &lt;Father Teacher who is honoured.&gt;</bt><v n="8" />Te ngaa miu baku madhutu j'ara rèngu se'e! Dhèu baku paroa miu &lt;ama mese&gt;, lula Mese miu dhoka ca dhèu di. Aa miu aa'i-aa'i mi se'e, pa'a'ari.<bt>But you-p don't follow that way of theirs. People should not call you, saying &lt;father teacher&gt;, because your Teacher is only just one person. And you all here, [are] reciprocally siblings (= term used to imply same status).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="haplology: pa-a'a-ari - pa'a'ari"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">haplology: pa-a'a-ari - pa'a'ari</Message></Annotation><v n="9" />Mage j'oka padedha dhèu ètu rai-haha ne, peka na, &lt;ama&gt;, lula Ama miu ètu sorga dhoka èci di.<bt>Don't lift.up/praise people in this world saying, &lt;&lt;father&gt;, because your Father in heaven is only just one.</bt><v n="10" />Dhèu baku paroa miu kahèi, &lt;lamatua&gt;, lula Ama Lamatua miu dhodhoka èci di, nuka Ja'a ne, dhu Ama Lamatua pajaji mema karèi nèti uru ka.<bt>People also should not call you saying &lt;lord/master/boss&gt;, because your Lord/Master/Boss is only just one, that is Me here whom God promised to send from long ago.</bt><v n="11" />Nèti èèna ka, Ja'a pasanèd'e mema miu, mage padedha iisi mi, nuka sèmi dhèu dhu d'èi dhoka dhèu pakab'ua ra. Nèti miu se, cee ka dhu neo j'aj'i dhèu kapai, nèngu hud'i j'aj'i ku nuka sèmi ènu, sèna ka lalau-lalo'o dhèu leo.<bt>That's why I remind/warn you to not elevate yourselves like those people who only want people to honour them. Whoever of you wants to become a big/important person, he must become the same as a slave/lowest level servant to serve (doublet) other people.</bt><note reference="23:11" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 20:26-27, Markus 9:35, 10:43-44, Lukas 22:26</note><v n="12" />Te dhèu dhu pamone-pabhèni, èèna na Lamatua pamanahu ne. Te ngaa dhèu dhu pahaha iisi nuka sèmi ana iiki, bèli-camèd'a Lamatua ded'e padedha ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>Cuz (elaboration) a person who shows male arrogance/female arrogance (doublet), later God2 will make him/her fall. But the person who lowers/humbles him/her self the same as a small/insignificant person, later God will lift him/her up.&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="23:12" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lukas 14:11, 18:14</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus pasanèd'e kètu agama sèra, lula rèngu padhai lii leo, tao leo<bt>The Lord Yesus reminds/warns the religious bosses, because they say one thing, and do another</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 12:40; Lukas 11:39-42, 44, 47-52; 20:47)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Ka Yesus tuhu hari lii padhai Na, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Hee, miu mese agama dènge dhèu Parisi se! Miu mema dhèu dhu padhai lii leo, tao leo! Bèli-camèd'a miu dui mere pala miu, lula miu mo'o boe parcaya Ja'a, nuka Dhèu dhu Ama Lamatua pamoa tèke pua mai. Aa dhu bhelu risi hari, miu bhabhae dhèu neo mai asa d'ara rai paredha Ama Lamatua, sèna ka ra baku parcaya Ja'a.<bt>After that Yesus continued speaking, saying, &lt;&lt;Hee, you religion teachers and Parisi people! You are people who say one thing and do another! Later you will get your just desserts (idiomatic), because you do not want to believe Me, who is that Person whom God promised to send here. And what's even more evil, you obstruct people who want to come into God's kingdom/governance, so that they don't believe in Me.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />[Hee, miu mese-mese agama dènge dhèu-dhèu Parisi! Mema miu dhèu dhu padhai lii leo, tao leo! Bèli-camèd'a miu pasae mere mamadhe-mamopo, lula miu d'èi kapod'e-kabèli bhèni balu, sèna ka parame mere èmu ra. Te ngaa ètu madha dhèu ae, miu pa'abhe bhabhelu miu, dènge j'ara sabaj'a panèbhu-nèbhu, ho dhèu peka na, miu dhèu d'ara mola. Te ngaa èèna na, Ama Lamatua hia huku dhu bia risi mi miu.]<bt>[Hee, you religion teachers and Parisi people! You really are people who say one thing and do another! Later you will shoulder.carry/ experience misfortune (doublet), because you like to twist-turn (=decieve) widows, then snatch away their house(s). But in front of many people, you cover over that evil of yours, by praying long-long so people say you are straight/righteous people. But later God will give a punishment which is very heavy/severe to you.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mamadhe-mamopo = doesn't have to involve"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">mamadhe-mamopo = doesn't have to involve death, musibah, yg menimbulkan kerugian ; era pea-palu'u = tempat tinggal</Message></Annotation><note reference="23:14" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Ayat 14 ne aad'o ètu d'ara sasuri lii Yunani uru-uru sèra.<bt>This verse 14 isn't in the Yunani language writings which are the oldest.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Hee, miu mese agama dènge dhèu Parisi sèra! Mema miu dhèu dhu padhai leo, tao leo! Bèli-camèd'a miu pasae mere mamadhe-mamopo, lula miu lami asa mia èèna ka, palème lèu, do, ca'e-puru ledhe, neo tenge dhoka ca dhèu di, sèna ka maso partei agama miu. Te ngaa ropa na maso, miu ad'u-ue mamuri na asa bhelu risi, toke na abhu hahuku dhu babia na, dua hari risi nèti miu ètu d'ara naraka.<bt>Hee, you religion teachers and Parisi people! You really are people who say one thing and do another! Later you will shoulder.carry/ experience misfortune (doublet), because you go all over the place, over the seas, up and down mountains, only to just find one person, so that he will enter into your religious party. But when he has entered, then you make his life become even more evil, to.the.point that he gets a punishment in hell two times heavier/more severe than you.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="are = cross (by foot), ford"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">are = cross (by foot), ford</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Wee! D'ara miu dhu bèdhu le. Nga tao ka limuri ne miu neo pad'elo j'ara hia dhèu leo? Pe miu abhu mamadhe-mamopo, lula miu aj'a leli, peka na, &lt;Ladhe dhèu pajaji pake soo-subha dhu ale Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i, na, dhèu ne pa'èki boe dènge lii pajaji na èèna. Te ngaa ladhe na pajaji pake subha dènge ale mèdha hualaa ètu d'ara Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i, na, nèngu heka pa'èki dènge lii pajaji na.&gt;<bt>Wee! You have become blind in your insides (heartless, unfeeling). Why are you still wanting to show the way for other people? Later you will get misfortune (doublet) because you teach recklessly, saying, &lt;If a person establishes a promise using an oath mentioning the *Temple (Main House of Worship), then that person is not tied to that promise of his. But if he establishes a promise using an oath mentioning the gold things which are in that Temple, only then is he tied to that promise.&gt;</bt><v n="17" />Miu goa kabao! Miu pangee na, Ama Lamatua pakab'ua risi mèdha hualaa sèra nèti Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i Na, do? Aad'o! Te Èmu ne'e ka dhu tao mèdha sèra j'aj'i mola-mèci!<bt>You here are stupid water buffaloes (=idiom, to the max)! Do you think God considers gold things more important than His Temple? No! Cuz (elaboration) that House is what makes those things become holy/clean (doublet)!</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Miu se aj'a ore-leli kahèi, peka na, &lt;Ladhe dhèu pajaji pake subha ale mei korban dhu ètu d'ara Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i, dhèu ne pa'èki boe dènge lii pajaji na. Te ngaa ladhe na pajaji pake subha aa ale mèdha ètu dedha mei korban, na, dhèu ne heka pa'èki dènge lii pajaji na kèna.&gt;<bt>You also teach recklessly (doublet), saying, &lt;If a person establishes a promise using an oath mentioning that sacrifice table which is in the Temple, that person is not tied to that promise of his. But if he establishes a promise using an oath mentioning the thing which is on top of that sacrifice table, na, only then is he tied to that promise.&gt;</bt><v n="19" />Miu mema bèdhu tare'a-re'a. Tatu mei korban ne, kab'ua risi nèti mèdha ètu dedha mei èèna. Te mei èèna ka dhu tao mèdha korban rèngu j'aj'i mola-mèci mi Ama Lamatua.<bt>You here, [are] really-really blind. Of course that sacrifice table there, is more important that the sacrifice which is on top of that table. Cuz (elaboration) that table there is what makes their sacrifices become clean/holy/pure to God.</bt><v n="20" />Nèti èèna ka, ladhe dhèu subha ale mei korban ne, na, be'a risi ale mei dènge aa'i-aa'i dhu ètu dedha mei èèna.<bt>Because of that, if people oath mentioning the sacrifice table, it's better to mention that table and also everything which is on top of that table.</bt><v n="21" />Aa ladhe dhèu subha ale Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i, na, be'a risi ale kahèi Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i dènge kolongara Ama Lamatua. Te Nèngu ka dhu pea ètu talora aae na.<bt>And if people oath mentioning the Temple, it's better they mention the Temple together with God's name. Cuz (elaboration) He is the one who lives in its midst.</bt><v n="22" />Aa ladhe dhèu subha ale sorga, na, èèna èci èèna ka dènge nèngu ale kadera paredha Ama Lamatua, palere-lere dènge kolongara Na, te Nèngu ka dhu madhèdi nèd'u paredha ètu èèna.<bt>And if people oath mentioning heaven, that is the same as his mentioning God's ruling chair together with His name, cuz (elaboration) He is the one who sits ruling there.</bt><note reference="23:22" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 66:1, Mateos 5:34</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Hee, miu mese agama dènge dhèu Parisi sèra! Mema miu dhèu dhu padhai leo, tao leo! Pe miu abhu mamadhe-mamopo, lula miu d'èlu-mèu titu kèna pa'iga capala nèti canguru pala dhu miu hia Lamatua. Miu pa'iga aa'i mèu-mèu, toke bubhu nèti d'ara oka, èci sa tèke eele boe. Miu ige toke lutu-sela nuka sèmi, rèu d'are, ka'unyi, dènge lasona. Te ngaa miu pabhèlu eele atora dhu kab'ua risi nèti Ama Lamatua! Te mamuri miu mola boe. Miu sue boe dhèu dhu unu aad'o. Aa mamuri miu madhutu boe dad'èi Lamatua. Be'a risi miu tao madhutu aa'i dhu pakarej'e d'ara Lamatua, heka mi pa'ige kèna bubhu-bubhu dhu lutu sèra, dhu miu neo hia mi Lamatua.<bt>Hee, you religion teachers and Parisi people! You really are people who say one thing and do another! Later you will get misfortune (doublet), because you are so clever counting one part of ten parts to give God2. You repeatedly count everything so carefully, including your spices from the garden, you don't overlook even one. For example you count in finest detail your {small leaf spice}, turmeric, and shallots. But you have completely forgotten the most important regulation/s of God's! Cuz (elaboration) you don't live straight (=are not honest/righteous/just). You don't love/pity poor people. And you don't live continually following God2's will. It's better you do all that which please God2's insides, before you go count your (various) spices that you want to give to God2.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rèu d'are = daun selasi [CHECK"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">rèu d'are = daun selasi [CHECK implosive] ; seke muru = [Mika &amp; Lena tidak tahu] ; ka'unyi = kunyit ; lasona = shallots ; lasona mea = shallots ; lasona kab'a = garlic ; masi = salt</Message></Annotation><note reference="23:23" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Atora nèti Ama-ama Agama 27:30</note><v n="24" />D'ara miu bèdhu, te ngaa tasamia ka neo era paj'uj'u j'ara hia dhèu leo? Miu tao atora toke lutu, ho pua dhèu madhutu, te ngaa atora dhu kab'ua risi nèti Ama Lamatua, miu mesa mi pusi-pahae boe. Nuka sèmi miu sule eele kikidui dhu ana iiki-iiki nèti èi dhu miu minu, te ngaa badha aae sèmi kabao, miu dhèle kateme!<bt>[NOTE RL often strains ants out of gula, nira.] Your insides are blind, but why are you still wanting to show the way for other people? You make regulations in finest detail to order other people to follow/obey, but that/those regulations of God's which are most important, you yourselves don't care about (doublet). It's as if you often filter out a tiny and from your drinking water, but a big animal like a water.buffalo, you swallow it down whole!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sule = saring ; lèg'u ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">sule = saring ; lèg'u = sandfly, agas ; kikidui = semut</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Hee, miu mese agama dènge dhèu Parisi sèra! Mema miu dhèu dhu padhai leo, tao leo! Pe miu abhu mamadhe-mamopo, lula miu rase pega-mago toke mèu kale'e, te ngaa dhoka re li'u di. Masi ka re d'ara na dhu kaj'alu titu kèna nèti mana'u miu dènge dèu ngara miu. Mamuri miu sèmi èèna kahèi.<bt>[CHECK if last sentence needed. Suggested by team.] Hee, you religion teachers and Parisi people! You really are people who say one thing and do another! Later you will get misfortune (doublet), because you wash your dishes (doublet) until they are shiny clean, but that is only just on the outside. Even though on the inside they are very filthy from that stealing of yours and your greediness. Your lives are also like that.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dèu ngara = rakus"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">dèu ngara = rakus</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Wee, dhèu Parisi dhu bèdhu, ee! Rase uuru ku re d'ara pega-mago miu sèra! Dènge sèmi èèna, re li'u na j'aj'i mèu kahèi!<bt>Wee! Blind Parisi people, ee! Wash first your dishes (doublet) inside part. In doing that the outside part can also become clean!</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Wee, miu mese agama dènge dhèu Parisi sèra! Mema miu dhèu dhu padhai leo, tao leo! Pe miu abhu mamadhe-mamopo, lula miu ca ropa dènge ro'a dhèu madhe dhu lame dènge èi dama pudhi. Dhèu ladhe re li'u na, be'a titu kèna. Te ngaa ètu d'ara, pènu dènge rui dhèu madhe, aa dhu hèu oone-oone.<bt>Wee, you religion teachers and Parisi people! You really are people who say one thing and do another! Later you will get misfortune (doublet), because you here are like a grave which has been painted white/ whitewashed. People can see that outside part, is very good. But the inside is full of bones of dead people, and everything which smells rotten.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lame = labur ; èi dama"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">lame = labur ; èi dama pudhi = oker ; hèu oone-oone = bau busuk (mayat)</Message></Annotation><note reference="23:27" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 23:3</note><v n="28" />Miu èci èèna ka! Miu d'èi tao iisi mi sèmi dhèu dhu mola-mèci. Nèti li'u dhèu rèdhi, na, miu nuka sèmi dhèu d'ara mola. Te ngaa ètu d'ara, miu cakaraa dhèu bhelu-katub'a. Te miu padhai lii leo, tao leo, aa pabhèlu eele paredha Ama Lamatua sèra.<bt>You are also like that! You like to make yourselves as if you are clean/holy people. From the outside people see you, like you are people who have straight/righteous/just insides. But on the inside, you are like an evil (doublet) person. Cuz (elaboration) you say one thing, do another, and forget away God's commands.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="29" />Hee, miu mese agama dènge dhèu Parisi sèra! Mema miu dhèu dhu padhai leo, tao leo! Pe miu abhu mamadhe-mamopo! Miu pakapai ro'a nèti dhèu rèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua, aa dule pabe'a-be'a ro'a dhèu d'ara be'a.<bt>Hee, you religion teachers and Parisi people! You really are people who say one thing and do another! Later you will get misfortune (doublet)! You enlarge grave/s for God's spokespersons, and fancily carve/decorate good people's graves.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dule = ukir"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">dule = ukir</Message></Annotation><v n="30" />Te ngaa miu peka na, &lt;Sèmi ji'i se mamuri tèu èci èèna ka dènge bèi-baki ji'i, tatu ji'i madhutu boe pamadhe dhèu dhu rèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua sèra.&gt;<bt>But you say, &lt;Supposing we lived at the same time/age with our ancestors, surely we would not have participated in killing God's spokespersons.&gt;</bt><v n="31" />Dènge j'ara ne'e, miu unu mi bhoke rahasia miu, na, miu bhelu èci èèna ka dènge bèi-baki miu.<bt>In that way, you yourselves have revealed your secret, that you are also evil the same as your ancestors.</bt><v n="32" />De la'a, sina ma. Miu tao taruu la bhabhelu toke d'ai èle, madhutu tatao bèi-baki mi!<bt>So (consequently) just get on with it (idiomatic). Keep doing evil like that until it's finished, following your ancestors deeds!</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="33" />Miu tare'a-re'a bhelu-katub'a, èci èèna ka dènge mege dhu dènge raco. Miu pangee, na, Ama Lamatua huku boe miu? Aad'o! Tatu Na pèci miu asa d'ara ai naraka!<bt>You here are really evil (doublet) the same as poisonous snakes. Do you think God won't punish you? No! Surely He will throw you away into hell fire!</bt><v n="34" />Sanèd'e paie! Pe Ja'a pua ana madhutu Ja'a mai, ho ra aj'a-nori dènge pad'elo miu j'ara mamuri Lamatua dhu lèke. Te ngaa èèna na miu pamadhe cahag'e, aa cahag'e hari miu paku pamadhe si ètu aj'u palolo-palèbha. Abhu kahèi dhu miu hake-paru si ètu d'ara èmu-èmu sabaj'a, aa abhu cahag'e kahèi miu paj'èra si toke ra rai nèti kota èci asa kota leo.<bt>Listen carefully! Later I will send you My followers, so they teach (doublet) and show you the Lord's life path/way which is correct/true/ right. But later you will kill some of them, and nail kill some others of them on *crossed wood (doublet). There are also some you will whip/slap (doublet) in the (various) worship houses, and some you will torture until they run/flee from one city to the next.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hake-paru = beat"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">hake-paru = beat</Message></Annotation><v n="35" />Lod'o uru sèra, bèi-baki miu pamadhe Habel. Masi ka nèngu ne, d'ara dhu mola. Bèi-baki miu dhu loe boe pamadhe dhèu dhu d'ara mola nèti lai ana-lai èpu. Toke d'ai Sakaria, ana nèti Barakia. Ra pamadhe ne ètu madha Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i padètu dènge mei korban. Lula miu madhutu bhabhelu bèi-baki mi, nèti èèna ka miu hud'i tago mere raa nèti dhèu dhu d'ara mola se'e.<bt>[CHECK /lai ana-lai èpu/] Long ago your ancestors killed Habel. Even though he [was] a person whose insides are straight (=just/righteous). Your ancestors didn't stop killing (=repeatedly) straight/righteous people from one generation to the next generation. Until Sakaria, who was Barakia's child. They killed him in the yard of the Temple near the sacrifice table. Because you follow that evil of your ancestors, that's why you must carry/bear responsibility for the blood of these straight insided people (=righteous people).</bt><v n="36" />Mema lèke tare'a! Te miu ana lod'o limuri ne, bèli-camèd'a abhu huku lula j'ara-j'ara bhabhelu dhu bèi-baki miu ad'u-ue karèi nèti uru ka mai.&gt;&gt;<bt>That's true! Cuz (elaboration) you who are here now, later will be punished because of all those evil things which your ancestors did long ago.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">D'ara Yesus susa lula tatao dhèu Yerusalem<bt>Lord Yesus is troubled because of the deeds/behaviour/character of the people of Yerusalem</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Lukas 13:34-35)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="37" />&lt;&lt;Hee, miu dhèu Yerusalem! Miu dhu loe boe pamadhe dhèu-dhèu rèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua, aa pèci pamadhe dhèu pajuu-paleha Na dhu mai soru-bara miu. Ja'a ke'a boe roca pamako miu, sèna ka lèpa mai asa Ja'a ne, nuka sèmi manu rena dhu bhiri-sarobho ana na ètu d'ara èla na. Te ngaa miu pusi-pahae boe Ja'a.<bt>&lt;&lt;Hee you-pl people of Yerusalem! You-pl are the ones who repeatedly kill God's spokespersons, and stones to death emmissaries/envoys who come to help (doublet) you. I tirelessly try to persuade/coax you to come to Me, like a mother chicken who covers/protects her children under her wings. But you don't care (doublet) about Me.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bhiri-sarobho = cover-protect"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">bhiri-sarobho = cover-protect</Message></Annotation><v n="38" />Nèti èèna ka, Lamatua pusi-pahae heka dènge èmu miu. Ka bèli-camèd'a, èmu èèna dhèu pea heka ètu d'ara.<bt>Because of that, God2 no longer cares anymore about your-pl house/s. Then2 in the future in that house people will no longer stay inside [it].</bt><v n="39" />Nanene paie-iie! Te bèli-camèd'a miu mèdhi heka Ja'a toke d'ai lod'o na, miu mangaku, peka na, &lt;Èdhi manèngi sèna ka Ama Lamatua pala-bagi mamèngi-nale mi Dhèu ne'e, lula Lamatua ka dhu pua Na mai.&gt; Miu mangaku sèmi èèna, heka mèdhi hari Ja'a kèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>Listen carefully! Cuz (elaboration) you-pl won't see Me anymore, until the day/time when you acknowledge, saying, &lt;We-inc request God to give blessing to this Person, because God2 is the one who sent/commissioned Him.&gt; You will acknowledge/ confess like.that [first], before you will see Me again.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus peka tèke gaguri Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i<bt>The Lord Yesus tells ahead of time about the Temple's destruction/collapse</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 13:1-2; Lukas 21:5-6)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="24" />
      <v n="1" />Ka Yesus neo tèke eele Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i. Ropa Na kalua, ana madhutu Na mai paj'uj'u babe'a Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i ne.<bt>Then2 Yesus wanted to leave the Temple. When He went out, His followers came pointing to/out that Temple's goodness.</bt><v n="2" />Te ngaa Yesus peka dènge ra, na, &lt;&lt;Èmu ne, mema saraga. Te ngaa nanene, ee! Nèbhu heka dhèu mai paguri eele aa'i hadhu se.&gt;&gt;<bt>But Yesus told them, saying, &lt;&lt;This House is really beautiful! But listen, ee! Not much longer (=soon), people will completely knock over all these stones.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ata = sisa"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">ata = sisa</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ata boe cue sa."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">ata boe cue sa.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus peka tèke, na, bèli-camèd'a ana madhutu Na paraga dènge j'aj'èra<bt>The Lord Yesus tells that, later His followers will encounter/experience suffering</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 13:3-13; Lukas 21:7-19)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Hèia Yesus la'e madhèdi asa ledhe Saitun. Ka ana madhutu Na mai padhai lii mesa ra dènge Ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Peka hari ku laa, lii padhai Ama deo na. J'aj'aj'i na pèri lod'o? Mamai hari Ama na lod'o mia? Aa tadha-tadha na tasamia? Tasamia kahèi dènge lod'o èle rai-haha?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus went to sit at Saitun mountain. Then2 His followers came in.order.for them to speak alone with Him, saying, &lt;&lt;Father! Please tell again that talking of Father's earlier. When will it happen? Father's return will be when? And its (various) signs, are how? How also with the end of the world?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Ka Yesus dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;J'aga paie mamuri miu, sèna ka dhèu baku kapod'e-kabèli miu.<bt>Then Yesus replied, saying, &lt;&lt;Guard your-pl lives, so that people don't decieve (doublet) you.</bt><v n="5" />Te bèli-camèd'a dhèu ae mai tèb'a kakara, peka na, &lt;Ja'a ne, Kristus, Dhèu dhu Ama Lamatua padhadha karèi nèti uru ka.&gt; Dènge j'ara ne, rèngu monya dhèu ae.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) later there will be many people who come beating their chest (=bragging), saying, &lt;I here, am Kristus, the Person whom God promised from long ago.&gt; In doing that, they will decieve many people.</bt><v n="6" />Ladhe miu mèdhi ka, dhèu pamusu, do, tadèngi lii palolo dhèu papara-pakèj'i ètu mia-mia, na, miu baku madha'u kahèi. Te j'ara se'e se, hud'i j'aj'i uuru ku, te ngaa lod'o èle rai-haha ne dhae d'ai mèka.<bt>If/when you see people warring, or, you hear news that there is war/fighting (doublet) all over the place, na, you don't need to be afraid. Cuz (elaboration) things such as those, must happen first, but the end of the world has not yet arrived.</bt><v n="7" />Dhèu nèti ca suku, èèna na pamusu dènge suku leo. Negara èci pamusu, lab'a negara leo. Ètu mia-mia abhu rai opo, aa manganga-mad'èu dhu kapai titu kèna.<bt>[CHECK manganga-madèu] Later one ethnic.group will war with another ethnic.group. One country (loan) will war opposing another country. There will be earthquakes all over the place, and also very severe hunger (doublet) seasons (=famines)!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="manganga-madèu = sangat lapar (or miskin)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">manganga-madèu = sangat lapar (or miskin)</Message></Annotation><v n="8" />Te ngaa sèra sa, heka tadha partama kèna, dhu peka na, lod'o èle rai-haha dètu ae le. Èèna nuka sèmi bhèni dhu mulai kabake pèd'a neo nara iisi.<bt>But all those, are just the first signs which tells that, the end of the world is already near. That is like a woman who begins to feel pain/sick in the abdomen about to give birth.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />De miu hud'i j'aga paie ku ngi'u miu! Te bèli-camèd'a dhèu mai paj'èra dènge pamadhe miu. Aa dhèu nèti suku aa'i-aa'i, èèna na d'èi boe miu, lula miu madhutu Ja'a.<bt>So (consequently), you must guard yourselves well! Cuz (elaboration) later people will come torture you, and kill you. And people from all ehtnic.groups will not like you (no lexeme for hate), because you follow Me.</bt><note reference="24:9" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 10:22</note><v n="10" />Taa èèna, dhèu ae ka dhu soro kabodho dènge ro'o heka madhutu Ja'a. Rèngu panasa èci dènge èci, aa èci pahie èci.<bt>At that time2, many people will turn their backs and not want to follow Me anymore. They will be angry with each other, and sell (=betray) each other.</bt><v n="11" />Èèna na abhu dhèu dhu tema leko-monya se, peka na, rèngu dhèu rèti lii padhai Lamatua. Ka dhèu ae ka dhu lèka si.<bt>Later there will be habitual decievers who say they are God2's spokespersons. And many people will believe2 them.</bt><v n="12" />Bèli-camèd'a bhabhelu dhèu asa tabha, toke dhèu re'a heka pasue èci dènge èci.<bt>Later people's evilness will increase, to the point that people do not love each other anymore.</bt><v n="13" />Te ngaa dhèu dhu taha taruu toke madhe, tatu Ama Lamatua pala hia ne mamuri.<bt>But the person who endures continually until death, God will certainly save him/her.</bt><note reference="24:13" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 10:22</note><v n="14" />Te dhèu hud'i palolo pale-lème ku Lii Lolo Be'a Ama Lamatua, toke suu-suu rai d'ai ro'a kakilu ètu rai-haha ne, sèna ka dhèu aa'i-aa'i re'a mèu j'ara mamuri Lamatua. Èle èèna ku, rai-haha ne heka èle kèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>Cuz (elaboration) people must go tell all around God's Good News, reaching the world's corners and nooks (literary doublet), so that all people can clearly know God2's live path/way. After that, only then the end of the world will come.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus peka mema, bèli-camèd'a dhèu bhelu-katub'a èci mai pa'ele iie dhèu parcaya<bt>The Lord Yesus tells beforehand that an evil person will come to destroy believers</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 13:14-23; Lukas 21:20-24)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Yesus padhai lii hari, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Daniel, ca dhèu nèti dhèu rèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua, dhu suri tèke le, peka na, bèli-camèd'a dhèu èci dhu bhelu-katub'a risi eele mai. Èèna na maso titu ètu era laluri ètu d'ara Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i Ama Lamatua. Dènge j'ara ne, nèngu pahera eele era ne'e. Nèti èèna ka, Ama Lamatua soro kabodho tèke eele era ne'e. De ropa miu mèdhi ka sèmi èèna, na mi pajiko paie-iie ka! (Dhèu cee dhu baca sasuri ne'e hud'i pajiko paie-iie ku!)<bt>Yesus continued speaking, saying, &lt;&lt;God's spokesperson Daniel has written that in the future about a person who is excessively evil will come. He will enter and stand in the taboo place in God's Temple. In doing so, he will defile that place. That's why God will turn his back and leave that place. So (consequently), when you see like that, be really careful! (Whoever reads this writing here, must consider carefully!)</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="era laluri ; pahera eele ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z" status="Anyone">era laluri ; pahera eele = bekin kamomos/kotor</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pahera "><Message author="Chuck" created="2009-11-28 00:38:13Z" status="Anyone">pahera = pakaj'alu (both places and people</Message></Annotation><note reference="24:15" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Daniel 9:27, 11:31, 12:11</note><v n="16" />Te ne'e ne j'aj'i tadha dhu peka na, lod'o-lod'o j'aj'èra dètu ae le. Ropa mèdhi ka sèmi èèna, dhèu ètu propensi Yudea, rai ka asa ledhe.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) that becomes a sign saying, suffering days are very close. When you see like.that, people in Yudea province must run/flee to the mountains.</bt><v n="17" />Ladhe abhu dhèu dhu kalua nèti d'ara èmu le, na maso ia ka mere mèdha-panyau. Te ngaa rai dènge ka, sèna ka baku lèke mamadhe-mamopo.<bt>If there is a person who has gone out of the house, don't go home to get things/ belongings anymore. Just run immediately to not be overcome by misfortune (doublet).</bt><v n="18" />Dhèu ètu d'ara oka, lèpa ia ka mere mèdha-papake mi. Te ngaa rai dènge ka!<bt>A person in the garden, don't go back to get warm clothes anymore. Just flee immediately!</bt><note reference="24:17-18" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lukas 17:31</note><v n="19" />Dhu j'èra risi ka, ina dhu dènge babia, aa ina-ina dhu pasusu ana dhu heka rara iisi hiu sèra. Te rèngu se bisa boe rai pamèri.<bt>The ones who will suffer most, are the women who are pregnant, and the mothers who are nursing red children (=newborns). Cuz (elaboration) they can't run fast.</bt><v n="20" />De hua iia miu sabaj'a, manèngi sèna ka lod'o j'aj'èra èèna mage lèke dènge hèru èj'i lai, do, lod'o ae sasab'a.<bt>So (consequently), it's better you pray and request that that those days of suffering don't happen during the rainy season, or happen on a day of stopping work/rest.</bt><v n="21" />Te lod'o èèna j'èra titu kèna! Karèi nèti Ama Lamatua paj'aj'i rai-haha ne, toke d'ai sange ne'e ne, dhèu dhae ladhe rèdhi mèka j'aj'èra dhu kapai sèmi èèna na. Aa èèna na, dhèu paraga heka dènge j'aj'èra dhu sèmi èèna.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) those days will be exceedingly extremely difficult! Beginning from when God make this world until now, people have not yet seen difficulty/trouble as big as that. And later people also will not encounter again difficulty like that.</bt><note reference="24:21" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Daniel 12:1, Rai-haha Rupa Hiu 7:14</note><v n="22" />Te ngaa miu oto kapai, te Ama Lamatua pab'ab'e lod'o èèna. Ladhe aad'o, na, abhu boe ca dhèu sa dhu bisa taha mamuri. Te ngaa, lula Ama Lamatua sue dhèu unu Na dhu hag'e nare sèra, nèti èèna ka Na pab'ab'e lod'o j'aj'èra sèra.<bt>But you are very fortunate, cuz (elaboration) God shortened those days. If not, there would not be even one person who could endure living. But, because God loves/pities His people whom He has chosen, that's why He shortened those difficult days.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Ladhe lod'o èèna d'ai ka, miu tadèngi dhèu, peka na, &lt;Ladhe ku la! Kristus ka ne'e!&gt; Aa dhèu leo peka na, &lt;Kristus ka nèi!&gt; Te ngaa baku miu parcaya!<bt>Later if/when those days have arrived, you will hear people saying, &lt;Look! Kristus is here!&gt; And other people saying, &lt;Kristus is there (remote)!&gt; But you don't believe it!</bt><v n="24" />Te èèna na, abhu dhèu mai tèb'a kakara, peka na, &lt;Ja'a ne, Kristus!&gt; Aa dhèu leo peka na, &lt;Ja'a ne, dhèu kèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua.&gt; Èèna na rèngu tao tadha malaa rupa-rupa, pake koasa nidhu, sèna ka kapod'e-kabèli dhèu. Dhèu se tenge j'ara ho dhèu unu Ama Lamatua sèra lèke tipu kahèi!<bt>Cuz (elaboration) later there will be people coming out beating their chests, saying, &lt;&lt;I here, am Kristus!&gt; And yet others who say, &lt;I here, am God's spokesperson.&gt; Later they do all kinds of miracles using evil.spirits power in.order.to decieve (doublet) people. These people will try so God's people also get decieved!</bt><v n="25" />De miu hud'i j'aga paie-iie mamuri miu! Lod'o-lod'o j'aj'èra se, dhae d'ai mèka, te ngaa Ja'a pasanèd'e mema le miu!<bt>So (consequently) you must guard your lives carefully! Those difficult days have not yet arrived, but I have reminded/warned you ahead.of.time!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Ladhe dhèu peka dènge miu, na, &lt;Kristus ètu le d'ara tana lapa nèi!&gt;, na baku lami kahèi. Aa ladhe abhu dhu peka na, &lt;Kristus nuka ètu d'ara èmu!&gt;, na, baku miu parcaya kahèi.<bt>If/when people tell you, saying, ‘Kristus is at the open field over there!’, na, you don't need to go there. And if there are those who say, ‘Kristus is in this house!’, na, you don't need to believe that either.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nuka here functions like sedang"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">nuka here functions like sedang</Message></Annotation><v n="27" />Te Ja'a ne, Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a. Bèli-camèd'a ladhe Ja'a mai hari asa rai-haha ne, dhèu aa'i-aa'i ladhe rèdhi Ja'a, nuka sèmi dhèu ladhe rèdhi bela kaha'a nèti dhimu asa haa.<bt>[CHECK /bela kaha'a/ order?] Cuz (elaboration) I here, [am] the Ideal/Prototypical Human. Later when I come back to this world, all people will see Me, just like people see lightning which flashes from the east side to the west side.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nèti dhimu asa haa"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">nèti dhimu asa haa</Message></Annotation><note reference="24:26-27" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lukas 17:23-24</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Ladhe Ja'a lèpa hari mai, pe miu me'a Ja'a ètu era mia. Nuka sèmi dhèu re'a na, ladhe dhèu rèdhi manu-bhui dhu tema ra'a sisi badha madhe, ra lela pa'oru ètu mia, na ra re'a èèna j'aj'i mi tadha, na, tatu abhu sisi hèu ètu era èèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>If/When I come back, later you will know where I am. Just like people know that, if they see corpse-eating birds flying gathered over one place, then that is a sign that there is certainly rotting meat there.&gt;&gt; [NOTE to daughter translations: compare with your wording in Luke 17:37.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Nuka sèmi dhèu re'a na, ladhe"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">Nuka sèmi dhèu re'a na, ladhe manu-bhui dhu ra'e sisi hèu ètu mia, tatu ètu era èèna abhu badha madhe.</Message></Annotation><note reference="24:28" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lukas 17:37</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus peka mamai hari Na<bt>The Lord Yesus tells about His coming back</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 13:24-27; Lukas 21:25-28)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="29" />Èle èèna ka, Yesus tuhu hari lii padhai Na, ho peka dènge ana madhutu Na sèra, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe oe èle ka lod'o j'aj'èra sèra,<bt>Then Yesus continued speaking, to tell His followers, saying, &lt;&lt;If/when those difficulty days are finished,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;Èèna na, madha lod'o maroga kiu-kiu,<bt>&lt;The sun will become pitch dark,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">hèru heo heka.<bt>the moon also will no longer shine.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Hua hètu-hua hètu kabhui nèti dedha-liru,<bt>[CHECK kabhui] Stars will fall from the sky (doublet),</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kabhui = jato (like fruit, barang"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">kabhui = jato (like fruit, barang yang tagantong)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">aa koasa-koasa ètu dedha-liru patogo èci dènge èci.&gt;<bt>and the powers in the sky (doublet) will become chaotic (banging into each other).&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="patogo = bertabrakan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">patogo = bertabrakan</Message></Annotation><note reference="24:29" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 13:10, 34:4, Yeskial 32:7, Yoel 2:10, 31, 3:15, Rai-haha Rupa Hiu 6:12-13</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="30" />Ka dhèu aa'i-aa'i ladhe rèdhi kahèi tadha ètu dedha-liru, dhu pad'elo, peka na, Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a neo mai hari kèna. Ropa rèdhi sèmi èèna, hèia suku aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha ne j'aj'i madha'u toke ra tangi. Te bèli-camèd'a Ja'a puru mai dènge ra'i-liru, heka rèngu ladhe rèdhi koasa dènge dadedha Ja'a kèna.<bt>Then2 all people will see sign/s in the sky (doublet), that show, the Ideal Human is going to/about to come back. Seeing like that, then all ethnic.groups on earth will become afraid to the point that they cry. Cuz (elaboration) later [when] I will come down by/with a cloud, then they will see My power and My high-ness (=glory).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="peka na, D"><Message author="From Merge" created="2009-12-01 09:34:36Z" status="Anyone">Merge Conflict: Original was "peka na, Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a neo mai hari kèna. Ropa rèdhi sèmi èèna, hèia suku aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha ne j'aj'i madha'u toke ra tangi. Te,"; Ours was "peka na, Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a neo mai hari kèna. Ropa rèdhi sèmi èèna, hèia suku aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha ne j'aj'i madha'u toke ra tangi. Te"; Theirs was "dhu padelo na, Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a neo mai hari kèna. Ropa rèdhi sèmi èèna, hèia suku aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha ne j'aj'i madha'u toke ra tangi. Te,"</Message></Annotation><note reference="24:30" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Daniel 7:13, Sakaria 12:10-14, Rai-haha Rupa Hiu 1:7</note><v n="31" />Ka Ja'a pake lii tèbhe dhu mèdhu ho pua ana-ana pajuu Ama Lamatua nèti sorga, sèna ka pakaboko rare dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu Ja'a kabhili kore le, nèti suu-suu rai-haha, nèti haa toke dhimu, nèti badae toke balèu.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then2 I will use the loud sound of a trumpte to send God's underlings from heaven, to2 go gather up all the people whom I have chosen from the world's ends, from west to the east; from the north to the south.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lod'o-lod'o j'aj'èra j'aj'i mi tadha mamai Lamatua Yesus [\s2]<bt>The difficult days are a sign of Lord Yesus' coming [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 13:28-31; Lukas 21:29-33)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="32" />&lt;&lt;Ja'a pakasame sèmi aj'u ca kapua. Ladhe rèu na mulai karara, tadha na, oe dètu hèru hadhu kèna.<bt>&lt;&lt;I compare it to a tree. If/When it's leaves begin to yellow, that is sign that the hot season (lit: rock season) is almost come.</bt><v n="33" />Sèmi èèna kahèi, ladhe miu mèdhi ka d'ai lod'o-lod'o j'aj'èra, nuka sèmi dhu Ja'a peka-padhai deo na, èèna tadha, na, mamai Ja'a dhu dètu iiki le.<bt>Like that also, when you see the difficult days come, like I told you just now, that is a sign saying I am almost coming.</bt><v n="34" />Nanene paie-iie! Nèti dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu mamuri loo-limuri ne, èèna na abhu cahag'e dhu dhae madhe mèka, te lod'o j'aj'èra se dhu j'aj'i le.<bt>Listen carefully! From all the people who live nowadays (doublet), later there will be some who have not yet died, when those difficult days have come.</bt><v n="35" />Masi ka liru dènge rai-haha ne ele, te ngaa lii padhai Ja'a ne ca lamusi sa bisa boe ele.&gt;&gt;<bt>Even if/though the sky and the earth disappear, nevertheless these words of Mine, not a single word will disappear.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus peka na, ca dhèu sa re'a boe lod'o mamai Nèngu [\s2]<bt>The Lord Yesus tells that, nobody knows the time of His coming [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 13:32-37; Lukas 17:26-30, 34-36)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="36" />&lt;&lt;Ca dhèu sa re'a boe pèri lod'o Ja'a mai hari. Ana pajuu Ama Lamatua ètu sorga re'a boe kahèi. Ja'a mesa ku ke'a boe kahèi. Dhodhoka Ama Ku mesa Na dhu ne'a.<bt>There is no person who knows when I come again. God's underlings in heaven, also don't know. I myself also don't know. Only just My Father himself knows.</bt><v n="37" />Te Ja'a ne, Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a. Bèli-camèd'a ropa Ja'a mai hari, nuka sèmi taa uru sèra, lod'o Noh mamuri era.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) I here, am the Ideal/Prototypical Human. Later when I come again, that will be like long ago when Noh was still alive.</bt><note reference="24:37" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 6:5-8</note><v n="38" />Èi aae dhae j'aj'i mèka lala, te ngaa dhèu-dhèu dhu ra'a-rinu, aa paleo èmu sèmi biasa. Dhèu sèra tao taruu sèmi èèna, toke Noh maso asa d'ara kapa aae èèna.<bt>(Even though) That big flood had not yet come, nevertheless people were eating drinking (doublet), and marrying each other as normal. They did like that continually up until Noh entered into that big boat/ship.</bt><v n="39" />Te ngaa ropa èi aae lala, hae nèti aa'i si, rèngu heka kabèdhi kèna, lula ngaa dhu j'aj'i sèra. Èci èèna ka dènge mamai Ja'a bèli-camèd'a.<bt>But when the flood came sweeping taking them, only then did they become aware about what was happening there. My coming later will be like that also.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hae nèti = bawa hanyut"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">hae nèti = bawa hanyut</Message></Annotation><note reference="24:39" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 7:6-24</note><v n="40" />Lod'o èèna, ladhe abhu dhèu dua ètu d'ara oka, cag'ag'a laa Ama Lamatua ded'e nèti ca dhèu, aa ca dhèu hari tèke eele.<bt>At that time, if two people are in a garden, suddenly/unexpectedly God will lift up take the one person, but the other will be left.</bt><v n="41" />Ladhe dhèu bhèni dhèu dua dhu maj'u are, kaca'a la Ama Lamatua ded'e nèti ca dhèu, aa ca dhèu hari tèke eele.<bt>If two women are pounding rice/grain, suddenly/unexpectedly God will lift up take the one, but the other will be left.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="maj'u are = tumbuk padi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">maj'u are = tumbuk padi</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="42" />Nèti èèna ka, miu hud'i bori pa'èra mema kahèi, te miu me'a boe pèri lod'o Lamatua miu lèpa hari mai.<bt>Because of that, you-p must watch/guard2 (idiom) constantly, cuz (elaboration) you don't know when your Master/Lord will come back.</bt><v n="43" />Pangee paie-iie! Ladhe lamatua èmu dhu ne'a mema, na, mèda none dhèu mana'u mai, tatu na pasaruru boe musi madha na, sèna ka dhèu mana'u baku maso asa d'ara èmu.<bt>Think carefully! If a house master/owner knows ahead of time that tonight a robber will come, surely he will not close his eyes the whole time, so that that robber doesn't come into his house.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mèda none = sabantar malam ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">mèda none = sabantar malam ; pasaruru = ngantuk, nap, baring-baring</Message></Annotation><v n="44" />Nèti èèna ka, miu hud'i pa'èra mema kahèi. Te mamai hari Ja'a èèna, dènge sahèka!&gt;&gt;<bt>Because of that you must also be ready/prepared ahead of time. Cuz (elaboration) that coming back of Mine, will be sudden/unexpected2.&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="24:43-44" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lukas 12:39-40</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus aj'a, peka na, dhèu sab'a hud'i madhutu taruu ku dad'èi lamatua na<bt>The Lord Yesus teaches that the worker must continually follow/obey the master's will</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Lukas 12:41-48)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="45" />Ka Yesus tuhu hari lii padhai Na, peka na, &lt;&lt;Miu hud'i j'aj'i ku nuka sèmi dhèu sab'a dhu madhutu dhodhoka dad'èi lamatua na. Te ladhe lamatua na neo la'e rai kaj'èu, na ded'e dhèu sab'a dhu sèmi èèna ku, ho uri nganga'a-nganginu hia isi èmu na.<bt>Then Yesus continued speaking, saying, &lt;&lt;You-p must become like a servant/worker who continually follows/obeys his master's will. Cuz (elaboration) if/when the master wants to go to a faraway land/country, he lifts/appoints a worker like that, to manage all his household's food-drink.</bt><v n="46" />Ladhe lamatua na lèpa, ladhe nèdhi dhèu sab'a na dhu sab'e dènge be'a, tatu na karej'e.<bt>If/when the master comes home, if he sees his worker is working well, surely he is happy.</bt><v n="47" />Parcaya la Ja'a, te bèli-camèd'a lamatua èmu hia dhèu sab'a ne koasa, sèna ka ladhe-leru mèdha-panyau na aa'i-aa'i.<bt>Believe Me, cuz (elaboration) later that house owner will give that servant authority to oversee (doublet) all of his possessions.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="48" />Te ngaa ladhe dhèu sab'a ne, dhèu bhelu, tatu na ngee ètu d'ara na,<bt>But if that worker is evil, surely he will think in his insides (=to himself), saying,</bt><v n="49" />&lt;Be'a kèna! Lamatua ja'a la'e le, de cee ne'a na pèri lod'o lèpa hari mai!&gt; Nèti ngangee sèmi ne'e ne, hèia na kalabhe dhèu sab'a leo sèra. Aa nèngu madhèdi na'a-ninu mau-mau bera-bera dènge dhèu mahu sèra.<bt>&lt;Good! My master has gone away, so who knows when he will return!&gt; From thinking like that, then he begins to beat the other workers. And he sits eating-drinking luxuriously together with drunkards.</bt><v n="50" />Te ngaa dhu ne'a nare boe, na, cag'ag'a laa lamatua na lèpa hari mai.<bt>But unexpectedly, his master suddenly comes home.</bt><v n="51" />Hèia lamatua na capa paj'èra ne, ka core ne asa li'u, sèna ka na pa'èci dènge dhèu padhai lii leo, tao leo sèra. Ètu era ne'e, dhèu aa'i-aa'i ra tangi d'ara pèd'a, lula ra j'èra d'ai seli.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then his master causes him great suffering, then throws him outside, so he joins together with the hypocrites (Lit: those who say one thing and do another). In that place, they all cry wailing because they are suffering greatly.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="capa = (menyusahkan) very"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">capa = (menyusahkan) very</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus hia lii pakasame lula-nèti dhèu bhèni dhu tatae mamai dhèu mone dhu neo kab'i<bt>The Lord Yesus gives an example/comparison about the girls who wait the coming of the bridegroom</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="25" />
      <v n="1" />Èle èèna, hèia Yesus tuhu hari lii lula-nèti Ama Lamatua nèd'u paredha, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Miu hud'i bori mema-mema ho soru mamai Ja'a, nuka sèmi lii pakasame ne. Sèmi ne'e: ca tèka dhèu bhèni dhèu canguru dhu kalua re mèda, lasi soru broit dhèu mone, rèti dènge labhu èi mènyi asa èmu angalai ra.<bt>After that, then Yesus continued speaking about God's rule/kingdom, saying, &lt;&lt;You-p must be prepared to meet/greet My coming, the same as in this example here. It's like this: one time, there were ten girls who went out at night to go greet a bridegroom, bringing their lamps to their friend's house.</bt><note reference="25:1" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lukas 12:35</note><v n="2" />Te ngaa nèti rèngu canguru dhèu se, abhu lèmi dhu goa, aa lèmi dhu d'èlu-mèu.<bt>But from those ten people, there were five who were stupid, and five who were smart/wise/intelligent.</bt><v n="3" />Lèmi dhu goa se, rèti boe èi mènyi dhu risi.<bt>The five who were stupid, forgot to bring extra oil.</bt><v n="4" />Te ngaa lèmi dhu d'èlu-mèu se, rèti parisi.<bt>But the five who were smart, had brought it extra.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="parisi = lebe"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">parisi = lebe</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />D'ai èmu, broit dhèu mone dhae mai mèka. Nèbhu-nèbhu ka, dhèu bhèni se musi madha ra sakaa, hèia ra bhèj'i luu titu kèna.<bt>Arriving at that house, that bridegroom had not come yet (implies he was late or something). Eventually those girls eyeballs were heavy (=drowsy), and they fell soundly asleep.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Re'a rare boe te, d'ai talora mèda sa, hèia tadèngi lii pa'oo, peka na, &lt;Wee! Broit mai le! Mai lati soru ne!&gt;<bt>&lt;&lt;Unexpectedly in the middle of the night, then they heard people calling out, saying, &lt;Wee! The bridegroom has come! Let's go greet/meet him!&gt;</bt><v n="7" />Ropa ra tadèngi, hèia dhèu bhèni se kèd'i ka. Ka ra kèpe ka labhu ra èci-èci.<bt>Hearing like that, then those girls got up. Then2 each of them prepared their lamps.</bt><v n="8" />Te ngaa dhèu bhèni dhu goa se, peka dènge bhèni aanga ra, aku rèngu na, &lt;Angalai, ee! Bagi hia ji'i èi mènyi miu ciki la, te labhu ji'i di ruru-ruru kèna!&gt;<bt>But those stupid girls spoke to their friends saying, &lt;Friends, ee! Divide/give a little oil to us, cuz (elaboration) our lamps are almost out here!&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ruru = suram-suram (about to go"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">ruru = suram-suram (about to go out)</Message></Annotation><v n="9" />Te ngaa dhèu bhèni dhu d'èlu-mèu se dhaa, aku rèngu na, &lt;Irii! Baku nasa, te bisa boe. Te èi mènyi ji'i d'ai boe èdhi aa'i-aa'i ti! De be'a risi lami hèli ètu era dhu pahia èi mènyi.&gt;<bt>But those smart girls replied, saying, &lt;Irii! [+objection] Don't get angry (=sorry) but can't do. Cuz (elaboration) our oil here is not enough for all of us! So (consequently) it's better if you just go buy it some place where they sell oil.&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="èi mènyi rai = kerosene"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">èi mènyi rai = kerosene</Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Hèia lasi ka hèli èi mènyi. Te ngaa ropa rèngu lasi, broit dhu d'ai le. Ka dhèu bhèni dhu d'èlu-mèu se, lasi ka asa d'ara pesta, palere-lere dènge broit dènge tamu aa'i-aa'i ra. Ropa rèngu aa'i-aa'i d'ai d'ara, ka ra bèdho èmu.<bt>Then they went to buy oil. But when they were gone, that bridegroom arrived. Then2 those girls who were smart went into the feast/party place, together with the bridegroom and all the guests. When they all entered inside, then they shut the door.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Hèia dhèu bhèni dhèu lèmi dhu goa se, lèpa mai. Ka ra paroa peka na, &lt;Ama! Ama! Conge ku èmu hia ji'i la!&gt;<bt>Then those stupid girls came back. They called out, saying, &lt;Father! Father! Please open the door for us-exc!&gt;</bt><v n="12" />Te ngaa ama ne dhaa, aku nèngu na, &lt;Wee, bisa boe, te miu se cee, ja'a tadhe boe!&gt;<bt>But that father answered, saying, &lt;Wee, can't do, cuz (elaboration) I don't know who you are!&gt;</bt><note reference="25:11-12" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lukas 13:25</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Nèti èèna ka, miu hud'i pa'èra taruu, te miu me'a boe kahèi, lod'o do hake pèri Ja'a lèpa hari mai.&gt;&gt;<bt>Because of that, you must be prepared continually, cuz (elaboration) you also do not know what day or what hour is My coming back.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus pake lii pakasame lula-nèti dhèu sab'a dhu uri doi-dhari lamatua na<bt>The Lord Yesus gives an example about the worker/servant who manages his master's money</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Lukas 19:11-27)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Ka Yesus peka hari lii pakasame èci, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ropa Ja'a tèke eele miu, na, miu hud'i sab'a paie-iie hia Ja'a, nuka sèmi lii pakasame ne: abhu lamatua ca dhèu neo pakèd'i la'e asa rai kaj'èu. Ropa na pa'èra neo la'e, hèia na paroa nare dhèu-dhèu sab'a na, ka na paredha si, aku nèngu na, &lt;Miu pake doi ne, tao mi poko. Ladhe ja'a lèpa mai, miu pad'elo dènge ja'a, miu abhu leto ca ngaa.&gt;<bt>Then Yesus added another example, saying, &lt;&lt;If/When I have left you, you must work hard for Me, the same as this example here: there was a master/owner wanting to go to a far land/country. When he was ready to go, he called his workers/servants, then2 he ordered them, saying, &lt;You-pl use this money as (financial) capital (initial seed money). When I come home, you must show me how much profit you have gained.&gt; [NOTE: Dhao men are goldsmiths, and boat builders, so they have words for capital, and profit.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="poko = modal awal ; leto"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">poko = modal awal ; leto = keuntungan = oto (bunga) ; ca ngaa = berapa?</Message></Annotation><v n="15" />Ka na pabagi doi hualaa mi dhèu sab'a ka èci, lèmi saku,<bt>Then he gave his first worker/servant five bags of gold money, [EXEG: See LN, BAGD, NRSV note for value. Follows NLT text.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kanoto = tampa sirih laki-laki (tas"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">kanoto = tampa sirih laki-laki (tas yg gantong) ; kapepe nana = tampa sirih perempuan ; juru = doi hualaa, gold sovereign, sofren</Message></Annotation><note reference="25:15" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Lii Yunani ètu ne'e, suri peka na, lèmi τάλαντον (<span class="Italic">talanton</span>). Talanton èci na, nuka sèmi gaji ca dhèu tuka d'ara 15 tèu. De lèmi talanton èèna, gaji 75 tèu.<bt>The Yunani language here says, five τάλαντον (<span class="Italic">talanton</span>). One of those talanton, is equal to a craftsman's wages for 15 years. So (consequently) five talanton, is 75 years of wages.</bt></note>sèna ka pab'unge ne. Dhèu sab'a ka dua abhu doi dua saku, aa ka tèlu abhu doi ca saku, madhutu a'èra rèngu èci-èci ra. Ka lamatua ne pakèd'i la'e ka.<bt>in.order.for him to make a yield/gain on that money. Next, he gave the second worker/ servant two sacks, and the third got one sack, according to each one's ability. Then2 the master left.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Ropa sèmi rare doi ne, hèia dhèu sab'a ka èci la'e dènge d'aga. Nèbhu boe, na abhu leto doi lèmi saku hari.<bt>Receiving/Accepting that money, then that first worker/servant went out straight away to go trade. Not long, he had gained a profit of five more sacks of money.</bt><v n="17" />Sèmi èèna kahèi dènge dhèu sab'a ka dua. Na abhu leto, doi dua saku hari.<bt>Like that also with the second worker/servant. He gained a profit of two more sacks of money.</bt><v n="18" />Te ngaa dhèu sab'a ka tèlu dhu abhu doi ca saku deo na, la'e kèi ro'a ka na padhènu doi lamatua na asa d'ara.<bt>But the third worker/servant who recieved that one sack of money, he went to dig a hole to bury that money of his master.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="padhènu = kubur, timbun, tutup"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">padhènu = kubur, timbun, tutup</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Nèbhu ae ku, heka lamatua rèngu lèpa. Hèia na paroa dhèu sab'a na sèra, ho parisa doi na, dhu na hia si uri.<bt>After a long time, that master came home. Then he summoned his workers/servants to examine his money which he had given them to manage.</bt><v n="20" />Dhèu sab'a ka èci, la'e ka saraka doi canguru saku, ka na peka, &lt;Ama! Doi ama ka ne'e. Ca hari ni, ama hia ja'a doi lèmi saku. Te ngaa limuri ne, ja'a abhu leto lèmi saku kahèi.&gt;<bt>That first worker/servant entered and handed over ten sacks of money saying, &lt;Father! Here is father's money. Before father gave me five sacks of money. But now, I have gained a profit of five more sacks.&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Ropa lamatua na tadèngi, hèia na karej'e. Ka na peka, na, &lt;Be'a! Èu ne dhèu sab'a dhu be'a. Èu ne maj'èni, aa d'èi madhutu taruu lii paredha ja'a, masi ka ja'a aad'o. Lula èu ne bisa uri dhu ciki sèmi ne'e, de èèna na ja'a ded'e èu sèna ka uri j'ara dhu kapai aae hari. Pe ja'a tao pesta, sèna ka ta'a-tinu sama-sama.&gt;<bt>Hearing like that then, that master was happy. And he said, &lt;Good! You here are a good worker/servant. You have been diligent and you have followed continually my commands, even though I wasn't here. Because you can manage small things like this, so (consequently) later I will elevate/ appoint you to manage things which are even bigger/greater. Later I will make a feast so we-inc can feast/celebrate together.&gt; [EXEG: “small matters” here is understatement.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Èle ka, dhèu sab'a ka dua, la'e saraka mi lamatua na, doi èpa saku, ka na peka na, &lt;Ama! Ca hari ni, ama hia ja'a doi dua saku. Te ngaa ladhe ku la, ja'a abhu leto dua saku kahèi.&gt;<bt>Then, the second worker/servant came and handed over his master's four sacks of money, and said, &lt;Father! Previously father gave me two sacks of money. Now look, I have gained a profit of two more sacks.&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Ka lamatua ne karej'e kahèi, ka na peka na, &lt;Be'a! Èu ne dhèu sab'a dhu be'a kahèi. Èu ca dhèu dhu maj'èni, aa madhutu taruu lii paredha ja'a, masi ka ja'a aad'o. Lula èu bisa uri dhu ciki sèmi ne'e ne, de èèna na ja'a ded'e èu ho uri dhu kapai hari. Pe ja'a tao pesta, sèna ka ta'a-tinu sama-sama.&gt;<bt>That master was also happy, and he said, &lt;Good! You here are a good worker/servant. You are diligent and you have followed continually my commands, even though I wasn't here. Because you can manage small things like this, later I will appoint you to manage things which are even bigger/greater. Later I will make a feast so we-inc can eat/celebrate together.&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Èle èèna ka, dhèu sab'a ka tèlu, la'e peka dènge lamatua na, aku nèngu na, &lt;Ama! Ja'a ke'a na, ama ca dhèu dhu d'ara adhu. Te ama more ngaa dhu dhèu leo tao, aa puu more ngaa dhu dhèu leo sèle.<bt>[CHECK dara adhu in this context.] After that the third worker/servant came, reporting to his master, saying, &lt;Father! I know father (=you) are a person with hard insides (=strict/severe). Cuz (elaboration) father takes what other people do, and picks that which other people plant.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dara adhu = hati karas"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">dara adhu = hati karas</Message></Annotation><v n="25" />Ka ja'a madha'u, mage doi se ele, hèia ama huku ja'a. Nèti èèna ka, ja'a huni paie-iie ne. Ka se'e, ama! De more hari ka, te doi ama se, kura boe ca ana ma sa!&gt;<bt>I was afraid lest this money disappear, then father would punish me. That's why I hid it carefully. Here it is, father! Take it back, cuz (elaboration) father's money here is not missing a single coin!&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="huni = vt @@GRAMMAR"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">huni = vt @@GRAMMAR</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Ropa lamatua ne tadèngi nare, hèia na jèke dhèu sab'a ne, aku nèngu na, &lt;Wee, èu ne dhèu sab'a dhu bhelu aa bai-eed'a! Èu dhu me'a, na, ja'a kore ngaa dhu dhèu leo tao, aa puu kore ngaa dhu dhèu leo sèle,<bt>Hearing like that then that master scolded the worker/servant saying, &lt;Wee, you here are a worker/servant who is evil and lazy (doublet)! [If] You know that I take what other people do, and pick that which other people plant,</bt><v n="27" />nga tao ka èu lamu boe tèke doi ne mi bank? Sèna ka ropa ja'a lèpa, ja'a kore bunga na, masi ka ciki oo'e, ngaa-ngaa tao boe!&gt;<bt>why did you not just go save my money in the bank (loan)? So when I came home, I could get it's interest (lit: flower), even a little bit, would be good!&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bang = bank"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">bang = bank</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Ka lamatua ne pua dhèu sab'a dhu leo sèra, aku nèngu na, &lt;Mere doi nèti nèngu ne, ho hia mi dhèu sab'a dhu abhu leto lèmi saku èèna.<bt>Then2 that master ordered his other workers/servant, saying, &lt;Take that money from him, and give it to the worker/servant who gained a profit of those five sacks of money.</bt><v n="29" />Te dhèu dhu uri paie-iie ngaa dhu ètu adhe-aai na, èèna na, na abhu ae hari. Te ngaa dhèu dhu ro'o boe uri ngaa dhu ètu d'ara adhe-aai na, èèna na rare aa'i nèti nèngu.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) a person who manages well what s/he already holds in his hand, later s/he will get even more again. But a person who does not want to manage what s/he already has in his hand, later they will take that all from him/her.</bt><note reference="25:29" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 13:12, Markus 4:25, Lukas 8:18</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="30" />Kèpe mere dhèu sab'a dhu guna boe ne. Nuni pa'oro ne, pèci asa li'u nèi. Soro tèke ne, sèna ka na tangi, aa dui nare j'aj'èra ètu era maroga aatu-aatu nèi!&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>Capture this worker/servant who does not have any use here. Pull drag and pick him up throw him away outside (remote). Leave him so he cries and bears suffering in that dark place (remote)!&gt;&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="25:14-30" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lukas 19:11-27, Mateos 8:12, 22:13, Lukas 13:28</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus lole a'èle rai-haha, dènge lod'o Nèngu neo j'ue lii langu dhèu aa'i-aa'i<bt>The Lord Yesus describes the end of the world, and when He will decide all people's cases/litigations</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Ka Yesus tuhu hari lii padhai Na, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a, Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a ne, bèli-camèd'a puru mai dènge dadedha nèti Ama Ku, palere-lere dènge ana pajuu Na nèti sorga. Èle na Ja'a madhèdi ètu kadera paredha dhu dedha risi, sèna ka parisa mamuri dhèu aa'i-aa'i.<bt>Then2 Yesus continued speaking, saying, &lt;&lt;I, the Ideal/Prototypical Human here, later will come back down with My Father's high-ness/glory, together with His underlings from heaven. Then I will sit on My ruling chair which is very high (=status/authority) in.order.to examine all people's lives.</bt><note reference="25:31" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 16:27, 19:28</note><v n="32" />Bèli-camèd'a dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu mamuri rèdhi ètu rai-haha, mai asa madha Ja'a. Pe Ja'a hag'e si, nuka sèmi dhèu madhenga badha pacèri kahib'i-kalèbho nèti kahib'i-ka'ia, sèna ka j'aj'i mi dua kaboko.<bt>Later all the people who ever lived on earth, will come face Me. Then I will separate them out, like a shepherd separates sheep from goats, to become two groups.</bt><v n="33" />Dhèu-dhèu dhu mamuri madhutu dad'èi Ama Lamatua, Ja'a hia si re g'ana Ja'a. Te ngaa dhu leo sèra, Ja'a hia si re kariu Ja'a.<bt>[CHECK last sentence w/UNS] People who live according to God's will, I will put on My right side. But those others, I will give (?) on My left side.</bt><v n="34" />Lod'o èèna, Ja'a kèd'u paredha nuka sèmi Dhèu Aae. Èèna na dhèu-dhèu ètu g'ana Ja'a, Ja'a peka dènge rèngu, na, &lt;Miu se'e se, ka dhu abhu mèngi-nale nèti Ama Ku. Mai lati asa d'ara èmu Na, dhu Na tao tèke hia miu, karèi nèti uru ka.<bt>At that time, I will hold rule/govern like a King. Later I will tell those people who are on My right side, saying, &lt;You here are who will obtain/receive blessing from My Father. Come on into His house, which He has prepared ahead of time for you from the very beginning.</bt><v n="35" />Ja'a nèru miu, lula uru èèna lod'o Ja'a manganga, miu ka dhu panga'a Ja'a. Aa lod'o Ja'a koko kamango, miu ka hia Ja'a kinu. Ja'a mai nuka sèmi dhèu leo kara, te ngaa miu hia Ja'a manubha ètu d'ara èmu miu.<bt>I invite you, because previously when I was hungry, you are the ones who gave Me food. And when I was thirsty, you are the ones who gave Me drink. I came like an outsider/foreigner, but you are the ones who allowed Me to stay (temporarily) your homes.</bt><v n="36" />Ja'a dènge boe mèdha-papake, te ngaa miu ka dhu papake Ja'a. Ja'a ètu d'ara papèd'a-tarègu, te ngaa miu ka dhu lalau-lalo'o Ja'a. Ja'a ètu d'ara bèdho, aa miu ka dhu mai pa'asu-pareo dènge Ja'a.&gt;<bt>I did not have clothes, but you are the ones who clothed Me. I was sick (doublet), but you are the ones who took care of (doublet) Me. I was in jail, and you are the ones who came and visited (doublet) Me.&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="37" />Ropa dhèu-dhèu ètu sebhe g'ana Ja'a se tadèngi lii Ja'a ne, ra dhaa peka na, &lt;Lamatua, ne'e ne tasamia kèna? Lamatua peka na, Lamatua manganga, ka ji'i panga'a. Lamatua koko kamango, ka ji'i hia minu.<bt>When the people on My right side hear what I am saying, they will respond, saying, &lt;Lord, how is this? Lord says Lord was hungry, then we fed (You). Lord was thirsty, then2 we gave drink.</bt><v n="38" />Lamatua sèmi dhèu leo kara, ka ji'i hia manubha ètu d'ara èmu ji'i. Lamatua dènge boe mèdha-papake, ka ji'i papake Lamatua.<bt>Lord was like an outsider/foreigner, then we allowed (You) to stay in our homes. Lord did not have clothing, then we clothed Lord (=You).</bt><v n="39" />Lamatua pèd'a, ka ji'i lalau-lalo'o Lamatua, Lamatua ètu d'ara bèdho, ka ji'i dhiu pa'asu-pareo. Te ngaa j'ara se'e se, lod'o mia ka dhu ji'i tao mi Lamatua?&gt;<bt>Lord was sick, then we went to take care (doublet) of Lord. Lord was in jail, then we went to visit (doublet). But, when did we do all those things to Lord?&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="40" />Pe Ja'a dhaa si, peka na, &lt;Parcaya la Ja'a! Te lod'o miu tao j'ara se'e se mi dhèu unu Ja'a, masi ka tao mi dhèu dhu haha d'ai seli èèna ka, sèra sa miu tao le mi dedha Ja'a kahèi!&gt;<bt>Later I will reply to them, saying, &lt;Believe Me! Cuz (elaboration) when you did things like that to My people, even to people who are lowest/most insignificant, you were also doing it to/for Me!&gt; [EXEG: “my brothers” -NRSV members of my family, NLT my bro &amp; sis, CEV my people]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="41" />Èle èèna, dhèu-dhèu dhu ètu sebhe kariu Ja'a, Ja'a peka dènge rèngu, na, &lt;Hee, dhèu bhelu-katub'a! Ama Lamatua dhu dhoo le miu. Pakaj'èu nèti ne'e ne! Pe Ja'a paredha dhèu mai kèpe miu, sèna ka pèci asa d'ara ai naraka dhu heo robhe-robhe. Te Ama Lamatua dhu sadia nare le era j'aj'èra ne, hia mi nidhu dènge dhèu aae ra.<bt>After that, I will tell those people on My left side, saying, &lt;Hee, evil (doublet) people! God has cursed (doublet) you. Get away from here! Later I will command people to arrest/catch you and throw you away into hell fire which burns with ever ending. Cuz (elaboration) God has prepared that suffering place there, for the evil.spirits and their king.</bt><v n="42" />Ja'a babège eele miu, lula lod'o Ja'a manganga, miu hia boe Ja'a ku'a. Aa lod'o Ja'a koko kamango, miu hia boe Ja'a kinu.<bt>I am expelling you, because when I was hungry, you did not give Me to eat. And when I was thirsty, you did not give Me to drink.</bt><v n="43" />Ja'a mai nuka sèmi dhèu leo kara, te ngaa miu soru boe Ja'a asa d'ara èmu mi. Ja'a dènge boe mèdha-papake, te ngaa miu papake boe Ja'a. Lod'o Ja'a pèd'a-tarègu, miu lalau-lalo'o boe Ja'a. Ja'a ètu d'ara bèdho, te ngaa miu pa'asu-pareo boe Ja'a sa kahèi.&gt;<bt>I came like an outsider/foreigner, but you did not welcome Me into your house. I did not have clothes, but you did not clothe Me. I was sick (doublet), but you did not come take care of (doublet) Me. I was in jail, but you did not come visit Me.&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="44" />Ropa dhèu bhelu-katub'a se tadèngi lii Ja'a sèmi èèna, hèia ra b'ala, peka na, &lt;Lamatua ne tasamia kèna? Lamatua peka na, Lamatua manganga, te ngaa ji'i hia boe mu'a. Lamatua koko kamango, te ngaa ji'i hia boe minu. Lamatua nuka sèmi dhèu leo kara, te ngaa ji'i ngo'o boe hia manubha ètu d'ara èmu ji'i. Lamatua dènge boe mèdha-papake, te ngaa ji'i papake boe. Lamatua ètu d'ara papèd'a-tarègu, te ngaa ji'i lalau-lalo'o boe. Lamatua ètu d'ara bèdho, te ngaa ji'i pa'asu-pareo boe. Te ngaa j'ara se'e se, ji'i tao mi Lamatua lod'o mia?&gt;<bt>Hearing like that, later those evil (doublet) people will respond, saying, &lt;Lord, how can this be? Lord says Lord was hungry, but we did not give to eat. Lord was thirsty, but we did not give to drink. Lord was like an outsider/foreigner, but we did not want to let you stay in our houses. Lord did have clothes, but we did not clothe (You). Lord was sick (doublet), but we did not go take care (doublet). Lord was in jail, but we did not go visit (doublet). But when did we do like that to Lord?&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="45" />Pe Ja'a dhaa mi rèngu, peka na, &lt;Parcaya la Ja'a! Te lod'o miu soru-bara boe dhèu-dhèu dhu haha ae d'ai seli, èci èèna ka dènge miu soru-bara boe Ja'a.&gt;<bt>I will reply to them, saying, &lt;Believe Me! Cuz (elaboration) when you did not help (doublet) the lowly/insignificant people, that was the same as if you did not help (doublet) Me.&gt;</bt><v n="46" />Ka dhèu bhelu-katub'a abhu j'aj'èra, toke d'ai mia-mia. Te ngaa dhèu-dhèu dhu d'ara mola, abhu mamuri taa-taa, toke d'ai mia-mia dènge Ama Lamatua.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then those evil (doublet) people will get/experience suffering continually forever. But those people with straight insides they will live continually with God forever.&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="25:46" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Daniel 12:2</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Kètu agama Yahudi sèra tenge j'ara ho pamadhe Lamatua Yesus<bt>The Yahudi religious leaders look for a way to kill the Lord Yesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 14:1-2; Lukas 22:1-2; Yohanis 11:45-53)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="26" />
      <v n="1" />Ropa Yesus aj'a nare j'ara se aa'i-aa'i ra, hèia Na lii dènge ana madhutu Na, aku Nèngu na,<bt>When Yesus had finished teaching all those things, then He told His followers, saying,</bt><v n="2" />&lt;&lt;Miu me'a le, na, di dua lod'o ka d'ai lod'o babe'a èdhi, nuka Pesta Paska. Lod'o èèna, abhu dhèu dhu pahie Ja'a, Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a ne. Èle èèna, ra paku pamadhe Ja'a ètu aj'u palolo-palèbha.&gt;&gt;<bt>&lt;&lt;You know that in two more days it is our-in good day (=holiday), that is, the Paska (Indo loan: Easter &amp; Passover) Feast. At that time, there will be a person who sells Me off (=betray), this Ideal/Prototypical Human. Then they will nail killing Me on the crossed sticks.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="di = sisa, lagi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">di = sisa, lagi</Message></Annotation><note reference="26:2" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 12:1-27</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Lod'o èèna, kètu agama Yahudi dènge dhèu heka ad'a sèra, dhu pakaboko ètu d'ara èmu Kayafas. Kayafas ne, nuka kètu kapai risi agama Yahudi.<bt>On that day, the *chief priests and the traditional elders were gathered at Kayafas' house. That Kayafas, was the Yahudi religion's Top Head.</bt><v n="4" />Rèngu se tenge j'ara ho neo kèpe Yesus pahuni-pahuni, sèna ka pamadhe Ne.<bt>They were looking for a way to capture/arrest Yesus quietly, so they could kill Him.</bt><v n="5" />Te ngaa rèngu rare lii èci, peka na, &lt;&lt;Mata ku! Mage èdhi kèpe Ne ètu d'ara lai-lai ne, lula lod'o-lod'o be'a dètu le. Mage dhoka dhèu ae dhu d'èi Nèngu, tao maruru.&gt;&gt;<bt>But they came to an agreement, saying, &lt;&lt;Wait up! We-inc shouldn't capture Him too quickly, because the holidays are near. May it not be that many people who like Him, run.amok/create chaos.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Bhèni ca dhèu pahae èi hèu mèngi dhu kab'ua mi Lamatua Yesus<bt>A woman pours fragrant oil which is expensive on the Lord Yesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 14:3-9; Yohanis 12:1-8)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Ètu rae Betania, abhu ca dhèu ngara na Simon. Uru èèna, dhèu madenge dènge ne, lula nèngu dhu lèke èi papèd'a kusta. Te ngaa limuri ne, èle le nèti papèd'a na. Lod'o dhu d'ai mèka lod'o babe'a dhèu Yahudi, Yesus si ra'a ètu d'ara èmu Simon.<bt>In Betania village, there was a person named Simon. Previously, people were abhorred by/with him, because he was afflicted with leprosy (assimilated loan) illness, But now, he was healed of his sickness. When those Yahudi holidays had not yet come, Yesus (coll.) went to eat at Simon's house.</bt><v n="7" />Ropa rèngu ra'a era, bhèni ca dhèu mai paraga dènge Yesus. Nèngu nèd'u boto cue dhu tao nèti hadhu dhu kab'ua.<bt>While they were still eating, a woman came to meet Yesus. She was holding a bottle, made from stone which was expensive.</bt><note reference="26:7" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Boto ne, ra tao nèti hadhu kab'ua dhu dhèu bisa pae. Alkitab lii Yunani peka na boto ne ra tao nèti hadhu dhu ngara na, ἀλάβαστρος (<span class="Italic">&lt;alabastros&gt;</span>). Ladhe kahèi ètu Lukas 7:37-38.<bt>That bottle, they made from expensive stone that could be carved/chiselled. The Yunani language Bible says that bottle they made out of a stone with its name <span class="Italic">ἀλάβαστρος (&lt;alabastros&gt;</span>). Also see in Lukas 7:37-38.</bt></note>Boto ne dhu isi na, èi hèu mèngi dhu kab'ua titu kèna. Ka bhèni ne hake pamae katanga boto ne. Hèia na pahae mau-mau èi hèu mèngi ne mi kètu Yesus, sèna ka j'aj'i tadha, nèngu pakab'ua Yesus.<bt>That bottle's contents were very expensive. Then2 that woman hit breaking that bottle's cover. Then she slowly poured that oil on Yesus' head, as a sign she was honouring Him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pahae = pour (constant stream) ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">pahae = pour (constant stream) ; pasuti = pour (in drops)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Te ngaa ropa ana madhutu Na ladhe rèdhi tatao bhèni ne, hèia ra nasa. Ka ra paka'uu, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Heh! Bhèni ne bhori eele iia d'ara, èi hèu mèngi dhu kab'ua aae ne. Baku na tao sèmi èèna!<bt>But when Yesus' follower/s saw that woman's deeds/behaviour, then they got angry, and they complained to each other saying, &lt;Heh! [+critical] That woman is needlessly throwing away that fragrant oil that is so expensive. She shouldn't do that!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="cebe-lebhe = buang sembarangan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">cebe-lebhe = buang sembarangan</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Ngaa unu bhèni ne, ka na"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">Ngaa unu bhèni ne, ka na cebe-lebhe èi hèu mèngi dhu kabua aae ne!</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Heh"><Message author="Chuck" created="2009-11-28 03:30:32Z" status="Anyone">heh = talking among themselves (longer and dipping intonation); weh = talking to the woman ; heh = (short, sharp) direct expression of anger to the woman.</Message></Annotation><v n="9" />Be'a risi nèngu pahie! Sèna ka kab'ua na bagi mi dhèu-dhèu dhu unu boe ngaa-ngaa.&gt;&gt;<bt>It's better she just sells it! So that its value/price can be divided out to the poor people!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Te ngaa Yesus ne'a ngangee rèngu, hèia Na lii peka na, &lt;&lt;Miu se baku pasusa bhèni ne! Hud'i laa! Ja'a karej'e, lula na pahae le èi hèu mèngi ne mi ngi'u Ja'a.<bt>But Yesus knew that thinking of theirs, and He spoke saying, &lt;&lt;You don't need to cause trouble for this woman! Just leave her alone! I am happy, because she has poured this fragrant oil on My body.</bt><v n="11" />Te dhèu dhu unu boe ngaa-ngaa pa'èci taruu dènge miu. Te ngaa Ja'a ne mamuri nèbhu heka dènge miu.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) poor people will always be with you. But as for Me, (My) life is not much longer with you.</bt><note reference="26:11" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 15:11</note><v n="12" />Aa bhèni dhu pahae èi hèu mèngi mi ngi'u Ja'a ne, sèmi ngaa te, nèngu pahèu mèngi mema le ngi'u aae Ja'a. Te mamuri Ja'a nèbhu heka.<bt>By this woman pouring this fragrant oil on My body here, it's like she has fragranted (verb) ahead.of.time My corpse. Cuz (elaboration) My life is not much longer.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sèmi ngaa te = sepertinya, it's"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">sèmi ngaa te = sepertinya, it's as if</Message></Annotation><v n="13" />Ngee paie-iie! Sad'i ètu mia èèna ka, ladhe dhèu palolo Lii Lolo Be'a Ama Lamatua palème rai-haha ne, tatu rèngu papeka kahèi babe'a bhèni ne, sèna ka dhèu aa'i-aa'i sanèd'e ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>Remember well! Wherever people tell God's Good News around this world, they will also certainly tell this woman's goodness, so that all people remember her.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Sad'i ètu mia èèna ka, ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">Sad'i ètu mia èèna ka, = wherever</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Sad'i ètu mia èèna ka ladhe"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">Sad'i ètu mia èèna ka ladhe Lii Lolo Be'a Ama Lamatua ne, dhèu palolo pale-lème rai-haha ne, tatu rèngu papeka kahèi babe'a bhèni ne, sèna ka dhèu aa'i-aa'i sanèd'e ne.&gt;&gt;</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yudas pane'a lii dènge kètu agama Yahudi sèra, ho pahie Lamatua Yesus mi rèngu<bt>Yudas agrees with the Yahudi religious leaders to sell the Lord Yesus to them</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 14:10-11; Lukas 22:3-6)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Ca dhèu nèti canguru dua ana madhutu Yesus se, dhu ngara na Yudas Iskariot. Lod'o èèna kahèi, kalua la'e tenge kètu agama Yahudi sèra, sèna ka neo pahie Yesus mi rèngu.<bt>One of Yesus' twelve followers, was named Yudas Isakariot. That same day, he went out to go look for the *chief priests, in.order.to sell Yesus to them.</bt><v n="15" />Ropa Yudas d'ai dhèu se'e, hèia na karèi, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama-ama! Ladhe ja'a bhoke j'ara ho miu bisa kèpe Yesus, miu hia ja'a ngaa?&gt;&gt;<bt>When Yudas arrived at these people, then he asked, saying, &lt;&lt;Fathers! If I open the way so you can capture/arrest Yesus, what will you give me?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia dhèu se dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe èu neo pahie Ne dènge ji'i, na ji'i b'ae.&gt;&gt; Ka ra ige rare 30 (tèlu nguru) doi iia, aa ra j'ole asa Yudas.<bt>Then they replied, saying, &lt;&lt;If you want to sell Him to us, na, we will pay.&gt;&gt; Then2 they counted out thirty silver money to hand over to Yudas.</bt><note reference="26:15" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Sakaria 11:12</note><v n="16" />Èle, ka Yudas li'u ka la'e, hèia na tenge j'ara ho saraka Yesus asa d'ara adhe-aai rèngu.<bt>After that, Yudas went out, and he looked for a way to hand over Yesus into their hands. (possession/ control)</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus na'a kalela Paska dènge ana-ana madhutu Na<bt>The Lord Yesus eats Paska feast with His followers</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 14:12-21; Lukas 22:7-14, 21-23; Yohanis 13:21-30)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />D'ara tèu mai-tèu mai, abhu lod'o babe'a dhèu Yahudi dhu nanèbhu na pidhu lod'o. Ra pangare lod'o babe'a se, na, &lt;Pesta Roti dhu Pake boe Ragi&gt;.<bt>Every year, the Yahudi people had holidays which lasted seven days. They called those holidays saying, &lt;The Feast of Bread that doesn't use Yeast&gt;.</bt><note reference="26:17" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Kalela èèna pasanèd'e lod'o bèi-baki dhèu Yahudi kalua nèti rai Masir. Lod'o èèna, rèngu pakèd'i dènge lai-lai. Nèti èèna ka, abhu boe tebho dhu nèbhu ho tao reis roti pake ragi. Baca ètu <span class="Italic">Kalua nèti Masir</span> 12:6,15.<bt>That feast remembers when the Yahudi people's ancestors were fleeing from the land/country of Masir. At that time, they left very quickly. That is why there was not enough time to raise their bread using yeast (loan). Read <span class="Italic">Exiting from Masir</span> 12:6,15.</bt></note>Ropa pesta èèna neo mulai, ana madhutu Yesus se mai karèi Ne, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Mèda ne'e, èdhi bhoke lod'o babe'a èdhi. De Ama neo sèna ka ji'i la'a roro kahib'i-kalèbho, aa lalau era pesta Paska ètu mia?&gt;&gt;<bt>When that feast was about to begin, Yesus' followers came asking Him, saying, &lt;&lt;Father! Tonight we-inc must open/start our holidays. So (consequently), where does Father want us to go cut/slaughter the sheep, and prepare palce for the Paska feast?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Ka Yesus b'ala si, peka na, &lt;&lt;Lami asa d'ara kota, pe mi paraga dènge ama ca dhèu. Miu peka dènge ne sèmi ne'e, &lt;Ama! Ama Mese rasa lod'o mamadhe Na nèbhu heka. Hèia Na manèngi era èci ètu d'ara èmu ama, sèna ka Na tao kalela Paska dènge ana-ana madhutu Na.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus replied, saying, &lt;&lt;Go into the city, and you will meet/ encounter a father/man. Tell him saying like this, &lt;Father! Father Teacher feels the time of His death is soon. So He is requesting a place in father's house, for Him to make the Paska feast with His followers.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Ropa ra tadèngi rare, hèia ana-ana madhutu Na, tao sèmi dhu Na peka. Ka ra lalau nganga'a kalela Paska ètu era èèna.<bt>Hearing like that then, His followers went to do according to that speaking of His. Then they prepared the Paska feast food there.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Ropa d'ai mèda, hèia Yesus dènge ana-ana madhutu Na, dhèu canguru dua sèra, madhèdi ra'a-rinu.<bt>When it was night, then Yesus 12 followers sat down to eat/feast (doublet).</bt><v n="21" />Ropa dhu ra'a era, hèia Na lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;Mi nanene! Ca dhèu nèti miu se, èèna na pahie Ja'a asa adhe-aai dhèu leo kara.&gt;&gt;<bt>While they were eating, then He spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;You listen! There is one of you, who later will sell Me (=betray) into the hands of other (foreign) people.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Ropa ra tadèngi sèmi èèna, d'ara rèngu roe-bhilu. Ka rèngu èci-èci karèi Yesus, peka na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu dhu Ama peka deo na, ja'a aad'o, sina ma?&gt;&gt;<bt>Hearing like that, then their insides were weak (doublet) (disturbed/upset). Next each one asked Yesus, saying, &lt;&lt;That person whom Father was talking about there, it's not me, right?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Hèia Na peka, na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu dhu cèb'u roti na palere-lere dènge Ja'a asa d'ara mago ne, nèngu ka dhu pahie Ja'a.<bt>Then He replied, saying, &lt;&lt;The person who dips his bread into this cup together with Me, it's he who will later sell Me.</bt><note reference="26:23" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 41:10</note><v n="24" />Sanèd'e, ee! Ja'a, Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a ne, hud'i madhe ku, nuka sèmi dhu suri tèke ètu d'ara Sasuri Mola-Mèci Ama Lamatua. Te ngaa mate unu na! Dhèu dhu neo pahie Ja'a, bèli-camèd'a pasae nare pala na! Hua iia risi, ina na baku nara iisi ne!&gt;&gt;<bt>Remember, ee! I, this Ideal/Prototypical Human, must die first, just like they wrote ahead of time in God's Scriptures. But, be careful! The person who wants to sell Me, later he will carry his portion [idiomatic: language of threat]. It's better if his mother didn't give birth to him!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Èle èèna ka, Yudas karèi kahèi, peka na, &lt;&lt;Tatu dhèu dhu Ama peka deo na, ja'a aad'o, sina ma?&gt;&gt;<bt>After that, Yudas also asked saying, &lt;Surely that person whom Father is speaking about there, it's not me, right?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia Yesus b'ala ne, &lt;&lt;Mema tare'a èu unu mu ka dhu peka lii èèna. De cee hari?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus replied to him, saying, &lt;&lt;Actually you yourself have said like that. So (consequently) who else?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus peka na, roti dènge èi anggor j'aj'i mi tadha ho sanèd'e Nèngu [\s2]<bt>The Lord Yesus says the bread and grape water/juice are signs to remember Him [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 14:22-26; Lukas 22:14-20; 1 Korintus 11:23-25)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Rèngu dhu ra'a era, hèia Yesus ded'e nare roti cue, aa Na manèngi makasi mi Ama Lamatua. Ka Na pamae roti ne, hèia j'ole asa ana-ana madhutu Na, aa Na peka, &lt;&lt;Roti ne'e ne, ngi'u Ja'a. Mere ho mi'e ka!&gt;&gt;<bt>While they were still eating, then Yesus picked up a (loaf of) bread, and gave thanks to God. Then2 He broke up that bread, and extended it to His followers, and said, &lt;&lt;This bread here, [is] My body. You take [it] and eat [it]!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Èle ka, Yesus nare galaa dhu pènu dènge èi anggor, ka Na manèngi makasi mi Ama Lamatua. Hèia Na j'ole asa ana-ana madhutu Na, aa Na lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;Miu aa'i-aa'i mi, mere ho minu.<bt>After that, He took a glass full of grape juice/liquid, and gave thanks to God. Then He extended it to His followers, and spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;You all take [it] and drink [it].</bt><v n="28" />Te èi anggor ne'e ne, raa Ja'a kèna. Èèna na Ja'a madhe, te ngaa raa Ja'a suti, sèna ka sui kore dhèu ae nèti koasa sasala-sasigo ra. Raa ne'e j'aj'i mi tadha ho pasanèd'e dhèu, peka na, ngaa dhu Ama Lamatua pajaji èèna, mema limuri ne j'aj'i le. De mere ho minu ka!<bt>Cuz (elaboration) this grape juice here, is My blood. Later when I die, My blood I will spill out to save/redeem many people from their wrongs (doublet). [NOTE: this ‘spill blood’ term evokes ‘for a cause/purpose/movement’] This blood is a sign to remind people that, what God promised before, actually now it has happened. So (consequently), take and drink!</bt><note reference="26:28" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 24:8, Yermia 31:31-34</note><v n="29" />Te ngaa nanene paie-iie! Mulai nèti mèda ne, Ja'a kinu heka èi anggor. Pe Ja'a dènge Ama Ku madhèdi ngèd'u paredha sama-sama ètu sorga, heka Ja'a kinu hari kèna dènge miu.&gt;&gt;<bt>But listen carefully! Starting from this night, I will no longer drink grape juice again. Later (when) I and My Father in heaven sit ruling/governing together, only then will I drink again with you.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="30" />Èle èèna, hèia rèngu sod'a lii sod'a èci, ho koa-kio Ama Lamatua. Ka mèda èèna kahèi, rèngu lasi dènge ka asa ledhe Saitun.<bt>After that, they sang a song to praise (doublet) God. Then2 that same night then they went out to Saitun mountain.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus peka mema, na, bèli-camèd'a Petrus pasili Nèngu<bt>The Lord Yesus tells beforehand, saying, Petrus later will deny (knowing) Him</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 14:27-31; Lukas 22:31-34; Yohanis 13:36-38)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Ropa ètu d'ara kakako rèngu, Yesus peka dènge ana madhutu Na, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ciki hari ètu d'ara mèda ne'e kahèi, miu aa'i-aa'i mi rai tèke eele Ja'a mesa-mesa Ku. Te dhu suri tèke le ètu d'ara Sasuri Mola-Mèci Ama Lamatua, peka na,<bt>While they were walking there, Yesus told His followers, saying, &lt;&lt;A little later tonight, you all will run/ flee leaving Me alone. Cuz (elaboration) they have written ahead of time in the Scriptures, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;Èèna na, Ama Lamatua pamadhe ana madhenga badha,<bt>‘God will kill the shepherd,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">ka kahib'i-kalèbho na rai paj'ala.&gt;<bt>And his sheep will run scattering.’</bt><note reference="26:31" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Sakaria 13:7</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="32" />Ja'a madhe tare'a, te ngaa ladhe Ja'a mamuri hari, laku mate miu ètu propensi Galilea.&gt;&gt;<bt>I will really die. But when I live again, I will go wait for you in Galilea province.&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="26:32" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 28:16</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="33" />Te ngaa Petrus d'èi boe nanene lii Na, ka na peka, &lt;&lt;Ama! Masi ka dhèu leo rai tèke eele Ama, te ngaa ja'a rai boe!&gt;&gt;<bt>But Petrus didn't want to hear what He said, and said, &lt;&lt;Father! Even if the other people run/flee leaving Father, nevertheless I will not flee!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="34" />Hèia Yesus b'ala aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Petrus! Sèmi èèna, do? Lèka la lii Ja'a ne! Ètu d'ara mèda ne'e ne kahèi, manu dhae kokotoo mèka, te èu dhu pasili le tèlu hari, peka na, èu tadhe boe Ja'a!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus responded, saying, &lt;&lt;Petrus! Is that right? Believe2 Me! This night, the chicken will not yet crow, and/but you will have denied three times, saying you do not know Me!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="35" />Te ngaa Petrus no'o boe sèmi. Ka na peka, &lt;&lt;Aad'o, Ama! Ladhe Ama madhe, ja'a madhe kahèi. Te ja'a rai boe, tèke eele Ama!&gt;&gt; Angalai Petrus se, peka sèmi èèna kahèi.<bt>But Petrus didn't want to accept that. And he said, &lt;&lt;No, Father! If Father dies, then I will also die. Cuz (elaboration) I will not run away abandoning Father!&gt;&gt; Each one of Petrus' friends also said like that.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus manèngi-mangaj'i ètu d'ara oka Getsemani<bt>The Lord Yesus prays (doublet) in Getsemani garden</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 14:32-42; Lukas 22:39-46)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="36" />Ka Yesus si kako taruu asa ledhe Saitun, d'ai d'ara oka cue, ngara na <span class="Italic">Getsemani.</span><bt>[CHECK gegili in the ftn] Then Yesus (coll.) walked on to Saitun mountain, arriving at a garden, named <span class="Italic">Getsemani.</span></bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gili ; gegili = alat untuk"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">gili ; gegili = alat untuk giling</Message></Annotation><note reference="26:36" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Ètu d'ara lii Ibrani, &lt;Getsemani&gt; sasoa na, &lt;gagili dhu gili èi mènyi nèti hua saitun&gt;.<bt>In the Ibrani language, &lt;Getsemani&gt; means &lt;instrument to press oil from saitun fruit&gt;.</bt></note>Ètu era ne'e Yesus peka dènge ana madhutu Na, &lt;&lt;Miu madhèdi uuru ku mi ne'e, te Ja'a neo laku manèngi-mangaj'i asa nèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>There He told His followers, &lt;&lt;You sit a while here, cuz (elaboration) I want to go pray (doublet) over there (yonder).&gt;&gt;</bt><v n="37" />Te ngaa Na paroa nare Petrus, Yakobis dènge Yohanis, ho lasi palere-lere dènge Ne. Mulai nèti èèna ka, d'ara Na ma'ète laho mae-mae, aa roe-bhilu.<bt>But He called/summoned Petrus, Yakobis, and Yohanis, to go accompanying Him. Starting from that time, then His insides felt distraught (extreme) and weak (doublet) (sad, discouraged, troubled).</bt><v n="38" />Rèngu kako kaj'èu mèka, te Na peka dènge rèngu, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;D'ara Ja'a susa titu kèna! Ja'a nuka sèmi oe madhe sa. Miu madhèdi, mate Ja'a mi ne'e.&gt;&gt;<bt>They had only walked not far, cuz (elaboration) He told them, saying, &lt;&lt;My insides are very distressed! I feel as if I am about to die. You-pl sit and wait for Me here.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="39" />Ka la'e ako kaj'èu ciki, hèia Na patitu kètu urutuu ho sabaj'a, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama pasue! Ladhe Ama d'èi na, Ja'a baku pasae j'aj'èra ne'e. Te ngaa baku madhutu dad'èi Ja'a, hud'i laa madhutu dad'èi Ama di.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then He went foreward a little bit further, and He knelt to pray, saying, &lt;&lt;Beloved/dear Father! If Father agrees then, I don't need to carry/ experience this suffering. But don't follow My will; allow it to just follow Father's will.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="40" />Sabaj'a nare, hèia lèpa la'e asa era ana madhutu Na dhèu tèlu sèra. Te ngaa rèngu dhu bhèj'i luu. Ka Yesus parèi si, hèia Na lii dènge Petrus, peka na, &lt;&lt;Hee, Petrus! Nga tao ka miu se bhèj'i? Ja'a ètu nèi nèbhu boe, te ngaa miu lake mere boe beke ciki sa mate Ja'a!<bt>After finished praying, then He returned to those three followers of His. But they were sleeping soundly. Then2 He woke them up, and He spoke with Petrus, saying, &lt;&lt;Hee! Petrus! Why are you-p sleeping? I was yonder only just a short time, but you could not stay awake even a little bit to wait for Me!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lake mere boe"><Message author="Chuck" created="2009-11-28 04:49:54Z" status="Anyone">tidak sanggup (UNS)</Message></Annotation><v n="41" />Ruri pamako musi madha miu. Kèd'i ho beke dènge Ja'a. Te d'ara miu mema d'èi tao dhu be'a, te ngaa ngi'u miu èra boe. De hua iia miu sabaj'a, sèna ka ladhe lèke dadugu-rariu miu bisa taha.&gt;&gt;<bt>Rub and make your eyes clear. Wake/get up to stay.awake with Me! Cuz (elaboration) your insides really want to do what is good, only your bodies are not strong. So (consequently), it's better you pray, so that if you are affected by temptation (doublet), you can endure.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ruri = rub (eyes)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">ruri = rub (eyes)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="42" />Ka Yesus la'e hari sabaj'a, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Ladhe Ja'a hud'i pasae ku j'aj'èra ne'e, hud'i laa madhutu dad'èi Ama di.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then He went again to pray, saying, &lt;&lt;Father! If I must shoulder carry/experience this suffering, allow it to just follow Father's will.&gt;&gt;</bt><v n="43" />Sabaj'a nare, hèia na mai hari asa era ana madhutu Na dhèu tèlu se. Te ngaa dhu ra bhèj'i hari, lula musi madha ra sakaa titu kèna.<bt>After praying, then He came back to those three followers of His. But they were sleeping again, because their eyes were very heavy.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="44" />Ka Na tèke eele si, la'e hari manèngi-mangaj'i catèka. Na manèngi-mangaj'i hari mi Ama, sèna ka baku soro tèke Nèngu pasae j'aj'èra èèna, te ngaa hud'i laa madhutu dhoka dad'èi Ama di.<bt>Then2 He left them to go pray (doublet) one more time. He prayed (doublet) again to the Father, to not leave Him to carry that suffering, but allow it to just follow the Father's will.</bt><v n="45" />Sabaj'a nare ka, Na lèpa hari, la'e parèi ana madhutu Na, peka na, &lt;&lt;Miu se bhèj'i taruu, do? Kèd'i ka! Te dhèu dhu neo pahie Ja'a, Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a ne, dètu le. Dhèu se mai ho kèpe Ja'a kèna, ho saraka asa adhe-aai dhèu bhelu-katub'a.<bt>After praying then, He went back and woke up His followers, saying, &lt;&lt;You are still sleeping on here? Get/Wake up! Cuz (elaboration) the person who wants to sell (=betray) Me, this Ideal/ Prototypical Human, is near. These people have come to want to capture/ arrest Me, to hand over to evil (doublet) people's hands.</bt><v n="46" />Wee, kèd'i ka! Bhoke musi madha miu, ladhe ku asa nèi. Te dhèu dhu pahie Ja'a, nuka mai nèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>Wee, get up! Open your eyes and look over yonder! Cuz (elaboration) the person/people who is/are selling Me, have come.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu kapai-dhèu kapai pua dhèu lasi kèpe Lamatua Yesus<bt>The leaders send people to go capture/arrest the Lord Yesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 14:43-50; Lukas 22:47-53; Yohanis 18:3-12)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="47" />Ropa Yesus padhai lii era, Yudas dhu nare le era èèna dènge dhèu ae-ae. Dhèu se mai rèti hela dènge aj'u cèki ho neo kèpe Ne. Rèngu tao sèmi ne'e, lula madhutu paredha nèti kètu agama Yahudi, dènge dhèu heka ad'a sèra.<bt>[CHECK aj'u cèki] When Yesus was still talking, Yudas had come to that place with many people. They came bringing short swords and clubs, to capture/arrest Him. They did like that, because (they were) following the command from chief priests, and the traditional elders.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="aj'u cèki = kayu kudung"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">aj'u cèki = kayu kudung</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="aj'u cèki"><Message author="Chuck" created="2009-11-28 04:55:38Z" status="Anyone">club; 3 UNS not know, but they feel context is redundant enough to leave it even if not everyone knows the term</Message></Annotation><v n="48" />Yudas dhu peka mema le mi dhèu se'e, na, &lt;&lt;Miu ladhe paie-iie! Dhèu dhu ja'a uu, Nèngu ka dhu miu kèpe! Te Nèngu ka dhu miu tenge!&gt;&gt;<bt>Yudas told ahead.of.time to them, saying, &lt;&lt;You watch carefully! The person whom I kiss, He is the one for you to capture/ arrest! Cuz (elaboration) He is the one whom you are looking for!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="49" />Ropa rèngu d'ai madha Yesus, hèia Yudas lii dènge ka, &lt;&lt;Saloom, Ama Mese!&gt;&gt; Hèia Yudas uu Yesus.<bt>When they arrived before Yesus, then Yudas spoke immediately, &lt;&lt;Peace, Father Teacher!&gt;&gt; Then Yudas kissed Yesus.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="50" />Èle ka, Yesus peka dènge ne, &lt;&lt;Hee, Yudas! Tao ka laa, madhutu dad'èi èu.&gt;&gt; Ka dhèu ae sèra ara lasi neo kèpe Ne.<bt>Then3 Yesus asked him, &lt;&lt;Hee Yudas! Do what you came for.&gt;&gt; Then2 those many people came forward, to capture/arrest Him. [NOTE to daughter translations: ALT (like NLT): “go ahead and do what you have come for.”]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="51" />Te ngaa dhu re'a boe, na, dhèu unu Yesus ca dhèu dhu bete hela na, ka seru pama'ète rèu dhilu dhèu èci. (Dhèu dhu nu'a ne, nuka ca dhèu ènu nèti kètu kapai risi agama Yahudi.)<bt>But unexpectedly, one of Yesus' people pulled out his machete, and slashed severing a person's ear leaf. (That person who was wounded there, it was the servant/slave of the high head of the Yahudi religion. [=*high priest]) [NOTE: RL context. Fishermen and farmers would have access to parangs (machetes), not kelewangs (fighting swords). The Gk term covers a wide range.]</bt><v n="52" />Ropa ladhe nèdhi sèmi èèna, hèia Yesus lii dènge ne, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Pasaluu hela èu èèna asa d'ara sope na. Te dhèu dhu pake rèka ho neo uri pamere lii langu, èèna na nèngu madhe dènge rèka kahèi.<bt>Seeing like.that, then Yesus told him, saying, &lt;&lt;Put your machete back in its scabbard. Cuz (elaboration) a person who uses weapons to try to handle disputes, later he will also die by weapons.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pasaluu = pemaso (parang, pedang) ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">pasaluu = pemaso (parang, pedang) ; sope = sheath, sarong (parang, kelewang) ; uri pamere = urus penyelesaian</Message></Annotation><v n="53" />Èu me'a boe, do? Ja'a bisa manèngi Ama Ku, ho Na hia ana pajuu Na d'ai nguru riho<bt>Don't you know [tag question]? I can request My Father to send tens of thousands</bt><note reference="26:53" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Alkitab lii Yunani suri, peka na, 12 <span class="Italic">legion</span>. Ca legion tentara Roma, ele boe d'ai èna riho (6.000) dhèu.<bt>The Yunani language Bible says 12 <span class="Italic">legion</span>. One legion in the Roma army, is around 6,000 people.</bt></note>mai nèti sorga, sèna ka soru-bara Ja'a.<bt>of his underlings from heaven, to come help (doublet) Me.</bt><v n="54" />Te ngaa hud'i laa, ra kèpe Ja'a. Te aa'i-aa'i dhu suri tèke le ètu d'ara Sasuri Mola-Mèci Ama Lamatua lula-nèti Ja'a ne, hud'i j'aj'i ku.&gt;&gt;<bt>But just let these people capture Me. Cuz (elaboration) everything which is written ahead.of.time in the Scriptures about Me there, must happen.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="55" />Èle èèna ka, Yesus peka dènge dhèu-dhèu dhu mai kèpe Ne, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Madhutu miu, Ja'a ne dhèu bhelu, do? Nga tao ka miu mai kèpe Ja'a ne, mèti dènge hela dènge aj'u cèki? Bèli-bèli Ja'a aj'a miu ètu d'ara Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i Ama Lamatua, te ngaa dhèu èci sa tao boe ngaa-ngaa mi Ja'a.<bt>Then3 Yesus spoke with those people who came to capture Him, saying, &lt;&lt;According to you-pl, am I an evil person [tag question]? Why do you come capture Me bringing swords and clubs? Every day I teach you in God's Temple, but there is not even one person who did anything to Me.</bt><note reference="26:55" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lukas 19:47, 21:37</note><v n="56" />Te ngaa hud'i laa! Mai ka, kèpe Ja'a! Te j'ara ne'e ne, dhu suri tèke le karèi nèti uru ka, ètu d'ara Sasuri Mola-Mèci Ama Lamatua.&gt;&gt;<bt>But just allow it! Come, capture Me! Cuz (elaboration) all of this is written ahead.of.time from long ago in the Scriptures.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ropa ana madhutu Yesus rèdhi sèmi èèna, ra madha'u titu kèna. Hèia ra rai tèke eele Ne mesa-mesa.<bt>Seeing like that then, Yesus' underlings were very afraid. They got up and ran off leaving Him.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Rèti Lamatua Yesus asa madha dhèu pama'ète lii langu agama<bt>They bring the Lord Yesus to the people who decide religious disputes</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 14:53-65; Lukas 22:54-55, 63-71; Yohanis 18:13-14, 19-24)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="57" />Èle èèna, hèia dhèu dhu kèpe Yesus, rèti Ne asa èmu kètu kapai risi agama Yahudi dhu ngara na, Kayafas, lula dhèu kapai sèra dhu pakaboko le ètu era èèna. Dhèu se nuka, kètu agama Yahudi, mese agama, aa dhèu heka ad'a sèra.<bt>Afterthat, then the people who captured/arrested Yesus brought Him to the house of the top head of the Yahudi religion, whose name was Kayafas, because the big (=important) people had already gathered in that place. These people were, the chief priests, the religion teachers, and the traditional elders. [EXEG: ‘chief priests’ from vs. 59; but here for RL background patterns.]</bt><v n="58" />Ropa ra rèti Yesus, Petrus madhutu nèti limuri, toke d'ai èmu kètu kapai risi agama Yahudi èèna. Petrus la'e kahèi asa madha èmu, ho madhèdi dènge dhèu-dhèu dhu ètu sèra. Te neo ne'a, ngaa ka dhu j'aj'i.<bt>When they brought Yesus, Petrus was following from behind, until arriving at that top head's house. Petrus also entered the yard, to go along sitting together with people who were there. Cuz (elaboration) he wanted to know what would happen.</bt><v n="59" />Ètu d'ara èmu ne, kètu agama Yahudi sèra dhu padhue-padhai dènge dhèu-dhèu dhu madhèdi uri lii langu agama. Rèngu aa'i-aa'i ra tenge j'ara, sèna ka pamanahu Yesus, lula ra neo huku pamadhe Ne.<bt>In that house, the chief priests were conferring (doublet) with the people who handle religious disputes. They all were looking for a way to bring down Yesus, because they wanted to punish Him with death. [DISCOURSE: RL, generic here, specific (false witnesses) in 60)]</bt><v n="60" />Masi ka rèngu hia sakasii monya ae kahèi, te ngaa rèngu abhu boe sasala èci sa dhu rèngu bisa pake. Nèbhu boe ka, rèngu abhu sakasii dhèu dua.<bt>But even though they put forward many false witnesses, they could not get any wrong they could use. Finally they got two witnesses. [NLT]</bt><v n="61" />Dhèu dua se, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ji'i tadèngi le kahèi, Dhèu ne peka na, &lt;Bèli-camèd'a Ja'a paguri eele Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i. Te ngaa ètu d'ara tèlu lod'o, Ja'a patitu kore hari.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>Those two people said, &lt;&lt;We once heard this Person speak saying, &lt;Later I will knock down this Temple. But within three days, I will build it back again.&gt;&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="26:61" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yohanis 2:19</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="62" />Ka kètu kapai risi agama Yahudi, kèd'i titu ètu madha dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu madhèdi ètu era èèna. Hèia na karèi Yesus, peka na, &lt;&lt;Èu tadèngi le lii galaa dhèu se'e dhu ra galaa Èu. Nga tao ka Èu b'ala boe ca hèb'a sa?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then2 that Yahudi religion's top head stood up in front of all the people who were sitting there. Then he asked Yesus, saying, &lt;&lt;You have heard many people accuse You. But, why are You not responding even a little?&gt;&gt;</bt><v n="63" />Te ngaa Yesus dhaa boe ngaa-ngaa. Hèia kètu kapai ne karèi hari, na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a neo karèi! Te ngaa Èu hud'i dhaa tare'a-re'a ku, nuka sèmi Èu dhaa mi Ama Lamatua dhu mamuri ètu sorga. Abhu dhèu dhu peka na, Èu ne, Kristus, Ana Ama Lamatua dhu Na moa tèke karèi nèti uru ka. Tare'a sèmi èèna, do?&gt;&gt;<bt>But Yesus did not reply anything. Then that top head asked again, saying, &lt;&lt;I want to ask! But You must reply correctly as if You were replying to God who lives in heaven. There are people who say, You here, are Kristus, that Child of God's whom He promised3 from long ago. Is that right?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="64" />Hèia Yesus b'ala, peka na, &lt;&lt;Tare'a, nuka sèmi lii ama èèna. Te ngaa sanèd'e! Te bèli-camèd'a miu mèdhi Ja'a, Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a ne. Pe Ja'a madhèdi ètu baboa g'ana Ama Lamatua ètu sorga, sèna ka kèd'u paredha sama-sama dènge Ne, dhu koasa Na kapai risi eele èèna. Èle na, Ja'a puru mai hari ètu dedha ra'i-liru.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus replied, saying, &lt;&lt;It's true, like father says there. But remember! Cuz (elaboration) later you will see Me, this Ideal/ Prototypical Human. I will sit at God's right side in heaven in.order.to hold rule/govern together with Him, who is most powerful. After that, I will come back down on cloud.&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="26:64" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Daniel 7:13</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="65" />Ropa na tadèngi nare Yesus peka sèmi èèna, hèia kètu kapai ne nasa bia, toke na ciu pamae kodho madhera na. Hèia na pa'oo mi dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu madhèdi ètu sèra, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Èdhi parluu sakasii tao ngaa hari era! Miu unu mi tadèngi le dènge ro'a dhilu miu, lii padhai Na. Nèngu tao iisi Na j'aj'i Ana Ama Lamatua. Ne'e ne pahaha Ama Lamatua! Miu aa'i-aa'i mi me'a le, na, madhutu atora agama èdhi, ladhe abhu dhèu dhu tao iisi na nuka sèmi Ama Lamatua, na, dhèu ne hud'i madhe ku!<bt>Hearing Him speaking like that, then that top head was heavily angry, to.the.point.that he yanked ripping his long robe. Then he called out to all the people who sat there, saying, &lt;&lt;We-inc don't need any more witnesses! You have heard with your very own ear holes, that speaking of His. He has made himself to be God's Child. This is slandering/belittling God! You all know that, according to our-inc religious regulations, if a person makes himself the same as God, na, that person must die!</bt><v n="66" />De miu neo pama'ète sèmi mia hari?&gt;&gt;<bt>So (consequently), what do we want to decide?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia aa'i-aa'i ra parodha, peka na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu ne'e ne mema sala tare'a! De hud'i huku pamadhe Ne!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then they all yelled, saying, &lt;&lt;This person is truly wrong/guilty! So (consequently), He must get the death penalty!&gt;&gt; [NOTE to daughter translations: Avoid impression that Jews have authority to carry it out. Gk focuses on result, not Actor.]</bt><note reference="26:65-66" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Atora nèti Ama-ama Agama 24:16</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="67" />Ka dhèu pèri-pèri lasi sabhuu ilu mi Yesus. Hèia ra hake-paru, aa tèb'e pa'oke Ne.<bt>Then2 several people came and spat spittle at Yesus. And they beat (doublet) [Him] and slapped Him.</bt><note reference="26:67" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 50:6</note><v n="68" />Èle ka, ra lalangu Ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Wee! Èu ne'e ka Kristus, si? Èu peka sèku! Dhèu cee ka dhu j'ubhu Èu?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then3 they mocked Him, saying, &lt;Wee! You here, are Kristus, right? Try and discern! Who is it who punched You?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Petrus pasili tèlu hari, peka na tadhe boe Lamatua Yesus<bt>Petrus denies three times, saying he does not know the Lord Yesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 14:66-72; Lukas 22:56-62; Yohanis 18:15-18, 25-27)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="69" />Lod'o èèna, Petrus madhèdi era ètu madha èmu. Ka ènu bhèni ca dhèu mai lii dènge ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Deo na, èu kahèi palere-lere dènge Yesus, dhèu Nasaret èèna, si?&gt;&gt;<bt>At that time, Petrus was still sitting in the yard. Then a female slave came speaking with him, saying, &lt;&lt;Earlier, you were also accompanying Yesus, that Nasaret person, right?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="70" />Te ngaa na pasili ètu madha dhèu ae sèra, peka na, &lt;&lt;Aad'o! Nga tao ka èu karèi sèmi èèna! Ja'a tadhe boe Ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>But he denied it in front of those many people, saying, &lt;&lt;No! Why are you asking like that! I don't know Him.&gt;&gt;</bt><v n="71" />Ka Petrus kalua la'e titu ètu hèb'a oka.<bt>Then2 Petrus went out to go stand at the fence gate. Then there was another woman who saw him there. Next this woman told the people there, saying, &lt;&lt;Earlier I saw this person together with Yesus, that Nasaret person.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia bhèni leo hari èci ladhe nèdhi ne ètu èèna. Ka bhèni ne peka dènge dhèu ètu sèra, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Deo na ja'a kèdhi dhèu ne'e ne palere-lere dènge Yesus, dhèu Nasaret èèna.&gt;&gt;</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="72" />Hèia Petrus jèke ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Èu ne tao-tao huj'u! Ja'a bani subha! Ja'a tadhe boe Dhèu nèi!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Petrus spoke angrily at her, saying, &lt;&lt;You are crazy probably! I dare to swear [it]! I don't know that Person [protest]!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="73" />Nèbhu boe ka dhèu leo ètu sèra sa peka dènge ne, &lt;&lt;Hee! Èu ne baku kapod'e-kabèli d'ara lii, dhu peka na, èu kako palere boe dènge Dhèu ne! Te nèti lii padhai èu, èci èèna ka dènge laloe lii dhèu Galilea!&gt;&gt;<bt>Not long again, other people who were there spoke with him, saying, &lt;&lt;Hee! You don't twist-turn (decieve) again, saying, you weren't travelling together with that Person! Cuz (elaboration) from your speech, it is exactly like the accent of Galilea people!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="laloe1 = logat ; laloe2 ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">laloe1 = logat ; laloe2 = urut, pijit ; laloe3 = deep part of sea (can be near island)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="74" />Te ngaa na padhèd'a, ka b'ala, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Wee! Ja'a subha dènge kolongara Ama Lamatua! Ja'a tadhe boe Dhèu ne'e ne!&gt;&gt; Ropa na peka nare sèmi èèna, hèia manu kokotoo dènge.<bt>But he replied with a curse, saying, &lt;&lt;Wee! I swear by God's name/ reputation! I don't know that Person!&gt;&gt; When he spoke like.that, then the chicken crowed immediately. [EXEG: curse/swear is explicit in Gk. Also the particular Gk lexical item for ‘swear’ here isn't the normal one, but invokes the wrath of a divine being if the oath is violated. In Kupang and surrounds this is classed as a “sumpa mati” -extreme category of oath.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="padhèd'a = curse, swear, cuss, maki"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">padhèd'a = curse, swear, cuss, maki</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="75" />Ropa na tadèngi lii kokotoo manu, hèia Petrus ngee nèdhi lii Yesus, dhu peka na, &lt;&lt;Manu dhae kokotoo mèka, te èu dhu pasili le tèlu hari, peka na, èu tadhe boe Ja'a.&gt;&gt; Sanèd'e nare lii ne'e, hèia la'e asa li'u ka tangi d'ara pèd'a.<bt>Hearing that chicken's crowing, then Petrus remembered Yesus language earlier, which said, &lt;&lt;The chicken will not yet crow, and/but you will deny three times, saying that you do not know Me.&gt;&gt; Remembering like that, then he went outside to cry in sorrow.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ama-ama dhèu Yahudi rèti Lamatua Yesus asa gubernur Pilatus<bt>The Yahudi leaders bring the Lord Yesus to gubernur Pilatus</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 15:1; Lukas 23:1-2; Yohanis 18:28-32)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="27" />
      <v n="1" />Mad'ae aae era, dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu uri lii langu agama sèra, rare lii èci sèna ka neo pamadhe Yesus.<bt>Very early in the morning, all those people who decide religious disputes, came to an agreement to kill Yesus.</bt><v n="2" />Nèti èèna ka, ra èki Ne rèti asa madha gubernur Pilatus. Te rèngu d'èi sèna ka gubernur huku pamadhe Ne.<bt>Because of that, they tied brought Him before governor Pilatus. Cuz (elaboration) they wanted the governor to give the death penalty to Him.</bt><note reference="27:2" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Lod'o èèna, dhèu Yahudi dhu dènge boe koasa ho pamadhe dhèu. Nèti èèna ka, rèngu rèti Lamatua Yesus asa dhèu paredha Roma.<bt>At that time, the Yahudi people did not have the authority to kill people. That is why they brought the Lord Yesus to the government of Roma.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yudas kadhoe iisi na, ka na madhe aapa<bt>Yudas hangs himself, and he dies (a bad death)</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 1:18-19)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Ropa Yudas tadèngi na, Yesus abhu hahuku madhe, hèia na manyasa, lula nèngu ka dhu pahie Yesus. Ka la'e hari asa kètu agama Yahudi dènge dhèu heka ad'a sèra, ho neo hia hari la'a doi iia 30 (tèlu nguru) bua sèra.<bt>When Yudas heard that Yesus had gotten the death penalty, then he regretted, because he was the one who had sold (=betrayed) Yesus. Then he went back to the chief priests and the traditional elders, wanting to give back those thirty silver moneys.</bt><v n="4" />Na peka na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a tao le sasala-sasigo, lula ja'a pahie le Dhèu dhu dènge boe sasala.&gt;&gt;<bt>He told saying, &lt;&lt;I have done wrong (doublet), because I have sold a Person who does not have even any wrongs (=innocent).&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Te ngaa dhèu se b'ala, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Wee! Ji'i se pusi-pahae heka èu ne! Èu mesa mu ka dhu d'ui more sasala èèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>But they replied, saying, &lt;&lt;Wee! We don't want to know/care about (doublet) you anymore. You yourself are the one who has to be responsible for that sin.&gt;&gt;</bt><v n="5" />Ka Yudas ceb'e eele doi sèra asa d'ara Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i. Hèia la'e kadhoe iisi na, toke na madhe aapa.<bt>Then Yudas threw that money into the Temple. Then he went and hanged himself until he died (a bad death).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ceb'e = hambur"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">ceb'e = hambur</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Hèia kètu agama Yahudi sèra kaboko rare doi dhu na ceb'e eele sèra. Ra padhue, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Doi se'e mage èdhi tao asa d'ara boaraka doi, lula doi se doi kaj'alu.<bt>Then the chief priests gathered up that money which Yudas had thrown there. They spoke with each other, saying, &lt;&lt;We-inc can't put this money back in the collection box, because this is dirty money. [NOTE: here just chief priests (probably the “elders” had no authority in this matter)]</bt><v n="7" />De be'a risi èdhi hèli tare rai ca kasib'i nèti dhèu tao èru rai sèi. Ladhe dhèu mai nèti rai leo, do, dhèu dhu èdhi tadhe boe madhe, èdhi padhane si ètu era ne'e ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>So (consequently), it's better we go buy a piece of land from a (clay) pot maker. If there is a foreigner who dies, and there is no one who we know dies, then we can just bury him/her in that place.&gt;&gt;</bt><v n="8" />Ka ra hèli rai ne, kab'ua na nèti doi deo sa. Nèti èèna ka, rai ne, toke d'ai sange ne'e, dhèu pangare na, &lt;Rai Raa&gt;.<bt>Then2 they used that money, to go buy land. That is why to this day, people call that land, saying, &lt;Blood Land&gt;.</bt><note reference="27:3-8" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 1:18-19</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Dènge j'ara ne'e, rèngu madhutu lii nèti ca dhèu nèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua, ngara na Yermia, dhu suri tèke na,<bt>In that way, they followed what the Lord's spokesperson Yeremia has written ahead of time, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Rèngu pake doi iia 30 (tèlu nguru) bua ho hèli rai.<bt>[CHECK UNS use of /bua/] &lt;&lt;They used thirty silver moneys to buy land.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Rèngu pake doi se, lula doi se kab'ua nèti hèli dhèu,<bt>They use that money, because that money there, [is] the price of buying a person,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">madhutu sèmi dhu dhèu Isra'el pama'ète rare le.<bt>according to what the Isra'el people have decided ahead.of.time.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="10" />Rai ne, rèngu hèli nèti dhèu tao èru rai,<bt>That land they bought from the (clay) pot maker,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">madhutu lii paredha dhu Ama Lamatua hia mi ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>following God's command to me.&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="27:9-10" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Sakaria 11:12-13; Yermia 18:2-4, 19:1-11, 32:6-15</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus ètu madha gubernur Pilatus<bt>The Lord Yesus before governor Pilatus</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 15:2-5; Lukas 23:3-5; Yohanis 18:33-38)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Ropa dhèu se rèti Yesus d'ai gubernur, hèia na karèi Yesus, &lt;&lt;Tasamia? Èu ne, tare'a-re'a Dhèu Aae dhèu Yahudi, do?&gt;&gt;<bt>When those people brought Yesus to the governor, then he questioned Yesus, &lt;&lt;How is it? Are you, really the Yahudi people's King, [tag question]?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Na dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Tare'a. Ama peka lèke kèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>He replied saying, &lt;&lt;True/correct. Father has spoken correctly there.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Te ngaa ropa kètu agama Yahudi dènge dhèu heka ad'a sèra galaa Ne dènge lii langu ae-ae, Na dhaa boe ca hèb'a sa hèi.<bt>But when the chief priests and traditional elders accused Yesus of many things, He did not respond even a mouth/word.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Ka gubernur karèi hari Ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Èu tadèngi boe lii padhai lii rèngu, do? Dhèu se hia sasala ae-ae mi dedha Èu. Te ngaa tasamia ka Èu b'ala boe si hèi?!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then2 the governor questioned Him again, saying, &lt;&lt;Don't You hear that speaking of theirs? These poeple are accusing you of many things. But why are You not responding to them?!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Te ngaa Na dhaa boe ca hèb'a sa hèi, toke gubernur malaa.<bt>But He didn't reply even one mouth/word, to the point that the governor was amazed.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Gubernur Pilatus pama'ète sèna ka huku pamadhe Yesus<bt>Governor Pilatus decides to punish to death Yesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 15:6-15; Lukas 23:13-25; Yohanis 18:39--19:16)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Tèu mai-tèu mai, dhu tema le, ladhe d'ai ka lod'o kalela Paska, dhèu Yahudi hag'e rare ana bèdho ca dhèu, sèna ka gubernur patabuli ne.<bt>Each year, what was common/ normal was when the days/time of the Paska feast arrived, the Yahudi people chose a jail person, for the governor to free him.</bt><v n="16" />Tèu èèna, dhèu bèdho ca dhèu, ngara na Barabas.<bt>That year/ time there was a jail person, named Barabas.</bt><note reference="27:16" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Sasuri lii Yunani cahag'e suri, peka na, &lt;Yesus Barabas&gt;, aa cahag'e hari suri, peka na, &lt;Barabas&gt; di.<bt>Some Yunani language writings write, saying, ‘Yesus Barabas’, and some others write, just saying, ‘Barabas’.</bt></note>Dhèu aa'i-aa'i tadhe le nèngu ne, lula nèngu ca dhèu bhelu-katub'a titu kèna.<bt>All the people knew who he was, because he was very evil (doublet).</bt><v n="17" />Lod'o èèna kahèi, dhèu ae lasi asa gubernur Pilatus ho manèngi, sèna ka patabuli dhèu bèdho èci, sèmi biasa. Hèia Pilatus karèi si, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Be'a. De ja'a patabuli cee? Ètu ne'e Barabas, aa abhu kahèi Yesus, dhu dhèu paroa Ne, Kristus. Mia ka dhu ja'a patabuli? Miu ka dhu pama'ète.&gt;&gt;<bt>That day/time also, many people went to governor Pilatus to request that he free a jail person the same as always. Then Pilatus asked them, saying, &lt;&lt;Ok/good! But whom do I free/ release? Here there is Barabas, and there is also Yesus, whom people call Kristus. Which one should I free/ release. You decide.&gt;&gt;</bt><v n="18" />(Gubernur peka sèmi èèna, te ne'a na kètu agama Yahudi rèti Yesus asa nèngu, lula rèngu se tèka d'ara dènge Yesus.)<bt>(The governor spoke like that, cuz (elaboration) he knew the chief priests had brought Yesus to him, because they were terribly jealous/vengeful of Him.)</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Gubernur ètu d'ara uri lii langu ne era, dhèu èmu na moa lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Mage-mage, oo! Te Yesus ne dhu dènge boe sasala. Lula Nèngu ne'e ka, mèda deo na, ja'a nii aapa. Toke d'ai sange ne'e, d'ara ja'a dhae tèka mèka.&gt;&gt;<bt>When the governor was still handling the case, his wife sent instructions to him, saying, &lt;&lt;Father! [=appropriate term for a wife in this context] Be careful, oo! Cuz (elaboration) Yesus is without wrongs/is innocent. Because of Him, last night I had a bad dream. Even until now I still feel very uneasy.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nii aapa = mimpi buruk, nightmare,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">nii aapa = mimpi buruk, nightmare, bad dream</Message></Annotation><v n="20" />Te ngaa kètu agama Yahudi dènge dhèu heka ad'a sèra, dadugu dhèu ae ètu èèna, ho ra manèngi gubernur patabuli Barabas, aa huku pamadhe Yesus.<bt>But those chief priests and traditional elders kept stirring up/ inciting those many people, for them to request the governor to free Barabas, and give death penalty to Yesus.</bt><v n="21" />Ka na karèi hari si, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Nèti dhèu dua se, mia ka dhu ja'a patabuli?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then2 he asked them again, saying, &lt;&lt;From these two here, which one do I free?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia aa'i-aa'i ra dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Barabas! Patabuli Barabas di!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then they all replied, saying, &lt;&lt;Barabas! Just free Barabas!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Èle ka na karèi si, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe sèmi èèna, ja'a tao tasa mera mia mi Yesus, dhu ra peka na Kristus ne?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then he asked them, saying, &lt;&lt;If that's the case, then what do I do with this Yesus, whom people refer to, saying, Kristus?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia aa'i-aa'i ra pa'oo-parodha peka na, &lt;&lt;Paku pamadhe Ne asa aj'u palolo-palèbha!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then they all called out (doublet), saying, &lt;&lt;Nail Him to death on the crossed wood!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Èle èèna ka, gubernur karèi hari, peka na, &lt;&lt;Te sala Na, ngaa? Ja'a parisa le, te ngaa abhu boe sasala Na èci sa!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then3 the governor asked again, saying, &lt;&lt;So what is His wrong? I have examined Him, but I don't find any wrong of His!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Te ngaa ra asa pa'oo-parodha, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Pamadhe Ne! Paku Ne asa aj'u palolo-palèbha!&gt;&gt;<bt>But they all yelled (doublet) even louder again, saying, &lt;&lt;Kill Him! Nail Him on the crossed wood!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Nèbhu boe, na ne'a heka tao tasamia hari, lula dhèu se'e asa ka ra hino neo patao. Nèti èèna ka, nare èi ho j'amo ai ètu madha dhèu ae-ae sèra, aa na peka dènge ra, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a tago boe mamadhe Dhèu ne'e ne! Miu aa'i-aa'i mi ka dhu hud'i pasae mere mamadhe Na!&gt;&gt;<bt>Not long then he knew that he could not do anything more, because those many people were about to riot. That's why he took water to wash his hands in front of them, and psoke to them, saying, &lt;&lt;I do not bear responsibility for this Person's death! Just let it be you-pl who must carry/bear responsibility2!&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="27:24" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 21:6-9</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Hèia dhèu se'e dhaa dènge lii pa'oo-parodha peka na, &lt;&lt;Oo, hud'i laa! Hud'i laa ji'i dènge ana-èpu ji'i tago ngare raa Na!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then those many people called out (doublet) in response, saying, &lt;&lt;Yes, allow that! Allow that we and our children-grandchildren are the ones who are responsible for that blood of His!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Ropa tadèngi nare, hèia na peka, &lt;&lt;La'a, sina ma.&gt;&gt; Hèia na patabuli Barabas madhutu dad'èi ra. Èle èèna ka, na pua dhèu j'aga, lasi kalabhe Yesus pake gui. Game rare, ka sordad'u rèti Yesus, sèna ka neo paku pamadhe Ne ètu aj'u palolo-palèbha.<bt>Hearing like that then he said, &lt;&lt;Alright (idiomatic).&gt;&gt; Then he freed Barabas, according to their will. Then3 he ordered guards, to go whip/ strike Yesus using a whip/beating stick. After beating, then the soldiers took Yesus, to go nail Him to death on the crossed wood.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Sordad'u sèra pamakae Lamatua Yesus<bt>The soldiers ridicule/shame the Lord Yesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 15:16-20; Yohanis 19:2-3)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Èle èèna ka, sordad'u ère rèti Yesus asa tana lapa ètu d'ara benteng rèngu. D'ai nèi, rèngu paroa rare angalai ra ca batalion.<bt>After that, the soldiers dragged taking Yesus to their muster yard/parade ground. [NOTE: every village and city has a kind of a town square/field for ball games and flag raising ceremonies.] Arriving there, they called/summoned their friends from one batalion [+/- 750 people].</bt><note reference="27:27" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Era sordad'u se, ra pangare madhutu lii Latin, peka na <span class="Italic">praetorium.</span> Era ne ètu d'ara kompleks èmu jabatan. Alkitab lii Yunani peka ra paroa angalai ra ca <span class="Italic">speira.</span> Ca speira na, nuka èna ngasu (600) sordad'u.<bt>That place of the soldiers, they called in the Latin language, saying, <span class="Italic">praetorium</span>. It is the soldiers' own place in the complex of the official house. The Yunani language Bible says they summoned their friends from one <span class="Italic">speira</span>. One speira, is the same as 600 soldiers.</bt></note><v n="28" />Hèia ra papake Ne kodho madhera èci dhu mea aae.<bt>Then they put on Him a long scarlet robe (lit. great red).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mea sanama ahu = ??"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">mea sanama ahu = ??</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mea sanama mangèru"><Message author="Chuck" created="2009-12-05 02:16:22Z" status="Anyone">female UNSs say this is how ‘purple’ should be phrased. mea aae = scarlet</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mea sanama mangèru sa, dhu dhèu aae tema pake."><Message author="Chuck" created="2009-12-05 02:36:31Z" status="Anyone">OV</Message></Annotation><note reference="27:28" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Mateos suri, peka na, kodho madhera Na &lt;mea aae&gt;. Markus suri, peka na, &lt;mea sanama mangèru&gt;.<bt>Mateos writes that this long robe was &lt;scarlet&gt;. Mark writes that is was &lt;purple&gt;.</bt></note><v n="29" />Ka rare loro aj'u padhudhu ra ènyu tao sèmi solo. Hèia ra ènyi solo ne mi kètu Yesus, ho ra sasei Ne, tao nuka sèmi rèngu ded'e dhèu aae hiu, dhu pake solo dhèu aae. Èle èèna ka, ra j'ole hia Ne aj'u ca'èta asa ai g'ana Na, nuka sèmi tatea paredha. Hèia ra patitu kètu urutuu ra, patangara dènge Yesus, aa ra pamakae Ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Pakab'ua dhèu aae dhèu Yahudi.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then2 they took a thorn tree's branches and entwined them to make a hat. Then they pressed down that hat on Yesus' head, to play around as if they were lifting/appointing a new king using a king's hat. Then they had Him hold a stick in His right hand, like a ruling staff. Then they knelt in front of Him and they ridiculed Him, saying, &lt;&lt;Honor to the Yahudi people's king.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sasèi = olok"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">sasèi = olok</Message></Annotation><v n="30" />Hèia ra sabhuu Ne ilu, aa rare aj'u ca'èta dhu Na kèpe deo na, ka ra d'eu kètu Na.<bt>Then they spit spittle at Him, [NOTE: in contrast to a healer spitting medicine on someone] and they took that staff from His hand, to beat/bop him on the head.</bt><v n="31" />Ropa ra sasei rare Ne, hèia ra bhoke eele kodho madhera. Èle èèna ka, ra papake hari mèdha-papake Na. Ka rèti Ne asa li'u kota Yerusalem, ho neo paku Ne mi aj'u palolo-palèbha.<bt>They finished playing ridiculing Him, then they took off that long robe. Next they put back on His clothes. Then they brought/took Him outside Yerusalem city, intending to nail Him on the crossed wood until death.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Rèngu paku Lamatua Yesus ètu aj'u palolo-palèbha<bt>They nail the Lord Yesus on the crossed wood</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 15:21-32; Lukas 23:26-43; Yohanis 19:17-27)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="32" />Ropa ra ère rèti Yesus, d'ai talora j'ara paraga dènge dhèu kota Kirene èci dhu neo la'e asa d'ara kota. Ngara na, Simon. Dhèu se laka-seti ne, sèna ka pasae aj'u palolo-palèbha gati Yesus.<bt>When they were dragging bringing Yesus, in the middle of the road/journey they met/encountered a person from Kirene city who was just entering the city. His name was Simon. They forced him to shoulder carrying the crossed wood, replacing Yesus. [EXEG: Gk makes it clear he is a Cyrenian (origins), not that he was just coming from there.]</bt><v n="33" />Ka ra d'ai era èci, ngara na Golgota. (Ètu d'ara lii Aram, sasoa na, &lt;&lt;Era rui kètu.&gt;&gt;)<bt>Then2 they arrived at a place named Golgota. (In the Aram language, it's meaning says, &lt;&lt;Head bone place.&gt;&gt;)</bt><v n="34" />Ètu era ne'e, dhèu se'e hia Yesus ninu èi anggor dhu pab'ali rare le dènge èi na'i dhu pèd'u, sèna ka bisa taha rarii. Ka Yesus camuci, hèia juku eele.<bt>There they wanted to give Him to drink wine which was mixed with bitter medicine, so that He could endure pain. Yesus tasted a bit, but then He refused it. [EXEG: Because gall isn't known to reduce pain, some commentators think the term refers to a generic class of bitter medicines. See LN. NLT, CEV]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="èd'u = empedu ; capèle ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">èd'u = empedu ; capèle = jilat ; juku = tule</Message></Annotation><note reference="27:34" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 69:22</note></p>
    <fig path="HK-LB\LB00324C.tif" rtfFormat="width:5.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left">Lamatua Yesus ètu aj'u palolo-palèbha<bt>The Lord Yesus on the crossed wood</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="35" />Èle èèna ka, dhèu se'e paku Yesus asa aj'u palolo-palèbha. Hèia sordad'u se ère lot, sèna ka nèti rèngu, cee ka dhu abhu mèdha-papake Na.<bt>After that, they nailed Him on the crossed wood. Then the soldiers drew lots to know who would get those clothes of His. [NOTE: yes, they have lots; and they draw lots, not cast them.]</bt><note reference="27:35" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 22:19</note><v n="36" />Ka ra madhèdi madhenge Yesus ètu era ne'e.<bt>Then they sat guarding Yesus there.</bt><v n="37" />Ra suri kahèi ètu papa èci, peka na,<bt>They also wrote on a board, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line Centered" usfm="qc">&lt;&lt;NE'E NE YESUS, DHÈU AAE DHÈU YAHUDI&gt;&gt;<bt>&lt;&lt;THIS IS YESUS, THE YAHUDI PEOPLE'S KING&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka ra paku papa ne re dedha kètu Yesus, sèna ka dhèu re'a nga tao ka rèngu huku Ne.<bt>Next they nailed that board above His head, so people would know the reason why they punished Him.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="38" />Ètu era ne'e, ra paku pamadhe parapo dhèu dua kahèi. Ca dhèu re bèka g'ana Yesus, aa èci hari re bèka kariu Na.<bt>There they also nailed killing two robbers. One on His right side; one on His left side [CHECK two different words for ‘side’.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="@@ STYLE the variation is considered"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">@@ STYLE the variation is considered nice</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="39" />Dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu kako re sèra, laladhe Ne. Hèia ra pakapengo hèb'a ra, ho lalangu Ne.<bt>All the people who walked by there, saw Him. And they twisted their mouths to mock Him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kareko kètu = shake head back"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">kareko kètu = shake head back and forth</Message></Annotation><note reference="27:39" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Dhèu Yahudi dhu tema kareko kètu, ho tadha na, rèngu pamakae dhèu.<bt>Yahudi people often shake their heads as a sign that they were mocking/ shaming someone.</bt></note><note reference="27:39" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 22:8, 109:25</note><v n="40" />Dhèu se'e rodhe Ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Eeh! Èu peka na, Èu bisa paguri eele Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i Ama Lamatua, ho èèna na patitu hari ètu d'ara tèlu lod'o, si? Ladhe Èu tare'a-re'a Ana Ama Lamatua, na, papuru ngi'u Mu nèti aj'u palolo-palèbha èèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>They yelled out at Him, saying, &lt;&lt;Eeh! [+negative challenge] You say You can knock down God's Temple, then build it back up again in the time of three days, right? If You are really God's Child, then You free Yourself in.order.to get down from that crossed wood.&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="27:40" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 26:61, Yohanis 2:19</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="41" />Sèmi èèna kahèi dènge kètu agama Yahudi, mese agama, dènge dhèu heka ad'a sèra. Ra pahahe Yesus, aku rèngu na,<bt>Like that also the *chief priests, teachers of religion, and the traditional elders. They ridiculed/belittled Yesus, saying,</bt><v n="42" />&lt;&lt;Nèngu ne pamamuri le dhèu leo, te ngaa Na bisa boe patabuli eele ngi'u Nèngu unu Na. Nèngu mesa Na peka na, Nèngu dhèu aae Isra'el! Ladhe sèmi èèna, be'a risi Na puru ka nèti aj'u palolo-palèbha èèna. Ladhe ji'i ngèdhi ka j'aj'i sèmi èèna, ji'i heka parcaya Nèngu kèna.<bt>&lt;&lt;He has saved3 other people, but He cannot save2/rescue/release His own self. He himself said that He was Isra'el people's King! If that's the case, it's better He gets down from that crossed wood. If/when we see like that, then we will believe Him.</bt><v n="43" />Ladhe Nèngu ne tare'a-re'a Ana Ama Lamatua, hud'i laa,<bt>If He is really God's Child, allow that</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;Na maena mi Ama Lamatua.<bt>&lt;He hopes in God</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">De ladhe Lamatua d'èi Ne,<bt>So (consequently), if God2 likes Him,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">hud'i laa Lamatua ka dhu pamamuri Ne.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>let it be God2 who saves3 Him.&gt;</bt><note reference="27:43" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 22:9</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="44" />Dhèu parapo dhèu dua se, pahahe Ne sèmi èèna kahèi.<bt>Those two robbers, also went along mocking Him like that.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Mamadhe Lamatua Yesus<bt>The Lord Yesus' death</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 15:33-41; Lukas 23:44-49; Yohanis 19:28-30)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="45" />Èle èèna ka, maroga kiu-kiu saguru nare era ne'e, karèi nèti lod'o titu mera toke d'ai hake tèlu nihia.<bt>After that, pitch blackness covered over that place from mid day until three oclock in the afternoon.</bt><v n="46" />D'ai hake tèlu, hèia Yesus pa'oo pake lii Aram, na, <span class="Italic">&lt;&lt;Eli! Eli! Lema sabaktani?&gt;&gt;</span> (Sasoa na, &lt;&lt;Ama Lamatua Ja'a! Lamatua Ja'a! Nga tao ka Ama soro kabodho ho tèke eele Ja'a mesa-mesa Ku sèmi ne'e ne?&gt;&gt;)<bt>At three in the afternoon, then Yesus called out using Aram language saying, <span class="Italic">&lt;&lt;Eli! Eli! Lema sabaktani?&gt;&gt;</span> (It means &lt;&lt;My Father God! My God2! Why has Father turned [Your] back abandoning Me alone like this?&gt;&gt;) [NOTE to daughter translations: Aramaic form here different than in Mark.]</bt><note reference="27:46" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 22:2</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="47" />Abhu pèri-pèri dhèu dhu dètu ètu sèra, tadèngi lii Na sèmi èèna, hèia ra papeka, &lt;&lt;Mi nanene ku laa. Na paroa Elia, ca dhèu nèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua dhu uru sèra!&gt;&gt;<bt>Several people near there heard that voice of His, then they said, &lt;&lt;You-p listen up! He is calling Elia, that *spokesperson of God's from long ago!&gt;&gt;</bt><v n="48" />Ka ca dhèu rai la'e nare ula, cèb'u asa d'ara èi anggor manyilu. Hèia na èki mi suu tatea èci, ka j'ole asa hèb'a Yesus sèna ka Na camuci.<bt>Then a person ran to get sea.sponge to dip into sour wine. Then he poked that sponge on the end of a staff, and extended it to Yesus' lips for Him to suck. [NOTE to daughter translations: if your lg has a word for sponge that people know, use it, rather than moss as in Kupang. Gk only has “put on stick”, so poked or tied both work.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ula = (also sponge from the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">ula = (also sponge from the sea)</Message></Annotation><note reference="27:48" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 69:22</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="49" />Te ngaa cahag'e hari peka na, &lt;&lt;Èdhi ladhe sèku, teko-teko Elia mai pamamuri Ne, do aad'o?&gt;&gt;<bt>But there were other people who spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;Let's wait a bit and see if perhaps Elia comes to save3 Him, or not?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="50" />Ka Yesus pa'oo hari dènge lii mèdhu, hèia Na madhe.<bt>Then Yesus called once again with a loud voice, then He died.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="51" />Ètu d'ara Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i, abhu bèla dhu bhèla aae kadhoe pa'abhe Kama Luri Mola-Mèci Ama Lamatua. Lèke dènge Yesus ma'ète a'ae èèna, bèla dhu bhèla aae ne mae, cèri mi dua, nèti dedha toke haha. Hèia rai opo, toke hadhu aae-hadhu aae mae sèg'i bagi mi dua.<bt>In the Temple, there was a big curtain hanging in.order.to block God's Holy Room. Exactly at Yesus' stopping of breath (=death), then that curtain ripped severing in two, from the top to the bottom. Then the earth quaked, until big rocks split open in two.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sèg'i = tabalá"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">sèg'i = tabalá</Message></Annotation><note reference="27:51" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 26:31-33</note><v n="52" />Ro'a-ro'a dhèu madhe bhoke kahèi. Aa dhèu unu Ama Lamatua dhu madhe le, abhu dhu Na pamamuri hari.<bt>Graves also opened. And God's people who had died, there were some whom He made live again.</bt><v n="53" />Ropa Yesus mamuri hari le nèti mamadhe Na, hèia dhèu madhe sèra bhodho mai nèti d'ara ro'a, ka lasi asa Yerusalem. Ètu era ne'e dhèu ae rèdhi si.<bt>When Yesus had come back to life from His death, they came out of the graves, and then came into Yerusalem. Many people saw them there. [EXEG: After his res, they came out; order of events; CEV rendering of Gk participle complicates other passages; follow NRSV, NLT.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="54" />Ètu Golgota, abhu komedhaa dènge sordad'u na dhu j'aga ètu aj'u palolo-palèbha Yesus èèna. Ropa ladhe rèdhi rai opo, dènge aa'i-aa'i dhu j'aj'i se'e, rèngu madha'u titu kèna. Ka ra papeka, na, &lt;&lt;Ira ii! Dhèu ne'e ne, tare'a-re'a Ana Lamatua!&gt;&gt;<bt>At Golgota, there was a commander and his soldiers who guarded Yesus' crossed wood there. When they saw the earth quake, and all the things which had happened there, then they became very afraid. They spoke to each other, saying, &lt;&lt;Ira ii! [+amazement] This Person here, really truly was God's Child!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Ropa ladhe rèdhi rai opo dènge"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">Ropa ladhe rèdhi rai opo dènge aa'i-aa'i dhu j'aj'i se'e, komedhaa j'aga dènge sordadu-sordadu na madha'u titu kèna. Ka ra papeka, na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu ne'e ne tare'a-re'a Ana Lamatua dedha!&gt;&gt;</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="55" />Ètu era ne'e, abhu bhèni pèri-pèri dhèu dhu laladhe mamadhe Yesus nèti kaj'èu. Rèngu se'e ka dhu madhutu Ne nèti Galilea, te rèngu ka dhu lalau-lalo'o Ne karèi nèti uru.<bt>At that place also there were several women, who followed watching His death from far. They had followed Him from Galilea, cuz (elaboration) they had served (doublet) Him from the beginning. [NOTE to daughter translations: KM works for KM, but these women mentioned below may not all be married, so don't force ‘ina’.]</bt><v n="56" />Dhèu bhèni se'e, nuka Maria nèti rae Magdala, Maria èci hari (nuka ina Yakobis dènge Yusuf), aa dènge dhèu èmu Sabadeus (nuka ina nèti Yakobis dènge Yohanis).<bt>Those women were Maria from Magdala village, another Maria (who was Yakobis and Yusuf's mother), and Sabadius' spouse (that is, Yakobis and Yohanis' mother).</bt><note reference="27:55-56" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lukas 8:2-3</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ra padhane Lamatua Yesus<bt>They bury the Lord Yesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 15:42-47; Lukas 23:50-56; Yohanis 19:38-42)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="57" />Ètu èèna, abhu dhèu kaja èci nèti rae Arimatea, ngara na Yusuf. Nèngu ne dhu nèbhu le madhutu a'aj'a Yesus. Lod'o mamadhe Yesus lèke hari Jumat. Asa bèli èèna, lèke dènge lod'o sabaj'a dhèu Yahudi. Nèti èèna ka, ropa lod'o oe cèna, hèia Yusuf tenge j'ara ho neo papuru ngi'u aae Yesus nèti aj'u palolo-palèbha.<bt>There, there was a rich man from the village of Arimatea, named Yusuf. He had followed/obeyed Yesus' teaching(s) for a long time. Yesus' death was on a Friday (assimilated loan). The next day was the Yahudi people's prayer/worship day. That's why when the sun was about to go down, Yusuf was looking for a way to take down Yesus' corpse from that *cross. [EXEG: vs.57-58; For timeframe, see NLT, and discussion in Carson &amp; Morris.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Yesus madhe lèke hari jumat. Asa"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">Yesus madhe lèke hari jumat. Asa bèli èèna lèke dènge lod'o manèngi-mangaj'i dhèu Yahudi. Nèti èèna ka, ètu hari jumat èèna abhu ca dhèu tenge j'ara ho neo papuru ngi'u aae Yesus nèti aj'u palolo-palèbha. (Ngara dhèu ne, Yusuf nèti rae Arimatea, dhu nèbhu le madhutu Lii Holo Nori Yesus.)</Message></Annotation><v n="58" />Hèia la'e asa gubernur Pilatus, sèna ka manèngi papuru ngi'u aae Yesus. Ka gubernur paredha, sèna ka ngi'u aae Yesus saraka mi Yusuf.<bt>So/then he went to governor Pilatus, to request to take down Yesus' corpse. Then2 the governor ordered for them to hand over that corpse to Yusuf.</bt><v n="59" />Ka Yusuf la'e asa Golgota, hèia na papuru ngi'u aae Yesus nèti aj'u palolo-palèbha. Hèia na hutu pabe'a-be'a ngi'u aae ne dènge bèla hiu dhu kab'ua.<bt>Then2 he went to Golgota, then he took down Yesus' corpse from that crossed wood. Then he wrapped that corpse up really well with new cloth that was expensive.</bt><v n="60" />Tèu èèna, dhèu heka pae rare ro'a èci ètu ledhe hadhu, sèna ka tao tèke ro'a hia Yusuf dènge a'ari na, ladhe d'ai lod'o rèngu madhe. De Yusuf si nedhe rèti ngi'u aae Yesus ne, lasi paj'unu asa ro'a deo na. Ka ètu hèb'a ro'a ne, ra saguru dènge hadhu kabela aae cue, ho ra bèdho pabe'a-be'a hèb'a ro'a ne. Èle èèna ka Yusuf si lèpa.<bt>At that time, people had recently finished chiselling a hole in a rock mountain/ hill, to prepare ahead.of.time a grave for Yusuf and his family should they die. So (consequently), Yusuf (coll.) carried entered Yesus' corpse into that aforementioned grave. Next, they rolled a big flat stone, to close/cover the mouth of that hole well. After that, Yusuf (coll.) went home.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nèdhe = angkat"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">nèdhe = angkat</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="61" />Lod'o èèna, Maria nèti Magdala, dènge Maria dhu leo èci madhutu d'ai era èèna kahèi. Ra madhèdi patangara dènge ro'a ne.<bt>At that time, Maria from Magdala and another Maria, also followed to that place. They kept just sitting facing that hole.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Gubernur paredha ho dhèu madhenge ro'a Yesus<bt>The governor orders people to guard Yesus' grave</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="62" />Asa bèli èèna, lèke dènge lod'o ae sasab'a dhèu Yahudi. Hèia kètu agama Yahudi dènge dhèu Parisi lasi paraga dènge gubernur.<bt>The next day, was the Yahudi people's day of stopping work/rest. Then the chief priests and Parisi people went to meet with the governor.</bt><v n="63" />Ra peka, &lt;&lt;Ama. Ji'i sanèd'e era, lod'o dhèu kapod'e-kabèli èèna mamuri era, Na peka, na, &lt;Ja'a madhe tare'a, te ngaa èle tèlu lod'o, Ja'a mamuri hari.&gt;<bt>They said, &lt;&lt;Father. We-exc still remember when that habitual deciever (doublet) was still alive, he said, &lt;I will really die, but after three days, I will live again.&gt;</bt><note reference="27:63" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 16:21, 17:23, 20:19, Markus 8:31, 9:31, 10:33-34, Lukas 9:22, 18:31-33</note><v n="64" />Nèti èèna ka, ama paredha ku sordad'u sèra, ho ra j'aga paie-iie ro'a èèna d'ai tèlu lod'o. Dènge j'ara ne'e, ana madhutu Na bani boe mana'u rèti ngi'u aae Na, sèna ka ra monya peka na, Nèngu mamuri hari. Te ladhe rèngu kapod'e-kabèli sèmi èèna, risi eele nèti mamonya rèngu uru sèra, lod'o dhu ra peka na, Nèngu ne nuka Kristus.&gt;&gt;<bt>Because of that, father please order the soldiers to carefully guard that grave for three days. In that way, His underlings won't dare to steal away His corpse, to decieve people saying He is alive again. Cuz (elaboration) if they decieve (doublet) like that, that's even more than their earlier deceptions, when they said He was Krisitus.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="65" />Ropa tadèngi nare, hèia gubernur dhaa, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Be'a kahèi! Te ngaa miu dènge dhèu madhenga kahèi. Be'a risi miu pua si, ho lasi j'aga paie-iie ro'a nèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>Hearing like that, then the governor responded, saying, &lt;&lt;Ok/good! But you have guard people. It's better to just use them, to go carefully guard that (remote) place.&gt;&gt; [EXEG: Note Carson &amp; Morris have conflicting views on the interpretation of this verse (whose guard is it?); this has support from Carson, NLT, etc. TB goes the other way.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="66" />Èle ka lasi asa era èèna, rèti dènge dhèu madhenga ra. D'ai era ne'e, ra segel madhe babèdho ro'a ne.<bt>Then they went to that place, and brought their guards. Arriving there, they completely sealed that grave's hole covering.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="caloa = counter for thread"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:42:04Z">caloa = counter for thread</Message></Annotation><note reference="27:66" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Dhèu d'èlu-mèu sèra, peka na, ra segel dènge j'ara ra tao loa hèngu caloa ètu hadhu dènge kadidhi ro'a èèna, pake lak, reo rare hadhu.<bt>The experts say, they sealed by means of placing a thread on the rock and walls of the hole, using wax around that rock.</bt></note>Hèia ra pua dhèu sèra madhenga, sèna ka dhèu leo baku mai rare ngi'u aae Yesus.<bt>Then they ordered those people to guard, so that other people didn't come take Yesus' corpse.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus mamuri hari!<bt>The Lord Yesus lives again!</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 16:1-10; Lukas 24:1-12; Yohanis 20:1-10)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="28" />
      <v n="1" />Ka ètu d'ara hari Migu mad'ae aae era, Maria nèti Magdala, dènge Maria dhu leo èci, lasi asa ro'a Yesus.<bt>Then2 early Sunday morning, Maria from Magdala and another Maria went to see Yesus' grave.</bt><v n="2" />Kaca'a la rai opo kapai titu kèna. Ana pajuu Ama Lamatua ca dhèu puru mai nèti sorga, hèia na loli eele hadhu aae dhu saguru ro'a. Ka na madhèdi ètu dedha hadhu ne.<bt>Suddenly there was a big earthquake. One of God's underlings from heaven came down, and he rolled away that big stone which was closing that hole/ grave. Then2 he sat on that stone.</bt><v n="3" />Rèhu ana pajuu ne kale'e sèmi kaha'a bela, aa mèdha-papake na pudhi mèu.<bt>That underling's face shone like lightning, and his clothes were pure/ clean white.</bt><v n="4" />Dhèu madhenga se, madha'u bia toke ra karèbha, ka rèngu bisa boe kalau-karèto, nuka sèmi dhèu madhe sa.<bt>Those guards were terrified to the point that they trembled, and were unable to move, like they were dead people. [EXEG: Both Carson &amp; Morris talk about “soldiers were made helpless” “paralysed”, others “incapacitated” which also fits the higher level context better than ‘pale’.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Hèia ana pajuu nèti sorga ne, lii dènge dhèu bhèni se'e, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Miu baku madha'u! Ja'a ke'a miu se mai tenge Yesus, Dhèu dhu ra paku pamadhe ètu aj'u palolo-palèbha èèna.<bt>Then that underling from heaven told those women, saying, &lt;&lt;You don't need to be afraid! I know you come to find Yesus, that Person whom they nailed killed on that crossed wood.</bt><v n="6" />Te ngaa Nèngu aad'o heka ètu era ne'e. Te Na mamuri hari le, sama sèmi dhu Na peka le uru èèna. Maso mai, sèna ka mèdhi unu mi era dhu ra paj'unu ngi'u aae Na. Era ne ngaa-ngaa aad'o heka!<bt>But He is not here anymore. Cuz (elaboration) he is alive again, like he spoke about beforehand. Come in to see for yourselves that place where they laid His corpse. That place is empty!</bt><v n="7" />De pamèri lèpa ka! Lami lolo dènge ana madhutu Na, peka na, Yesus mamuri hari le. La'e uuru le asa Galilea. Rèngu hud'i lasi paraga uuru ku dènge Ne ètu nèi, sèmi dhu uru èèna, Na moa mema mi rèngu. Parcaya la. Lèpa ka, lami lole ngaa dhu ja'a peka ne!&gt;&gt;<bt>So (consequently), now you must hurry home. Go tell straightaway to His followers, saying, Yesus is alive again. He has gone on ahead to Galilea. They must go meet Him there first (i.e. before doing anything else), like He previously instructed ahead of time to them. Just believe. Go home and tell what I have spoken here!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Hèia bhèni se rai li'u lasi, tèke eele era ne'e. Ra madha'u, te ngaa ra karej'e-karae kahèi. Ka ra pamèri-mèri lèpa, lasi peka j'ara se aa'i-aa'i ra mi ana madhutu Yesus.<bt>Then those women ran outside leaving that place. They were afraid, but they also were happy (doublet). They went home quickly to report that all those things to Yesus' followers.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Te ngaa ropa d'ai talora j'ara, kabèdhi la Yesus mai paraga dènge ra. Ka Na lii, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Saloom!&gt;&gt; Ropa ladhe rèdhi, hèia lasi padètu-dètu, liku rare haga Na, dènge pahaha iisi ra mi Yesus.<bt>But in the middle of the road, unexpectedly Yesus came and met them. He spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;Peace! (Saloom)&gt;&gt; Seeing like that they came close and embraced His feet, and worshipped Him.</bt><v n="10" />Hèia Na padhai lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;Baku madha'u! Lami peka dènge ana madhutu Ja'a, sèna ka ra lasi mate ja'a ètu Galilea nèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then He spoke saying, &lt;&lt;Don't be afraid! Go tell My underlings for them to go wait for Me in Galilea (remote).&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu madhenga lasi lolo ngaa dhu j'aj'i ètu era padhane Lamatua Yesus<bt>The guards go report about what happened at the place where they buried the Lord Yesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Lod'o dhèu bhèni se ètu talora j'ara era, dhèu madhenga se lèpa le asa kota. Rèngu lasi lole ngaa dhu j'aj'i se mi kètu agama Yahudi sèra.<bt>When those women were still in the middle of the road (=halfway home), those guards returned to the city. They went to report what had happened to the chief priests.</bt><v n="12" />Hèia kètu agama Yahudi rare lii èci dènge dhèu heka ad'a sèra, sèna ka b'ae doi ae-ae mi dhèu j'aga ho ra hutu hèb'a.<bt>Then those chief priests strategised/ plotted with the traditional elders, to pay alot of money to close those guards mouths.</bt><v n="13" />Kètu agama Yahudi sèra peka, na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe dhèu karèi miu, dhaa sèmi ne'e: d'ara mèda, ropa ji'i bhèj'i luu, nge'a boe, na, ana madhutu Na mai mana'u rèti ngi'u aae Na.<bt>Those chief priests said, &lt;&lt;If people/someone asks you-pl, respond like this: at night when we were sleeping soundly, apparently/evidently His followers came and stole away His corpse.</bt><v n="14" />Aa ladhe gubernur tadèngi, mage miu madha'u, te ji'i ka dhu ator dènge ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>And if the governor hears (this matter), then you don't be afraid, cuz (elaboration) later we'll be the ones who handle him.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Hèia dhèu madhenga se rare doi. Aa ra tao madhutu dad'èi kètu agama se'e. Nèti èèna ka, toke d'ai sange ne'e dhèu-dhèu Yahudi parcaya era lii lolo kapod'e-kabèli ne.<bt>Then those guards took that money. And they did according to those chief priests will. That's why until now Yahudi people still believe that twisted/deceitful (doublet) story.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus pad'elo ngi'u Na mi ana madhutu Na<bt>The Lord Yesus shows Himself to His followers</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 16:14-18; Lukas 24:36-49; Yohanis 20:19-23; Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 1:6-8)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Ropa tadèngi rare lii lolo nèti dhèu bhèni se'e, hèia ana madhutu Yesus dhèu canguru èci, lasi paraga dènge Yesus asa propensi Galilea, ètu ledhe èci, madhutu lii moa Na.<bt>After hearing those women's reports, then those eleven followers of Yesus, went to meet with Yesus in Galilea province at a mountain, according to His instructions.</bt><note reference="28:16" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 26:32, Markus 14:28</note><v n="17" />Ropa ra ladhe rèdhi Ne, ka ra pahaha iisi mi Nèngu. Masi ka sèmi èèna, te ngaa abhu kahèi dhu d'ara ra kajari era.<bt>When they saw Him, then2 they worshiped Him. Even though it was like that, nevertheless there were still some who had forked insides (=doubted).</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Hèia Na ara mai padètu-dètu dènge ra, ka Na lii, &lt;&lt;Ama Lamatua pangèd'u le koasa mi Ja'a, sèna ka Ja'a paredha aa'i-aa'i ètu sorga, aa dènge aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha ne.<bt>Then He came close to them and spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;God has entrusted/ given Me power/authority, for Me to rule everything which is in heaven, and everything which is on earth.</bt><v n="19" />De miu lami asa mia-mia, miu hud'i peka-padhai ku dènge dhèu nèti suku aa'i-aa'i ra, Lii Lolo Be'a Ja'a ne. Aa miu hud'i aj'a si paie-iie, ho sèna ka rèngu j'aj'i ana madhutu Ja'a. Aa miu hud'i sarani si ho j'aj'i mi tadha, peka na, rèngu dhu pa'èki le dènge Ama, dènge Ana, aa dènge Roh Na dhu Mola-Mèci.<bt>So (consequently), (as) you go wherever (=anywhere you go at anytime), you-pl must tell all ethnic groups My Good Story. And you must teach them well, so that they become My followers. And you must baptise them as a sign saying they are tied/ bound together with Father, and Child, and His Spirit who is Clean/Holy.</bt><note reference="28:19" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 1:8</note><v n="20" />Aa nori si sèna ka ra tao madhutu paredha aa'i-aa'i dhu Ja'a peka tèke le dènge miu. Sanèd'e, ee! Ja'a bera-bera dènge miu toke èle rai-haha ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>And teach them to do according to all the commands which I told you. Remember, ee! I am together with you continually, until the world ends.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
  </book>
</bible>